38.prez_name: 3D Printing in Maxillofacial Surgery: Assessment to Print Mandibular Fixation Plates
38.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
38.prez_authors: Ilaria  Campioni, Nikhil  Gupta, Ilaria  Cacciotti
38.prez_abstract: The purpose of the study is to investigate the feasibility and risks associated with the design and the fabrication of plates for mandibular applications in trauma patients using 3D printing. Due to the potential to achieve the patient specific design of the implants, 3D printing is very promising in this field. A commercial prototyping plastic material with PolyJet machine was used and STL models of different resolution were printed using the same CAD design. Finite element analysis was conducted to study the capability of the implant design to resist the biomechanical loads. Micro-tomography analysis was performed to verify the internal structure of the printed objects. The presence of defects can affect the quality and compromise the final performance of the implant. Results are analyzed to understand the effect of design and print conditions on the implant quality.

39.prez_name: A-1: 3D Printing of Hierarchical Porous Thermoplastic Polyurethane Foam with Tuned Piezoresistivity Behavior
39.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
39.prez_abstract: Porous thermoplastic polyurethane is widely applied in many fields including strain sensor, biomedical scaffold, electromagnetic interference (EMI) shielding, and super adsorbents. The hierarchical porous structure is known to out-perform its mono-scale porous counterparts. This study aims to fabricate hierarchical porous TPU/graphene nanocomposites by using paste extrusion printing. Paste ink were prepared by adding sufficient clay into TPU solution where clay acts as rheology modifier and pore template. The addition of graphene introduces electrical conductivity. The mechanical response and piezoresistivity can be tuned by changing porous structure which are controlled by altering clay loading and 3D printing design.

40.prez_name: A-2: Additive Manufacturing of Clay Modified with Primary Battery Waste
40.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
40.prez_abstract: This investigation summarizes results from additive manufacturing (AM) of kaolinite clay modified with primary battery waste following the extrusion freeforming (EFF) method. The battery waste is a hazardous material available in millions of tons generated worldwide. The main goal in this research is to study the AM of kaolinite clays modified with primary battery waste and to explore diverse applications. Different samples fabricated from clays were built with different water to clay ratios (W/C) and Waste contents between 0 and 10wt%. Cylinders were fabricated by AM and exposed to 1100°C for 2 hours in air atmosphere, and tested in compression. Materials characterization was conducted with scanning electron microscopy, x-ray diffraction, and other performance tests.

41.prez_name: A-4: Development of SiC Ceramics with Complicated Shape Using the FDM Type 3D Printer
41.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
41.prez_authors: Hisaya  Masuda, Yoshio  Ohta, Mikito  Kitayama
41.prez_abstract: Silicon carbide (SiC) ceramics have excellent properties and widely used for high temperature applications. So far, joining techniques have been applied to fabricate large SiC ceramics with complicated shape. In this work, the additive manufacturing (AM) technique was examined to fabricated SiC ceramics with complicated hollow structures using the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) type 3D printer. To construct the hollow structure, the “support-less” condition must be achieved. For this purpose, extruded SiC-phenol resin compounds must be cured immediately after molding to keep the molded shapes. To increase the thermal conductivity of the SiC compounds, the combinations of commercial SiC powders with different average diameters were examined for increasing the volume fraction of SiC particles against the phenol resin. SiC compounds with optimized viscosity and fluidity for the modified FDM type 3D printer were successfully obtained.

42.prez_name: A-5: Surface Morphology of Additive Manufactured Metal Matrix Composites
42.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
42.prez_authors: Cindy  Waters, Bernard  Ilogebde, Mohammad  Khan, Amy  Elliott
42.prez_abstract: This project entails research conducted to create a higher quality microscopic surface morphology of an additively manufactured metal composite. The goal is to compare density and structural morphology of metal BinderJetting processes and die pressing.  The samples in this study were created with amorphous steel powder by the means of Binder Jet printing at Oak Ridge MDF and others were created via die compaction. Both samples were injected with liquid bronze to act as space filler for any observed porosity. Detailed characterization of the raw powders was conducted on the Malvern powder characterization instrument. An interesting product was the similarity of the densities of our SAM alloy binder jet sample and comparable SAM alloy die-pressed samples which measured to be 3.96g/cm3 and 3.89g/cm3 respectively.. The final shape of the bronze infiltrated binder jet sample was a net shaped structure.

43.prez_name: A Novel Concept of Micro-extrusion through High Aspect Ratio Nozzles for High Speed Additive Manufacturing
43.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
43.prez_authors: Leon  Shaw, Ling  Li, S. M. Imran  Ayub
43.prez_abstract: A novel concept of layer-by-layer manufacturing through high aspect ratio (HAR) nozzles is proposed. Various conditions for extruding pastes including nozzle moving speed, piston speed, extrusion rate, and distance between the nozzle tip and the substrate have been evaluated. By linking various micro-extrusion parameters together with the aid of a critical distance concept and addressing the extrusion delay in response to the change of the piston speed and air pocket problems properly, we have successfully micro-extruded single planes, multi-layer objects, and larger planes made of multiple smaller planes side by side through HAR nozzles. It is shown that the X-Y dimensions of an extruded plane in the steady-state extrusion stage are determined by the nozzle travel distance and the length of the HAR nozzle opening. The demonstrated feasibility of using a HAR nozzle machine has opened the door to manufacture multi-material, multi-layer devices with high productivity in the future.

44.prez_name: Additive Manufacturing for Innovative Electric Motor Designs
44.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
44.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing processes are enabling for new innovative electric motor designs which have higher power densities and/or efficiencies. Compared to conventional manufacturing, components can be more geometrically complex, compact, multi-material, innovatively cooled, integrated, and multifunctional. Two optimized stator designs concepts are being pursed in which advanced electrically conductive coils are fabricated using direct silver printing and direct copper wire imbedding methods. Other additive manufacturing techniques are focusing on additional structural motor components such as the rotor backing plate, the housing, or the motor mount which can be made with reduced mass, lightweight structures, and efficient cooling.

45.prez_name: Additive Manufacturing of Functional Graded Multi-materials via Selective Laser Melting – Microstructure and Mechanical Behavior
45.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
45.prez_authors: Florian  Hengsbach, Peter  Koppa, Martin Joachim Holzweissig, Madison  Burns, Peter  Hoyer, Thomas  Tröster, Mirko  Schaper
45.prez_abstract: Recently, additive manufacturing (AM) attracted substantial attention from academia and industry. Advantageous such as the fabrication of unrivalled complex parts accompanied with reduced time to market phases, or tool free productions result in the increased demand for AM. Besides the latter benefits, novel metallic, complex materials, e.g., functional graded materials (FGM) are feasible by employing AM based on wire or powder feedstock. These materials possess locally adjusted properties in which a gradation stems either from microstructure manipulation or from material variation. However, the current work addresses the generation of FGM by utilizing a powder bed based technology, i.e., selective laser melting. The recoater, hence, was modified in order to allow an inline fabrication of the multi-material in which two powder materials such as steel and bronze are separated. The investigations shed light on the microstructural evolution at the interface as well as the mechanical performance of the specimens built.

46.prez_name: Additive Manufacturing of Interpenetrating Phase Composites with Exceptional Damage-tolerance
46.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
46.prez_authors: Alexander  Pawlowski, Zachary  Cordero, Matthew  French, Thomas  Muth, J. Keith  Carver, Ralph  Dinwiddie, Amy  Elliott, Amit  Shyam, Derek  Splitter
46.prez_abstract: Recently developed additive manufacturing (AM) processes offer exceptional control over form and microstructure. However, it remains an open challenge to print high-performance composites and functionally graded components in which the constituents are patterned for optimal performance. One of the major challenges associated with printing composites using fusion-based AM techniques is that the mixing and reactivity of the constituents is promoted inside the melt pool.  In this talk, we will describe a simple processing route that excludes such liquid-phase mixing.  Using A356/316L composites as a model system, we demonstrate how to print composites with tailorable thermal and mechanical properties as well as exceptional damage-tolerance when loaded in tension.

47.prez_name: Additive Manufacturing via Ambient Reactive Extrusion
47.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
47.prez_authors: Cynthia  Kutchko, Orlando  Rios, David   Fenn, Reza  Rock, Kurt  Olson
47.prez_abstract: Additive-manufacturing (AM) potentially offers many benefits over traditional methods in the fabrication of complex parts. In practice, today’s methods for AM are often limited by long build times and unpredictable mechanical properties.  Reactive mixture deposition approaches can enable higher rates of 3D printing and reductions in write-head mass in comparison to thermal AM systems. Additionally, the reaction kinetics and transient rheological properties can be specifically designed for the deposition rates, enabling the synchronized development of increasing shear modulus and extensive cross linking across the z-layers at ambient temperatures. Material chemistries tuned for specific properties and inter-layer covalent bonds significantly improve the strength along the axis of printing. The fast, tunable cure kinetics combined with Big-Area-Additive-Manufacturing (BAAM) enable rapid vertical builds.

48.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
48.prez_authors: Gerard Klint Simon, Thomas F. Ekiert
48.prez_abstract: When a radio frequency (RF) structure such as a radome requires good mechanical strength, high transmission, and low weight, A-sandwich designs are sometimes chosen.  These structures consist of a foam core with high RF transmission qualities laminated between two thin sheets of solid material, also possessing high transmission properties.  Using a fused deposition modeling system, this design principle was applied to create a pseudo A-sandwich structure.  The ability of the additive manufacturing system to alter the build properties of the structure provided the flexibility to rapidly explore the effect of the infill density and orientation on the RF transmission of a radome.  Structures were fabricated to function within the W-band.  RF characterization was performed to determine the overall transmission through the radome material as well as the effective dielectric constant of the core.  This data was compared to the performance of solid laminate structures and actual A-sandwich structures.

49.prez_name: Development of High-performance 316L Stainless Steel Nanocomposites by Selective Laser Melting: Processing-microstructure-property Relation
49.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
49.prez_authors: Bandar  AlMangour, Dariusz  Grzesiak, Jenn-Ming  Yang
49.prez_abstract: Selective laser melting (SLM), an additive manufacturing technology, was utilized to process TiC/316L nanocomposite systems with various TiC volume contents. The influence of the starting TiC volume content on microstructural features, and mechanical properties of the SLM-processed nanocomposite parts was investigated. In general, the TiC particles were homogeneously dispersed and they formed nanoscale ring-like structures along the grain boundaries. Further, by increasing the volume content of the TiC, the hardness and compressive yield strength increased while the wear rate deceased owing to the combined effects of grain refinement and grain-boundary strengthening.

50.prez_name: Development of New Resin Chemistries for Additive Manufacturing Processes of Composites
50.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
50.prez_abstract: Performance and service life of polymer based additively manufactured components are limited by the availability of standard polymer resins with poor inter-road/layer bonding and upper service temperatures limited to 250C. Existing thermoplastic materials for FDM and SLS exhibit poor z-directional mechanical properties, poor fatigue behavior and little solvent/fuel resistance. High performance thermosetting resins that are currently used in conventional composite manufacturing exhibit the performance characteristics and properties required for extreme environment Air Force applications, but are not readily usable for additive manufacturing processes. Several approaches will be presented addressing this gap by modification of chemistry and rheology of thermosetting resins and pre-ceramic polymers. Cure cycle optimization and initial predictive modeling efforts on cure shrinkage of printed parts will be presented. Mechanical properties of printed thermoset coupons are compared to state of the art thermoplastic materials with and without reinforcement filler.

51.prez_name: Effect of Porosity on Stochastic Fracture of Additive Manufactured Polymer Matrix Composites
51.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
51.prez_abstract: Consumer level Fused deposition modeling (FDM )systems have been used for production of open-source free designs that contain intentional porosity. Despite the increasing use of FDM, the effect of porosity on the mechanical behavior of FDMed short-carbon-fiber-reinforced composites are unclear. In this talk, we will discuss the effect of internal porosity and extrusion tip vibrations on the mechanical properties and mechanical reliability of the FDMed composites containing up to 50 vol. % porosity.  Seven batches of thirty specimens were tensile tested at different porosity levels, a total of ~210 tests.  Weibull statistics was used to quantify variations in the mechanical properties. A novel and inexpensive extrusion tip vibration technique was used eliminate road-to-road porosity, which resulted in an increase in both fracture strength and its Weibull modulus from 23 to 54 for dense samples. The resulting microstructures were investigated using X-ray microscopy and scanning electron microscope.

52.prez_name: Experimental and Computational Study of Novel Additively Manufactured Foams
52.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
52.prez_authors: Diab  Abueidda, Iwona M. Jasiuk, Rashid  Abu Al-Rub
52.prez_abstract: We study novel polymeric cellular materials (CMs) represented by triply periodic minimal surfaces (TPMS) for various technological applications. TPMS are infinitely continuous smooth surfaces that separate the space into two intertwined complex regions. Mathematically they are locally area minimizing surfaces with zero mean curvatures at each point on the surface. The connectivity and continuity of the TPMS-CMs allow a smoother transfer of loads. We investigate these materials computationally and experimentally. We additively manufacture the CMS and their base materials. Their properties are tested to provide inputs and serve as validation for finite element modeling. Two finite deformation elastic/hyperelastic-viscoplastic constitutive models calibrated based on the mechanical response of the base material are used in the computational study. It is shown that the specimen size of the TPMS-CMs affect their mechanical properties. Moreover, the finite element results agree with the results obtained experimentally.

53.prez_name: Formulation of UV Curable Resins Utilized in Vat Photo Polymerization for the Additive Manufacturing of Gun Propulsion Charge in 3D Printers
53.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
53.prez_abstract: Formulating UV curable resins for Additive manufacturing (AM), or 3D printing, is an area that spans various industrial sectors from adhesives, inks and optical fibers to nanotechnology and biomaterials.  UV curable resins such as epoxides, vinyl ethers and acrylates are important monomers that offer effective mediums for energetic materials, and the potential exists to develop environmentally friendly formulations with suspended energetic materials at various solids loading levels.  Developing techniques for UV curing formulations of highly loaded energetic suspensions is a challenging system that must satisfy several requirements as a high quality formulation with synergistic ingredient combinations to enhance the propulsion is required.  The candidate formulation must be able to operate in an SLA resin tank, meaning the suspension must be at least as fluidic as conventional SLA resins; and a thorough understanding of the polymerization reaction, photoinitiating systems and cure depth must be understood as dominating factors for stability.

54.prez_name: Functionally Grading Aluminum Alloy to Titanium Aluminide (TiAl3) by Laser Based Directed Energy Deposition
54.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
54.prez_authors: Jay S. Keist, Jessica  Pehr, Abdalla R. Nassar, Wesley  Mitchell, Todd A. Palmer, Ted  Reutzel
54.prez_abstract: There are many engineering applications within extreme environments that require components with properties that vary as a function of location within the component.  Functionally graded materials (FGMs) can be designed to exhibit gradients in material properties to help address the engineering needs for these extreme environments.  A laser based directed energy deposition process was used to fabricate components with a gradient in composition from an aluminum alloy 2219 to a titanium aluminide (TiAl3).  Thermal expansion behavior, microstructure, chemistry and microhardness were analyzed as a function of location within graded simple wall builds.  The thermal expansion behavior of the graded structure varied by location depending on the local chemistry and phase composition.  As a proof of concept, an aluminum to titanium aluminide FGM component was fabricated that would be used as a bridge for connecting components that exhibit significantly different thermal expansion behaviors.

55.prez_name: Integrating Fiber Optic Strain Sensors into Metal Using Ultrasonic Additive Manufacturing
55.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
55.prez_authors: Adam Jacob Hehr, Justin  Wenning, Mark  Norfolk, John  Sheridan, John Andrew Newman
55.prez_abstract: Ultrasonic Additive Manufacturing (UAM), a rather new three-dimensional (3D) printing technology, uses ultrasonic energy to produce metallurgical bonds between layers of metal foils near room temperature.  This low temperature attribute of the process enables integration of temperature sensitive components, such as fiber optic strain sensors, directly into metal structures for load and health monitoring applications.  This study evaluates the consolidation quality, interface robustness, and load sensing limits of commercially available fiber optic strain sensors.  Applications for measuring crack initiation in fatigue samples is also given.  Lastly, a future outlook on the technology and its applications is described.

56.prez_name: Interfacial Bonding Quality Prediction and Improvement for Fusion Deposition Modeling by Layerwise Additive Manufacturing Analytical Block Technique
56.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
56.prez_abstract: As is well known, adjacent filaments’ bonding quality in fusion deposition modeling (FDM) completely relies on the inherent microstructure evolution mechanism and its evolution completeness over a critical temperature. Thus, the part quality of fusion deposition modeling is very strong dependent on the tracks’ temperature variation, especially for a large-scale deposition part.  In order to quickly simulate the full-scale temperature field in track-by-track deposition, a layerwise additive manufacturing analytical block technique has been developed to carry out the full temperature field throughout the deposition for FDM processing. Then, based on the microstructural evolution characteristics and whole temperature field changes, the interfacial bonding quality index is established to reveal the interface bonding weakness and relevant location in the whole part. In terms of the bonding quality index and layerwise model, the deposition strategy can be modified to improve the bonding quality.

57.prez_name: Laser-matter Interactions in Laser Beam Melting of High Performance Alumina-zirconia Oxide Ceramics
57.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
57.prez_authors: Liliana  Moniz, Christophe  Colin, Marie-Hélène  Berger, Jean-Dominique  Bartout
57.prez_abstract: Laser Beam Melting of ceramics offers new design possibilities of complex structures with good oxidation and temperature resistances. Poor absorptivity in near infra-red wavelength is overcome with addition of a sorbent to ceramic powder, and weak thermal shock resistance by using preheating systems. High thermal gradients and cooling rates are generated, which enable directional solidification of nano-metric eutectic microstructures, known for their creep resistance. Laser-powder bed interactions are characterized. An interaction model is developed, based on the analysis of volume interaction, allowing determination of solid and liquid optical properties of fused materials. In-situ optical measurements are performed to monitor evolution of materials properties during manufacturing. Influences of laser, powder and sorbent parameters are assessed. Specific criteria are adapted from metals study to evaluate ceramic melt pool stability and stable window for dense part manufacturing is identified. Proof is made that laser interaction with ceramics shows large differences compared to metals.

58.prez_name: Laser Additive Manufacturing of In Situ Metal Matrix Composites
58.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
58.prez_abstract: Laser additive manufacturing opens up a new horizon in terms of processing in situ metal matrix composites as well as functionally graded materials that are difficult, if not impossible, to process using conventional techniques. This talk discusses such a novel approach to process in situ metal-matrix composites with refined microstructures using the laser engineered net shaping (LENS<SUP>TM</SUP>) process based on laser additive manufacturing. Few case studies will be used as examples, mainly based on nickel-based and titanium-based composites. Ni-Ti-C composites consist of an in situ formed and homogeneously distributed titanium carbide (TiC) phase reinforcing the nickel matrix where in situ reaction is taking place between elemental blend powders. In situ nitridation of -titanium alloys was achieved by direct introduction of gaseous nitrogen in systematic manner during LENS<SUP>TM</SUP>. These examples help illustrate the concept of using additive manufacturing to in situ process novel composites from a feedstock of simple elemental powders.

59.prez_name: Micro-galvanic Corrosion of Ti-6Al-4V In-situ Alloyed with Molybdenum via Selective Laser Melting
59.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
59.prez_authors: Chwayita  Madikizela, Lesley  Cornish, Hein  Moller, Lesley  Chown
59.prez_abstract: Powder-bed laser metal additive manufacturing via in situ alloying is currently of interest for alloy development. Molybdenum is a beta stabilizer which is added to Ti-6Al-4V to produce a more ductile beta alloy. Previous studies have shown that in situ alloying of Ti-6Al-4V with Mo results in a composite consisting of a beta stabilized matrix with umelted Mo particles. This microstructure was found to improve mechanical properties. A concern of such a composite is possible micro-galvanic corrosion effects since Ti-6Al-4V is more noble on the galvanic series than Mo. Immersion tests were done where a composite sample was placed in a 3.5% NaCl solution and a scanning electron microscope was used to examine the corrosion effect weekly. Corrosion attack of the anodic Mo particles was found. The resulting composite microstructure might therefore be beneficial for improving mechanical properties, but its corrosion resistance might be problematic in certain applications.

60.prez_name: Microstructural Origins of Spatially Tailored Functional Response in NiTi SMAs
60.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
60.prez_authors: Ji  Ma, Brian  Franco, Kubra  Karayagiz, Luke  Johnson, Jun  Liu, Gustavo  Tapia, Alaa  Elwany, Raymundo  Arroyave, Ibrahim  Karaman
60.prez_abstract: Through Transmission Electron Microscopy (TEM) studies, we demonstrate micro- and nanoscale differences in the dislocation, second-phase, and sub-grain structures caused by differences in the processing parameter during selective laser melting (SLM) of a nickel-titanium shape memory alloy.  These controlled variations in microstructure can be harnessed to create location-dependent functional properties in the same part, such as solid-state actuators showing multiple shape recovery stages activated at different temperatures.  However, the complex thermal history of the SLM process begets multi-scale microstructures that may be highly heterogeneous even within a small spatial region, and creates unanticipated couplings between materials properties that one may wish to control separately.

61.prez_name: Phase Field Simulation of Dendritic Solidification during Additive Manufacturing
61.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
61.prez_authors: Linmin  Wu, Yi  Zhang, Jing  Zhang
61.prez_abstract: Understanding and controlling dendritic patterns during additive manufacturing is important because it affects the composition distribution and mechanical properties of 3D printed parts. In this study, a phase field model is developed to predict dendrites growth during rapid solidification in additive manufacturing process. Temperature gradient and solidification growth velocity obtained from finite element simulation are incorporated to the phase field model as the initial boundary conditions. The effects of cooling rate and temperature gradient on microstructures are investigated through simulation. Finally, the simulation results are compared with experimental findings.

62.prez_name: Selective Laser Melting of Tungsten Heavy Alloys
62.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
62.prez_authors: Aljaz  Ivekovic, Kim  Vanmeensel, Jef  Vleugels, Jean-Pierre  Kruth
62.prez_abstract: Selective laser melting (SLM) was used to fabricate different W-Ni-Fe tungsten heavy alloy grades (Ni:Fe=7:3). Microstructural development and the resulting texture in the finished parts was evaluated with respect to the Ni and Fe content, initial powder characteristics, process parameters (laser power, scanning speed, hatch spacing) and the used scanning strategy. The effect of Ta alloying (W5Ta7Ni3Fe) on grain refinement and strength was also investigated. To obtain full densification, a sufficient energy density has to be provided to melt the tungsten particles as the amount of the liquid phase forming elements is not sufficient to densify the material only by liquid phase sintering. Due to the rapid solidification during cooling, a dendritic microstructure of tungsten in γ-phase, as well as increased contiguity of W grains was observed. To obtain the desired microstructure and properties, a post-process heat treatment was required.

63.prez_name: Selective Reinforcement of Aerospace Structures Using Ultrasonic Additive Manufacturing
63.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
63.prez_authors: Adam Jacob Hehr, Justin  Wenning, Mark  Norfolk, John  Sheridan, Marcia  Domack
63.prez_abstract: Ultrasonic Additive Manufacturing (UAM), a rather new three-dimensional (3D) printing technology, uses ultrasonic energy to produce metallurgical bonds between layers of metal foils near room temperature.  This low temperature attribute of the process enables joining of dissimilar metals and materials which are constrained through production, e.g., a temperature sensitive product limited in thickness and width.  This study describes creating 3D structures with UAM and a light-weight metal matrix composite material called MetPreg for selective reinforcement applications.  Tensile testing and modeling of MetPreg composites made with UAM is described in detail.  Optical microscopy and computed tomography (CT) scans of composites, which inform the modeling and testing efforts, are also presented.

64.prez_name: Structural Integration of Sensors / Actuators by Laser Beam Melting for Tailored Smart Components
64.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
64.prez_authors: Thomas  Toeppel, Holger  Lausch, Michael  Arnold, Michael  Brand, Eric  Hensel
64.prez_abstract: Laser Beam Melting (LBM), an additive laser powder bed fusion technology, enables the structural integration of temperature-sensitive sensors and actuators in complex monolithic metallic structures. The objective is to embed a functional component inside a metal part without losing its functionality by overheating. The first part of this paper addressed the development of a new process chain for bonded embedding of temperature-sensitive sensor/actuator systems by LBM. These systems are modularly built and coated by a thermal-shielding multi-material / multi-layer protection system from ceramic and metallic compounds. The characteristic of low global heat input in LBM is utilized for the functional embedding. In the second part the specific functional design and optimization for tailored smart components with embedded functionalities are addressed. FEA and experimental validated results are demonstrated on a smart femoral hip stem.

65.prez_name: Thermomechanical Characterization of 3D Printed Epoxy Nanocomposites
65.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
65.prez_abstract: Recent work has demonstrated great potential for 3D printing of thermoset polymer-based composite materials using direct ink writing (DIW). In this process a viscoelastic feedstock material is deposited via extrusion to “write” components in a layer-by-layer process. The potential use of thermoset or reactive polymer-based feedstock materials is attractive because physical crosslinks can form between deposited layers to drastically increase interlayer strength compared to the thermoplastic polymers that are used in fused filament fabrication (FFF). The flow fields in extrusion-based deposition are known to preferentially align high aspect ratio filler materials (e.g. carbon fibers), but the effects of deposition on nanoscale fillers (e.g. nanoclay, carbon nanotubes, etc.), and the resulting effects on thermomechanical properties of printed composites has not been studied in depth. In this work, we investigate the effects of such filler materials on rheology of the feedstock and the deposition behavior, as well as the resulting thermomechanical properties and anisotropy in printed composites as characterized by flexural testing, dynamic mechanical analysis (DMA), and cross-polarized light microscopy.

66.prez_name: Tunability via Field-assisted Printing of Magnetic-mechanoluminescent Nanofibers
66.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Composites and Complex Materials II
66.prez_authors: Madhuparna  Roy, Jolie Breaux Frketic, Geoffrey   Strouse, Subramanian  Ramakrishnan, Larry  Holmes, Tarik  Dickens
66.prez_abstract: Reinforced composites have advanced mechanical properties in the direction of the fiber orientation. However, damage detection at the fiber level remains underexplored, especially for additively manufactured composites. The phenomenon of mechanoluminescence (ML) has promise to indicate microstructural failure and damage propagation in engineering materials. These materials allow piezoelectrification during structural deformation resulting in elastico-, plastico-, and fracto-luminescence. This paper discusses the relationship between multi-phase prints where fiber orientation can be manipulated in-process, and the stress-to-ML experienced by the fibers dictate the spatial-luminescent response. Multifunctional nanofibers composed of magnetic nanowires used as reinforcement allows for fiber orientation manipulation, while a mechanoluminescent doping on these fibers emit light on fracture. Thermoset polymer matrices were chosen for their range of viscosities allowing for printability and easy fiber orientation.  Mechanical tests, detection of dynamic response and fractography on the printed composites will validate the performance of the composite allowing microstructure tunability for multifunctional performance.

94.prez_name: A-10: On the Microstructure of Alloy 625 Produced by Laser AM
94.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
94.prez_authors: Cilene  Medeiro, André Luiz  Pinto, Guillermo   Solórzano
94.prez_abstract: The additive manufacturing (AM) technique is based on layer-by-layer growth, by fusing thin layers of loose powder with a scanning laser beam, for constructing three-dimensional (3D) shaped objects. This study reported the investigation on an AM produced alloy 625 sample. Alloy 625 is a solid-solution and precipitation strengthened nickel-base alloy. This alloy is extensively used in industrial applications that require a combination of excellent creep and high corrosion resistance at temperatures below 800 °C. This investigation focused on the microstructure evolution of alloy 625 in different steps from an alloy powder and an AM produced sample. SEM and TEM/STEM observations show that this process yields to columnar grains parallel to the direction of the piece growth with inter granular precipitation. EDS and morphological analyzes indicate the presence of MC carbide and Laves phase. Inside those columnar grains a fine γ '' precipitation is also observed.

95.prez_name: A-11: Vavadium-titanomagnetite Phase Change Process before Sintering Equilibrium
95.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
95.prez_abstract: The effect of TiO2 content on the vavadium-titanomagnetite sinter from 1763 K to 293 K under argon atmosphere was simulated and calculated using FactSage 6.3. Two phases, Fe-Spinel and Fe-Melilite, were predicted to be generated during the cooling process. Phase changes process were also observed using a confocal laser scanning microscope (CSLM). The results showed that the primary phase was Fe-Spinel. In addition, with the increase in TiO2 content in the sinter, the melting point increased, while the liquid phase decreased. The sinters after cooling were analyzed with a scanning electron microscope(SEM) and the result showed that the white phases were primarily composed of Fe-Spinel, while the greyish-white phases and grey phases were composed of Calcium Ferrite and Fe-Melilite, respectively. The other homogeneous phase is assumed to be the glass phase.

96.prez_name: A-7: Analysis of How Post Processing Affects the Material Properties and Microstructure of Components Built Using Laser Rapid Manufacturing
96.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
96.prez_abstract: This study evaluated the effect of different post processing techniques on the microstructure, static tensile, and fatigue properties of Ti-6AL-4V ELI parts produced by laser rapid manufacturing (LRM). Mechanical test coupons were printed, subjected to either annealing or hot isostatic pressing (HIP), and tested according to ASTM standards. As-built (no post processing) coupons were tested as controls. As-built coupons exhibited martensitic microstructure, resulting in low elongation with high yield and ultimate strength relative to ASTM F136. All samples from this group failed in fatigue. The post processed coupons exhibited a Widmanstatten alpha-beta structure which resulted in mechanical properties more consistent with ASTM F136.  The HIP’d group exhibited consolidation of internal defects and had a higher median fatigue strength than the annealed group.  Results demonstrated that as-built LRM Ti-6Al-4V ELI parts typically have low elongation and fatigue strength, and these properties can be improved through post processing.

97.prez_name: A-8: Experimental Research on Solidification of Duplex Stainless Steel Refined by Complex-nucleus with TiN
97.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
97.prez_authors: Zongxu  Pang, Rong  Zhu, Tu  Kailu
97.prez_abstract: Through slag-steel reaction balance experiment of 2205 duplex stainless steel, inclusion of MgO-Al2O3 binary system solid solution in different proportion of slag was obtained. After reaching an equilibrium, 0.05% of Ti was added into steel and complex inclusion with “MgO-Al2O3 solid solution + TiN” was obtained. After water quenching, the inclusions were studied by electronic microscope analysis, the sample was electrolyzed by oxalic acid with mass fraction of 10%. The grain morphology and size were compared with those of casting structure δ ferrite without Ti. The results of experiments showed that precipitation quantity TiN increased with the increase of Al2O3 in MgO-Al2O3 solid solution, and the grain of casting δ ferrite could be refined obviously.

98.prez_name: A-9: Manufacturing of Titanium Porous Layers by LENS Method
98.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
98.prez_authors: Tomasz  Durejko, Magdalena   Łazińska, Justyna  Aniszewska, Paweł  Jóźwik
98.prez_abstract: The titanium based alloys are very attractive materials for medical application, including orthopedic area. One of the most popular Ti alloys is Ti6Al4V used inter alia on cementless hip implants. Their surface layer should be characterized mainly by high grade of development and porosity of 35-43%. In the present work, the LENS additive manufacturing method have been applied to produce titanium porous structures dedicated for biomedical applications. Additionally, the Ti layer by microplasma spraying method was fabricated as a reference sample. The microstructural analysis were carried out by a light optical microscopy and scanning electron microscopy. The surface texture and integrity of the deposited layers were measured by profilometer and µCT scan, respectively. The chemical and phase homogeneity after laser deposition (especially in interface region) was analyzed using an energy dispersive X-ray spectrometer coupled with SEM.

99.prez_name: A Comparative Study of Solidification Microstructure of Electron Beam and Laser Melted Powder Mixtures of Ni and Sn
99.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
99.prez_authors: Jianrong  Gao, Rijie  Zhao, Yeqing  Wang, Jerry  Guo, Brant  Wu
99.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing using laser or electron beams involves nonequilibrium solidification of millimeter-sized pools at high cooling rates. An understanding of microstructure formation in this non-equilibrium solidification process is of great importance to improvement of mechanical properties of additively manufactured products. In this work, mixed powders of pure Ni and Sn with nominal near-eutectic bulk compositions were in-situ alloyed using a laser and an electron beam. The alloyed material was characterized by means of scanning electron microscopy. A banded microstructure was observed in the alloyed material under given alloying conditions. The formation of such a microstructure was attributed to competitive growth of different morphologies in non-equilibrium solidification.

100.prez_name: Additive Manufacturing of 316L Stainless Steel Using Electron Beam Melting Technology
100.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
100.prez_abstract: Today, Additive Manufacturing (AM) is being accepted as a mainstream manufacturing process. 316L stainless steel (SS) has been one of the early adopted materials in AM due to its wide application base in oil and gas, marine, food, pharmaceutical, nuclear and medical industries. However, most of the development work in powder bed AM processes has been restricted to laser systems. The electron beam melting process has some unique features that makes it an attractive technology when it comes to processing speeds and part quantities for production. Given the potential multi-market impact, EWI has created a four-phase approach for development of 316L SS. It comprises of powder characterization, material parameter development, build sample analysis and mechanical property testing. In this work, a detailed study was performed to understand the material’s behavior in the EBM system and the ability to successfully produce fully-dense parts.

101.prez_name: Additive Manufacturing of CoFe-based Magnetostrictive Materials Using the LENS System
101.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
101.prez_authors: Nicholas J. Jones, Jin-Hyeong  Yoo, Tomoko  Sano, Ryan  Ott
101.prez_abstract: Magnetostrictive materials are materials that exhibit a strain in the presence of a magnetic field. They can function as both passive and active components of a structure, allowing the user to both sense the local environment and actively respond to it. Rods of Co<SUB>75.8</SUB>Fe<SUB>24.2</SUB> and Co<SUB>63.7</SUB>Fe<SUB>36.3</SUB> have been fabricated using the Laser Engineered Net Shaping (LENS) system to evaluate the performance of additive manufactured magnetic and magnetostrictive materials. Strain has been measured under various compressive stresses as a function of applied magnetic field. Micro-computed tomography has been used to evaluate the internal quality of the sample, and serial sectioning electron back scattered diffraction (EBSD) has been used to link the performance to crystallographic orientation. To determine the effect of composition on the magnetostriction of Fe-Co alloys, small pillars of various compositions have also been fabricated, and the magnetostrictive and magnetic performance will be presented as a function of composition.

102.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
102.prez_authors: Paul S Korinko, Matthew  Van Swol, Alexander   Hollingshad, Haley   McKee, Frederick  List, Keith  Carver
102.prez_abstract:
SRNL has been developing a unique heat exchanger application that is designated for hydrogen isotope purification.  The design has undergone several iterations with the final one being printed on a selective laser melting system out of Type 316L stainless steel.  The build volume included samples for testing various materials and process characteristics.  The characterization portfolio included metallographic examination, powder characterization, tensile mechanical properties, burst testing and prototypic testing.  These samples were harvested from either the sacrificial components or the actual component.  The parts have been characterized and the results of the testing will be described in this presentation.  
This document was prepared for the U.S. Department of Energy under contract number DE-AC09-08SR22470.

103.prez_name: Analysis of Solidification Parameters in Additively Manufactured 304L Stainless Steel
103.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
103.prez_authors: Bineh  Ndefru, George T. Gray, Saryu  J. Fensin, Cameron M. Knapp
103.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing is being explored as an alternative processing technique to not only create complex geometries but also for quick repair purposes. However, there is currently no broadly accepted “ASTM- or DIN-type” additive manufacturing certification process or AM-produced material specifications. In order for this process to be adopted widely, it is important to understand the effect of various parameters used during the additive manufacturing of a part on its microstructure and eventually properties. In this work, we systematically explore the effect of solidification parameters like laser power and deposition on the microstructure of 304L SS. Preliminary results from optical and electron back scatter diffraction indicates a strong dependence on processing parameters and powder quality for solidification and obtaining a fully dense material.

104.prez_name: Build Rate Improvement for Powder Bed Fusion
104.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
104.prez_abstract: Powder bed fusion is a promising manufacturing process but faces the challenge of the slow production. The volumetric build rate is the product of scanning speed, hatch spacing, and layer thickness. The default conditions provided by the vendor are conservative, apparently to avoid lack-of-fusion porosity. In the authors’ previous research, a conceptually simple geometric model was developed to predict the volume fraction of lack-of-fusion porosity. In this work, the model was experimentally validated by printing AlSi10Mg parts in an EOS M280 with different combinations of parameters. The volume fraction of residual voids in the products was quantified by the Archimedes method and automatic feature analysis with a scanning electron microscope (SEM). Results show that the geometric model successfully predicts the residual porosity in the AlSi10Mg parts. Relative to the default conditions suggested by the vendor, revised processing parameters offer at least 50% higher volumetric build rate without causing lack-of-fusion porosity.

105.prez_name: Characterisation of Additively Manufactured 316L Stainless Steel Crystal Structure
105.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
105.prez_authors: Maija  Nyström, Jorma  Roine, Hannu  Heikkinen, Antti  Pörhönen, Olli  Nyrhilä
105.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing (AM) of metal materials utilises laser beam to selectively melt powder layer by layer. This technique enables rapid production of three-dimensional parts with a high level of precision and freedom in design. During the sintering process, the metal powder is exposed to an intensive and highly localized peak of thermal energy, and therefore the melting and cooling cycles are considerably fast. The solidification process mainly determines the microstructure and mechanical properties of the final parts. The thermal history varies across the different regions of the built part, and in this sense the final piece is non-uniform. In the present study, the surfaces of additively manufactured 316L stainless steel samples were studied by X-ray diffraction.

106.prez_name: Characterization of 316L Lattice Structures Fabricated via Electron Beam Melting
106.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
106.prez_authors: Stefan  Roos, Lars-Erik  Rännar, Andrey  Koptyug, Jonas  Danvind
106.prez_abstract: One of the promising application areas of additive manufacturing (AM) relates to light weight structures, including complex near net shape geometries and lattices. So far one of the limiting factors hampering wider industrial usage of AM technologies is the limited availability of processed materials. The aim of present study was to expand the previous success in electron beam melting (EBM®) manufacturing of 316L bulk materials into thinner lattice structures thus further widening the application areas available for the method. Present paper reports on the initial results where lattice structures with octagonal basic cells were manufactured using EBM® and characterized using microscopy and compression testing.

107.prez_name: Characterization of Additively Manufactured 316L Stainless Steel for Naval Applications
107.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
107.prez_authors: Lily  Nguyen, Richard  Fonda, David  Rowenhorst
107.prez_abstract: 316L stainless steel is used in many Naval applications, including bracket fasteners and valve bodies. Many parts have a custom configuration, typically making repair and replacement difficult and expensive. Additive manufacturing (AM) promises to greatly reduce the cost and time for their replacement. However, many of our predictive models of material performance are based on our knowledge of the microstructure and properties of conventionally processed 316L. We require new robust models of AM built 316L. In this presentation, we will show that the powder bed fusion process creates a highly complex microstructure unlike that of conventionally manufactured 316L. We will use 3D x-ray tomography to analyze the pore structure along with a combination of conventional EBSD and large-scale 3D serial sectioning with EBSD to analyze the grain structures which can range from long and columnar to small and equiaxed. Specifically, the grain boundary character and grain morphology will be explored.

108.prez_name: Characterization of Deformation-induced Phase Transformation and Mechanical Properties of Additively Manufactured Stainless Steel
108.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
108.prez_abstract: The effect of chemistry, including initial powder chemistry and spatial chemical variation, on strain-induced martensitic phase transformation in additively manufactured 304L austenitic stainless steels was studied.   The powder chemistry was varied by mixing pre-alloyed 304L stainless steel powder with Fe powder to decrease the weight fraction of austenite stabilizing elements, which resulted in an increase in the propensity for strain-induced martensitic transformation.  The chemistry also varied spatially due to the vaporization of volatile elements during deposition, including austenite stabilizing elements Cr, Ni, and Mn.  The activation of the austenite-to-martensite phase transformation, due to chemical variations, increased the ultimate tensile strength and elongation over pure additively manufactured 304L stainless steel.  A martensitic transformation kinetics equation will be presented to describe martensite volume fraction as a function of plastic strain and chemistry for additively manufactured 304L stainless steel.

109.prez_name: Characterization of Novel Lattice Structures Formed through Additive Manufacturing with Aluminum, Titanium, and Magnesium Alloys
109.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
109.prez_abstract: The additive manufacturing process allows formation of complex structures that can be difficult or impossible to fabricate using conventional machining techniques.  Lattice structures are an example of a complex structure that can be fabricated through additive manufacturing and integrated within a component to reduce weight while maintaining structural requirements.  Aluminum, titanium, and magnesium alloys are lightweight and have desirable mechanical properties for use in many aerospace and defense applications.  In this study, powder bed fusion laser additive manufacturing was used to synthesize lattice structures with aluminum, titanium, and magnesium alloys.   Various types of lattice structures were fabricated, and the influence of lattice structure, strut diameter, and process parameters were investigated.  Lattice structures were characterized using pycnometry, microscopy, and mechanical testing to evaluate microstructural and mechanical properties.  The influence of post-processing techniques, such as hot isostatic pressing, was also evaluated.

110.prez_name: Characterization of Precipitation Hardening 13-8 Stainless Steel Fabricated with Hybrid-DED Manufacturing
110.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
110.prez_authors: Michael  Juhasz, Jason  Walker, Brett  Conner
110.prez_abstract: This research investigates the effect of laser processing parameters and in-envelope CNC milling during fabrication of precipitation hardening Fe13Cr8Ni stainless steel (PH 13-8 SS) with blown powder directed energy deposition (DED). While additive manufacturing (AM), and hybrid-DED in particular, offers many advantages in creating or repairing complex parts, the unique processing conditions involved result in microstructures unlike those in traditionally produced components. Here, a parametric study was designed to explicate the relationships between processing parameters (laser power, scan velocity, and powder feed rate), in situ milling operations, and part outcome (microstructure and mechanical properties). All of the test coupons were produced using a Hybrid Manufacturing Technologies AMBIT DED system retrofitted to a Haas VF3 machining center. Traditionally produced PH 13-8 SS samples with varying levels of heat treatment are used as controls. This presentation will cover processing parameter development, optimization, and demonstration that will advance state-of-the-art applications in aerospace manufacturing.

111.prez_name: Comparisons between 316L Stainless Steel Made Using Multiple Laser Powder Bed Fusion Systems
111.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
111.prez_abstract: Metal powder bed fusion (PBF) additive manufacturing (AM) systems fabricate material layer-by-layer using an energy source that selectively melts or sinters raw powder feedstock. There are multiple original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) for PBF systems and each OEM utilizes its own unique software, system controls, processing parameter options, etc. that can result in material and mechanical variation. This project focuses on the results from using three different OEM PBF systems to fabricate 316L austenitic stainless steel; the purpose is understanding variability when a reasonable attempt is made to maintain consistency between build files and using OEM recommended system processing parameters and raw materials. Results include powder feedstock characterization, mechanical and corrosion testing, and microstructural feature comparisons between fabricated coupons from each system.

112.prez_name: Compositional and Processing Effects in Ti-alloys for Additive Manufacturing Technologies
112.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
112.prez_authors: Michael Y Mendoza, Peyman  Samimi, Matthew  Rolchigo, Richard  Lesar, Peter  Collins
112.prez_abstract: Microstructural control of additively manufactured titanium alloys would allow for manipulation of their properties. The microstructure can be controlled via a change in the composition and processing parameters. In this research effort, a binary compositionally graded titanium specimen (Ti-xMo  0≤x≤10 wt%) was produced via LENS™ technology to assess the effects of composition on the microstructure of additively manufactured titanium. In addition, a set of single composition binary and ternary titanium alloys (e.g. Ti-15Mo-0.5Si and Ti-15Mo-0.25B) were produced via LENS™ to investigate the influence of processing parameters (e.g. heat source power and scan speed), represented by the energy density term. The samples were analyzed to systematically observe the variation of different aspects such as unmelted particles, porosity and grain size, as a function of composition and processing parameters.

113.prez_name: Creep Response of Post-processed Electron-beam-melted Inconel 718 at 650°C and 580/600 MPa
113.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
113.prez_authors: Alfred Ogola Okello, Ryan  Dehoff, Michael  Kirka, Kinga  Unocic
113.prez_abstract: Inconel 718 is the most widely used Ni-based superalloy in the aerospace industry due to its favorable properties in corrosion and oxidation resistance, and high-temperature creep strength. In this work, a build was fabricated by additive manufacturing via electron beam melting (EBM) to study the effects of microstructure (equiaxed/columnar grains) and loading direction (longitudinal/transverse) on creep deformation of EBM Inconel 718 at 650°C and 580 MPa/600MPa. Observed deformation rates of EBM Inconel 718 are comparable to conventional material, with creep lifetimes in agreement with literature data. The equiaxed material exhibited low ductility (2%) and short creep lifetimes (800 h), whereas longer times (~4500 h) and high ductility (up to 23%) were observed for the columnar material. The high stress components (>14) observed reflect resistance to dislocation motion by γ” particles during creep. This deformation occurring in the grain interiors is accommodated by grain boundary sliding as intergranular fracture takes place.

114.prez_name: Decomposition of α’ Martensite of Ti-6Al-4V Alloy during Electron Beam Melting
114.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
114.prez_authors: Kenta  Yamanaka, Manami  Mori, Yusuke  Onuki, Shigeo  Sato, Akihiko  Chiba
114.prez_abstract: The microstructural evolution of a Ti-6Al-4V alloy during the additive manufacturing process of electron beam melting (EBM) was investigated using advanced characterization techniques. The initially formed α’ martensite was tempered due to the high process temperature. However, X-ray diffraction line-profile analysis revealed a relatively high dislocation density (in the order of 10^14 1/m^2), which showed no significant variation along the build direction. The film-like β phase precipitation occurred simultaneously at the interfaces of the α’ martensite laths. We successfully revealed that the β phase fraction decreased from 3.1% to 1.9% with increasing the specimen height using Rietveld texture analysis based on neutron diffraction measurements at the iMATERIA (BL20) in J-PARC, Japan. It was also found with this technique that the β phase precipitated in the α’-martensite matrix in accordance with the Burgers orientation relationship. These findings would provide a deeper understanding on the structure-property relationship of EBM-built materials.

115.prez_name: Determination of Residual Stresses in Additively Manufactured Parts Using Deep Hole Drilling, X-ray Diffraction and Synchrotron Diffraction
115.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
115.prez_authors: Florian  Brenne, Arnaud  Magnier, Sebastian  Degener, Behzad  Aminforoughi, Wolfgang  Zinn, Manuela  Klaus, Christoph  Genzel, Thomas  Niendorf
115.prez_abstract: Due to their unique processing conditions, additive manufacturing techniques lead to complex stress states in the parts produced. These are critical as warpage or crack formation can occur already during manufacturing, resulting in process instabilities or defective parts. Furthermore, residual stresses eventually determine the part performance, especially under cyclic loading. Thus, a profound understanding of residual stress formation is vital for robust application. However, applicability of established methods for straightforward determination of residual stresses is questionable, as the microstructural characteristics of additively manufactured materials differ from those of conventionally processed materials. In this study deep hole drilling, x-ray diffraction and synchrotron diffraction were employed for determination of residual stresses in Inconel 718. The material was processed using exposure parameters resulting in distinct microstructural conditions and residual stress states. The outcomes of the different measuring techniques are compared and challenges in determination of residual stresses are highlighted.

116.prez_name: Development of Novel Alloys for Additive Manufacturing Applications
116.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
116.prez_authors: David  Heard, Lynne  Karabin, Jen  Lin, Yijia  Gu, Andreas  Kulovits
116.prez_abstract: The design of novel alloys for use within additive manufacturing (AM) processes has enabled high performance components with unique physical and mechanical properties.  Arconic has developed unique aluminum alloys for AM applications which offer significant benefits over traditionally available materials.  This talk will include a metallurgical assessment of new aluminum-based alloys designed specifically for AM processing routes, including microstructure, elevated temperature tensile, creep and fatigue results.  Case studies will be presented to demonstrate how these products offer original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) the ability to reduce component weight, while improving performance.

117.prez_name: Effect of Build Parameters on Microstructure of Stainless Steel Laser Additive Manufactured Components
117.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
117.prez_authors: Penn  Rawn, Steven Thomas Keckler, Ronda  Coguill, K.V.  Sudhakar, Bruce  Madigan
117.prez_abstract: In recent years laser additive manufacturing (LAM) has seen much development as it increasingly becomes a viable manufacturing option. Due to the youth of this technology it is critical to expand the base of information available on the effect that build parameters have on final components. 316L stainless steel was selected for investigation on the effects that the global energy density (GED) and build orientation has on microstructure.  By varying the build parameters significant modification of the microstructure has been observed. Initial results indicate that an increase of GED leads to a finer grained microstructure and increased densification.

118.prez_name: Effect of Geometry on Grain Structure for a Custom High Gamma Prime Ni-alloy Processed by EBM AM
118.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
118.prez_authors: Curtis Lee Frederick, Edwin  Schwalbach, Michael  Kirka, Alex  Plotkowski, Suresh  Babu
118.prez_abstract: Research on Electron Beam Melting Additive Manufacturing (EBM AM) of Nickel based superalloys is currently focused on using existing alloys (e.g. Inconel 718). The primary goals of most research in this area are to develop process parameters that produce porosity free cuboidal shapes and to map the resulting grain structure. The effects of complex geometries (thin walls vs bulk parts) on the formation of grain texture for these developed process parameters is being ignored. To study this and push the use of EBM AM further a custom high gamma prime alloy was chosen using a Columnar to Equiaxed Transition (CET) model. The alloy was built using an Aram A2 with a reduced build chamber and three geometries of varied complexity were used (cuboidal, solid right triangular prism, thin walled right triangular prism).  The resulting effects from geometry and scan strategy on microstructure will be presented.

119.prez_name: Effect of Microstructure on Anisotropic Ductility in Additively Manufactured Metallic Materials
119.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
119.prez_authors: Allison M. Beese, Zhuqing  Wang, Alexander  Wilson-Heid
119.prez_abstract: The complex thermal cycles experienced by metals in additive manufacturing (AM) result in anisotropic microstructures.  In both titanium and stainless steel alloys, this anisotropic microstructure consists of columnar grains and often internal porosity.  Most detrimental to mechanical properties of components made by AM is sharp lack-of-fusion porosity.  In this talk, we will present results on Ti-6Al-4V and an austenitic stainless steel deposited using laser-based additive manufacturing with powder feedstock.  We will present characterization and mechanical testing used to link the anisotropic microstructure in these materials to the resulting anisotropic ductility behavior.

120.prez_name: Effect of Processing Parameters on the Properties of Inconel 718 Manufactured by Direct Metal Laser Sintering
120.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
120.prez_authors: Grace  Vanessa  De Leon Nope, Diego  German Espinosa-Arbelaez, Jorge   Corona, Juan  Muñoz-Saldaña, Luis Gerardo  Trapaga Martinez, Juan M Alvarado-Orozco
120.prez_abstract: Inconel 718-(IN718) is the most used Ni-based superalloy in aeronautic applications due to its outstanding mechanical properties at high temperatures and thus fabrication of different parts by additive manufacturing (AM). For an industrial implementation, a better understanding and control of the processing and post-processing parameters in AM are strongly required. Direct Melting Laser Sintering-DMLS) has become a promising technology for manufacture and re-manufacture due to its flexibility to fabricate complex geometries. However, the use of DMLS in the aeronautics is still restricted to parts without high mechanical requirements. To extend this knowledge, this study is focused on the Process-Structure-Properties Relationship of IN718. Structural, chemical and mechanical characterizations were performed on DMLS-manufactured IN718 specimens, with the aim to investigate the effect of feedstock properties, sintering pattern, and the volumetric energy density on the microstructure, porosity and thermo-mechanical properties including: tensile strength and fatigue resistance at temperatures from 427 to 1200°C.

121.prez_name: Effect of Processing Variables on Porosity Formation in Laser Power-bed Additive Manufacturing of Ti-6Al-4V
121.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
121.prez_authors: Sneha Prabha Narra, Ross  Cunningham, Colt  Montgomery, Anthony  Rollett, Jack L. Beuth
121.prez_abstract: The porosity observed in additively manufactured (AM) parts is a concern for components designed to undergo high-cycle fatigue. Laser powder-bed AM Ti-6Al-4V samples are fabricated over a range of processing conditions to investigate the effects of processing parameters on porosity.  Process mapping techniques are used to control melt pool size and the minimum depth of melt pool overlap.  Synchrotron-based X-ray microtomography is performed on the specimens and also on the powder to measure porosity within the powder that may transfer to the samples.  Clear connections between processing parameters and resulting porosity formation mechanisms are observed.  Cases with essentially no porosity are identified.

122.prez_name: Effects of Argon-nitrogen Shielding Gas Mixtures on Ferrite-austenite Phase Balance of Additively Manufactured 2205 Duplex Stainless Steel
122.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
122.prez_abstract: Duplex stainless steel (DSS) offers improved performance over traditional austenitic or ferritic stainless steels due to the balance between austenite and ferrite. The rapid melting and solidification, inherent to additive manufacturing (AM), presents challenges to the formation of a desirable DSS microstructures due to the potential for precipitation of intermetallic phases and imbalances in the austenite to ferrite phase ratio. Using a laser based directed energy deposition (DED) AM process, 2205 DSS material demonstrated an as-deposited microstructure comprised of nearly equal amounts of ferrite and austenite, quantified using x-ray diffraction and verified by image analysis.  Increases in build height showed increasing austenite levels and changes in austenite morphology.  By adding nitrogen to the shielding gas, the phase quantification analyses also showed increasing levels of austenite. Additional characterization tools, including electron backscatter diffraction (EBSD), were used to analyze the ferrite and austenite phases, providing insight to the mechanisms of ferrite/austenite transformations.

123.prez_name: Effects of Process Parameters in Laser Metal Deposition on Inclusion Evolution in Stainless Steel 316L
123.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
123.prez_abstract: With the increasing demands for application of laser metal deposition methods in manufacturing and repairing large-scale parts, controlling the melting and solidification process becomes more important. Especially during the process without chamber system, melt pool oxidation and inclusion formation are unavoidable. In this study, in order to investigate the influence of process parameters such as scan speed and laser power on melt pool oxidation, bulk samples were deposited on substrate using stainless steel 316L powders. Due to oxidation, sub-micron size Si-Cr-Mn oxide inclusion could be observed along inter-dendritic boundary. For a better understanding of oxidation kinetics and inclusion evolution mechanism, number density and size distribution of the oxide inclusions were characterized by SEM image analysis. Increase of melt pool temperature resulted in the increase of oxygen content, and inclusion area fraction. Also, inclusion size was found to be closely related to solidification speed and oxygen solubility limit of melt pool.

124.prez_name: Experimental and Numerical Study of Additive Manufactured Stain-less Steel Lattice Structures
124.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
124.prez_authors: Alexander  Taube, Wadim  Reschetnik, Kay-Peter  Hoyer, Gunter   Kullmer, Mirko  Schaper
124.prez_abstract: Selective Laser Melting (SLM), as an additive manufacturing technology, is particularly suited for the production of complex, cellular lightweight structures, due to the high geometric design freedom. In the context of cellular structures, SLM enables a local design adaption regarding the loading conditions. A detailed understanding of the mechanical behavior of lattice structures is essential for utilizing these high potential parts. Therefore, experimental and numerical investigations of different types of lattice structures (stainless steel 316L) are addressed in this study. Digital Image Correlation (DIC) was conducted for detailed analysis of the local strain distribution during the deformation. Electron Backscatter Diffraction (EBSD) analysis, as well as scanning electron microscopy (SEM), were carried out to characterize the microstructural properties and the surface quality of the specimens. In order to decrease computing effort, a Finite-Element Method (FEM) model was developed. Finally, both methods, the experimental procedure and the numerical simulation reveal good correlations.

125.prez_name: Fabrication of Fe-based Bulk Metallic Glass via Direct Metal Laser Sintering
125.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
125.prez_authors: Zaynab  Mahbooba, Lena  Thorsson, Mattias   Unosson, Timothy  Horn, Ola  Harrysson
125.prez_abstract: Bulk metallic glasses are among the strongest engineering materials known today.  Fe-based BMGs are of increasing research interest due to their superior mechanical, magnetic and chemical properties, and low manufacturing cost.  Existing manufacturing techniques limit thickness and geometry of BMGs.  This work examines the use of direct metal laser sintering to produce an Fe-based BMG.  Alloys fabricated using the EOSINT M 280 exceed the critical casting thickness of the BMG by greater than 15 times in all dimensions.   Resulting chemical, magnetic and mechanical properties are reported.  Despite decreasing quench effect with increasing build thickness, XRD, SEM and DSC analysis suggest that a fully amorphous structure was maintained throughout the build.  However, a low concentration of nano-grain clusters was discovered using a high resolution EBSD scan.  Opportunities for novel and unique applications of metallic glass are achievable through appropriate material design and optimization of existing AM processes.

126.prez_name: Fabrication of Large Additively Manufactured 316L Stainless Steel Structures Using Directed Energy Deposition
126.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
126.prez_abstract: The directed energy deposition (DED) Additive Manufacturing (AM) process can be scaled to produce large structures with build volumes far in excess of those commonly encountered with powder bed fusion.  When scaling to large structures, the need to increase deposition rates, suitable powder feedstock supplies, and start/restart procedures, need to be addressed.  A series of 316L stainless steel structures have been fabricated using DED AM techniques as part of the design of a next generation low pressure head hydro-turbine.  Mechanical and microstructural characterization of test specimens in the as-deposited and hot isostatically pressed (HIP) conditions for gas atomized powder feedstock showed suitable properties and microstructures. Additionally, the performance of water atomized powders were also examined and the need for tight control of the powder chemistry for controlling solidification structures has been defined.  Challenges encountered in the design and fabrication of the near net shape component are reviewed.

127.prez_name: Identifying Laser Powder Bed AM Processing Windows and their Dependence on Laser Spot Size
127.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
127.prez_abstract: Laser spot size is a geometric process variable that can alter melt pool shape, and can impact the formation of porosity form lack of powder fusion and keyholing.  In this research, experiments and modeling are performed to identify an operating window for three stainless steel alloys in laser powder bed additive manufacturing.  Nominal parameters are identified in relationship to the operating windows.  The operating windows are bordered by regions experiencing lack of fusion and keyholing porosity, but those borders are not fixed.  Results are presented demonstrating the use of laser spot size to move the boundary for keyholing to greatly increase the size of the operating window.

128.prez_name: Impact of Composition on the Properties of Additively Manufactured Inconel® 625 Using Directed Energy Deposition
128.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
128.prez_authors: Zakariya  Khayat, James  Zuback, Todd  Palmer
128.prez_abstract: Standard specifications for Inconel® 625 feedstock powders used in Additive Manufacturing (AM) allow for wide ranges of Fe (0 – 5.0 wt. %) and Si (0 – 0.5 wt. %) compositions.  It is well established that both elements contribute to the formation of undesirable Laves phases during solidification, which affects the mechanical properties of the AM fabricated component.  The impact of wide variations in both Fe and Si compositions on the properties of as-deposited and hot isostatically pressed (HIP) directed energy deposition (DED) components has been quantified.  Statistically significant differences in the static mechanical properties are observed with wide changes in Fe content from 1 wt.% to 4 wt.%. Interactions between the Fe and Si and other alloying elements and their role in promoting Laves phase formation have been investigated and generalized models for the formation of these undesirable phases have been developed.

129.prez_name: Influence of Arcam EBM Parameters on Properties in Aluminum Alloy 2024
129.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
129.prez_authors: Chris  Rock, Maria  Withrow, Tim  Horn, Harvey  West
129.prez_abstract: Aluminum 2024 is an age hardenable cast-wrought alloy with excellent strength and low weight but has been slow to be adopted in additive manufacturing processes due to material compatibility issues.  In this study Al 2024 was manufactured through electron beam melting (EBM) at a build temperature of 525C to produce dense parts. Build parameters had a noticeable influence on the chemistry, grain morphology, CuAl2 precipitation, and density of the samples. Solution studies of selected specimens were also performed and compared with wrought Al 2024 to determine the influence of EBM on CuAl2 solution and formation.

130.prez_name: Influence of Scan Velocities on Material Properties of Laser Based Coatings of Ni-Co on Ti-6Al-4V Alloy
130.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
130.prez_abstract: Laser clad Ni+Co layers were produced on Ti-6Al-4V substrates using Nd:YAG high power laser beam. The effects of laser scanning speed and volume fraction of the reinforced Ni-Co powders on clad layer formation and its properties were investigated. Laser power of 750W, beam size of 3mm with argon shield gas flow rate of 1.2l/min was made constant, while the scanning speeds were varied. The micro - structural analysis, phase constituents and hardness properties of Ni-Co intermetallics reinforced clads were also carried out. The morphology of the resultant coatings was examined using X-ray diffractometry and scanning electron microscopy. Results showed that the coatings displayed enhanced properties such as fine microstructure and good metallurgical bonding with the substrate containing minimal pores when compared with the substrate. Furthermore, the microstructure revealed the formation of various fractions of interdendritic compounds/intermeatallics dispersed within the coating matrix which could be responsible for the increased hardness obtained.

131.prez_name: Influence of Volumetric Energy Density and Temperature on Crystallographic Texture and Microscopic Defects in a 3-D Printed Stainless Steel Alloy
131.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
131.prez_authors: Hahn  Choo, Austin  Ngo, Xianghui  Xiao, Yang  Ren, Manyalibo  Matthews, Elena  Garlea
131.prez_abstract: Understanding the relationship between processing parameters and defect characteristics (e.g., porosity; size, shape, and geometrical distributions of pores and microcracks) is of fundamental and technical importance in the area of additive manufacturing of metallic alloy components.
