Another key issue related to processing-structure studies in additive manufacturing is the control of microstructure (namely grain size, morphology, and crystallographic texture) through the manipulation of thermal input during processing. Current literature, however, does not provide many examples where such microscopic and crystallographic issues were studied simultaneously and systematically. In this study, the influence of laser-beam power, scan speed, volumetric energy density, and temperature on crystallographic texture development and microscopic defect formation in a 316L stainless steel alloy produced with a 3-D laser printer was investigated using synchrotron x-ray diffraction and microtomography.

132.prez_name: Laser Metal Deposition of Ti-6Al-4V Structures: Analysis of the Build Height Dependent Microstructure and Mechanical Properties
132.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
132.prez_authors: Markus  Heilemann, Mauritz  Moeller, Claus  Emmelmann, Irmela  Burkhardt, Stefan  Riekehr, Volker  Ventzke, Nikolai  Kashaev, Josephin  Enz
132.prez_abstract: The Laser Metal Deposition (LMD) process is used to increase the productivity rate in the field of laser additive manufacturing. Large structural Ti-6Al-4V components can be manufactured resource efficiently with this approach. In contrast, conventional manufacturing processes machine up to 95% from the bulk material to produce parts for the aerospace industry. For high wall structures, the thermal boundaries vary with the building height and therefore a height dependent microstructure develops. In this paper, the mechanical properties along the build height of a wall structure are analyzed through micro-tensile specimens. In addition, these results are compared to a new approach of a building strategy by layer wise adapted process parameters. The developed approach leads to reduced shape deviation of the wall thickness and its influence on the microstructure and mechanical properties of Ti-6Al-4V is investigated in this paper.

133.prez_name: Linking Microstructure, Impact Properties and Deformation Mechanisms of Laser Powder Bed Fusion Ti-6Al-4V Parts
133.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
133.prez_authors: Joon Phil  Choi, Flavio  Silva, Mathieu  Brochu
133.prez_abstract: Laser powder bed fusion of Ti-6Al-4V parts is known to produce orientation-specific properties owing to the long columnar grain developed.  An increasing body of work demonstrating these interactions exists for static properties, but efforts must be devoted to better understand such relationships for dynamic properties. In that context, this presentation will show the linkage between the built orientation, heat treatment, impact properties and deformation mechanisms. Modeling results and experimental validation will be shown.

134.prez_name: Location Dependence of the Microstructure in Selectively Laser Melting NiTi
134.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
134.prez_authors: Brian  Franco, Ji  Ma, Gustavo  Tapia, Jun  Liu, Alaa  Elwany, Raymundo  Arroyave, Ibrahim  Karaman
134.prez_abstract: Metal parts prepared by Selective Laser Melting (SLM) undergo complex thermal histories which often result in complex microstructures. Differences in thermal history will lead to differences in microstructure, and in the current work we use a wide variety of characterization techniques at the micro- and nano-scale in order to oberve these microstructures. These include wavelength dispersive spectroscopy, energy dispersive x-ray spectroscopy, scanning electron microscopy, and transmission electron microscopy. We consider two parameter sets with identical laser power, laser speed, and layer thickness, but with different hatch spacing. We observe significant differences in the microstructures of these two cases, and show how these affect the shape memory behavior.

135.prez_name: Manufacturing TiAl Parts with Electron Beam Melting: Processing - Microstructure - Mechanical Property Relationships
135.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
135.prez_authors: Ercan  Cakmak, Peeyush  Nandwana, Yukinori  Yamamoto, Dongwon  Shin, Indrani  Sen, Thomas R Watkins, Ryan R Dehoff, Roger D England, Allen  Haynes
135.prez_abstract: Titanium aluminide alloys based on the γ-TiAl phase have been of great interest owing to their high specific strength, good strength retention and good corrosion and oxidation resistance at high temperatures. However, their brittle nature makes them hard to manufacture and machine using conventional techniques. Additive manufacturing is a promising alternative for the manufacture of complex geometries with its near net shape manufacturing capability. In this feasibility work, TiAl preforms have been manufactured using the electron beam melting technique. Mechanical testing was performed both at room and high temperature. Characterization experiments were performed to assess the constituent phases, residual stresses, microstructures and grain orientations. Effect of process conditions on the resultant microstructures and microstructure-mechanical property relations are discussed.

136.prez_name: Mechanical and Corrosion Properties of CoCrFeNiTi-based High-entropy Alloy Additive Manufactured Using Selective Laser Beam Melting
136.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
136.prez_authors: Tadashi  Fujieda, Hiroshi  Shiratori, Kosuke  Kuwabara, Kenta  Yamanaka, Yuichiro  Koizumi, Akihiko  Chiba, Seiichi  Watanabe
136.prez_abstract:
We have reported that CoCrFeNiTi-based high-entropy alloy with superior tensile strength and corrosion resistance by a combination of additive manufacturing using selective electron beam melting (SEBM) and heat treatment [1]. We could succeed in producing the high-density and homogeneous CoCrFeNiTi-based high-entropy alloy by using selective laser beam melting (SLM), which exhibited superior tensile properties and corrosion resistance without any heat treatments. I’ll discuss about the differences of microstructure and mechanical and corrosion resistance properties between the alloys fabricated by SLM and SEBM.
[1] T. Fujieda, et. al, Mater Lett, 189 (2017) 148–151.

137.prez_name: Mechanical Property and Microstructural Comparison of Additively Manufactured Titanium (Ti64) Lattices and Bulk Material
137.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
137.prez_authors: Michael  Brand, Chris   Chen, Matthew   Tucker, Mark  Miller, Peter   Quadbeck
137.prez_abstract: A method for producing metal foams are manufactured by investment casting or melt deposition by using the polyurethane foams as a precursor.  Another method for producing metal foams is by Powder Bed Fusion or Additive Manufacturing.  This work studied the comparison of tensile and compression properties of Titanium (Ti64) foams produced by investment casting starting with a polyurethane foam and Titanium foams produced on the EOS M280 additive manufacturing instrument.  The specimens were tested in two different directions (1) the loading direction perpendicular to the foaming or build direction where the cells are equiaxed (EQ direction) and (2) the loading direction parallel to the foaming and build direction where the cells are elongated (EL direction).  The results show that the compression responses for both directions are isotropy for the additive and investment casting specimens.  Results indicate that the additive manufactured specimens have higher mechanical properties than the investment casting specimens.

138.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
138.prez_authors: David L Bourell, Allison M. Beese
138.prez_abstract: Additive Manufacturing (AM) of metals poses a number of challenges currently, but the possibilities for disrupting manufacturing technology are virtually boundless.  The historical development of metal AM will be given including recent growth within the context of all AM.  Microstructural development and defects will be described.  Properties of AM metal parts will be reviewed, with an emphasis on linking the mechanical properties to microstructure. The benefits of novel feedstock compositions on AM manufacturability will be described, including an approach to produce difficult to AM process metals such as aluminum alloy 6061.

139.prez_name: Microstructural Characterization and Modeling of SLM Superalloy 718
139.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
139.prez_authors: Timothy Michael Smith, Pete  Bonacuse, Chantal K. Sudbrack
139.prez_abstract: Superalloy 718 is an excellent candidate for selective laser melting (SLM) fabrication due to a combination of excellent mechanical properties and workability. Predicting and validating the microstructure of SLM-fabricated Superalloy 718 post heat-treatment is an important step towards producing components comparable to those made using conventional methods. At present, obtaining accurate volume fraction and size measurements of gamma-double-prime, gamma-prime and delta precipitates has been challenging due to their small size, low volume fractions, and similar chemistries. A technique combining high resolution distortion corrected SEM imaging and with x-ray energy dispersive spectroscopy has been developed to accurately and independently measure the size and volume fractions of the three precipitates. These results were further validated using x-ray diffraction and phase extraction methods and compared to the precipitation kinetics predicted by PANDAT and JMatPro. Discrepancies are discussed in context of materials properties, model assumptions, sampling, and experimental errors.

140.prez_name: Microstructural Evolution and Mechanical Properties of Optomec LENS Fabricated Ti6Al4V (ELI) Alloy Components
140.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
140.prez_authors: Nana  Arthur, Hein  Moller, Annelize  Botes, Sisa  Pityana
140.prez_abstract: Cylindrical components of dimensions 15 mm in diameter and 11 mm in height were laser printed by additive manufacturing.  Process parameters used in layer by layer build-ups, viz. laser power, scanning speed and powder flow rate, were varied in order to determine their influence on the physical properties, and resulting microstructure of Ti6Al4V Extra-Low Interstitials (ELI) build-ups.  The components were manufactured using the Optomec LENS™ system and evaluation was conducted for the qualification of additively manufactured aerospace components. As a continuation from previous investigations, results of this paper will analyze the influence of developed microstructures on mechanical properties such as hardness (HV) and tensile strength of components. Test coupons for evaluation were produced employing optimized laser process parameters. Specimens consisted of laser printed cylindrical components and tensile specimens were produced and machined according to specifications contained in applicable test standards. Mechanical properties of “as-built” samples are discussed in this paper.

141.prez_name: Microstructural Evolution of Rapidly Solidified Al-Si and Al-Ge Alloys
141.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
141.prez_authors: Adam  Stokes, John  Roehling, Joseph  McKeown, Daniel  Coughlin, Amy  Clarke
141.prez_abstract: Metal additive manufacturing (AM) typically imparts localized heating and cooling that influences microstructural evolution.  During metal AM, higher cooling rates are usually encountered that produce rapidly solidified microstructures with characteristics that may differ from those observed after conventional processing (e.g. casting).  The development of solidification patterns and growth regime transitions that control morphological (and microstructural evolution) are related to experienced temperature gradients (G) and solidification velocities (R).  To move toward modeling of rapid solidification, experimental methods that exclude complexeties, such as convetion, are needed.  Here we use dynamic transmission electron microscopy (DTEM) to study two-dimensional, rapid (up to a m/s) solidification that occurs in melt pools produced by laser melting of nanocrystyalline, 100 nm-thick Al-Si and Al-Ge alloys for different solidification conditions (G and R) and growth regimes.  Post-mortem TEM and DTEM provide significant insights into the solidification dynamics and conditions that control microstructural and phase evolution.

142.prez_name: Microstructural Properties of Heat Treated LENS In-situ Additively Manufactured Titanium Aluminide
142.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
142.prez_authors: Monnamme  Tlotleng, Thabo  Lengopeng, Sisa  Pityana, Lerato  Tshabalala, Ntombi  Mathe, Bathusile  Masina
142.prez_abstract: The use of titanium aluminides (TiAl) as high temperature materials is becoming a reality now since their early research and development.  Their light weight and mechanical properties at elevated temperatures make them attractive as high temperature structured materials for the aerospace and automotive industries. Binary TiAl structures however, lack ductility at room temperature hence it is difficult to manufacture with conventional methods. This research looked into additive manufacturing of TiAl microstructure using the Laser Engineering Net Shaping (LENS) System. TiAl microstructures were produced by co-feeding the elemental powders (Ti and Al) into the laser melt-pool created on the base plate at different set laser powers. The results reported here are on TiAl microstructure that was produced with laser power of 400W. The produced samples were heat treated post manufacturing. Heat treatment led to a homogeneous structure (SEM) with increased Al content (EDS). The hardness remained the same before and after heat treatment.

143.prez_name: Microstructure and Mechanical Properties of Direct Laser Metal Deposited Inconel 718
143.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
143.prez_authors: Ajay  Bhagavatam, Abhishek   Ramakrishnan, Karthik  Adapa, Amrinder  Singh, Guru P. Dinda
143.prez_abstract: Inconel 718 gas turbine blade was fabricated layer-by-layer using direct laser metal deposition process. Metal deposition was carried out by a 1.2 KW diode laser with a circular spot diameter of 2 mm. Tensile test results revealed very low yield strength of 500 MPa with high ductility about 35%. However, post deposition heat-treatment improved the yield strength to 1115 Mpa with an elongation of 15%. Scanning electron microscopy exhibited the segregation of strengthening elements Nb, Mo and Ti in the interdendritic region, leading to laves phase (Ni,Cr,Fe)2(Nb,Mo,Ti) formation. Due to the high cooling rate of laser deposition process and very slow precipitation kinetics of gamma double-prime, as-deposited materials showed low strength due to the absence of gamma double-prime precipitates.  X-ray diffraction investigation revealed the formation of gamma double-prime (Ni3Nb) and M6(Ni, Mo, Nb)C precipitates during heat treatment that improved the strength by more than 100% compared to as-deposited state.

144.prez_name: Microstructure Control in Additive Manufacturing of Aluminum Alloys
144.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
144.prez_authors: Hunter  Martin, Brennan  Yahata, Eric  Clough, Jacob  Hundley, Tobias  Schaedler, Tresa  Pollock
144.prez_abstract: Additive Manufacturing of aluminum alloys has been limited to a select group of weldable Al-Si alloys, however many applications require materials with significantly higher strength.  Standard high strength aluminum alloys, 2000 and 7000 series, suffer from hot tearing during solidification making them unsuitable for processing in additive manufacturing.  We have developed a predictive framework to identify alloys susceptible to hot tearing and mechanisms to reduce this tendency in the unique solidification conditions during direct laser melting.  By modifying material feedstock and controlling processing parameters, the hot tear susceptibility can be reduced. In addition, the microstructure and mechanical properties of additively manufacture aluminum alloys can be optimized. Through simulations the optimum solidification path can identified and parameters are tailored to control solidification of the melt pool accordingly.  We will show that application of this process can be used to enable additive manufacturing of new high strength aluminum alloy systems.

145.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
145.prez_abstract: An overview is offered of microstructure development in metals printed from powders.  Certain properties are dominated by the defect structure, which, in this case, is dominated by voids or pores.  The density and size of pores varies markedly with power and speed. At high speed there is a transition to lack-of-fusion pores. At high power there is a transition to intermittent key-holing. In between, porosity is significantly less and inherited from the powders. Grain size is dependent primarily on cooling rate, which is closely related to the ratio of power to speed. Grain structures generally exhibit substantial orientation gradients, indicative of plastic deformation from thermal stresses. Grain morphologies can be modeled at various scales and kinetic Monte Carlo offer an efficient approach when multiple melt tracks need to be simulated.

146.prez_name: Microstructure Gradient Development in A356 AM Parts
146.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
146.prez_authors: Melissa  Trask, Shih  Chou, Mathieu  Brochu
146.prez_abstract: The solidification conditions change throughout AM part, resulting in a gradient of microstructure along geometrical features and depends on the specific geometry and the size of the feature. Using the concept, the effect of the microstructure on the mechanical behaviour can be predicted using Finite Element Analysis (FEA). This study was conducted on sample geometries manufactured using Al7SiMg powder. The features that were studied included thin walls ranging in thickness from 0.5 mm to 10 mm, cylindrical posts, ranging in diameter from 1 mm to 10 mm, and crosses of 45°, ranging in diameter from 1 mm to 10 mm. Differences in the microstructure were found between features of different thicknesses. The differences of microstructure in different geometries were more pronounced in the grain size and grain directionality, rather than the aluminum dendrite cell size. The mechanical property gradients and anisotropic behaviours were modeled and analyzed through finite element methods.

147.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
147.prez_authors: Patcharapit  Promoppatum, Shi-Chune   Yao, Austin  Gerlt, P. Chris   Pistorius, Anthony  Rollett, Richard  Martukanitz, Peter  Coutts
147.prez_abstract: Simulation of microstructure development in 3D powder bed printed IN 718 is described that is directed towards prediction of grain structure, texture and void (pore) content.  A model previously developed for the prediction of lack-of-fusion defects is applied to IN 718 and validated against experimental data. For simulation of grain structure development, the Sandia spparks kinetic Monte Carlo code is used to model multiple melt tracks in successive layers. By treating the liquid as random lattice points and varying the interface mobility according to the externally computed temperature gradient, the characteristic columnar growth pattern is obtained.  Variations in the as-solidified microstructure are then governed by the geometry of the variations in the direction of growth within the individual melt tracks.  Finally, we describe modeling the thermal history of a particular data set that was the subject of a winning entry for the Modeling Challenge for Additive Manufacturing.

148.prez_name: Microstructures and Mechanical Properties of TiAl Alloys Fabricated by Electron Beam Melting
148.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
148.prez_authors: Ken  Cho, Ryota  Kobayashi, Naohide  Morita, Masahiro  Sakata, Hiroyuki Y Yasuda, Mitsuharu  Todai, Takayoshi  Nakano, Ayako  Ikeda, Daisuke  Kondo, Yuto  Nagamachi, Minoru  Ueda, Masao  Takeyama
148.prez_abstract: The specific strengths of TiAl alloys are much higher than that of other high temperature materials such as Ni-based superalloys. Therefore, TiAl alloys have been used as new material for jet engine low-pressure turbine blades. Electron beam melting (EBM) is a new technology for additive manufacturing, which is able to fabricate metallic components with high degree of complexity. In this study, cylindrical rods of TiAl alloys were fabricated by EBM. Tensile and fatigue properties of the alloys were investigated as a parameter of an angle (θ) between the building and cylinder directions. TiAl alloys fabricated by EBM consist of duplex-like structure and coarse γ phase grains, which form a chain perpendicular to the building direction. θ=45 deg sample shows 4 times and 1.5 times higher elongation and fatigue strength, respectively than θ=0 deg sample at room temperature.

149.prez_name: Microstructures of Low-C and Medium-C Steel Hybrid Layers Additively Deposited on Cast Iron Using Directed Energy Deposition (DED) Technique
149.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
149.prez_authors: Seul Bi  Lee, Yoon Suk  Choi, Jae Hyun  Yu, Sang-Hu  Park, Do-Sik  Shim, Dae-Geun  Nam
149.prez_abstract: Multi-layers of low-C steel (AISI P21) and medium-C steel (AISI H13) powders were additively deposited on cast iron using a directed energy deposition (DED) technique. In order to understand the microstructure evolution during the multi-layer DED process, the layer-by-layer microstructural change and chemistry variation were investigated using an electron microscopy and an electron probe micro-analyzer (EPMA). In particular, the microstructure variation across the interface was intensively analyzed to understand the deposition mechanism of laser-heated low or medium C steel powders on a (high C) cast iron substrate, in which a conventional welding technique is not applicable for joining or part-repairing. Thermodynamic calculations were also utilized to understand the through-thickness microstructural change caused by the chemistry variation and heat cycles during the DED process. Experimental results will be discussed along with some suggestions to better control interfacial microstructures and properties.

150.prez_name: Optimization of Titanium Alloys for Additive Manufacturing
150.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
150.prez_authors: Brian  Welk, Hamish  Fraser, Kevin  Chaput
150.prez_abstract: Alloys currently used in additive manufacturing (AM) were not designed for the processing technique.  This has led to processing defects such as porosity, residual stress and coarse, columnar microstructures in the as-built condition.  To further exploit the use of titanium alloys in AM, and reduce or eliminate the processing defects, titanium alloys must be developed which are optimized for AM.  In this study, compositionally graded specimens were deposited using the laser engineered net shaping (LENS) technique to determine the effect of alloy additions to conventional titanium alloys (e.g. Ti64 and Ti18).  A transition from a coarse, columnar microstructure to an equiaxed microstructure was observed along the composition gradient.  Microstructure characterization and modeling were used to determine the mechanism for producing an equiaxed microstructure.  Mechanical properties of select compositions were determined.

151.prez_name: Optimized Isotropic Properties in Ti-6Al-4V Parts via Additive Manufacturing
151.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
151.prez_authors: John E Barnes, Christopher B. Aldridge, Heath  Walker
151.prez_abstract: The mechanical properties of Ti-6Al-4V have been optimized to achieve isotropic properties as well as to understand the effect of processing on mechanical behavior.  Specimens were manufactured using the powder bed fusion selective laser melting additive manufacturing (AM) process and were subjected to various melt related optimizations as well as thermal treatments.  The properties were observed to be isotropic for the X-Y and Z orientations.  Comparisons have been made to AMS specifications for castings and plate which show promising results.  This presentation will provide the results from optimized processing with some run to run variability.

152.prez_name: Origins of Anisotropic Mechanical Behavior in Additively Manufactured Ti-6Al-4V by Directed Energy Deposition
152.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
152.prez_authors: Jay S. Keist, Daudi  Waryoba, Todd A. Palmer
152.prez_abstract: As-deposited additively manufactured (AM) Ti-6Al-4V components fabricated by laser based directed energy deposition (DED) exhibited both location and orientation dependent mechanical properties.  Secondary processing by hot isostatic pressing (HIP) reduced the location dependencies but the orientation dependencies remained.  This anisotropic behavior for the mechanical properties appeared to be related to the prior-beta grain morphology.  The prior-beta grain morphology depended on such considerations as geometry, size of the component, and the dwell time between individual layer depositions.  Significant texturing was also observed by electron backscattered diffraction (EBSD) at the prior-beta grain boundary regions, and this texturing remained after HIP.  By connecting the structure of the prior beta grains and the texturing at the grain boundaries to the different processing conditions helped further understand the origins of mechanical behavior anisotropy within AM Ti-6Al-4V components.

153.prez_name: Oxidation of Ni-based Alloys Fabricated by Additive Manufacturing
153.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
153.prez_abstract:
Additive manufacturing (AM) allows for the fabrication of complex near net shape components with optimized geometries to decrease weight and cost. Thinner high temperature components may suffer from corrosion degradation, and the oxidation performance of AM alloys need to be addressed. Hastelloy X (HX, Ni-22Cr-18Fe-9Mo) fabricated by electron beam melting (EBeam) and selective laser melting (SLM) and EBeam CM247 and MAR247 were oxidation tested at 900-1000ºC in air and humid air for duration ranging from 100h to 3500h. Increased spallation rates were observed for the AM HX alloys in comparison with wrought HX because of the AM alloy specific microstructures. Low mass gains were observed for the 247 EBeam alloys but thicker oxide scales were observed locally. Strategies to improve the oxidation performance of Ni-based AM alloys will be discussed.
Research sponsored by the U.S. DOE, Office of Fossil Energy and Advanced Manufacturing Office

154.prez_name: Porosity Analysis of AM Powder Based on Machine Learning Approach and In-situ Annealing Technique for Observation of  Property Evolution of AM Material
154.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
154.prez_authors: He  Liu, Rachel  Lim, Christopher Kantzos  Kantzos, A. D.   Rollett, R. M.  Suter
154.prez_abstract: The properties of porosity within AM powder will affect the quality of final product. A 3-D segmentation and analysis method based on machine learning approach was developed to analyze the porosity and size distribution of AM powders. Powders and pores are segmented and recognized in three dimensional volume data to increase accuracy. Valuable statistical information can be extracted to evaluate the quality of AM powder. This will give a quantitative guide for the selection of AM powder for manufacturing. We are also developing the capability to perform in-situ annealing of AM (and other) materials at the Advanced Photon Source during high-energy X-ray diffraction microscopy (HEDM) measurements. This will allow measurement of  the evolution of micro-structure of AM materials. First results from this technique will be presented.

155.prez_name: Porosity Analysis via 3D Serial Sectioning for Additively Manufactured Alloy Samples
155.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
155.prez_authors: Veeraraghavan  Sundar, Satya  Ganti, Bryan  Turner
155.prez_abstract: Porosity is a typical defect in additively manufactured (AM) parts. The automation of serial sectioning provides an opportunity to better quantify porosity in three dimensions in materials. In this work, we analyzed the porosity of additively and conventionally manufactured samples using Robo-Met.3D®, an automatic serial sectioning system. The results from this 3D serial sectioning analysis were then compared to classical 2D stereological methods. We found that for these datasets, the classical 2D methods underestimated the porosity size and distributions of the larger pores; a critical attribute to fatigue behavior of the AM part. The results suggest that acquiring experimental data with equipment such as Robo-Met.3D® to measure the number and size of particles such as pores in a volume irrespective of knowing their shape is a better choice.

156.prez_name: Processing-microstructure-mechanical Property Correlation in AlSi10Mg Parts Produced Using Selective Laser Melting
156.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
156.prez_authors: Edward  Stugelmayer, Bryce  Abstetar, K.V.  Sudhakar, Ronda  Coguill, Bruce  Madigan
156.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing of metal materials is a recently burgeoning manufacturing technique that provides numerous advantages and can produce components otherwise impossible using traditional techniques. Many variables exist during processing that can cause variations in dimensional or mechanical properties. The influence of these variables must be investigated and quantified in order to improve process reliability and to better predict mechanical properties of printed parts. This research observes the effect of build orientation on the mechanical properties of AlSi10Mg parts created using selective laser melting (SLM); as well as observing changes in microstructure due to varying process parameters such as the laser power, scanning speed, and hatch spacing. AlSi10Mg specimens printed at 0°, 30°, 60°, and 90° exhibited ultimate tensile strengths ~18% higher than traditional casting alloys and yield strengths ~36% higher. Variations in processing parameters had a significant effect on microstructural features such as grain size, grain shape, voids, and porosity.

157.prez_name: Quantitative Microstructure Analysis of Inconel 718 Grain Boundary Network
157.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
157.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing (AM) is a process where digital three-dimensional design data is used to build up a component with complex geometries in layers by depositing material, and selective laser melting (SLM) is a form of AM utilizing a high-power laser beam. AM creates complex shaped pieces from powder with nearly no waste (1). However, the extreme processing can create very unique microstructure which affect material performance. With the expansion of computer-processing power and the progression of material theories at different length scales the processing of engineering materials advancing at an exponential rate. Grain boundary engineering is an effective tool used to alter the polycrystal properties by modifying the grain boundary characters and grain boundary network topology. This study focuses on establishing a connection between the extreme processing conditions of SLM, Inconel 718 with its grain boundary network characteristics.

158.prez_name: Reducing Oxygen Content during the Manufacturing of OFHC Copper Using Electron Beam Melting
158.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
158.prez_authors: John Christopher Ledford, Harvey  West, Diana  Gamzina, N. C.  Luhmann, Ilbey  Karakurt, Liwei  Lin, Tim  Horn
158.prez_abstract: Electron beam melting has recently been explored for the fabrication of complex, high power, radio frequency (RF) components which have stringent specifications.  Oxygen contamination can make or break these RF components due to its effect on their chemical and electrical properties.  In this study we examine the use of a reducing atmosphere during the electron beam melting process in the manufacturing of oxygen free high conductivity (OFHC) copper RF components.  Powder and solid chemistry samples were taken from multiple locations of the build.  A residual gas analyzer was utilized to characterize the atmosphere inside the chamber during building.

159.prez_name: Residual Stress Characterization in Additive Manufactured Powder Bed Fusion – Laser (PBF-L) Ti-6Al-4V Alloy
159.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
159.prez_authors: You  Lu, Michael A Gharghouri, Srinand  Karuppoor, Manuel  Marya
159.prez_abstract: The high cost of raw materials and processing is a major issue limiting the application of Titanium alloys in the Oil-and-Gas industry.  Powder Bed Fusion–Laser (PBF-L) is an attractive additive manufacturing process for directly producing complex parts with little material loss. One of the drawbacks of PBF-L is the high residual stress induced in components by high local energy concentration, which leads to large temperature gradients during processing.  The induced residual stress contributes to crack formation and part distortion.  Moreover, porosity developed during PBL-F adversely affects mechanical properties. In this work, neutron diffraction is used to determine the residual stress in Ti-6Al-4V resulting from PBF-L and to evaluate the effectiveness of subsequent heat-treatments and Hot Isostatic Pressing (HIP) processes for stress relief.  The results will help to optimize the PBF-L processing parameters and subsequent heat-treatments towards achieving mechanical properties comparable to those of conventional wrought alloys.

160.prez_name: Selective Laser Melting of Cu10Ni Alloys Using Gas Atomized Powders
160.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
160.prez_authors: Suraj  Jadhav, Pierre  Van Cauwenbergh, Karel  Lietaert, Jan  Van Humbeeck, Jean-Pierre  Kruth, Sasan  Dadbakhsh, Aljaz  Ivekovic, Kim  Vanmeensel
160.prez_abstract: The selective laser melting (SLM) behaviour of surface modified, in-house prepared Cu based powders is investigated. Surface modification comprised applying thin (<100 nm) metallic coatings on spherical gas-atomized (d50 ~35 µm) copper powders with a maximum oxygen content of 50 ppm. The choice of coating element was predefined by its effect on the laser absorption behaviour of the as-prepared powder bed as well as the mechanical and electrical properties of the bulk material after selective laser melting. The interrelationship between the microstructure, quasi-static mechanical properties and electrical conductivity of the SLM processed parts is investigated.

161.prez_name: Solidification and Microstructure Mapping of Rapidly Solidified Hypoeutectic Al-Si Alloys
161.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
161.prez_authors: William  Hearn, Hani  Henein, Abdoul-Aziz  Bogno, Jonas  Valloton, Mark  Gallerneault
161.prez_abstract: Understanding rapid solidification (RS) in additive manufacturing is important to define the processing/microstructure/property relationship and effect of the starting raw material. Recent research has explored the evolution of microstructure at various stages of AM and found RS greatly affects the morphology/properties. However, the conditions leading to these morphologies are not understood in a quantitative and reproducible way.  Using DSC and a novel containerless solidification technique (Impulse Atomization), hypoeutectic Al-Si alloys were produced with a wide range of cooling rates (0.1-10^6 K/s). Here microstructural and phase characterization was conducted using OM, SEM, DSC and XRD to determine the influence of cooling rate. On this basis, the solidification pathways and formed microstructures were quantified for each cooling rate, providing a critical relationship between processing/microstructure/properties that can help with the use and development of AM processes. The paper will also compare the microstructural results to those obtained by others using other RS techniques.

162.prez_name: Spatial and Temporal Laser Modulation for Microstructural Control during Laser Additive Manufacturing of Metals
162.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
162.prez_authors: Tien T. Roehling, Sheldon S.Q. Wu, Saad A. Khairallah, John D. Roehling, Michael F. Crumb, Gabe  Guss, Manyalibo J. Matthews
162.prez_abstract: The performance disparity existing between additively-manufactured and conventionally-processed metals is partially explained by their dissimilar microstructures.  Until recently, the AM processing of metals has been optimized to mitigate defects and improve geometrical accuracy with less attention paid to microstructure.  Spatial and temporal laser modulation is explored to enhance the properties and processability of AM metals.  The effects of beam shape, dynamic power output, and polarization on solidification structure and track morphology are studied in common AM alloys.  The goals of these experiments are to (1) demonstrate control of the columnar-to-equiaxed transition, (2) identify tactics to reduce parasitic growth, and (3) lower the power requirements necessary to consolidate highly reflective and aggressively oxidizing alloys.  Preliminary results show that elliptical beam modulation provides an effective route towards site-specific microstructural control.  This work was performed under the auspices of the U.S. Department of Energy by Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory under Contract DE-AC52-07NA27344 (LLNL-ABS-728208).

163.prez_name: Statistical Analysis of Correlation between Part and Test Sample Properties
163.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
163.prez_authors: Lisa  Deibler, Jay  Carroll, Heather   Boldt, Clint  Holtey
163.prez_abstract: One of the serious concerns about using additively manufactured components is how to produce confidence that material properties are consistent from part to part and adequate for the component requirements.  Process monitoring to detect the formation of defects, nondestructive characterization, and greater understanding of possible defects created by the additive manufacturing process will all contribute to build the trust needed to use these parts.  In this work, we examine the relevant performance properties of components built over 8 build plates, and correlate the part performance to hundreds of test samples from the same build plates.  While it is impossible to guarantee that a component built on the same plate as a test sample will not have a fatal defect, building up of a statistical database of correlation between parts and test samples can provide more confidence in the process and knowledge of what defects are likely to cause potential failures.

164.prez_name: STEM Phase Mapping and Precipitate Evolution in Additively Manufactured Alloy 718
164.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
164.prez_authors: C. Austin  Wade, Bernd  Baufeld, M. Grace Burke
164.prez_abstract: Additively manufactured (AM) Alloy 718 has been demonstrated to form γ” (DO<SUB>22</SUB>) and γ’ (L1<SUB>2</SUB>) precipitates in the as printed condition. Here, blown powder direct laser deposition has been used to form walls at various laser scanning speeds. The distributions of γ” and γ’ precipitates are mapped using a scanning transmission electron microscope (STEM) equipped with an electron microscope pixel array detector (EMPAD) allowing both diffraction contrast and mass thickness contrast to be collected for complete phase mapping of the γ” and γ’. The EMPAD results are compared to STEM X-ray energy dispersive spectrometry (XEDS) chemical maps acquired on a FEI Talos F200A analytical electron microscope equipped with Super-X XEDS detector and G2 pulse processing electronics. The compositions of the precipitates are compared across AM process conditions and to traditional thermal treatments of Alloy 718 with XEDS quantification performed using Velox 1.4 software.

165.prez_name: Study of Oxide Inclusion Evolution in AM Stainless Steels
165.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
165.prez_authors: Fuyao  Yan, Wei  Xiong, Gregory B. Olson
165.prez_abstract: Control of oxide inclusion size is important to the mechanical properties of steel products. Unlike conventional manufacturing processes, nano-scale oxide inclusions were observed in stainless steels produced by additive manufacturing (AM). These were found to contribute to higher strength of the as-built AM alloy by the Orowan strengthening mechanism. They were also good Zener-pinning particles serving to slow grain growth in post heat treatment. The evolution of radius, volume fraction and number density of oxide particles during AM process and post heat treatment conditions was predicted by the PrecipiCalc® software using simulated thermal profiles. The resulting yield strength of the AM steel was then predicted by an analytical yield strength model.

166.prez_name: The Influence of Post-build Microstructure on the Corrosion of Additively-manufactured 17-4 Stainless Steel
166.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
166.prez_authors: Mark R. Stoudt, Eric  Lass, Maureen  Williams, Richard  Ricker, Carelyn   Campbell, Lyle  Levine
166.prez_abstract: The additive manufacturing (AM) build process produces segregated microstructures with significant localized variations in composition and phases that are uncommon in traditional wrought materials.  While these microstructural inhomogeneities are known to promote variability in the mechanical performance of AM parts, the relationship between the post-build microstructure and the corrosion resistance is not as well understood.  SS17-4 is industrially-relevant alloy for applications requiring high-strength and good corrosion resistance.  Wrought SS17-4 is a two-phase structure consisting primarily of δ-ferrite stringers in a martensite matrix, which can be heat treated to achieve a specific strength.  When atomized in nitrogen, the as-built microstructure is a mixture of α-ferrite and austenite, which does not promote transformation to martensite.  We evaluate the relationship between microstructural differences and the electrochemical performance of SS17-4.  The experimental approach and results comparing wrought to nitrogen-atomized and argon-atomized SS17-4 in the as-built and the heat-treated conditions will be presented and discussed.

167.prez_name: The Microstructure and Mechanical Performance of an Additively Manufactured Aluminum Alloy
167.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
167.prez_authors: Joe  Croteau, Davaadorj  Bayansan, Seth  Griffiths, Christian  Leinenbach, Nhon  Vo, David  Dunand, David  Seidman
167.prez_abstract: NanoAl has developed an economical Al-Mg-based alloy specifically for additive manufacturing processes. Components created by selective laser melting have a density greater than 99.5% and are strengthened by three mechanisms: (i) Mg solid-solution, (ii) L12-structured nano-precipitates, and (iii) nanocrystalline grains. The unique microstructure of the built component is strongly influenced by the alloy composition and manufacturing parameters, which are investigated by using scanning electron microscopy (SEM) and electron backscatter diffraction (EBSD). We discuss the directionally dependent mechanical properties of the as-deposited and aged material, the thermal stability of these strengthening mechanisms, and the possibility of eliminating anisotropy by optimizing the alloy composition.

168.prez_name: Thermal Ratcheting and Its Effects on Microstructure and Anisotropic Material Properties in Metal Melting Laser Powder Bed Fusion Based Additive Manufacturing
168.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
168.prez_authors: Deepankar  Pal, Javed  Akram, Pradeep  Chalavadi, Abdul Khader Khan, Brent  Stucker
168.prez_abstract: The complex motion of the energy source in laser powder bed AM leads to thermal ratcheting which could be spatio-temporally predicted. Aspects of these predictions such as the top surface temperature could be also validated accurately using state-of-the-art high speed cameras in temperature regimes of interest as a single emissivity value does not apply for a wide temperature range although the volumetric response and its instantaneous effects could not be observed in-situ and therefore an end-to-end approach is required to predict microstructural information and mechanical properties for taking on-the-fly decisions. To address this issue, a new approach will be discussed which captures instantaneous variables of interest such as thermal gradient and cooling rate, residual stress which contributes as back stress and porosity which prevents in-service stresses from distributing uniformly as a function of thermal ratcheting and leads to prediction of microstructures and anisotropic mechanical properties for a range of alloys.

169.prez_name:
Ultimate Functionalities in 3D-cellular Mesh Structures: 
Optimization of Structure-mechanical Property Relationship via Unit Cell Design
169.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
169.prez_authors: Krishna Chaitanya  Nune, RDK  Misra, SJ  Li, YL  HAO
169.prez_abstract: Titanium and its alloys with open cellular mesh structures are characterized with low Young’s modulus similar to that of human bone and provide the space required for bone tissue in-growth. However, for the porous implant to attain long-term mechanical and biological stability, it is expected to possess high porosity-high strength combination with long-term endurance and high energy absorption capability. By optimizing the unit cell structure, shape, distribution of pore size, pore morphology, and relative density, the aforementioned properties can be attained in a single material. Ti–6Al–4V meshes with different unit cell elements (cubic, G7, and rhombic dodecahedron) were designed in Materialise software and are fabricated by additive manufacturing using the electron beam melting (EBM) method. The effects of cell shape on the mechanical properties of these samples were studied. Furthermore, graded/gradient structures are fabricated to withstand varying mechanical stress at specific regions, which mimics the natural bone architecture.

170.prez_name: Wire + Arc Additive Manufacture for Maraging Steels
170.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
170.prez_authors: Xiangfang  Xu, Jialuo  Ding, Supriyo  Ganguly, Chenglei  Diao, Stewart  Williams
170.prez_abstract: Wire + arc additive manufacturing (WAAM) is a new process for fabricating large-scale metallic components. WAAM has been shown to be able to produce parts with excellent material properties in a range of materials including titanium, steel and aluminium and gives substantial savings on lead time, energy use and waste material compared to machining from billet. This paper reviews the work on WAAM for maraging steel components. Materials properties were tested and analysed to compare with the traditional wrought materials. The ultimate tensile strength (UTS) of WAAM structure (994-1282 MPa) is slightly better than the unaged wrought maraging 250-grade steel (1000-1140 MPa) due to the precipitates formed by massive thermal cycles in WAAM. An improvement of 24.7% on the UTS was achieved by applying a standard heat treatment specification. In additional, interpass cold rolling was applied to induce recrystallization and improve the response to the aging treatment.

171.prez_name: XRM: Tomography and 3D Grain Mapping for Additive Manufacturing
171.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing of Metals: Microstructure and Material Properties
171.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing techniques can produce complex anisotropic 3D structures.  The reliability and performance of the produced parts relies heavily on the resultant microstructure from often-proprietary feedstock. Materials designed for high-stress applications can be quite sensitive to discrete, complex pore structure, therefore the need to investigate and understand the morphology in 3D at the appropriate pore scale to avoid premature failure. X-ray microscopy (XRM) for tomography using a laboratory source was used to characterize porosity in additive process control study for various steel input materials and Ti-6Al-4V built with Arcam SEBM.  For additional process and material qualification, a new XRM commercial development for 3D grain mapping termed diffraction contrast tomography (DCT) will be discussed.  An example of this capability was used to follow the sintering of copper particles through a series of time-lapsed DCT measurements.  XRM can provide accurate 3D internal structural information critical to aid computational design of next-generation materials.

217.prez_name: Anomaly Detection and Classification in a Laser Powder Bed Additive Manufacturing Process Using a Trained Computer Vision Algorithm
217.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
217.prez_abstract: Despite the rapid adoption of laser powder bed (LPB) Additive Manufacturing by industry, current processes remain largely open-loop with limited real-time monitoring capabilities.  While some machines offer powder bed visualization during builds, they lack automated analysis capability. This work presents an approach for in-situ monitoring of powder bed images with the potential to become a component of a real-time control system. A computer vision algorithm is used to detect and classify anomalies that occur during the powder spreading stage of the process. Anomaly detection and classification are implemented using an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, operating on a training database of image patches. Information about the frequency and location of the detected anomalies is presented in multiple formats including plots (as a function of build height) and 3D reconstructions with flaw locations highlighted. The performance of the final software tool is evaluated, and its usefulness is demonstrated with case studies.

218.prez_name: Assessing Surface Porosity Using Physics-based Surrogate Models for Selective Laser Melting
218.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
218.prez_authors: Alexander  Wolfer, Umberto  Scipioni Bertoli, Dogan  Timucin, Kevin  Wheeler, Saad  Khairallah, Andy  Anderson, Manyalibo  Matthews, Rose  McCallen, Julie  Schoenung, Jean-Pierre  Delplanque
218.prez_abstract: A fast and approximate model for predicting temperature in powder bed fusion processes (such as Selective Laser Melting) is useful for real-time process monitoring as well as uncertainty quantification. Commonly, analytic temperature solutions that consider only thermal conduction and a moving heat source in a continuous medium have been used for these purposes. Adding more physics to these simple models increases the complexity of the solution, usually resulting in a significant increase in computational time. Without key physics, however, results often fail to be useful. We present a semi-analytic model that adds the physics of evaporation and effective powder bed properties in a novel way, which quickly predicts melt pool geometry and thermal gradients as a function of process and material parameters. This fast model of the melt pool scale is then used as a tool to assess probabilities of part scale defects, such as surface porosity.

219.prez_name: Automated Laser Track Trace Identification and Defect Characterization in SLM Processes Using Laser Profilometer Data
219.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
219.prez_authors: Subhadeep  Chakraborty, Anil B. Chaudhary, Sudarsanam S. Babu
219.prez_abstract: This paper presents recent developments in statistical image processing to demonstrate feasibility of layer-by-layer nondestructive inspection for selective laser melting (SLM) of metallic parts. A matrix of 10x10mm Stainless 316 squares were deposited with the first row consisting of just the sintered surface, Row 2 a single layer, Row 3 with 2 layers and so on. These layers were scanned to emulate the layer-by-layer collection of top surface geometry using a laser sensor. The resultant data was utilized to generate ISO 25718 roughness parameters and subsequently to perform track identification. This calculation consisted of two salient steps: (1) Computing the gradients of surface roughness, which vanish at the peaks and pits and (2) Extracting the scanning direction by taking Hough Transform of the geometry. This algorithm was repeated for all layers and the alignment of the roughness with the rotating scan was observed to be persistent for all layers.

220.prez_name: Development and Deployment of a Wire Arc Additive Manufacturing Capability
220.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
220.prez_authors: Paul S Korinko, Anthony   Reynolds, Anna  d'Entremont, Andrew  Duncan, Poh-Sang  Lam, John   Bobbitt, Eric  Kriikku, Derek  Gobin, Matthew  Folsom
220.prez_abstract: Wire arc additive manufacturing (WAAM) is proposed as a viable technology for fabricating fairly complex shapes from reactive metals.  Savannah River National Laboratory (SRNL) and the University of South Carolina (USC) are collaborating on bringing this technology for welding aluminum alloys on line.  USC has invested in a multi-axis robot and cold wire feed gas tungsten arc welder as their platform of choice whilst SRNL is developing a large area gantry robot using a cold metal transfer gas metal arc welding.  In combination with the equipment capabilities, thermal, mechanical and microstructural models are being developed.  The approach being taken to develop the processing and models is to start with a simple ternary solution strengthened alloy such as 4043 to initially calibrate the models and to fabricate exemplar components.  This presentation will describe the hardware, the software, the initial models and results.   Prepared for the USDOE under contract number DE-AC09-08SR22470.

221.prez_name: Dynamics of Droplet Ejection from Metal Powder Bed Layer in Laser Additive Manufacturing as Probed by High Speed Imaging
221.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
221.prez_authors: Sonny  Ly, Alexander M. Rubenchik, Saad A. Khairallah, Guss  Gabe, Manyalibo  Matthews
221.prez_abstract: We present experimental results and modeling of melt pool dynamics and particle ejection associated with metal powder bed fusion additive manufacturing processes.  Ultra-high speed imaging up to 1 Mfps are used to probe droplet ejection from laser irradiated SS316L and Ti6-4 powder layers.  Our results demonstrate that two main mechanisms contribute to the ejection phenomena: the well-known vapor recoil pressure and a lesser known but even more dominant micro-particle entrainment by an ambient gas flow.  The physics of droplet ejection under strong evaporative flow is described using simulations of the laser powder bed interactions to elucidate the experimental results.  Hydrodynamic drag analysis is used to augment the single phase flow model and explain the entrainment phenomenon for 316L stainless steel and Ti-6Al-4V powder layers.

222.prez_name: Exploring Deposition at Elevated Temperatures for Laser Powder Bed Ti64
222.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
222.prez_abstract: In order to ensure widespread adoption of Laser Powder Bed Fusion (LPBF), the ability to ensure part quality while also allowing for the creation of complex geometries is critical. One limiting factor of LPBF is the introduction of significant residual stress into parts during printing. The current means to mitigate residual stress is to heat parts in a furnace after printing, but this still leaves the problem of warping during a build, resulting in limited part geometries and excessive support structures. This project addresses the need for reduced residual stress by exploring the elevated temperature LPBF processing space for Ti-64 up to 500C. An elevated temperature Process Map is generated using both simulations and single bead experiments. This information is then used to build and characterize blocks at elevated temperature using the existing EOS M290 at Carnegie Mellon University with a modified build envelope.

223.prez_name: High Speed, High Resolution In Situ Monitoring of Spatter during Laser Powder Bed Fusion
223.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
223.prez_authors: Christopher   Barrett, Jason  Walker, Rodrigo  Enriquez Gutierrez, Eric  MacDonald, Brett  Conner
223.prez_abstract: In this work, spatter generated during laser powder bed fusion (LPBF) is examined to better understand and improve the manufacturing process. During LPBF (3D Systems ProX 320), spatter particles are ejected as molten metal and solidify in mid-flight before landing in the powder bed or within the cross-section of the just-fabricated layer. Characteristics of the spatter - size, quantity, velocity, trajectory, and chemistry - are related to processing parameters and part outcome. Spatter is identified and tracked in three dimensions using multiple high speed, high resolution cameras synchronized in stereovision. Computer vision algorithms in conjunction with custom software are used to isolate and track spatter particles from ejection through collision with the powder bed, even if the collision point is not in frame. In situ spatter analysis is then correlated with ex situ spatter particle characterization (chemistry and microstructure) as well as with mechanical and microstructural properties of fabricated coupons.

224.prez_name: In-situ Inspection of Laser-based Directed Energy Deposition Processes Using Laser Ultrasonics
224.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
224.prez_authors: Marissa  Brennan, Todd A. Palmer, Maxwell  Wiedmann, Marvin B. Klein
224.prez_abstract: Directed energy deposition (DED) tends to form lack of fusion based defects as a result of changes to powder flow, molten pool shape, or incorrect selection of hatch spacing. With current post-processing inspection techniques, entire fabricated components are inspected, and any defects can only be repaired by post processing (HIP). Laser ultrasonics is an in-line, non-destructive inspection (NDI) technique capable of operating in close proximity to the DED head. The applicability of this technique for in-line inspection was demonstrated in simple DED builds in a range of titanium, nickel, and precipitation hardened (PH) grade stainless steel alloys. These defects were produced by changes in hatch spacing and powder flow to replicate defects typical of those that may form during processing. Anticipation rises for ultrasonic advancements in the detection of defect formation in recently deposited layers while also demonstrating practicality of monitoring microstructural evolution in both pure element and alloy builds.

225.prez_name: In-situ Laser Modification and Characterization of Materials in the TEM
225.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
225.prez_authors: Patrick  Price, Kahlid  Hattar, LaRico  Treadwell, Tim  Boyle
225.prez_abstract: Laser assisted additive manufacturing enables efficient rapid production of components. Successful laser sintering is dependent on the proper selection of energy, time, throughput, and feedstock characteristics. Ex-situ characterization of additively manufactured components gives insight into the effect of processing conditions on resulting component microstructure and properties, but does not describe changes during the process itself. In contrast, in-situ transmission electron microscopy (TEM) allows for real time imaging in changing systems with nanometer resolution. In this study we have investigated the in-situ laser sintering and grain growth behavior of metal nanoparticles inside the TEM in an effort to better understand the laser sintering process. Metal nanoparticles have been printed on TEM grids and heated in-situ with an infrared laser while imaging with TEM. The observed changes in microstructure and sintering behavior as a function of laser power and time will be discussed for different materials systems.

226.prez_name: In-situ Thermal Imaging and Ex-situ Surface Topology Measurements for Control of Laser Powder Bed Build Properties
226.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
226.prez_authors: Sarah J. Foster, Keith  Carver, Tim  Vincent, Ralph B. Dinwiddie, Alexander  Plotkowski, Anil B. Chaudhary, Sudarsanam S. Babu
226.prez_abstract: Components made by direct metal laser melting (DMLM) additive processes require extensive trial and error optimization to minimize defects and arrive at optimum properties.  In this work, in-situ infrared thermography and ex-situ surface roughness measurements were explored as methodologies to ensure Inconel 718 DMLM part quality. For a given energy input defined by the laser (200W), exposure time (80 to 110 µs), and hatch spacing (80 to 110 µm), the maximum infrared intensity of the molten pools was measured at 110 µs exposure time and 80 µm hatch spacing. Interestingly, the same conditions led to minimum porosity and the lowest surface roughness values.  The above samples were analyzed further to rationalize the spatially and temporally varying temperatures and underlying microstructural evolutions.  Analyses of the other processing conditions indicated that above 100 µm hatch spacing, the ability to maintain consistent melt regions decreases with concurrent increases in spatter.

227.prez_name: In Process Monitoring in Metal Powder Bed Fusion Processes Using Optical Coherence Tomography
227.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
227.prez_authors: Philip  DePond, Gabe  Guss, Sonny  Ly, David  Deane, Manyalibo J. Matthews
227.prez_abstract: Although extremely informative and prevalent, post-build non-destructive evaluation techniques can be costly, slow, and limited in terms of accessible range into large parts.  Advances in process monitoring in additive manufacturing has allowed for the investigation of morphological inconsistencies for the purpose of identification and remediation of micro and macroscopic defects during the layer to layer powder bed fusion process.  In-line optical diagnostics provide the extended advantage of tracing the tool paths non-invasively during the melting process (operando) or between layers (in-situ).  Compared with other techniques, optical coherence tomography (OCT), an interferometric technique, enables long working distance and with micrometer scale resolution of surface structure in metals.  With the goal of accelerating the certification of additively manufactured metals, we show how fast sampling 100kHz OCT, coupled with feed-forward algorithms can improve overall part quality (morphology, density, geometry, etc.)  We also discuss recent work in analyzing meltpool dynamics with operando OCT.

228.prez_name: In Situ Real Time Defect Detection of 3D Printed Parts
228.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
228.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing (AM) is a revolutionary technique that could usher in a new age of manufacturing technology.  AM allows for the production of custom parts with previously impractical internal features, but comes with the possibility of internal defects due to print error, residual stress buildup, or malicious intervention.  Conventional post process analysis techniques have difficulty detecting these defects, often requiring destructive tests that compromise the integrity (and thus the purpose) of the part.  Here, we present a “certify-as-you-build” quality assurance system with the capability to monitor a part during the print process, capture the geometry using three dimensional digital image correlation (3D-DIC), and compare the printed geometry with the computer model to detect print errors in situ.  A test case using a fused deposition modeling (FDM) 3D printer was implemented, demonstrating in situ error detection of localized and global defects.

229.prez_name: Melt Pool and Build Layer Monitoring on the NIST Additive Manufacturing Metrology Testbed (AMMT)
229.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
229.prez_authors: Brandon  Lane, Jason  Fox, Ho  Yeung
229.prez_abstract: The Additive Manufacturing Metrology Testbed (AMMT) is a facility at NIST which enables flexible and well-characterized monitoring and control of the laser powder bed fusion (LPBF) process.  Review of the overall AMMT system design is provided, with focus on the design of the in-situ monitoring systems.  Several experiments characterizing the performance of the AMMT monitoring systems are demonstrated, including laser power and speed control accuracy, and optical performance of high-speed melt pool imaging and layer-wise imaging systems.  Examples are then provided of in-situ measurements taken before, during, and after each build layer.  Results from in-situ measurements are discussed with regards to the spatial and temporal resolution results from the characterization tests, and the ultimate resolution requirements for observing particular physical phenomena in the LPBF process.

230.prez_name: Process Control and Defects in Ti-6Al-4V Additive Manufacturing Using Plasma Transferred Arc (PTA) Techniques
230.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
230.prez_authors: James C. Withers, Anil  Chaudhary, Grady  T. Phillips, Glen  Perram
230.prez_abstract: Defects during Plasma Transfer Arc processing of Ti-6Al-4V, including lack of fusion, porosity variations, and solidification cracking, have been monitored using near infrared (1.62 µm) imagery at 300 Hz, 300 µm spatial resolution and melt pool sizes  greater than 12 mm. The temperature evolution exhibits a periodic temperature modulation of more than 300 K, correlated with the scan rate reflecting several phenomena: (1) variations in plate translation speed and arc dwell time, (2) non-uniform, patterned substrate features, (3) heat transfer variation near the ends of the substrate, and (4) changes in plasma conditions as the arc approaches or surpasses the end of the build.  Melt pool temperatures reveal differences in thermal conduction associated with subsurface or prior deposit layer structures.  With these new monitoring capabilities, coupled with closed loop in-situ feedback control provides manufacturing complex geometries with known defect free microstructures, functionally graded materials, and selective reinforcement of metal structures.

231.prez_name: Status of In-situ Process Monitoring in the Electron Beam Melting Process
231.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
231.prez_authors: Michael M. Kirka, Ryan   Dehoff, Jacob  Raplee, Alex   Plotlowski, Vincent  Paquit, Sean  Yoder, Peeyush  Nadwanna
231.prez_abstract: The electron beam melting (EBM) process is one of the many powder bed additive manufacturing (AM) technologies capable of fabricating geometries of near limitless complexity which cannot be fabricated by traditional means. Currently, one of the greatest challenges facing AM is understanding the inherent process-structure-property relationships in Am processed materials. However, this requires methods to rapidly analyze the large data sets generated during a build and developing the relationship to defect. The focus of this work is on developing the tools and analysis techniques to accomplish this. Firstly utilizing IR imaging to relate inter-layer thermal histories with localized structure-property relationships and secondly utilizing the ability capture near-IR images of each layer for in-situ porosity detection and linkage to process parameters and resultant mechanical performance of material from similar builds. Specific examples will be discussed within the context of Ti-6Al-4V and Inconel 718.

232.prez_name: Supersonic Impact for Additive Manufacturing: An In-situ Study
232.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
232.prez_authors: Mostafa  Hassani-Gangaraj, David  Veysset, Keith A. Nelson, Christopher A. Schuh
232.prez_abstract: Eliminating thermal excursions from additive manufacturing could help address several key issues such as distortion, tensile residual stresses and metallurgical challenges, which all emerge at high temperatures. Processes like cold spray, which provide the driving force for bonding through kinetic rather than thermal energy, thus offer a significant departure from mainstream metal additive manufacturing. However, the mechanistic aspects of impact-induced adhesion of microparticles are still unresolved due to the lack of analytical tools that can provide the spatiotemporal resolution necessary to capture such events. Here, we employ an in-house-designed microscale ballistic test platform to accelerate individual metallic microparticles up to ~1 km/s, have them impact a substrate, and study their deformation/adhesion in real time. Unlike prior works’ emphasis on impact-induced adhesion being a temperature-driven phenomenon, we find that the interaction of a fast-traveling pressure wave with the contact periphery of supersonic microparticles is closely related to the phenomenon of adhesion.

233.prez_name: Titanium Powder Smoke during EB-PBF: Decoupling Charge and Heat Deposition at Different Beam Energies
233.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
233.prez_abstract: Electrostatic metal powder charging, known as ‘powder smoke’, remains an under-investigated component of the EB-PBF process, despite the hurdles it poses to powder development and minimum usable powder size. Experiments investigating smoke of titanium powder are presented based on a re-purposed, digitally controlled electron beam welder in a high vacuum, non-ionizing atmosphere. Using a novel single layer Ti powder fixture, we are able to control for powder depth, hold temperature and sinter state. The beam energy is varied over the range 40-80keV, and supporting Faraday Cup measurements demonstrate the incident current density distribution. Using micro-second resolved beam pulses, the powder oxide conductivity is probed, and the effects of energy and charge deposition are distinguished. These results are compared to simulations of the electron/matter interactions using Monte-Carlo methods, and discussed in the context of new powder smoke suppression techniques.

234.prez_name: X-ray Vision of Laser Powder Bed Fusion Process
234.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
234.prez_authors: Cang  Zhao, Kamel  Fezzaa, Ross   Cunningham, Haidan  Wen, Francesco De Carlo, Lianyi   Chen, Anthony  Rollett, Tao  Sun
234.prez_abstract: Metal additive manufacturing (AM) has witnessed a rapid growth during the past few decades. However, it is extremely challenging to directly observe the microstructural evolution during the highly dynamic and transient metal AM processes. In this presentation, we use the high-speed x-ray imaging and diffraction techniques at the 32-ID-B beamline of the Advanced Photon Source to characterize the laser powder bed fusion (LPBF) process of Ti-6Al-4V in real time and in situ. It has been demonstrated that many physical phenomena in LPBF, e.g. melt pool dynamics, particle ejection, rapid solidification, and phase transformation, can be probed and investigated with unprecedented temporal and spatial resolutions. Through a set of custom-developed algorithms, quantitative structural information is extracted, which will promote the development of physics-based, high-fidelity computational models.

235.prez_name: In Situ  Quality Monitoring in AM Using Acoustic Emission: A Machine Learning Approach
235.symp_name: Additive Manufacturing: In-situ Process Monitoring and Control
235.prez_authors: Kilian  Wasmer, Christoph  Kenel, Christian  Leinenbach, Sergey A.  Shevchik
235.prez_abstract: Most control methods in additive manufacturing (AM) are mainly based on temperature or high resolution imaging. However, no methods are known to monitor the quality of AM in real-time. Our approach is very innovative for the quality monitoring of the process online by combining acoustic emission (AE) with machine learning. The machine parameters were changed when processing a steel 316L to get three quality levels for AE data acquisition, processing and validation. We demonstrate that the AM process has a number of unique acoustic signatures that can be detected and interpreted in terms of quality. The classification of AE is made by machine learning (ML) methods. This includes the extraction and recognition of unique acoustic signatures from different sintering or melting events. The confidence level achieved in the classification is very high showing that our approach is very promising for in situ and real-time monitoring of AM processes.

287.prez_name: Selection of SLM Process Parameters to Tailor the Microstructure and Superelasticity of Ni-rich NiTi Alloys
287.symp_name: Advanced Manufacturing, Processing, Characterization and Modeling of Functional Materials
287.prez_authors: Soheil  Saedi, Narges  Shayesteh Moghaddam, Sayed Ehsan  Saghaian, Amirhesam  Amerinatanzi, Mohammad  Elahinia, Haluk  Karaca
287.prez_abstract: Selective laser melting (SLM) of metals has opened a new window to fabricate complex and porous parts. The combination of unique features of NiTi alloys together with the flexibility of SLM fabrication has made SLM NiTi a perfect candidate for numerous applications. Depending on the implemented process parameters, different microstructures are evolved due to the complex heat transfer and grain growth. This study is a systematic work to improve the understanding of the microstructures formed as the result of the different SLM fabrication parameters in Ni-rich NiTi alloys and their correlation to the thermo-mechanical response. It will be shown that i: SLM NiTi parts fabricated with same energy levels, but different parameters, do not show similar responses; ii: Via choosing appropriate processing parameters, 5.77% superelasticity was achieved for SLM Ni-rich NiTi in as-fabricated condition. iii: Decreasing the hatch spacing significantly improves the superelastic response of the alloys.
