432.prez_name: A Broadband, High Frequency Characterization Approach for Combinatorial Dielectric Thin-films
432.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
432.prez_authors: Eric  Marksz, Nathan  Orloff, Christian  Long, James  Booth, Ichiro  Takeuchi
432.prez_abstract: Dielectric ceramics play a critical role in the RF components of network-enabled devices. Due to ever-increasing demand for mobile data, telecoms are pushing to access available bandwidth in the tens of GHz with 5G networks. This has led to a push to better understand and discover dielectric materials with desirable properties in this high frequency regime. We present here advances to our combinatorial approach for broadband dielectric property extraction up to 110GHz. A suite of micro-fabricated devices allows for accurate determination of dielectric constant, dispersion and loss behavior, and possible tunability for multiple compositions of BaxSr1-xTiO3 (BST) using a single sample. Integral to this approach is the compositionally graded BST grown by Pulsed Laser Deposition (PLD) from pure BaTiO3 and pure SrTiO3 targets to create a gradient ranging from x=0 to x=1. Finally, other potential combinatorial dielectric materials will be explored, as well as possible metamaterials applications of gradient dielectrics.

433.prez_name: Applications of Magnetoelectric Gradiometer and Its Vibration Rejetctioin Enhancement Based on H-Field Modulation Technique
433.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
433.prez_authors: Junran  Xu, Xin  Zhuang, Chung Ming  Leung, Jie-Fang  Li, Dwight  Viehland
433.prez_abstract: A magnetoelectric (ME) gradiometer of two Metglas/Pb(Zr,Ti)O3(PZT) fiber-based sensors was developed in this paper. The equivalent magnetic noise of both sensors was determined to be about 60 pT/√Hz using a H field modulation. The common mode rejection ratio (CMRR) of a gradiometer based on these two sensors was determined to be 74. We also measured the gradiometer curve in this study, which provides the dependence of the gradiometer output on distance measurement by using ME gradiometer. Investigations in the presence of mechanical noise showed that our ME gradiometer was capable of vibration rejection while working under H field modulation. By which were also compared to similar studies performed on ME gradiometers working in a passive mode. The findings demonstrated that the ME gradiometer has good vibration rejection capabilities in the presence of both mechanical and magnetic signals while working under H field modulation.

434.prez_name: BaTiO3 Ceramics Porosity Fractal Structured Approach
434.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
434.prez_authors: Vojislav V Mitic, Ljubisa M Kocic, Vesna V Paunovic
434.prez_abstract:
BaTiO3 ceramics is a porous material made out of grains and pores. The geometry of such a structure is best approximated by fractal approach, and thereby it influences microelectronic properties. A pore itself acts as a microcapacitor with traces of inductivity. A cluster of pores than makes an integral impedance with an equivalent circuit scheme.  Constructive theory of fractal helps in modeling of such impedance. The experimental data are acquired using SEM micro-graphs of the selected specimens. Further method is based on fractal analytic procedures based on extraction of fractal dimension and involving this as a key parameter. 
Such an approach, in combination with methods developed by the authors completes the extensive method for determination of relationship between microelectronic properties of sintered barium-titanate ceramics and technological parameters used in the sintering process. The issue of additives is also considered due the fact that dopants have considerable influence of electronic characteristics.

435.prez_name: Construction of Different Shaped Ferroelectric Filler and Its Effect on Dielectric Properties of Composite Materials
435.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
435.prez_authors: Jing  Fu, Yudong  Hou, Mupeng  Zheng
435.prez_abstract: In this work, different shaped ferroelectric filler, BaTiO3 spherical particles (BTNPs) and BaTiO3 nanorods (BTNRs), have been synthesized by topological chemistry method. By using these two kinds of BT as fillers, Polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF) based composites have been built and the related microstructure and electrical properties are systematically studied. It was found that a variety of factors, such as the intrinsic polarization of filler, interface polarization and electric field distribution between the filler and the matrix, affecting the dielectric properties of the composites. Although the intrinsic polarization of BTNPs is greater than that of BTNRs, the superior interfacial polarization and stronger electric field intensity distribution of BTNRs in PVDF matrix play the main roles in obtaining the enhanced dielectric properties in BTNRs/PVDF composites. This work has a good reference value for developing new composites based on tailoring the shape of ferroelectric filler.

436.prez_name: Crystal Structure, Ferroelectricity and Polar Order in Ba4R2Zr4Nb6O30 (R=La, Nd, Sm) Tetragonal Tungsten Bronze New System
436.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
436.prez_authors: Xiaoli  Zhu, Wen Bin  Feng, Xiao Qiang  Liu, Xiang Ming  Chen
436.prez_abstract: In the present work, zirconate niobate ferroelectric new system Ba4R2Zr4Nb6O30  with filled tetragonal tungsten bronze structure has been synthesized and investigated. The ferroelectricity and polar order are characterized together with the crystal structure. The present materials show a crossover from relaxor to ferroelectric feature with increasing the A-site ionic radii difference. The relaxor behavior in Ba4La2Zr4Nb6O30 is associated with the incommensurate modulation, while the commensurate structural modulation dominates the normal ferroelectric transition in Ba4Nd2Zr4Nb6O30 and Ba4Sm2Zr4Nb6O30. Compared with the titanate niobate tungsten bronzes, the present materials exhibit stronger relaxor nature. Micro polar regions are detected for the relaxor Ba4La2Zr4Nb6O30, while coexistence of macro ferroelectric domains and micro polar regions is observed in Ba4Nd2Zr4Nb6O30 and Ba4Sm2Zr4Nb6O30, and the micro polar regions can grow into the macro domains under high electric field. The present new system is expected as the promising new candidates as Pb-free ferroelectric materials.

437.prez_name: Cyclic Azasilanes as Volatile and Reactive Precursors for Atomic and Molecular Layer Deposition
437.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
437.prez_abstract: Cyclic azasilanes are a promising class of reactants for atomic and molecular layer deposition (MLD) due to their volatility, reactivity, and diverse set of peripheral chemical functionalities. Reaction with water or OH groups results in ring opening and Si-O bond formation and is a useful chemical step for controlled film growth. This work focuses on developing this class of molecules for use in MLD of hybrid inorganic-organic films. We report the growth of MLD films based on reaction with anhydrides, metal-organics, and water. In some processes, diffusion within the film was evidenced by large growth rates (~10 nm per cycle).  However, use of TMA arrested this diffusion. During annealing, films exhibited densification while maintaining low surface roughness.  Porosity was evidenced by a small dielectric constants. These chemistries offer a route to tunable thin films and have potential applications in diffusion barrier, low dielectric constant layers, and passivation layers.

438.prez_name: Dielectric Nanocomposites with Structure Tailoring for Energy Storage
438.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
438.prez_abstract: Dielectric capacitors for energy storage have advantages in fast charge-discharge capability and high power density are highly desirable and investigated to reduce the size and cost of electric power system. In this presentation, a brief review of the state of arts on the structure tailoring dielectric nanocomposites for energy storage applications including our recent highlight works that exhibit excellent energy storage properties will be given. Spatial organization of polymer matrix and ceramic nanofillers into multilayer structured nanocomposites with the compositional tailoring effect have been systematically studied. Layer-structured polymer-based nanocomposite exhibiting high energy density and improved discharge efficiency by a novel macro-micro structure design on the composite structure as well as the fillers distribution. An extend study for multilayer oxide capacitor has been down to show the interface effect on improving the dielectric strength as well as its high temperature applicability.

439.prez_name: Effect of Different Methods of Oxygen Treatment on Structure and Dielectric Properties of Mn-doped Ca0.6Sr0.4TiO3 Ceramics
439.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
439.prez_authors: Lin  Zhang, Michael T. Lanagan, Juan  Xie, Qi  Xu, Zhonghua  Yao, Hua  Hao, Hanxing  Liu
439.prez_abstract: Different methods of oxygen treatment (as sintered, dipped in H2O2, annealed in O2, and annealed in N2) was conducted on Mn-doped Ca0.6Sr0.4TiO3 (the Mn content was 0 mol%, 0.5 mol% and 2.0 mol%) ceramics. Microscopic morphology showed little change for O2 and N2 annealed samples, while grain boundaries were notably etched after dipping in H2O2. Annealing in O2 resulted in higher grain boundary resistance and improved energy storage properties for all the Mn-doped ceramics, and annealing in N2 led to the opposite results, however, dipping in H2O2 had complex influence on electrical properties. For 0 mol% and 2.0 mol% Mn-doped ceramics, bulk resistivities increased, while for 0.5 mol% Mn-doped ceramics, bulk resistivities decreased, ascribing to the battle between positive effect and negative effect of H2O2 on insulating properties of grain boundaries. Oxygen vacancies related physical mechanism was proposed for the explanation.

440.prez_name: Effect of Pb(Zn1/3Nb2/3)O3 Addition on the Phase Transition and Ferroelectric Behavior for Pb(Zr0.95Ti0.05)O3 Ceramics
440.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
440.prez_authors: Mupeng  Zheng, Yudong  Hou, Mankang  Zhu
440.prez_abstract: Antiferroelectric-ferroelectric (AFE-FE) phase boundary is an important phase boundary in PZT (near Zr:Ti = 95:5) system. Incorporation of the third component with PZT (near Zr:Ti = 95:5) can tailor the stability region of the AFE-FE phase boundary, obtaining new material system with excellent properties. In this work, a xPb(Zn1/3Nb2/3)O3–(1-x)Pb(Zr0.95Ti0.05)O3 (xPZN–(1-x)PZT) system close to antiferroelectric–ferroelectric (AFE–FE) morphotropic phase boundary has been prepared and investigated. The XRD results reveal PZN addition induces a phase transition from the orthorhombic (AFE) to rhombohedral (FE) phase through a phase coexistence region (AFE+FE). The polarization–electric field (P–E) measurements indicate that the AFE phase can be induced into a metastable FE (FEm) phase. A composition-temperature phase diagram was generalized within a certain range of PZN content in which an AFE–FE phase boundary connecting orthorhombic antiferroelectric to rhombohedral ferroelectric phase zones is formed near room temperature.

441.prez_name: Effect of Polymer Phase on Freeze-cast High Temperature Dielectric Composites
441.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
441.prez_abstract: In previous research freeze-casting was used to construct ceramic-polymer composites in which the two phases are arranged in an electrically parallel configuration.  By doing so, the composites exhibit dielectric constant (K) up to two orders of magnitude higher than that of composites with ceramic particles randomly dispersed in a polymer matrix.  This technique has been successful with both an aqueous and camphene based ceramic slurry that is frozen uni-directionally to form templates such that ceramic aggregates are aligned in the temperature gradient direction.  Freeze-casting is a versatile processing technique that has been demonstrated to work with many ceramic systems.  In this paper the continued study of freeze-cast processing of composites based around non-saturating Bi(Zn<SUB>0.5</SUB>Ti<SUB>0.5</SUB>)O<SUB>3</SUB> – BaTiO<SUB>3</SUB> ceramics for use in high power capacitor applications are discussed.  The processing parameters (dispersant, particle size, polymer composition, etc.), composite dielectric properties, and composite microstructure will also be presented

442.prez_name:
Effect of Processing Conditions on Electromagnetic (EM) Response Properties
 of Polymer-derived SiC Ceramics
442.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
442.prez_abstract: Traditional manufacturing process of SiC is to combine SiO2 and carbon in an Acheson graphite electric resistance furnace at a high temperature between 1600oC and 2500oC, where the crystal structure is formed at temperatures about 1700oC. Effect of processing temperature below 1700oC on its electromagnetic (EM) absorption property has not been studied and will be the motivation of this study. The SiC in this study will be produced via the pre-ceramic precursor route which allows the formation of such ceramics over a broad final processing temperature range, typically 1100oC - 2000oC. The microstructure and chemical compositions of the produced ceramics are determined by the final processing temperature and independent of its application temperature; but its electrical properties are determined by its application temperature and are temperature-dependent. Different processing conditions produce different microstructures, which will result in different permittivity values and in turn different EM response behaviors.

443.prez_name: Engineering the Dielectric and Mechanical Properties of Parylene-C Columnar Microfibrous Thin Films by Controlling the Deposition Angle
443.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
443.prez_authors: Ibrahim H Khawaji, Chandraprakash  Chindam, Osama O Awadelkarim, Akhlesh  Lakhtakia
443.prez_abstract: Columnar microfibrous thin films (μFTFs) of Parylene C are grown using an oblique-angle variant of standard physicochemical vapor deposition, whereby a collimated flux of Parylene-C monomers is directed at an angle χ<sub>v</sub> on to a substrate. The columnar μFTFs for χ<sub>v</sub> = 30°, 60°, and 90° were characterized for morphology by scanning-electron microscopy, porosity by measuring the mass density, and flexibility by evaluating the Young’s modulus and tensile strength. Also, metal-insulator-metal (MIM) structures, each incorporating either a columnar μFTF or bulk Parylene C, were investigated for their dielectric characteristics. The porosity of μFTFs increases with decreasing χ<sub>v</sub>. However, the Young’s modulus and the relative permittivity of the μFTF are both reduced with smaller χ<sub>v</sub>, hence enabling engineering the dielectric and mechanical properties during deposition.

444.prez_name: Enhanced Quality Factor of Mg2TiO4-based Ceramics at Microwave Frequencies
444.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
444.prez_abstract: Microwave dielectric ceramics with high qualty factor (Qf) are of increasing interest for 5G wireless communication systems, such as global communication satellites, mobile communications, and radar detectors. For the effective search and develop the microwave dielectric ceramics with high Qf, the relationships between microwave dielectric properties of Mg2TiO4-based ceramics with inverse spinel structure and the structural characteristics were investigated. By substitution of tetravalent cation, the characteristics of the bond between the cations and oxygen ions in oxygen octahedra can be modified to affect the dielectric properties of Mg2TiO4-based ceramics. Typically, two types of cation substitutions will be discussed; Mg2Ti1-x(Mg1/3B2/3)O4 (B=Nb5+,Ta5+,Sb5+) (0.025≤x≤0.15), and Mg2Ti0.95(MgxNb0.8-0.4x)0.05O4 (0.0≤x≤1.0). Quality factor (Qf) of the specimens was dependent on the bond valence of Ti-site and packing fraction of Mg2TiO4-based ceramics. Dielectric constant (K) and temperature coefficient of resonant frequency (TCF) of the specimens will also be discussed based on the structural characteristics of inverse spinel structure.

445.prez_name: Ferroics and Multiferroics for Terahertz-device Design
445.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
445.prez_authors: Moumita  Dutta, Soutik  Betal, Xomalin  Peralta, Amar  Bhalla, Ruyan  Guo
445.prez_abstract: The novel properties of ferroics and multiferroics have been extensively explored for various applications - memory, sensors, transducers are to name a few. In this work, we have taken advantage of their unique characteristics for the design of Terahertz (THz) devices. With the recent advancements in femto-second laser technology facilitating the coherent generation and detection of THz radiation,this spectral gap (100 GHz-30 THz,ranging between Microwave and Infrared) is now finding applications in wide range of disciplines like Biomedical-imaging, next-generation communications, airport security, spectroscopy of molecular/rotational vibrations etc. In this work, we report the interaction of THz-waves with different ferroic and multiferroic materials, excited by external fields, to exploit that knowledge for the design of THz devices. These devices can be envisioned to be the building-blocks for the future communication/computing systems.

446.prez_name: Fixing the Navy's Railgun: Raising the Glass Transition Temperature of PEN
446.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
446.prez_abstract: As the Navy attempts to increase the power of their Railgun, dubbed “America’s Supergun”, the high-energy environment is tearing the Railgun apart. Over 30 Megajoules of electrical energy is stored in capacitors, and when this is all discharged almost instantaneously, the capacitors heat up as a result. The thin-film polymeric dielectric material softens as the inside of the capacitors heat up. This softening makes the state-of-the-art polymer dielectric, BOPP, ineffective as a dielectric material.       This investigation resulted in a method to increase the softening temperature (T<SUB>g</SUB>) of a polymer with strong dielectric properties, PEN, above the desired operating temperature of 150°C. The shift in glass transition temperature was achieved by inducing an optimal crystallization morphology. The two key procedures to yield this morphology were slow, strain-induced orientation of the polymer chains, followed by annealing to induce crystallization.

447.prez_name: Functional Properties of Some Rare Earth Based Double Perovskite Oxides for Future Application
447.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
447.prez_abstract: Over the past few years, functional double perovskite (DP) oxides, A2BꞌB″O6, have attracted huge attention owing to their multi-disciplinary applications in intelligent sensor, spintronic and functional devices. A is usually divalent or trivalent cations and octahedral Bꞌ and B″ are 3d or 4d/5d transition-metal cations. Depending on the relative size of Bꞌ and B″ cations relative to A cations, A2BꞌB″O6 crystallizes as cubic (Fm3m), tetragonal (I4/m) or monoclinic (P21/n). The presence of different distinct cation sites greatly increases the possibility of functional design in DP. We report the observation of dielectric relaxations in a series of rare earth DP system and based on complex impedance analysis, various contributions to the observed magnetodielectric property have been discussed. Ac conductivity at high frequency region can be explained by various models. The structural, dielectric and magnetic data make this system for its multiferroic character a promising candidate to various modern functional device applications.

448.prez_name: Indialite/Cordierite Glass Ceramics Applied for LTCC
448.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
448.prez_authors: Hitoshi  Ohsato, Jobin  Varghese, Timo  Vahera, Heli  Jantunen, Makoto  Iwata
448.prez_abstract: Indialite/cordierite (in/co) Mg2Al4Si5O18 glass ceramics crystallized cordierite glass at 1200 to 1400 oC for 10 and 20h have good microwave properties of low dielectric constant of 4.7 and high Qf of more than 200,000 GHz. These properties could be applied to advanced 5G millimeter-wave applications. In this paper, in/co ceramics powder is applied for LTCC. The powder with around 1 μm particle size was fabricated by planetary ball milling using quenched glass crystallized at 1000 oC for 1h. Green tapes were casted by using xylene/ethanol slurry of the in/co powder with sintering aid Bi2O3, dispersant, binder and plasticizers by doctor blade method. The tapes were sintered at 900 oC/4h with 96% densification without any warping. The sintered samples shows excellent dielectric properties, relative permittivity of 6, dielectric loss (tanδ) of 5×10-5 and temperature coefficient of relative permittivity of 120 ppm/oC at 1MHz using low frequency measurements.

449.prez_name: Interfacing Oxides with Silicon Using Pulsed Laser Deposition
449.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
449.prez_authors: Matjaz  Spreitzer, Daniel   Diaz Fernandez, Tjaša  Parkelj, Danilo  Suvorov
449.prez_abstract:
Control at silicon-oxide interfaces is of great importance since it enables integration of oxide materials with Si platform and thus provides versatile additional functionalities to semiconductor industry. However, the ability to control such interfaces is hindered by the intense reaction of constituents. Therefore Si has to be passivized, which is normally performed by the formation of an appropriate buffer layer that is chemically and structurally compatible with silicon and the oxide. 
In our study pulsed laser deposition (PLD) was used to prepare Sr-based buffer layers. By optimization of deposition conditions of metallic Sr we were able to monitor Si surface reconstructions, which is needed for proper Si passivization. Subsequently, epitaxial layer of SrTiO<SUB>3</SUB> with STO(001)║Si(001) and STO[110]║Si[100] was grown on as-prepared buffer layers and analyzed using different analytical techniques. Results of our study revealed new PLD-based path towards epitaxial integration of STO and other functional oxides with Si.

450.prez_name: Magnetoelectric Nanorobots for Remotely Controlled Dynamic Cell Manipulation
450.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
450.prez_authors: Soutik  Betal, Moumita  Dutta, Amar  Bhalla, Ruyan  Guo
450.prez_abstract: A remotely controlled dynamic process has been developed for manipulation of targeted biological cells using inorganic heterostructured magnetoelectric nanocomposites which are core-shell nanoparticles comprised of single crystalline ferromagnetic cores (CoFe2O4) and ferroelectric crystalline thin film shells (BaTiO3).  We demonstrated that these nanocomposites behaves as a unique family of inorganic magnetoelectric nanorobots (MENRs), which can be controlled remotely by directional ac or dc magnetic fields for dynamic cellular manipulation including cell targeting, permeation, and transport.  MENRs performs these functions via localized electric periodic pulse generation, local electric-field sensing, or thrust generation and acts as the unique tool for remotely controlled dynamic cellular manipulation. We have designed a custom build systematic setup to accurately examine the MENRs-cellular interaction and performed experiments in microvascular structured microfluidic chamber (MSMC) with complex junctions and variable pressure gradient corresponding to vascular environment. The details of these MENRs and their performance will be presented in this paper.

451.prez_name: Observation of Ti-Ti Bonding in Ti/Cu/Pt-supported Rutile TiO2(110) Surface: Ab Initio Calculations
451.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
451.prez_authors: Lei  Li, Wenshi  Li, Han  Qin, Canyan   Zhu, Lingfeng  Mao
451.prez_abstract: The structures of metal-supported TiO2(110) surface are analyzed via ab initio calculations to investigate the effects of the adsorption on the formation of Ti-Ti bonding. Subsequently, the dependent of the Ti-Ti bonding on the adsorption of the popular metal (Ti, Cu, and Pt) at four low-coordinated sites of the defective TiO2(110) surface are compared. Finally, the Ti adsorption gives a larger contribution to the occurrence of Ti-Ti bonding than Cu or Pt adsorption does. This Ti-Ti bonding benefits the formation of the lateral conductive path in the TiO2(110) layer. These foundations may be helpful to clarify the resistive switching phenomena.

452.prez_name: Phase-field Model of Ferroelectric Domain Dynamics under Ultrafast Stimuli
452.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
452.prez_authors: Tiannan  Yang, Zijian  Hong, Jiamian  Hu, Long-Qing  Chen
452.prez_abstract: Applying an ultrafast stimulus to a ferroelectric material allows one to explore possible new transient phenomena or new metastable domain patterns that may emerge during the relaxation from its excited state to its original or a new equilibrium state. In this work, we develop a phase-field model for understanding and predicting the dynamical responses of both ferroelectric and ferroelastic domain patterns under ultrafast electric and mechanical stimuli. As an example, we studied the nanoscale domain dynamics of barium titanate crystals under high frequency stimuli. We successfully explained the experimentally observed phenomena with distinct responses determined by both the orientation and the location of the domains. Mesoscale mechanisms of ferroelectric domain and domain wall responses as well as intrinsic lattice vibrations are revealed. The theoretical insights on ultrafast domain dynamics will provide useful guidance for manipulating the dynamic functionalities of ferroelectric materials.

453.prez_name: Preparation and Characterization of Aurivillius Phase Na0.5Bi2.5Nb2O9 by an Economical Aqueous Sol-Gel Technique
453.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
453.prez_authors: Yu Dong  Hou, Mu Peng  Zheng, Jing Yang  Rong, Man Kang  Zhu
453.prez_abstract: An Aurivillius phase bismuth layer-structured compound, Na0.5Bi2.5Nb2O9 (NBN), have been prepared by an economical aqueous sol-gel technique, in which Nb2O5 was changed into a water-soluble species through the chemical chelation as the Nb source. The results indicated that a pure NBN orthorhombic aurivillius phase with space group of A21am has been obtained at the temperature as low as 650°C, which is lowered by about 150°C than solid state method. The morphology of the obtained powders was plate-like and the mean particle size was about 200 nm. Using these nano-particles as precursors, the dense NBN ceramics with relative density above 96% were fabricated at 1050 °C for 2h by pressureless sintering. The dielectric studies indicate that the Curie temperature Tc is 780°C. The d33 value is 11pC/N at room temperature, and shows no obvious decline when the annealing temperature is lower than 700°C, that is a potential candidate for high-temperature applications.

454.prez_name: Relaxor Ferroelectric and Antiferroelectric Materials as Dielectric Coolants
454.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
454.prez_authors: Bouchra  Asbani, Brigita  Rozic, Hana  Ursic, Mimoun  El Marssi, Rasa  Pirc, Jurij  Koruza, Barbara  Malic, Zdravko  Kutnjak
454.prez_abstract: The electrocaloric (EC) effect has recently attracted significant interest for developing new devices that have the potential to replace the existing heat-management technologies [1].  In this contribution the direct measurements of the large EC effect in antiferroelectric and ferroelectric materials [2] will be presented. The negative EC effect in antiferroelectric n/95/5 PLZT and PBZ ceramics will be investigated by direct experiments. It is demonstrated that both negative and positive EC response can be arbitrarily invoked in antiferroelectric materials by properly controlling the electric field and temperature. In addition, the large positive EC response observed by direct experiments in lead-free BCTZ-based ferroelectric materials will be reviewed. [1] Z. Kutnjak., B. Rožič, R. Pirc., Wiley Encyclopedia of Electrical and Electronics Engineering, p. 1-19 (2015). [2] B. Asbani, J.-L. Dellis, A. Lahmar, M. Courty, M. Amjoud, Y. Gagou, K. Djellab, D. Mezzane, Z. Kutnjak, M. El Marssi, Appl. Phys. Lett. 106, 042902 (2015).

455.prez_name: Study Broadband Dielectric Spectroscopy of (Ba,Sr)TiO3 at Different Temperatures
455.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
455.prez_abstract: (Ba1-xSrx)TiO3 has been received considerable attention due to its high energy density, high dielectric permittivity and low loss. Dielectric properties of ceramics can be strongly influenced by sintering temperature. High sintering temperature not only affects microstructure of ceramics but it can also increase oxygen vacancies. Re-oxidation through annealing in air at 1000 ºC is one of the possible methods to lower oxygen vacancy concentration. In this study, dielectric properties of (Ba1-xSrx)TiO3 ,  x=0.4 (BST) have been investigated before and after annealing in a broad frequency  (10 mHz- 1 GHz) and temperature ranges (200-500 ºC). Complex impedance spectroscopic and resonant post analyses have been used for low and high frequency measurements. In Low frequencies, we were be able to separate the effect of grain and grain boundary contribution to the impedance, and at high frequency we will look at the contribution of both to the overall Q value in microwave frequency.

456.prez_name: The Effects of Metal Work Function, Doping, and Source-drain Underlap Variation on Id-Vg Characteristics of a Highly Scaled InAs Hetero Structure Field Effect Transistor
456.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
456.prez_abstract: Drain Current-Gate Voltage characteristics of InGaAs-InAs-InGaAs Hetero-Junction Field Effect Transistor is investigated by quantum mechanical calculation in real space solving two-dimensional (2D) Schrodinger-Poisson equations self-consistently. The results obtained demonstrate that various physical and process parameters such as Gate Metal work function, Doping, and finally Source-Drain Underlap, which is not so much pronounced in literature, separately can be tuned to optimize device operation such as decreasing OFF current while maintaining appropriate ON current. Among all results, outputs generated from the change of Gate Metal Work Function is the most predictable one. However, it is still a tunable parameter for better performance. Doping density in the delta-doped region could be tuned by the device engineers to reduce sub-threshold slope without compromising ON-state current. Since the impact of two parameters (Side spacer & Doping) are in the same direction, they could be varied together to boost the operation of the device further.

457.prez_name: Topochemical Conversion under Hydrothermal Conditions as a Route for the Preparation of Anisotropic Perovskite Particles
457.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
457.prez_authors: Danilo  Suvorov, Marjeta   Maček Kržmanc, Alja  Čontala, Hana  Uršič
457.prez_abstract: Anisotropic perovskite particles are of great scientific interest because of their shape- and size-dependent properties and their wide applications as μm- and nm-sized particles. The former are used for the preparation of highly oriented ceramics by templated grain growth.  In this study we show that under certain hydrothermal conditions, that favour Frank-van-der-Merwe layer-by-layer growth, (001)-oriented Bi<SUB>4</SUB>Ti<SUB>3</SUB>O<SUB>12</SUB> plates directly transform into (100)-oriented SrTiO<SUB>3</SUB> plates with a preserved shape. Variation of the hydrothermal conditions alters the prevailing growth mechanism of SrTiO<SUB>3</SUB> on the Bi<SUB>4</SUB>Ti<SUB>3</SUB>O<SUB>12</SUB> plates from the Frank van der Merwe, to Volmer-Weber and to Stranski-Krastanov and the corresponding morphology of the final SrTiO<SUB>3</SUB> plates changes from plates, to cubes and to frames, respectively. Similarly to SrTiO<SUB>3</SUB> the hydrothermal conditions needed to induce a certain type of growth are also studied for BaTiO<SUB>3</SUB>. The ferroelectric and piezoelectric characteristics of BaTiO<SUB>3</SUB> particles as determined with a piezo-force microscope will also be presented.

458.prez_name: Topology Optimisation of a Piezoelectric Transformer for Cold Plasma Discharge
458.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
458.prez_abstract: Studies on cold plasma disinfection for the biomedical field have paved the way for new applications of high step up piezoelectric transformers. The voltage gain and the compactness of these components make them excellent and safety electric power sources- few tens volts at input voltage - and compact to supply plasma discharge. In our prototype, the transformer is immersed in a gas flow of Argon. This gas, once ionized and evacuated, mixes with ambient air, generating reactive oxide species that will be sprayed on the surface to be disinfected. In the presented study, optimization of the piezoelectric transformer topology is carried out in order to maximize the plasma discharge power. First, we focused on the 1D model generator with peculiarity to promote plasma on its surface in the gas flow under atmospheric pressure. Based on this model we proposed a topology adapted to maximize the discharges and disinfection capabilities.

459.prez_name: Volume and Polarization Induced Structural Phase Transitions of Pm3m Perovskites
459.symp_name: Advances in Dielectric Materials and Electronic Devices
459.prez_authors: Vignaswaran  Kaliyaperumal Veerapandiyan, YuHusn   Liao, Walter  A.  Schulze, Scott  T. Misture, Steven  M.  Pilgrim, Steven C Tidrow
459.prez_abstract: Using temperature dependent genome-like ion properties, radii and polarizability, as taken from the new “simple” “material” model (NSMM), we demonstrate the ability of NSMM to identify and a priori predict both polarization and volume induced structural phase transitions of “simple” and “simply mixed” Pm3m as well as some additional more complicated Pm3m Perovskites. In combination with geometric considerations, these results allow us to physically understand why the majority of “simple” and “simply mixed” Perovskites are not cubic Pm3m at room temperature and why so many of them undergo structural phase transitions to or from cubic at particular temperatures. Further, we demonstrate the ability of NSMM to provide temperature dependent relative permittivity of Perovskite Pm3m materials.

460.prez_name: A Phase Field Model for Multiphase Oxidation of Advanced High Strength Steels
460.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

461.prez_name: Application of V-N Microalloying in Ultra-high Strength Martensitic Sheet Steels for Hot-dip Galvanising
461.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

462.prez_name: Design and Characterization of Core-shell Nanocontainers Impregnated with Inhibitor for Active Corrosion Protection of Low Carbon Steel
462.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

463.prez_name: Electrochemical Properties of Continuous Galvanized Coatings on Direct Hot Pressed Steels
463.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

464.prez_name: Influence of Oxidizing Gas and Surface Microstructure on the Kinetics of High-temperature Oxidation of a CMnSi Advanced High-Strength Steel (AHSS)
464.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

465.prez_name: Internal Stresses and Processing Modeling for Galvanized and Galvannealed DP Steels
465.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

466.prez_name: New Filler Metal for Producing High-Speed Welds in Thin-Gauge Coated Steels with Minimal Porosity
466.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

467.prez_name: Obtaining Corrosion Zinc Aluminum Coatings on the Car Parts
467.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

468.prez_name: Reactive Wetting of Advanced High Strength Steels by a Zn-Al-Mg Bath
468.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

469.prez_name: Study on Selective Oxidation of a Mn-Al Advanced High Strength Steel
469.symp_name: Advances in Zinc-coated Sheet Steel Processing and Properties

470.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
470.prez_abstract: While additive manufacturing (AM)-technologies are already state-of-the-art in plastics processing or metalworking, the ceramic industry has been reluctant to implement this kind of technology due to the quality of the parts produced by this means. In recent years novel AM techniques dedicated to ceramics have been introduced, one of them being the lithography-based ceramic manufacturing (LCM)-process. This technique is based on the selective curing of photosensitive slurry. During this process, a crosslinked photopolymer matrix is generated, which acts as scaffold and binder for the ceramic particles and can subsequently be removed at elevated temperatures. Due to this approach, the LCM-process achieves high green densities and enables the production of strong, dense and accurate ceramic parts showing very similar properties to classically formed ceramics. For alumina, a relative density of over 99.4 % and 4-point bending strength of over 430 MPa with a Weibull modulus of 11 could be realized.

471.prez_name: An Exact DLVO Solution for Various Powders in Non-aqueous Mediums to Predict Suspension Stability
471.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
471.prez_abstract: Non-retarded Hamaker constants and double-layer potentials were calculated for 10 different colloids in 11 different suspension mediums and were then used to calculate the total interaction potential of particle-medium pairs via DLVO theory.  Colloids were selected based on crystal structure and bonding and included diamond, SiC, Cu and Co (both metallic particles and oxide particles), SiO2 (crystalline and amorphous), TiO2 (anatase and rutile), and a-Al2O3. The mediums were selected based on polarity and functional group and included methanol, ethanol, isopropanol, 2-butanol, acetone, 2-butanone, toluene, heptane, octanoic acid, poly(ethylene glycol), and water.  The double-layer interaction potential, and correspondingly, the predicted suspension stability, were calculated using an exact solution of the Poisson-Boltzmann differential equation.  To assess the theoretical prediction, rheology of each suspension combination was measured.  The results indicate that DLVO can be utilized to accurately predict colloidal stability in non- aqueous mediums.

472.prez_name:
Bonding of Sapphire to Sapphire, Ceramics, and Metallics Opening New Application Solutions 
Collaborative Development between Gavish and CRC
472.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
472.prez_abstract: Industrial sapphire has many applications in optics, aerospace, medical, semiconductor, and analytical instruments. Joining sapphire to itself and other materials is an important capability to enable industrial applications.  Currently, methods to join sapphire are limited to adhesives, solders, and direct-bonding.  Adhesives and solders are not compatible with many applications, specifically those requiring elevated temperatures and/or corrosive chemistries.  Direct-bonding has very limited applications; it is extremely costly, low yield, and applicable only for matched crystal structures.  We have demonstrated the feasibility of using a newly developed process to bond sapphire which provides high-temperature, corrosion resistant bonds which can join sapphire regardless of crystal structure to itself and to other materials.  This capability opens significant new market opportunities for industrial sapphire.  A number of successful applications of this bonding technology as well as overview applications now in the early development phase will be detailed.

473.prez_name: Colloidal Behavior of Alumina Suspended in an Aqueous Medium
473.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
473.prez_abstract: The rheological properties of colloidal alumina powders dispersed via either electrostatic or electrosteric stabilization technologies will be discussed.  Two approaches were evaluated for electrosteric stabilization:  organic and inorganic polyelectrolytes.  The results demonstrate that electrostatic stabilization approaches include limitations associated with corrosion of the particle surface and increasing counter-ion concentrations.  The electrosteric approach, however, appeared to be independent of the choice of dispersant (either organic, such as PAA or inorganic, such as Na-silicate) and is only limited by counter-ion concentration at high solids loadings or with high surface area alumina powders.  An approach for estimating the stability cutoff will be presented.

474.prez_name: Corrosion of Alumina Powders in an Aqueous Medium
474.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
474.prez_authors: William M. Carty, Hyojin  Lee, Randy  Mauzy, Paul  Ormond
474.prez_abstract: Alumina is typically viewed as a remarkably robust and corrosion resistant material when in an aqueous suspension.  That is true provided the pH of that suspension remains below the isoelectric point.  If the pH exceeds the iep, typically found to be between 8.5 and 9.0, the alumina particle surfaces start to corrode rapidly as evidenced as a disruption in the suspension flow behavior.  In addition to data supporting corrosion, it is proposed that the introduction of a protective colloid (such as colloidal silica), or a polyelectrolyte dispersant, prevents this corrosion and increases suspension stability and lifetime.

475.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
475.prez_authors: Zhenyu  Liu, Chen  Chen, Peter  Leicht, Rodrigo  Cooper, Dev  Banerjee
475.prez_abstract: Inspired by nanolayer coatings of PVD and multilayer CVD coatings development, we demonstrate a couple of potential Al2O3-based nanosomposite systems deposited by CVD process directly using multilayer concepts with well-controlled deposition conditions to maintain the deposited “thin film” at early stage, nucleation regime.  As a consequence, the “thin film” would maintain at the island forms or particles/nanoparticles states with the size smaller than 100 nm at least in one dimension, whilst the alumina matrix would keep depositing to form a continuous matrix.  Ultimately, a nanocomposite coating can be formed with improved wear resistance and metal-cutting performance. The ability to process nanocomposite by direct nucleation and growth of ceramic materials via CVD technique should provide new technical opportunity on the advanced materials development and applications.

476.prez_name: Densification and Grain Growth of Alumina in the Presence of a Liquid Phase
476.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
476.prez_authors: Sarah  Whipkey, Hyojin  Lee, William  Carty
476.prez_abstract: Sintering polycrystalline Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> in the presence of a liquid phase is a common industrial practice. The extent to which a liquid phase contributes to microstructural evolution in alumina, however, does not appear to have been addressed in the literature. This study investigated the effects of a liquid phase on the densification and grain growth of alumina during sintering. Three alumina samples were created: one without a liquid phase (99.8% alumina) and two 94% alumina compositions with a liquid phase composed of either a normal or invert glass composition (RO:SiO<sub>2</sub> = 1:2 or 2:1, respectively). The samples were sintered under several conditions, and the resulting density and average grain size were measured for each. The results indicate that the grain growth kinetics are slowed by the presence of a liquid phase compared to the high alumina composition.

477.prez_name: Evaluation of Polishing Damage and Relief in Sintered Alumina
477.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
477.prez_authors: Alicia  Mayville, Hyojin  Lee, William  Carty
477.prez_abstract: It is well known that grinding and polishing processes create damage on the surface of alumina and on ceramics in general.  The extent of this damage is often associated with a reduction in mechanical properties but is typically only qualitatively characterized using microscopy or surface roughness measurements.  This work evaluated the level of damage on sintered alumina compacts using coarse metal-bonded diamond wheels via X-ray diffraction.  The shift in the XRD peaks indicated surface compression compared to an unground surface.  The level of residual compressive strain was reduced by polishing using smaller diamond grits and further reduced by a high-temperature annealing step after the polishing was completed.

478.prez_name: High Purity Alumina for Hierarchical Porous Ceramics
478.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
478.prez_authors: Justin  Otto, Lionel  Bonneau, Philippe  Auroy
478.prez_abstract: As more performance is continually demanded from ceramics, so too are the capabilities of the raw materials.  Baikowski would like to introduce a new class of high purity aluminum oxide powders that will allow application engineers to continue to break the existing limits on ceramic technologies. Through a unique synthesis methodology, Baikowski has been able to produce an extremely high purity (99.99+%) aluminum oxide powder that is easily shaped into complex geometries and hold a very specified hierarchical macro and mesoporosity structure for projected use in highly specific catalytic support or diffusion applications. We will examine the powder synthesis, shaping, and ceramic properties associated with this new particle.

479.prez_name: Injection Molding Different Shaped Ceramics and Understanding Process Variation
479.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
479.prez_abstract: Polycrystalline alumina (PCA) in high pressure discharge lamps can have different shapes, such as spherical with two small openings or cylindrical, plugged with larger openings for electrodes. Cylindrical tubes can be vertically extruded, but due to low material efficiencies, injection molding was investigated. Electrical injection molders have precision to modify the velocity and easily mold arc tubes as well as complex shapes. Besides the molding equipment, a major modification is the debinding process, which uses a wicking agent to remove a percentage of binder. Due to one end of the tube being open, the wicking agent can coat all surfaces compared to the outer surface of a hollow body. Testing the effect of the direction of tube opening through debind resulted in varying sintered dimensions. Results show that the more intimate contact of the wicking agent produced increased shrinkage in the sintered state.

480.prez_name: Investigating the Origin of Abnormal Grain Growth in Specialty Alumina
480.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
480.prez_authors: Christopher J. Marvel, Yan  Wang, Animesh  Kundu, Jeffrey M. Rickman, Martin P. Harmer, Joe  Atria, Charles  Compson
480.prez_abstract: Abnormal grain growth during sintering of compacts made from specialty alumina is still rather unpredictable. While the influence of solitary dopants such as silica, calcia, and magnesia regarding grain growth have been determined in high-purity aluminas, the interdependence of numerous impurities found in commercial specialty aluminas is still relatively undetermined. This work studied the relationships between processing variables, impurities, and microstructure using a multi-scale characterization approach to investigate the origin of abnormal grain growth. Specifically, electron backscatter diffraction (EBSD) was utilized to “fingerprint” (i.e. map grain size and shape distributions) different microstructures exhibiting abnormal grain growth, and aberration-corrected electron microscopy was used to reveal the chemistry and structure of abnormal grain boundaries. It was determined that both the overall impurity content and the relative amounts of impurities dictated microstructure evolution.

481.prez_name: Modified Hydrothermal Synthesis of α-Alumina Nanoparticles below the Thermodynamic Size Limit
481.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
481.prez_authors: John  Drazin, James  Wollmershauser, Edward  Gorzkowski
481.prez_abstract: Nanocrystalline α-Alumina, with high optical clarity, is a highly desired material for its high hardness (through Hall-Petch strengthening) in ballistic armor applications. Unfortunately, α-alumina has birefringence, scattering some of the transmitted light naturally limiting its real in line transmission. With grain sizes below 30 to 40 nm, theoretical considerations predict an α-alumina plate would have minimal scattering loses. Currently, there is no commercially viable synthesis approach to produce nanocrystalline α-alumina nanoparticles with these grain sizes or smaller required to be sintered. Therefore, in this work, a modified hydrothermal synthesis technique using co-precipitated aluminum hydroxide powder as a precursor is explored to produce the desired grain sizes in the α-alumina powder.

482.prez_name: New Approaches for Grain Boundary Informatics as a Pathway to Processing Reliability
482.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
482.prez_authors: Jeffrey M. Rickman, Yan  Wang, Christopher J. Marvel, Martin P. Harmer, Anthony D. Rollett, Charles  Compson
482.prez_abstract: A major concern in the processing of commercial ceramics is batch-to-batch reproducibility. Impurities from raw materials and processing make identifying the most efficient and consistent processing strategy difficult. We propose a new approach consisting of a versatile Monte-Carlo based canonical correlation analysis (CCAMC) to identify a more predictable and reliable processing strategy. Contrary of other CCA methods, which also simplify a multidimensional parameter space by identifying combinations of variables that are maximally correlated, CCAMC identifies non-linear functions of the variables that lead to stronger input/output correlations. This approach also facilities the design of grain boundary types or networks that improve product reliability. We will show how CCAMC has been utilized to determine the link between processing variables and microstructure of doped aluminas, and to relate microstructure to the optoelectronic properties of CuInSe solar cells.

483.prez_name: Particle Packing and Sintering of 3-D Printed Alumina
483.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
483.prez_authors: Patrick  Cigno, William M. Carty, Hyojin  Lee
483.prez_abstract: 3-D printing has become a major “buzz word” in both the ceramic industry and in academia in recent years due to potential of becoming a “miracle” forming technique.  The primary problem is that particles that have sufficient flow have insufficient surface area to promote sintering and powders that sinter do not have the requisite flow characteristics.  This study focused on improving the pressureless sintering of 3-D printed alumina by improving the packing efficiency of the powder bed and through the addition of a liquid phase.  The packing efficiency of the 3-D printing powder bed was improved to 36.8% through mixed particle size granulation consisting of 70% 5 µm particles and 30% 0.5 µm particles and an 80:20 coarse to fine granule ratio for the feedstock while maintaining sufficient flow for printing.  Printed samples containing 20 weight percent of a commercial borosilicate glass frit obtained a relative density of 84% when fired in air at 1400°C.

484.prez_name: Pore Size Analysis for Alumina Ceramics
484.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
484.prez_abstract: Dielectric breakdown strength of alumina spark plug insulators is influenced by the internal porosity of the ceramic, following a weakest link theory.  In order to ensure reliable performance it is necessary to characterize the porosity of the ceramic.  A method was developed to characterize the porosity using image analysis on polished cross sections, with an emphasis on the largest pores. This method was extended to pore size analysis from computed tomography (CT scans) using nanofocus X-ray equipment, which permits investigation of a much larger volume of the material.  Statistical methods of representing the pore size distributions and issues with defining a metric for describing the critical pores are discussed.

485.prez_name: Powder Chemistry Effects on the Sintering of Bayer Alumina
485.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
485.prez_authors: Tobias  Frueh, Elizabeth  Kupp, Charles  Compson, Joe  Atria, Gary  Messing
485.prez_abstract: Commercial high purity Bayer aluminas are typically 99.8 - 99.9% pure and contain Na2O, SiO2, Fe2O3, and CaO as main impurities. During heating these impurities can combine to form a nanometer thick liquid phase at the grain boundary that controls the sintering behavior of the powder. We systematically show how the sintering kinetics and fundamental sintering mechanisms of Bayer alumina change as a function of the total amount and fractions of the different impurities and dopants. High-resolution TEM and EDS studies reveal how physical and chemical characteristics of the grain boundaries change as a function of powder chemistry, leading to an understanding of the observed sintering behavior. By comparing the sintering kinetics, grain boundary chemistries and structures of MgO-free and MgO-doped Bayer aluminas, we identify when MgO affects sintering and gain some insight about the role of MgO during the sintering of Bayer alumina.

486.prez_name: Reducing the Size of Alpha-alumina Nanocrystals below the Thermodynamic Size Limit and Related Sintering Phenomena
486.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
486.prez_authors: James A Wollmershauser, Boris N Feigelson, John W Drazin, Dana A Kazerooni, Edward P Gorzkowski
486.prez_abstract: In material systems with competing phase stabilities, such as alumina, simple growth techniques for nanocrystal synthesis are generally restricted to producing the thermodynamically lowest energy crystal structure. In the case of alumina, the excess enthalpy of high specific surface area structures forces synthesized nanocrystals to adopt crystal structures that deviate from those observed in large crystals. Additionally, coarsening kinetics at moderate temperatures prohibit phase transformation-based synthesis routes from producing the smallest alpha-alumina nanocrystals. In this work, high-energy processing was developed in order to reduce alpha-alumina crystallites down to sub-10 nm crystallites; below the thermodynamic crossover size limit. The nanocrystals were subsequently washed to remove contamination on the nanocrystal surfaces incurred during the high-energy process. The smallest crystallite size of high-energy processed powder was 8.7 nm.  Interestingly, issues related to the processing of the nanocrystals and intrinsic alpha-alumina coarsening rates impose difficulties when attempting to sinter the alpha-alumina nanocrystalline powder.

487.prez_name: Second Phase Formation During Sintering of Bayer Alumina
487.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
487.prez_authors: Tobias  Frueh, Elizabeth  Kupp, Charles  Compson, Joe  Atria, Gary  Messing
487.prez_abstract: Commercial high purity Bayer aluminas are typically 99.8 - 99.9% pure and contain Na2O, SiO2, Fe2O3, and CaO as main impurities and MgO as a sintering additive. Our studies show that a small amount of second phase can form during sintering of Bayer alumina powders due to these impurities. XRD and EDS studies showed that the observed second phase is sodium beta alumina and the number frequency and size of beta alumina grains in the microstructure strongly depends on the heat treatment and chemistry of the powder, i.e. the amount and ratios of Na2O, MgO, and SiO2. In this work we report the conditions for the formation of beta alumina in Bayer alumina and investigate the fundamental mechanisms for nucleation and growth. Finally, we explore potential strategies to avoid the formation of beta alumina in Bayer alumina.

488.prez_name: Surface Finish Improvements for Alumina Components Shaped by Green Grinding
488.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
488.prez_abstract: The surface finish of alumina spark plug insulators is controlled by the green state profile grinding process used to shape the insulators.  Surface texture in the form of parallel grooves formed by the abrasive grit of the grinding wheel can influence the mechanical durability of the insulator and promote adhesion of combustion deposits in the harsh environment of the internal combustion engine.  The objective of this project was to evaluate methods of improving the surface finish of alumina spark plug insulators.  Insulators surface were modified by two different methods, tumbling with ceramic tumbling media and polishing with diamond pastes. Surface roughness and  bending strength were tested with and without subsequent heat treatment.  The results demonstrate the effectiveness of the surface finishing methods and it was shown that the influence of the surface condition on the mechanical strength were consistent with well-established principles of fracture mechanics.

489.prez_name: Synthesis of Continuous Zirconia Modified Alumina Fibers
489.symp_name: Alumina at the Forefront of Technology II
489.prez_authors: Jingyu  Li, Tong  Zhao, Zihai  Yang, Yuanchao  Li
489.prez_abstract: Continuous ZrO2-modified Al2O3 ceramic fibers with high relative density and an average grain sized of 300nm were prepared by melt spinning process of a mixture of polymeric  ZrO2-Al2O3 precursor and alumina nanopowders. The sintering parameters and recipe were optimized with respect to powder content and type, powder size and ZrO2 content based on the influences on the average grain size, relative density, tensile strength and high temperature performance of the final ceramic fibers. The results showed that high temperature calcination contributed to the synchronized grain growth of both precursor-derived and doped alumina powders. The coarsening of alumina grain size could be restrained at high temperatures after introduction of a Zirconia-forming constituent.
