521.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
521.prez_abstract: The integration of materials with disparate electrical, optical, thermal, and mechanical properties into a single fiber with complex architecture and diverse functionalities presents new opportunities for extending fiber applications in both civil and military areas. The blooming development of materials science in various of fields should play a more powerful impact when it incorporates with fibers. Furthermore, the combination of fiber technique in photonics, sensing, nanofabrication, and energy areas with the traditional textile manufacturing technique would open a number of possibilities. The challenges hindering the thriving development of the advanced functional fibers are the missing bridge between each discipline (materials, chemistry, electronics, mechanics, photonics) and the powerless bond between academia and industry manufacturing. Here in this talk, I will introduce our effects on producing a new type of fiber based on a composite that fabricated as ceramic materials.

522.prez_name: Advanced Nanocomposite Ceramics for IR Solid State Lasers: A Series of Unfortunate Trade-offs
522.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
522.prez_authors: Victoria L. Blair, Zackery  Fleischman, Nicholas  Ku
522.prez_abstract: Transparency is difficult to achieve in ceramic nanocomposites because the material incorporates two phases with different indices of refraction leading to significant light scattering at grain boundaries. We have developed a co-precipitation method where the components are synthesized together for intimate mixing on the smallest scale to produce high purity powders with small crystallites which can lead to translucent parts upon hot pressing. We aim to use a ceramic nanocomposite containing Er:Y<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> and MgO to combat two challenges for mid-infrared laser materials: dissipation of heat generated in lasing and luminescence quenching by multi-phonon relaxation. However, a trade-off is observed when varying the ratio of the two constituents. If too little Er:Y<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> is included, the MgO grains grow too large, if too much Er:Y<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> is included, the material becomes opaque. This presentation will show our efforts to balance the ratio of components to achieve optimal transparency and luminescence behavior.

523.prez_name: C-1: Effects of Sintering Temperature on Structure and Photoluminescence of Eu-activated-Mg-doped Silicon Oxynitride Phosphors
523.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
523.prez_authors: Ying  Zhang, Jianglin  Qiu, Yuqian  Zhou, Xuan  Cheng, Jingyu  Sun
523.prez_abstract: A series of europium (Eu)-activated and magnesium (Mg)-doped silicon oxynitride phosphors were prepared by a novel polymer-derived method at the sintering temperatures varying from 1300℃ to 1650℃. The effects of sintering temperatures on crystal structures, surface morphologies, photoluminescence properties and chemical compositions of the phosphors were systematically investigated. The results revealed that the formations of SiO2 and Si2ON2 phases started at 1300℃. The β-Si3N4 phase was initially formed at 1400℃, and became well developed at 1550℃ and better crystallized at 1650℃. The phosphor sintered at 1650℃ achieved the strongest emission intensity and exhibited broad red emission at 620 nm when excited at 390 nm. The blue emission at 475 nm with the excitation of 370 nm and yellow emission at 577 nm with the excitation of 390 nm were observed with the phosphors sintered at 1400℃ and 1550℃, respectively.

524.prez_name: C-2: Preparation of Zirconia-strengthened Alumina by Polymeric Preceramic Method
524.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
524.prez_authors: Yuanchao  Li, Zihai  Yang, Wenfeng  Qiu
524.prez_abstract: A water soluble and Y-containing polyzirconoxane was synthesized and used as polymeric preceramic for Y2O3-partially stabilized ZrO2. Oxide ceramic powders could be easily dispersed well in the Y2O3-ZrO2 precursor solution to form a stable slurry. Thus, proper amount of Y2O3-ZrO2 precursors could be easily coated on the powders in spray granulation process by using polymeric preceramic as a binder. Composite ceramics of Al2O3 and Y2O3-partially stabilized ZrO2 (YSZ) were prepared by dry pressing and pressureless sintering of the spray-dried powder produced by Y2O3-ZrO2 precursor and submicrometer Al2O3 powders. Such homogeneous addition of YSZ in alumina could effectively reduce sintering temperature and greatly restrain the coarsening of alumina grain size. Its positive effect on fracture strength of the PSZ-Al2O3 composite ceramics was also studied.

525.prez_name: Coherent Poly-propagation of Diffracted White Light in a Natural Silicate
525.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
525.prez_abstract: This research examined a naturally occurring material, comprised of highly ordered silicon nano-spheres, that exhibits coherent poly-propagation (CPP). A CPP material causes incident white light to diffracts into the distinct spectrum of the constituent frequencies of the incident light while propagating the intact shape of the incident light source. CPD material causes duplications of the shape of the incident light source in each diffracted frequency. One possible application of CPP material. Diffracting poly-frequency photonic light into its constituent colors is not a property of fiber-optic cable. Rather, it is a property of diffraction materials that act as photonic beam splitters to transition particular cables from carrying poly-frequency photons to fewer frequencies so that other cables can be made to carry the remaining frequencies. At each such diffraction transition, the system incurs a loss of photon density. This research material demonstrates properties that may be utilized to lessen such loss.

526.prez_name: Correlation between Cr3+ Luminescence and Oxygen Vacancy Disorder in SrTiO3 under MeV Ion Irradiation
526.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
526.prez_authors: Miguel L. Crespillo Almenara, J. T. Graham, Fernando  Agulló-López, Yanwen  Zhang, William J. Weber
526.prez_abstract: SrTiO3, a clear example of a strongly correlated electronic system, has attracted recently much attention because it exhibits a rich variety of outstanding physicochemical properties and considerable potential for technological applications. Novel insights into the near infrared luminescence emission of Cr3+ centers in stoichiometric SrTiO3 are presented under 3 MeV proton irradiation at temperatures of 100 K, 170 K and room temperature. Our main purpose is to investigate the role of the oxygen vacancies introduced by irradiation on the shape and yield of induced luminescence spectra, offering a route to explore the interplay between the Cr3+ luminescence at 1.55 eV and oxygen disorder. A correlation is found suggesting irradiation-induced oxidation of Cr3+ (Cr3+ → Crn+, n>3) by trapping of holes, while electrons are self-trapped as Ti3+. This work was supported in part by the U.S. Department of Energy, Office of Basic Energy Sciences, Materials Sciences and Engineering Division.

527.prez_name: Current Progress on Solid-state Single Crystal Growth in Sr5(PO4)3F
527.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
527.prez_abstract: We herein report and discuss current progress on the solid-state single crystal growth of Sr5(PO4)3F, in conjunction with critical perspectives on the field of solid-state single crystal growth. In the discussed study, both conventional solid-state heat treatment and a field-assisted solid-state conversion method were applied to convert a polycrystal from a c-cut seed crystal. The results show that the application of a DC electric field may cause a reduction in grain boundary energy, which significantly enhances crystal growth. Other factors that might affect migration of the single crystal into the polycrystal, such as the effects of space charge and impurity ions, were also investigated. The exaggerated crystal growth from certain crystallographic planes was found to be independent of grain growth in the polycrystalline matrix, temperature, and external field. Such results may point to a new approach to achieving greater degrees of crystal growth in the SSCG of anisotropic crystals.

528.prez_name: Designing Transparent Ceramics for Electro-optic and Magneto-optic Light Manipulation
528.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
528.prez_abstract: Precise control of light has facilitated an incredible array of photonic devices from lasers to optical telecommunications. Electro-optic (EO) materials are vital to the photonic industry since the modulation of light is best accomplished by EO materials such as lithium niobate (LN). For example, optical-beam deflection, giant-optical-pulse generation, telecommunication optical switching, Q -switching, and mode-locking of lasers are all accomplished by EO modulation.  Increased EO coefficients lead to more compact and potentially less-expensive devices, expanding the proliferation of EO modulation in laser systems for scientific, medical, and manufacturing applications. We will discuss processing procedures (powder preparation and densification) that lead to viable EO and magneto optical ceramic materials. Specifically, we will show results on the processing of barium titanate based solid solutions and rare earth oxides. The role of microstructure—particularly the fine grain size—on the transparency and other important optical properties will be emphasized.

529.prez_name: Effect of Dopants on the Microstructure Evolution and Sintering Kinetics of PMN-PT Ceramics
529.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
529.prez_authors: Xuan  Chen, Shi  Chen, Romain  Gaume
529.prez_abstract: We will be reporting on the sintering kinetics and microstructure evolution of Pb-, Y-, La-, Gd-, and Ba-doped PMN-PT ceramics reactively sintered at temperatures between 850 and 1250°C. All sintered ceramics have a final relative density greater than 98%. With the exception of La-doping, all additives yield samples with minor pyrochlore phase contamination after sintering. We found that rare-earth dopants with large ionic radii are more effective at suppressing grain-growth than those with small ionic radii. In this respect, lanthanum-doped PMN-PT samples exhibit a very singular sintering behavior, in which phase-pure ceramics develop into fine-grained, unfaceted microstructures. This property enables the fabrication of fully dense, transparent La-doped PMN-PT ceramics.

530.prez_name: Effect of Minor Impurities on the Fabrication of Transparent Ceramics
530.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
530.prez_authors: Koji  Morita, Byung-Nam  Kim, Hidehiro  Yoshida, Keijiro  Hiraga, Yoshio  Sakka
530.prez_abstract: In order to obtain transparency in polycrystalline ceramics, it is required to reduce the residual porosity to extremely low level (<0.01%). Recently, spark-plasma-sintering (SPS) technique has been utilized to fabricate pore-free dense transparent ceramics. However, the SPS processed oxides exhibit discoloration. For example, the discoloration in spinel can be explained by the combination of carbon contaminations and lattice defects, which are introduced in the matrix during the SPS processing. Since the carbon phases transform to CO/CO<SUB>2</SUB> within the materials by the post-annealing in air, it is very difficult to remove the carbon from the sintered bulk materials. In addition to the contamination and defects formed during the sintering processing, pre-existing minor impurities also strongly affect the microstructures and resultant optical properties of ceramics. In the presentation, we will discuss the effect of the minor impurities and contamination, on the transparency of polycrystalline ceramics.

531.prez_name: Effect of SiO2 and MgO on the Sintering of High Density Bulk YIG Ceramics
531.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
531.prez_authors: Matthew  Julian, Clay  French, Romain  Gaume
531.prez_abstract: Yttrium Iron Garnet (YIG) is an important material in microwave applications and infrared magneto optical components used as Faraday rotators in lasers or imaging of superconductors. When processed in bulk polycrystalline form, the transmission of this cubic material is greatly affected by non-stoichiometry and porosity content. This work investigates the effects of SiO2 and MgO as sintering additives on the fabrication of YIG ceramics by way of conventional solid-state reactive (CSSR) sintering at 1380C for differing soak times. Specifically, we will be discussing the effect of these additives on the microstructure and densification kinetics and show that IR transparent bulk sized ceramics can be obtained with a grain size below 10 um.

532.prez_name: Effects of Surface Roughness on Optical Characteristics of Ho-doped Polycrystalline YAG Fibers
532.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
532.prez_authors: Hyunjun  Kim, Randall  Hay, Sean  McDaniel, Gary  Cook, Nicholas  Usechak, Augustine  Urbas, Kathleen  Shugart, Ali  Kadhim, HeeDong  Lee, Benjamin  Griffin, Dean  Brown, Randall  Corns
532.prez_abstract: Transparent polycrystalline ceramics have many advantages as laser gain media. Fibers have other advantages such as compactness, vibration-resistance, and reduced cooling requirements. Transparent polycrystalline ceramic fibers take advantage of the thermal and optical properties of ceramics and of fibers. We have been developing polycrystalline YAG fibers for optical applications. It was found that surface roughness caused by grain boundary grooving in polycrystalline fibers makes a significant contribution to optical scattering. A lot of effort went to develop a mechanical polishing method for polycrystalline YAG fibers. A Ho:YAG fiber with a diameter of 31 µm was prepared. Surface roughness was reduced by polishing, which decreased the fiber scattering coefficient from 76 m-1 to 35 m-1. Lasing tests were done on this fiber with SF57 Schott glass cladding. Lasing was confirmed by spectrum narrowing with threshold pump power lower than 500 mW and a slope efficiency of 7%.

533.prez_name: High Transparency Cr,Nd:LuAG Ceramics Prepared with MgO Additive
533.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
533.prez_authors: Pande  Zhang, Benxue   Jiang, Long  Zhang
533.prez_abstract: Cr (0.2 at.%) and Nd (0.8 at.%) co-doped Lu3Al5O12ceramics were fabricated with MgO as the sinteringadditive. The addition of a small amount of MgO can affect the grain boundary mobility and influencethe number and location of micropores in ceramics during the sintering process. The results show that when the MgO content is 0.02 wt.%, high-transparency Cr,Nd:LuAG ceramics can be obtained by vacuumsintering at 1670◦C for 5 h followed by hot isostatic pressing (HIP) post-sintering at 1750◦C in an argonatmosphere (P = 200 MPa) for 5 h. The optimum in-line transmittance of the HIPed Cr,Nd:LuAG ceramics(3 mm thick) is 83.5% at a wavelength of 840 nm and 84.0% at 710 nm.

534.prez_name: Improvement of Optical Transparency of Non-cubic Ceramic Polycrystals by Grain Orientation under Magnetic Field
534.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
534.prez_authors: Ying  Shi, Lincong  Fan, Debao  Lin, Lei  Zhang, Jianjun  Xie, Fang  Lei
534.prez_abstract: Low optical transparency of non-cubic ceramic polycrystals originated from considerable light scattering in the grain boundaries between anisotropic grains. The influence of refractive-index difference can be minimized by making the predominant orientation of the grains coincided with the direction of the optic axis. Such ceramics were simply fabricated by exposing the slip casting process to a strong magnetic field followed by the traditional densification processing for translucent non-cubic ceramics. Compared with non-textured SPS ZnO sample and HIP LSO specimen, the in-line optical transmission of textured ZnO transparent ceramic was improved greatly from 18.8% to 35.8% at 600 nm, and orientated LSO translucent ceramic increased its optical transmittance from 1.4% to 6.6% at 420 nm. XRD and EBSD were employed to investigate the mechanism of improvement.

535.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
535.prez_authors: Woohong (Rick)  Kim, Colin  Baker, Guillermo  Villalobos, Jesse  Frantz, Brandon  Shaw, Bryan  Sadowski, Shyam  Bayya, Jason  Myers, Darryl  Boyd, Lynda  Busse, Ishwar  Aggarwal, Jasbinder  Sanghera, Vihn  Nguyen
535.prez_abstract: In this paper, we report our recent progress in the development of various IR optical materials from ceramics, glasses, single crystals, and organic-inorganic hybrid polymers for DOD applications. We have developed high quality ceramic, glass, and glass-ceramic materials for low loss and rugged IR windows for high-energy laser systems. Various rare-earth sesquioxide ceramics have been successfully developed to demonstrate high efficiency laser oscillation. High quality fibers have been fabricated from undoped and RE-doped glasses, ceramics, and single crystals to demonstrate excellent IR transmission as well as high efficiency laser oscillation. We also developed a new class of IR transmitting and high refractive index inorganic-organic polymeric hybrid materials. In this presentation, we report the synthesis, purification and post-process techniques to prepare high purity materials suitable for IR applications. The optical, spectral and physical properties as well as the device performance from these IR optical materials are also presented.

536.prez_name: Microstructure Evolution of Europium Doped Magnesium Aluminate Spinel
536.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
536.prez_authors: Amanda Rochelle Krause, Carlen  Donahue, Animesh  Kundu, Richard  Vinci, Martin  Harmer
536.prez_abstract: Magnesium aluminate spinel is a desirable material for transparent armor because of its high hardness and wide range of optical transparency. However, the microstructure is difficult to control during the high temperature sintering that is necessary to achieve low porosity. Rare earth dopants have low solubility in spinel and segregate at the boundaries, providing a potential method of controlling grain boundary mobility. Previously, Eu-doped (500 ppm) MgAl<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB> was found to undergo a complexion transition that lead to a bimodal grain distribution at high temperatures (1400-1600 <SUP>o</SUP>C). Here, MgAl<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB> was doped with lower Eu-content (100 ppm) to investigate how a change in chemical potential affects the complexion transition. The resulting microstructure evolution and its effect on fracture toughness are elucidated.

537.prez_name: Microstructure, Mechanical, and Optical Properties of Nd,Y:CaF2 Transparent Ceramics
537.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
537.prez_authors: Yiguang  Jiang, Benxue  Jiang, Long  Zhang
537.prez_abstract: The Nd,Y-codoped CaF2 transparent polycrystalline ceramics were prepared by the ceramization of single crystals technique. The crystallization behaviors, microstructures, mechanical properties, and optical performances were studied. Transparent Nd,Y-codoped CaF2 ceramics (6-mm thick) achieved 93.7% transmittance at 1053 nm and >91% average transmittance over 200-1100 nm. Furthermore, transparent Nd,Y-codoped CaF2 ceramics exhibited low light scattering, superior fracture toughness (K1c ~0.71 MPa m1/2), strong fluorescence emission, long lifetime (τ=477 µs), and large FWHM (29.2nm). Meanwhile, a continuous-wave laser operation with an output power of 35 mW was also obtained through the application of a fiber-coupled laser diode with a central wavelength of approximately 808 nm.

538.prez_name: Microstructure, Optical, and Scintillation Properties of Ce:Gd2YAl2Ga3O12 Transparent Ceramics
538.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
538.prez_abstract: Inorganic scintillator materials are widely use in neutron detect, high energy particle physical experiments, new energy resource exploration and X-ray security, especially in medical imaging techniques . In this study, Cerium doped Gd2YGa3Al2O12 (GYGAG) ceramic with good performances have been fabricated by sintering in oxygen atmosphere and hot isostatically pressed (HIP). The microstructure, optical, scintillation characteristics of Ce:GYGAG ceramic were investigated. Transparent ceramic Ce:GYGAG ceramic achieves 78% transmittance in range from 500 to 800 nm. The light yield within 0.75μs shaping time in Ce:GYGAG ceramic is about 43200Ph/MeV under the 137Cs γ-ray irradiation. The result of using electron paramagnetic resonance indicate that there are Ce4+ ions in the oxygen-annealed Ce:GYGAG scintillator ceramics. The valence of Ce ions in the oxygen-annealed and hydrogen-annealed Ce:GYGAG scintillator ceramics was confirmed by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy. Scintillator performance affected by the different of anneal atmospheres are discussed

539.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
539.prez_abstract: Polycrystalline YAG or Sesquioxide ceramics can generate highly efficient lasers, and it was also demonstrated high power laser and new functionalities that cannot be achieved from conventional single crystal. What will be the next important technology in laser optics? We have produced TAG (Tb3Al5O12) ceramic Faraday rotator, which was difficult to produce by conventional single crystal growth technology. Its Verdet constant was approximately 1.5 times higher than that of commercially available TGG (Tb3Ga5O12) Faraday rotator, and its optical loss was as low as 1/100 to the TGG single crystal grown by FZ method. In addition, compared to the single crystal Faraday rotator, ceramic Faraday rotators can be produced with several tens of times larger sizes. Even in Faraday device, now the trend is changing from single crystal materials to polycrystalline ceramics.

540.prez_name: Novel Powder Synthesis/Consolidation Processing and Characterization of Yttria-based Transparent Optical Ceramics
540.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
540.prez_abstract: Yttria-based transparent ceramics is one of the most promising transparent materials as the infrared-domes and solid-state laser host because of its high thermomechanical property and high corrosion resistance as well as broad range of IR transparency. As increasing demand for high-end optical applications recently, it is becoming important to research and produce high quality transparent ceramics. In this regard, it is still required to study on the effects of powder characteristics and sintering technologies for property improvement. Here, we investigated on the novel techniques for powder synthesis, consolidation processing with defects control, and characterized the optical and mechanical properties of the yttria-based transparent ceramics. We also introduced new strategies to improve the optical properties of the sintered products considering thermodynamics of bulk defects. The calculation based upon Mie scattering theory was established in order to characterize the pore size distribution and bulk density of the transparent ceramics.

541.prez_name: Observations in Fracture Toughness Testing of Glasses and Optical Ceramics
541.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
541.prez_abstract: Fracture toughness is a critical structural design parameter and an excellent metric to rank materials.  It determines fracture strength by way of the flaws, both inherent and induced, and defines the endpoint of the slow crack growth (SCG) curve. The fracture toughness of structural and optical ceramics, and glasses as measured by several techniques, is compared. When good metrology is employed, the results are very comparable with two exceptions:  materials exhibiting crack growth resistance and those with a low SCG exponent. For materials with R-curves, the result is a function of extension and can be minimized with short cracks.  For materials with low SCG exponents, such as glasses, elimination of the corrosive media and/or increasing the stress intensity rate minimizes effects.  A summary of values is given, and it appears that highly modified glasses exhibit lower fracture toughness and slow crack growth exponent than high purity glasses such as fused silica.

542.prez_name: Role of Atomic-level Defects and Electronic Energy Loss on Amorphization in LiNbO3 Single Crystals
542.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
542.prez_authors: Neila  Sellami, Miguel L. Crespillo, Haizhou  Xue, Yanwen  Zhang, William J. Weber
542.prez_abstract: Understanding complex non-equilibrium defect processes, where multiple irradiation mechanisms may take place simultaneously, is a long standing subject in material science. In this work, LiNbO3 has been irradiated with 0.9 MeV Si+ and 8 MeV O3+, representative of regimes where nuclear (Sn) and electronic (Se) energy losses are dominant, respectively. The evolution of damage has been investigated by Rutherford backscattering spectrometry in channeling configuration. Below the threshold for amorphous track formation in LiNbO3, irradiation of pristine samples with highly ionizing 8 MeV O3+ ions induces a crystalline to amorphous phase transition at high ion fluences. In samples pre-damaged with 0.9 MeV Si+ ions, the electronic energy loss from 8 MeV O3+ ions interacts synergistically with the pre-existing damage, resulting in a rapid, non-linear increase in damage production. There is a significant reduction in the incubation fluence for rapid amorphization with increasing amount of pre-existing damage.

543.prez_name: Spark Plasma Sintering of Transparent YAG Ceramics
543.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
543.prez_authors: Takashi  Goto, Ying  Li, Hirokazu  Katsui
543.prez_abstract: Spark plasma sintering (SPS) is a versatile technique to prepare fully dense ceramics at a short time and relatively low temperature.  In order to use SPS commercially to prepare transparent ceramics, the sintering process of SPS should be understood and optimized for practical applications. Yttrium aluminum garnet (YAG) has high mechanical, thermal and optical properties, and is promising to a laser gain host material.  In this study, transparent YAG ceramics were prepared by SPS using commercial powder, and its microstructure and optical properties were investigated.  YAG powder with 0.25 mass% LiF were ball-milled, and consolidated by a two-step profile. The sintering temperature increased to 1273-1473 K at 0.83-1.67 K/s and then to 1573-1773 K at 0.05-0.5 K/s.  The transmittance depended on the two-step profile.  The maximum transmittance was 58 % at a wavelength of 550 nm and 75 % at 2200 nm.

544.prez_name: Theoretical Study on Transparent Spinel Solid Solutions through First-principles Calculation
544.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
544.prez_authors: Hao  Wang, Bingtian  Tu, Lu  Ren, Weimin  Wang, Zhengyi  Fu
544.prez_abstract: Transparent ceramics normally consist of highly dense, single phase, and cubic grains for retaining unique optical transparency. In this context, physical properties of transparent ceramics could be less affected by their microstructures. Instead, intrinsic properties of crystalline grains, which were determined by their composition, structure and bonding properties, play more important role. Thus, transparent ceramics could be readily treated as an appropriate sample studied by first-principles calculation. It is anticipated that one could further reveal the relationship among composition, structure, and properties and, in turn, search for new materials with the help of systematic theoretical study. In this work, Mg-Al-O-N defective spinel solid solutions, i.e. MgO•nAl2O3, γ-AlON, MgAlON, were studied based on the first-principles calculation. The principle for the construction of reasonable calculation models was proposed. The crystalline electronic, and bonding structures were quantitatively analyzed, and properties such as the optical, mechanical, thermal properties were investigated.

545.prez_name: Towards the Fabrication of Ba(Zr0.25Mg0.25Ta0.5)O3 Ceramics by Oxygen Controlled Sintering
545.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
545.prez_authors: Xianqiang   Chen , Yin   Liu, Yiquan  Wu
545.prez_abstract: BZMT ceramics were fabricated by oxygen-controlled pressureless sintering conducted at 1650-1800°C. The microstructural evolution of the ceramics with increasing sintering temperature was investigated by SEM, and the phase composition of the ceramics by XRD. It was determined that translucent BZMT ceramics can be obtained through sintering at 1750°C for 10hThe results indicate that intermediate-level properties can be achieved through oxygen-controlled pressureless sintering, and that through the application of an additional post-hot isostatic pressing step, it may be possible to obtain transparent BZMT ceramics.

546.prez_name: Transparent Nanocomposite Ceramics for Eye-safe Lasers and Phosphor Hosts
546.symp_name: Ceramic-based Optical Materials and Advanced Processing
546.prez_authors: Ho Jin  Ma, Wook Ki  Jung, Youngtae  Park, Do Kyung  Kim
546.prez_abstract: Transparent polycrystalline ceramics such as Y2O3, YAG and LuAG have outstanding transparency and can be a host to dope lanthanide ions for a variety of application including lasers, phosphors and scintillators ceramics. These materials are not suitable for high-power applications at high operating temperature because of the weak mechanical strength and low thermal conductivity. In addition, luminescence quenching resulted from phonon relaxation degrades the performance. An undoped composite phase with the host materials can enhance the mechanical and thermal properties although it brings about the light scattering at the grain boundaries due to a difference in the refractive index between two phases. In this study, rare earth-doped nanocomposite particles were synthesized by combustion and co-precipitation method. The consolidated transparent nanocomposite ceramics were obtained by pressure-assisted sintering method. The optical, mechanical and thermal properties of this material were analyzed.

547.prez_name: A Reax-Force-Field for Simulations of Silicon Oxycarbide Ceramics
547.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
547.prez_abstract:
We develop new parameter sets for the Reax-Force-Field for simulations of SiCO. Current implementations, which have been used for modeling of oxidation behavior of SiC, show an exaggerated propensity to segregate sp2-like carbon. We also observe a mistreatment of mixed SiCnO4-n tetrahedra, leading to fast Si-C bond rupture in such units. As a consequence, stable SiCO glass is destroyed in low-temperature simulations already. 
To derive new parameter sets, we use existing parameters for modeling of SiO2, but extend the fitting data by a library of more than 10,000 (hypothetical) crystalline SiCO models together with a library of more than 1,000 models of amorphous SiCO of various compositions, all which have been optimized by density functional methods. Suitable parameter sets are further differentiated in dynamic simulations of SiCO glass at elevated temperatures. We ultimately find new parameter sets for simulation of SiCO and will discuss their pro and cons in detail.

548.prez_name: Ab-initio Molecular Dynamic Simulations of Amorphous Nitrides at High-pressure
548.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
548.prez_abstract: We present ab-initio molecular dynamic (aiMD) simulations of high-pressure structure transformations of amorphous boron nitride and amorphous silicon nitride. Models comprise between 224 and 512 atoms, and the simulation times in the constant pressure (NPT) simulations extend 50-250 ps. At low pressure, extended “polymeric” a-BN transform into planar “turbostratic” BN, consistent with structure formation of BN observed at high-temperature and low pressures. Above 13 GPa a-BN transforms into cubic-BN. We investigate in detail the impact of Al and C as “alloying” elements on the pressure of a “phase boundary” between planar (sp2-like) and cubic (sp3-like) BN. Amorphous silicon nitride is converted into a high-pressure modification with 6-fold coordinated Si at pressures above 20 GPa.

549.prez_name: Atomic Level Simulation of Defects and Diffusion in Ceramics
549.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
549.prez_authors: Ram  Devanathan, Kerry  Garrett, Michele A. Conroy, Weilin  Jiang
549.prez_abstract: We present the findings of atomic-level simulations of defect production and atom/ion diffusion in several ceramic materials, including CeO<sub>2</sub>, UO<sub>2</sub>, ZrO<sub>2</sub> and UC.  The work bridges scales by combining defect formation and migration energies from density functional theory and experiment, molecular dynamics simulations of defect production by energetic particles, and Metropolis Monte Carlo simulation of defect evolution.  We will present the effect of structural disorder and introduction of dopants on diffusion in these ceramics.  We will also discuss strategies for extending the work to the grain scale.

550.prez_name: Characterization and Modeling of Microstructural Level Stresses in Brittle Materials
550.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
550.prez_abstract: Brittle failure is often influenced by difficult to measure and variable microstructure scale residual stresses. Recent advances in photoluminescence (PL) spectroscopy, including improved confocal laser measurement and rapid data collection spectroscopic data have established the potential to map residual stress variating with microscale spatial resolution (<2 microns) To investigate the limits of PL spectroscopy as a microscale stress mapping tool, results from the mapping stress generated in bonded, mis-oriented bi-crystals an polycrystalline alumina. These results will compared to microstructure models generated from electron backscatter diffraction (EBSD) to highlight the advances and limits of currently modeling capability to predict stresses within complex microstructures.

551.prez_name: Commonalities in Frequency-dependent Viscoelastic Damping in Glasses
551.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
551.prez_authors: Raghavan  Ranganathan, Pawel  Keblinski, Yunfeng  Shi
551.prez_abstract: Viscoelastic damping in glasses is an emerging field, with many structural applications. The nature of frequency-dependence of glass damping has hitherto not been fully understood. In this work, we use non-equilibrium molecular dynamics oscillatory shear simulations to study damping spanning nearly six decades in frequency range, in a wide range of model glasses including Cu-Zr metallic glass (MG), Wahnström glass, amorphous silica, Dzugutov glass and amorphous silicon. Firstly, for the Cu-Zr MG, we elucidate the role of quench rate, number of shear cycles, shear amplitude and shear temperature on damping characteristics. We observe striking commonalities in damping characteristics for all glasses studied - (i) a peak in the loss modulus in the high-frequency regime (~THz) arising from harmonic coupling between the vibrational modes, and (ii) persistent damping in the low-frequency regime (extending down to 10s of MHz), a result of long time-scale local, irreversible deformation.

552.prez_name: Development and Application of ReaxFF Reactive Force Field for Glass/Electrolyte Systems
552.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
552.prez_authors: Adri  van Duin, Seung Ho  Hahn, Mark  Fedkin, Yun Kyung Shin, Nabankur  Dasgupta
552.prez_abstract:
The ReaxFF bond order-based potential provides a simulation method for atomistic scale simulations on chemical reactions at the nanosecond and nanometer scale.  Since it initial development for hydrocarbons in 2001, we have found that this concept is transferable to applications to elements across the periodic table.
For all these elements we have demonstrated that ReaxFF can accurately reproduce quantum mechanics-based structures, reaction energies and reaction barriers, enabling the method to predict reaction kinetics in complicated environments at a modest computational expense.
This presentation will describe current concepts of the ReaxFF method, including parallel implementations and recently developed metadynamics options - which significantly increase its potential for surface chemistry applications. We will, in particular, focus on recent developments and application of the use of this method to silica interfaces with water and water/electrolyte mixtures, showing the influence of electrolyte composition on surface chemistry with applications to glass mechanics, tribochemistry and leaching.

553.prez_name: Direct Numerical Simulation of Failure Mechanisms in Brittle Polycrystalline Structures
553.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
553.prez_authors: Hao  Jiang, Zongyue  Fan, Bo  Li
553.prez_abstract: We propose an image-based computational tool for the high fidelity prediction of failure mechanisms in brittle polycrystalline structures. A three-dimensional finite element model of the polycrystalline structure is reconstructed based on the probability-distribution-functions (PDF) of grain sizes, orientations, and misorientation from EBSD data. The EigenFracture algorithm is employed as a variational approach to fracture mechanics. An equivalent energy-release-rate is defined at each element to evaluate the local failure state by comparing to the critical energy-release-rate, which varies at the grain boundaries and the interior of grains. In addition, constitutive models are considered as functions of the local microstructure features. As a result, a direct mesoscale simulation model is developed to resolve the anisotropic response, intergranular and transgranular fractures in brittle materials under general loading conditions. A micromechanics-based interpretation for the rate dependent strength of brittle materials is derived and verified in examples of dynamic compression tests of SiC material.

554.prez_name: Effect of Irradiation on Cement Hydrates: Evidence of a Topological Self-organization
554.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
554.prez_authors: N. M. Anoop  Krishnan, Bu  Wang, Gaurav  Sant, Mathieu  Bauchy
554.prez_abstract: Despite the crucial role of concrete in nuclear power plants, the effect of irradiation on calcium–silicate–hydrates (C–S–H, the glue of concrete) remains largely unknown. Here, based on molecular dynamics simulations, we systematically investigate the effect of neutron irradiation on C–S–H. Although C–S–H is more resistant to irradiation than fully crystalline silicates like quartz, we observe that irradiations affects C–S–H’s density, silicate mean chain length, and amount of undissociated water molecules. Based on a topological analysis, we show that these effects arise from a self-organization of the atomic network of C–S–H upon irradiation. Namely, over-coordinated C–S–H samples (i.e., with low Ca/Si molar ratios) are found to reduce their atomic connectivity towards that of an optimally connected (isostatic) network. This topological self-organization is driven by the initial presence of internal eigenstress in over-coordinated networks, and occurs through the dissociation of water molecules into hydroxyl groups, which decreases the overall degree of polymerization.

555.prez_name: Influence of Mass and Charge Disorder on Thermal Conductivity of Entropy Stabilized Oxides by Molecular Dynamics Simulation
555.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
555.prez_authors: Mina  Lim, Zsolt   Rak, Ashutosh   Giri, Samuel  Daigle, Jeffrey L Braun, Christina  Rost, Patrick  E Hopkins, Donald W Brenner
555.prez_abstract: Recent experiments have shown that the thermal conductivity of the entropy stabilized oxide (Mg0.1Co0.1Ni0.1Cu0.1Zn0.1)O0.5, termed J14, is reduced by the addition of a sixth cation Sc, Sn, Ge or Sb in an equi-molar proportion. Because classical phonon transport theory cannot account for this reduction based on mass scattering alone, we calculated thermal conductivities for these materials from molecular dynamics simulations from the Green-Kubo method using exponential-6 plus electrostatic interactions. Our simulations suggest that taken together, both changes in average mass and in electrostatic interactions due to ion addition to J14 can account for much of the reduction in thermal conductivity, with further scattering resulting from disorder in ion charges due to the structural entropy of these systems. We also evaluated whether the Bridgman equation for thermal conductivity, which has been used for ionic liquids where scattering lengths are of the order of inter-atomic distances, can be applied to these systems.

556.prez_name: Molecular Mechanisms of Amorphous Creep: Dynamical Heterogeneities in Deformation and Flow
556.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
556.prez_authors: Penghui  Cao, Michael P. Short, Sidney  Yip
556.prez_abstract: Rate-dependent phenomena in mechanical behavior are particularly vexing challenges to multiscale simulation because they are beyond the reaches of traditional molecular dynamics.  We study tensile strain evolution in a model metallic glass by metadynamics simulation at experimental time scales. Time evolutions of the local deviatoric strain and non-affine particle displacement and their statistical distributions are analyzed. The simulation results reveal clear details of atomic-level deformation and diffusion as the elementary processes that control the stress and temperature dependence of amorphous creep.  In particular, these details provide an explanation of the characteristic creep rate upturn behavior well known experimentally.  Based on the simulation results a mechanism map is established with regions of diffusional creep at low stress and high temperature and deformational creep, driven by shear transformation events, at high stress. Significance of our findings to other phenomena of slow dynamics, notably cement setting and cement paste creep, will be discussed.

557.prez_name: Rapid Composite Material Property Prediction Using Machine Learning
557.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
557.prez_authors: Grace  Gu, Chun-Teh  Chen, Markus   Buehler
557.prez_abstract: Composite development is crucial to achieve desired properties for engineering applications. Ceramics and glass, rather brittle materials, fail catastrophically with the presence of cracks. Incorporating softer materials to these materials can help alleviate stress concentration, leading to tougher composites. However, searching for the optimal designs of composites is challenging due to the astronomical number of possible combinations. Machine learning (ML) is a promising tool to overcome these limitations. Here, we apply ML to a 2-D composite system and demonstrate its potential to accurately and efficiently predict mechanical properties such as toughness and strength. Our ML model can predict the complete ranking of the properties, even when given only binary ranking information in the training process. This work paves a way to quickly discerning the mechanical properties of composites using ML, thus creating a paradigm shift in the exploration of design spaces, accelerating the discovery of new functional, customizable materials.

558.prez_name: Reaching Experimental Times at the Atomic Scale in Complex Materials: The Kinetic Activation-Relaxation Technique
558.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
558.prez_abstract: In spite of considerable advances in computational capacities over the last decades, there remains a considerable gap between experimentally relevant time scales and those accessible to atomistic simulations. This gap reflects the fundamentally multi scale nature of atomistic kinetics that can only be lifted partially through approximate methods that attempt to capture the most important aspect of specific phenomena. Among those approaches, the kinetic activation-relaxation technique (k-ART) is an off-lattice kinetic Monte Carlo with on-the-fly cataloging capabilities that allows fully atomistic second-long and more  simulations of complex alloys and amorphous systems such as amorphous silicon and steels, while incorporating exactly elastic effects. In this talk, I'll present the k-ART method, recent applications to various systems and its advantages and limitations in the study of complex materials.

559.prez_name: Tuning the Structure and Properties of Glass Aided by Computer Simulation
559.symp_name: Ceramics and Glasses Simulations and Informatics
559.prez_abstract: Using molecular dynamics simulations, our studies show that the elastic response of silica glass to initial compression gradually changes from abnormal to normal with increasing quench pressure, helium content or alkali modifier added in the glass matrix. We uncovered the structural origin of the elastic anomaly in silica glass as localized structural transitions between motifs of different stiffness that are similar to those found in its crystalline counterparts. Pressure-quenching, helium-stuffing or alkali-modifying plays a different role in changing the structure of silica glass, but all of the resulting structures reduce the propensity for such local structural transitions to take place, thus the degree of elastic anomaly.  Our studies demonstrate that by processing in ways that gradually eliminates the elastic anomaly, the degree of silica glass to undergo irreversible densification can be eventually eradicated. This provides a solid foundation for the bottom-up design of new glasses with tunable structure and properties.

560.prez_name: A Novel Approach for Selecting Grain Boundary Sets for Intergranular Fracture Studies Using Molecular Dynamics Simulations
560.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
560.prez_authors: Doruk  Aksoy, Remi  Dingreville, Douglas  Spearot
560.prez_abstract: All grain boundaries are not equal in their predisposition for fracture due to the complex coupling between lattice geometry, interfacial structure and mechanical properties. Here, a novel methodology is presented to isolate the influence of grain boundary structure on the inherent strength and work of separation of grain boundaries during intergranular fracture. Instead of constructing sets of grain boundary models by varying the misorientation angle around a fixed misorientation axis, it is proposed to create sets of grain boundaries by means of isocurves associated with important lattice properties. Such properties may include the Schmid factor for primary slip, the ratio between primary and secondary slip Schmid factors, and the elastic modulus in the loading direction. This approach eliminates the effect of lattice properties from the comparative analysis and thus enables the identification of structure-property relationships for grain boundaries.

561.prez_name: A Peridynamics-FEM Approach for Crack Path Prediction in Fiber-reinforced Composites
561.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
561.prez_authors: Quang  Truong, Srujan  Rokkam, Max  Gunzburger, Kishan  Goel
561.prez_abstract: We investigate crack propagation behavior in fiber-reinforced composite (FRC) structures using a Peridynamics (PD) approach that builds on finite element method (FEM) solution kernels. PD theory provides a means to investigate crack propagation, without the need for special treatments necessitated by conventional FEM approaches. The PD bonds representative of the composite are modeled as truss elements which accounts for the fiber/matrix micromechanics in definition of its constitutive behavior. The PD-FEM framework is implemented into a commercial FEA package using custom APIs. Subsequently, the framework is used to investigate crack propagation behavior in 3D composite structures including unidirectional composite at different fiber orientations and multidirectional composite (woven, multi-ply), subjected to various types of loading conditions. The developed framework is able to predict crack propagation behavior based on applied loading conditions and nature of pre-existing defects. This work was funded by NAVY SBIR Phase I program, Contract N68335-16-C-0301, awarded to ACT, Inc.

562.prez_name: A Peridynamics Framework for Modeling of Corrosion Damage Phenomena
562.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
562.prez_authors: Srujan  Rokkam, Michael  D Brothers, Max   Gunzburger, Sachin  Shanbhag, Kishan  Goel
562.prez_abstract: Peridynamics is a non-local reformulation for classical continuum mechanics that enables modeling of crack/discontinuities in a solid using integro-differential equations. In this work, we discuss a recently developed peridynamics approach for modeling of corrosion damage phenomenon in metals. The governing equations of the model prescribe the driving forces responsible for concurrent corrosion and mechanical loading using a system of integro-differential equations. The resulting framework enables, is well suited for capture of corrosion induced crack nucleation and growth, without the need to remesh the domain or the need for complicated crack path algorithms like that of XFEM or cohesive element method. We discuss the model features and demonstrative results of crack propagation in response to corrosive environments under concurrent action of mechanical loads. The approach predicts the internal load redistribution arising from local corrosion damage and captures the resulting failure of the structure under different loading conditions.

563.prez_name: An Integrated Two-scale Modeling Approach to the Simulation of Fragmentation in Brittle Materials
563.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
563.prez_abstract: Safety assessments for impact accidents involving brittle radioactive material forms (e.g., PuO<sub>2</sub>) require the determination of the respirable amounts of the materials (≤ 10 μm aerodynamic equivalent diameter) generated and released by the accident. Due to the challenges of resolving the length scales of interest using traditional finite element approaches, numerical analyses are usually limited to assessing containment structure performance, with quantities derived from the analyses used in empirical formulas to estimate source terms. Recently we have developed a new, computationally tractable, two-scale modeling approach that may be used to simulate the dynamic fragmentation of brittle materials across these length scales. The approach leverages a traditional finite element damage mechanics methodology to simulate dynamic fracture under general loading and boundary conditions, with an embedded one-dimensional model that simulates the microscale dynamic fragmentation. Results from the application of the model on a representative problem drawn from experimental studies are presented.

564.prez_name: Applying Micromorphic Filter on 3D Beam FEA with Idealized Periodic Micro-structure
564.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
564.prez_authors: Richard  Regueiro, Farhad  Shahabi, Boning  Zhang, Joseph  Bishop
564.prez_abstract: The talk will present the application of a "micromorphic filter" on a three-dimensional (3D) beam finite element analysis (FEA) with poly-crystalline elastic idealized periodic micro-structure. The goal of the study is to investigate the improvement that may be obtained on bridging underlying direct numerical simulation (DNS) of the material at the poly-crystalline grain-scale to continuum macro-scale through a micromorphic filter. The micromorphic continuum theory of Eringen and co-workers is proposed to incorporate material micro-structure within a continuum framework. A micro-deformation tensor is introduced to govern micro-element (microscale) deformation independent from the deformation gradient capturing macro-element (macroscale) deformation. The approach of applying a micromorphic filter directly onto the DNS will be briefly reviewed, and some initial results will be presented.  Extensions include applying the micromorphic filter to elastoplastic DNS for potentially improving ductile failure predictions in poly-crystalline metals through micromorphic elastoplasticity theory.

565.prez_name: Crack Growth Path Prediction Based on Surface Roughness Evolution
565.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
565.prez_authors: Jalal  Fathi Sola, Randall  Kelton, Haiying   Huang, Efstathios  Meletis
565.prez_abstract: Surface morphology changes are associated with crack propagation in metals.  In this work, surface roughness changes during fatigue are studied to predict the crack path in center cracked Nickel-200specimensprepared based on ASTM standard647.  During fatigue testing, the samples were imaged with in-situ white light interferometry. The three-dimensional surface topology images were taken from the initial crack nucleation site to 1.5 mm using 10X lens every 5000 cycles.  Then, images were taken with a 50X lens every 200 cycles. The images were analyzed using a custom-developed image processing method. The 10X images indicated that the Ra and Rt changes are the highest in area ahead of the crack tip. The 50X images revealed the pixels with the highest changes in Ra and Rt coincide with the path along which the crack will eventually propagate.  The present results suggest that the aforementioned indexes can predict future crack propagation path with good agreement

566.prez_name: Crystal Plasticity Finite Element Simulation of Fatigue Failure in Polycrystalline Al7075-T651 Alloys, Part II: Modeling Cyclic Deformation and Fracture
566.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
566.prez_authors: Ahmad  Shahba, Xiaohui  Tu, Jinlei  Shen, Somnath  Ghosh
566.prez_abstract: 7000-series aluminum alloys are bi-phasic, comprising of a crystalline Al matrix and brittle intermetallic Fe-rich particles. Experimental observations have shown that the fatigue failure in these alloys starts with the fracture of brittle particles, succeeded by the nucleation and propagation of cracks in the surrounding crystalline matrix. In this work, fatigue failure of polycrystalline Al7075-T651 alloys under cyclic loading is modeled within a stabilized large-deformation crystal plasticity finite element framework. Augmenting the free energy functional, crack phase field is used to model the fracture process. Crack phase field is coupled to the deformation constitutive models such that the asymmetry in material response in tension and compression is respected in the cracked zones. Moreover, wavelet transformation induced multi-time scaling (WATMUS) model is employed to perform accelerated high-resolution simulation of large number of cycles. The model is calibrated and validated using experimental data obtained from displacement-controlled cyclic fatigue loadings.

567.prez_name: Crystal Plasticity Finite Element Simulation of Fatigue Failure in Polycrystalline Al7075-T651 Alloys, Part I: The Reconstruction, and Microstructure/Property Convergence of RVE
567.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
567.prez_authors: Xiaohui  Tu, Ahmad   Shahba, Jinlei   Shen, Somnath   Ghosh
567.prez_abstract: 7000-series aluminum alloys are widely utilized in manufacturing critical components in automotive and aerospace industries. Fracture of brittle intermetallic particles is deemed as the genesis of fatigue failure in these alloys. Hence accurate representation of grains and intermetallic particles in virtual RVEs is of paramount importance for any subsequent fatigue crack modeling. Employing a GA-based stereological method, high-fidelity 3D virtual two-phase microstructures are constructed based on 2D EBSD/SEM data. The proposed reconstruction algorithm respects morphological and crystallographic distributions of grains, morphology and two-point correlation function of particles, and particle-grain correlations. Detailed analysis is carried out to determine the size of microstructure-based statistically equivalent RVE (M-SERVE), the minimum RVE size where convergence in microstructural descriptors is achieved. A stabilized large-deformation finite-element framework is then adopted to perform numerous crystal plasticity simulations to determine the size of property-based SERVE (P-SERVE), the minimum RVE size where convergence in micromechanical properties is attained.

568.prez_name: Do Voids Initiate at Grain Boundaries?
568.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
568.prez_authors: Philip  Noell, Brad L. Boyce, Jay D. Carroll, Khalid M. Hattar, Blythe G. Clark
568.prez_abstract: While ductile rupture processes initiate at inclusions or precipitates in many alloys, nucleation in pure metals is often associated with grain boundaries or triple junctions.  This study presents multiple ex-situ observations of incipient void nucleation in pure tantalum during tensile deformation that were made with electron channeling contrast imaging, electron backscatter diffraction, and transmission electron microscopy. Instead of forming at grain boundaries, voids initiated at and grew along deformation-induced dislocation cell and cell block boundaries. Most of the voids were associated with extended, lamellar dislocation boundaries that ran along the traces of the {110}  or {112} planes, though a few voids initiated at low-angle dislocation cell walls. 569.prez_name: Fracture between a Suspended Polymeric Film and a Metallic Substrate: Experiments and Models
569.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
569.prez_authors: Jing  Du, Emily  Hampp, Wanliang  Shan, Wole  Soboyejo
569.prez_abstract: This is a combined experimental, theoretical, and computational study of the adhesion between suspended polymeric films and a substrate in a model drug-eluting stent. Atomic force microscope is used to measure the pull-off force between the polymer and the mettalic substrate. The adhesion energy was then obtained from the measured pull-off forces and adhesion theories. Subsequently, the adhesion energy was incorporated into interfacial fracture mechanics zone model that was used to determine mode mixity dependence of the interfacial fracture toughness. The mode mixity-dependent fracture toughness conditions were then integrated into finite element models that were used to compute the critical push-out force of the suspended polymeric films. The predicted push-out forces were in good agreement with the results obtained from the experiments using the self-made micron-level push-out tester.

570.prez_name: In-situ 3D Observation of Grain Evolution in a Cu Polycrystal
570.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
570.prez_authors: Rulin  Chen, Reeju  Pokharel , Bjorn  Clausen, Ricardo  Lebensohn , Peter  Kenesei, Robert  Suter
570.prez_abstract: We use non-destructive measurements of the three-dimensional (3D) microstructure of a 99.995% pure polycrystalline Cu sample in 10 successive in-situ tensile loading steps to track the development of deformation.  Measurements were performed with near-field High Energy Diffraction Microscopy (nf HEDM) at the Advanced Photon Source with Forward Modeling Method (FMM) reconstructions to determine the spatially resolved three-dimensional crystallographic orientation fields in states with up to 14.2% macroscopic extension; the notched cross-section generates a significant strain gradient.The orientations under initial state S0 exhibit random texture.The plastic deformation leads to changes in the macroscopic texture.Inverse pole figures of voxels in the reconstructed orientation map show individual grains’ evolution under strain S1, S2, S3, S4, with higher strain states currently being analyzed.We use the machine learning k-means clustering method to quantify texture evolution.Further, we use an automated script that searches the measured volume for small angle rotations about specific axes in an effort to identify specific slip events.

571.prez_name: Interface Chemistry and Strain Rate Effect on Fracture in Energetic Material Interfaces
571.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
571.prez_abstract: The fracture failure behavior of Hydroxyl-Terminated Polybutadiene (HTPB)- Ammonium Perchlorate (AP) interfaces is investigated as a function of strain rate. A rate dependent power law viscoplastic constitutive model of HTPB, AP and the HTPB/AP interface is char-acterized using nano-scale impact experiments at strain rates up to 100 s-1. A cohesive finite element method (CFEM) is used to predict the effect of strain rates and the interface chem-istry on the interface fracture failure for a HTPB/AP sample with one AP particle. The cohe-sive parameters were obtained based on an in-situ mechanical Raman spectroscopy framework that measures cohesive strength and fracture energy correlation as a function interface chemistry.

572.prez_name: Investigating Heterogeneous Deformation in Polycrystalline Al 6061 Using In-situ SEM Tensile Test and HREBSD Characterization
572.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
572.prez_authors: Yung Suk Jeremy Yoo, Jay   Carroll, John M Emery, Josh  Kacher
572.prez_abstract: Al 6061 is a structural alloy that achieves a high strength-to-weight ratio with its complicated microstructure, which includes distributed intermetallic particles and precipitates as well as heterogeneities inherent to polycrystalline materials. Understanding how this complex microstructure dictates the local accumulation of defects is critical to understanding fracture mechanisms in Al 6061. In this study, notched Al 6061 dogbone samples were tested under tension in the scanning electron microscope (SEM) and electron backscatter diffraction (EBSD) scans were collected periodically at interrupted strain stages. Select subregions were investigated using high-resolution EBSD to investigate the evolving strain fields around triple junctions and intermetallic particles. The curl of the orientation field was used to map out the local accumulation of geometrically necessary dislocations. Discussion will focus on mechanisms leading to defect accumulation in relation to microstructural heterogeneities and their relationship with ductile fracture of Al 6061.

573.prez_name: Predicting the Impact of Material Microstructure on Brittle Fracture Using a Phase Field Fracture Model
573.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
573.prez_authors: Michael  Tonks, Shuaifang  Zhang, Srujan  Rokkam, Pritam  Chakraborty
573.prez_abstract: The microstructure of a brittle material has a significant impact on its fracture behavior, including grain structure, precipitates, impurities, dislocations, and pores. Thus, in order to accurately determine the fracture properties of a material, we must consider the impact of microstructure. However, determining the impact of various microstructural features on macroscopic fracture spans multiple length scales. In this presentation we present a quantitative phase field fracture model that considers the impact of grain boundaries, pores, and other heterogeneities on the fracture behavior. The fracture toughness of the various microstructural features in the model can be obtained from atomistic simulations or from experimental data. The model also considers anisotropic elastic properties of the microstructural features, though preferred cleavage planes are not currently considered. The model is implemented using the open source MOOSE finite element framework.

574.prez_name: Quantitative Phase-field Modeling of Crack Propagation in Multiphase Materials
574.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
574.prez_authors: Arezoo  Emdadi, Mohsen  Asle Zaeem, William  G Fahrenholtz, Gregory  Hilmas
574.prez_abstract: A quantitative phase-field model based on Griffith’s theory is developed for crack propagation in homogeneous and heterogeneous materials. To construct this model, the stress in front of the crack tip is equated to its counterpart from the classical fracture mechanics by utilizing correction factors in the total free energy functional of the phase-field model for the diffusive crack area. Crack propagation is simulated in plain concrete and ZrB2 as homogeneous materials and in ZrB2-based composite ceramics with different microarchitectures as heterogeneous materials. To test the accuracy of the model, both the crack path and force-displacement responses are examined against the experimental data and analytical solutions. The results indicate that this quantitative phase-field model is capable of accurately simulating crack growth in multiphase materials.

575.prez_name: Recent Advances in Gradient-based Damage Methods for Dynamic Fracture and Fragmentation
575.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
575.prez_abstract: Recently, much attention has focused on gradient-based damage and phase-field models for fracture problems. Such approaches often suffer from several shortcomings when applied to dynamic fracture and fragmentation. These include, for example, the computational cost of a global reaction-diffusion auxiliary equation and challenges associated with introducing critical thresholds that trigger the onset of damage.  To address these issues, we present a method for dynamic fracture and fragmentation that builds on recent efforts linking gradient-based damage models and cohesive models of failure. In particular, we incorporate a viscous regularization term that enables the use of a fully explicit treatment of the evolution equations. The approach naturally introduces a threshold for the onset of damage, and allows for a cohesive model to be recovered in the limit as the regularization length scale vanishes.  The utility of the method is demonstrated with a series of benchmark problems in large-scale dynamic fracture and fragmentation.

576.prez_name: The Effect of Loading Rate on Fracture Toughness Measurements for Various Materials
576.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
576.prez_abstract: The primary reason for this investigation was to measure the fracture toughness as a function of loading rate on a range of materials. Characterization has been done on PMMA, Plastic bonded explosives and their mocks and on some metals that have low strain to failure properties like magnesium and beryllium. The characterization technique uses digital image correlation to determine the crack properties. Analysis of the strain fields using linear elastic fracture mechanics provides consistent results that are typical of the standard fracture toughness evaluation. Further development in the characterization using continuum mechanics has led to a solution that more closely resembled the standard compact tension problem. In this solution, we have been able to extract the modulus values and Poisson’s ratio form the experimental analysis and make corrections to the solution that minimizes errors.

577.prez_name: Thermo-mechanical Deformation Responses in Transition Metal Carbides at Ultra-high Temperatures
577.symp_name: Characterization of Fracture and Fragmentation Phenomena Across Multiple Length Scales: From Atomistic to Macroscopic Approaches
577.prez_authors: Gregory B Thompson, Morgan  Ross, Chase  Smith, Nick  DeLeon, Christopher  R Weinberger
577.prez_abstract: Mechanical testing over 2000C is arduous because of the required heating, compliance in components, and potential specimen reactions. In this talk, the use of a non-contact means of thermomechanical loading, initially demonstrated by Gangireddy and Halloran, is applied to TaC and HfC. By passing a current through the carbide, it resistively heats it and, in the presence of a magnetic field, the specimen bends under the Lorentz force. Using a variety of loads and temperatures up to 3000C, the thermomechanical behavior has been quantified. TaC exhibited more deflection than HfC at equivalent load/temperatures and this is contributed to its ease of {111} slip. Furthermore, at failure, TaC exhibited abnormal grain growth with multiple slip band formations on the fractured surface. In contrast, HfC exhibited minimal grain growth and substantially less slip band formations.  Results are discussed in terms of TEM identification of dislocation types and DFT analysis of slip.

578.prez_name: Additive Manufacturing of Kaolinite Clay with Brick Dust Waste
578.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

579.prez_name: C4H11NO Performance on Steel-rebar Corrosion in Industrial/Microbial Simulating Environment
579.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

580.prez_name: Corrosion Behaviour of Steel-reinforcement in C3H7NO2S-admixed Concrete Immersed in Saline/Marine Simulating-environment
580.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

581.prez_name: Developing Heat Conduction Pathways through Short Polymer Chains in a Hydrogen Bonded Polymer System
581.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

582.prez_name: Effect of Coconut Fibers in Asphalt Properties
582.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

583.prez_name: Fabrication by Additive Manufacturing of Clay with Electric Arc Furnace Steel Dust (EAF Dust)
583.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

584.prez_name: Physical and Mechanical Properties of Sintered Bricks Produced with Red Mud
584.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

585.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

586.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment
