587.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

588.prez_name: Weibull Distribution and Mössbauer Spectroscopy of Portland Cement with Magnetite Particles
588.symp_name: Construction and Building Materials for a Better Environment

589.prez_name: A Computational Approach to Generate Amorphous Carbon Models Using Reactive Molecular Dynamics
589.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
589.prez_authors: Raghavan  Ranganathan, Srujan  Rokkam, Tapan  Desai, Pawel  Keblinski
589.prez_abstract: Amorphous carbon materials have been a subject of research for a spectrum of chemical, mechanical and bio-medical applications. In this work, we discuss a computational approach to generate models of amorphous carbon (a-C) using molecular dynamics simulations with a reactive force field (ReaxFF). The study describes structural features of a-C models obtained for densities of 0.5 g/cc to 3.2 g/cc, as a function of their simulation conditions (quench rate, anneal time and simulation box size). Further we characterize aspects like pore distribution, pore-connectivity and hybridization/graphitization. We find the structural features of generated a-C models agree well with similar models reported in literature.  We observe that a low densities (~ 0.5 g/cc), a-C models are likely to exhibit substantial anisotropy in their structure. Such effects are not present at high density a-C. The correlations developed in this work are expected to guide structure-property relations in the ever-evolving field of amorphous carbon.

590.prez_name: Activation Energy for Crystallization of Nanocrystalline Exchange Coupled Alloys
590.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
590.prez_authors: Jonathan   Healy, Bowen  Dong, Maria  Daniil, Matthew A. Willard
590.prez_abstract: In this study, the crystallization kinetics of alloys with composition (Fe,Ni,Co)89-xZr7B4Cux where x is equal to 0 or 1, are determined by Kissinger analysis of constant heating rate differential thermal analysis experiments.  The thermally activated primary and secondary crystallization temperatures were observed for each sample at numerous heating rates to provide accurate activation energies.  The trends of the activation energy for primary crystallization as a function of magnetic transition metal composition were examined in this study and compared to values in the literature.  Alloys rich in Fe show activation energies between 3 and 3.5 eV/atom while alloys rich in Ni have substantially lower activation energies, near 2.1 to 2.5 eV/atom.  The reduced activation energy likely results from the more active diffusion in Ni-based alloys and may be a reason for the deteriorated nanocrystalline alloy formation at these compositions.

591.prez_name: Bulk Monolithic Carbon Nanofibers: Tailoring Geometry, Properties and Hybrid Structures
591.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
591.prez_authors: Mark  Atwater, Roger  Welsh, Benjamin  Stone, Alix  Joy, Laura  Guevara
591.prez_abstract: Generating bulk quantities of nanoscale carbon and controlling the geometry and properties to create components is a challenge which limits commercial adoption of such structures. Using a direct synthesis technique, carbon nanofibers can be generated with tightly controlled geometry and with predetermined bulk properties. These materials exhibit mechanical strength and resilience; able to withstand as much as 90% compressive strain without disintegration. They also display functional promise, and it has been demonstrated that nanoparticles can be readily removed from water by passage through these materials. Not only are these fibrous structures suitable alone, they can be readily integrated with other materials and structures to create hybrids with unique properties. The methods, properties and applications of these materials will be discussed in context with other carbon nanomaterials.

592.prez_name: Carbon Nanotube Aerogels: Tailoring Mechanical Responses via Junction Modification
592.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
592.prez_authors: Michelle  Tsui, Kyu Hun Kim, Mohammad F. Islam
592.prez_abstract: Single-walled carbon nanotube (SWCNT) foams are highly desired to harness the intrinsic mechanical properties of individual SWCNTs for macroscale applications. We self-assemble SWCNTs into open-cell foams, and coat the junctions and struts with various two-dimensional materials such as graphene and hexagonal boron nitride to manipulate foams’ thermomechanical responses. Free rotation and sliding of SWCNTs about the junctions dictate mechanical properties of SWCNT foams. Coatings, on the other hand, suppress rotation and sliding at the junctions and stiffen the struts, enhancing Young’s moduli and imparting superelasticity, fatigue resistance and creep resistance that is preserved over a broad temperature range (-100–500˚C). Our fabrication process allows densification to at least 400 mg/mL, reaching high Young’s moduli of 0.4 GPa, while maintaining the microstructure, thermomechanical responses, and ultralow loss ≈0.01–0.04 of low density foams. These results motivate junction and strut modification to tailor the mechanical properties of CNT foams.

593.prez_name: Carboxymethyl Cellulose and Bile Salt Network Formation with Aqueous Graphene Solution
593.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
593.prez_authors: Julie E Muretta, Katherine  Kent, Stephen W. Sofie, Joseph  Seymour
593.prez_abstract: The compatibility of graphene in aqueous polymer systems is not fully understood, resulting in limited application of graphene in favor of graphene oxide in aqueous-processed polymer films. This work identifies that the presence of bile salt facilitates the formation of weak gel networks in the polyelectrolyte which are disrupted by the addition of small amounts of surfactant, but not by graphene/surfactant suspension, indicating that the surfactant preferentially associates with sites on the graphene sheets in aqueous suspension even at low pH. UV-Vis absorption, in the 260-270 nm range, shows that the electronic structure is preserved with this method of stabilization, a finding with huge implications for the promotion of aqueous processed graphene into more widespread use.

594.prez_name: Centrifuge-aided Micromolding of Micron- and Submicron-sized Patterns
594.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
594.prez_authors: Hongfei  Ju, Kaijie  Ning, Kathy  Lu
594.prez_abstract: Developed from soft lithography, replica molding has been proven to be a good method to prepare micron- and submicron-sized features. However, the fidelity of the features can be compromised by incomplete feature cavity filling and feature shrinkage during the forming process. In this study, centrifuge-aided micromolding is developed to prepare micro- and submicron-sized ZnO features. By introducing a centrifugal force, the shear-thinning behavior of the suspensions can be utilized to accelerate the cavity filling process and the diffusion of trapped air out of the features. The drying shrinkage is decreased by increasing the density of the wet nanoparticle packing from the centrifugal process. The centrifugal force improves the fidelity of all the designed features. ZnO ridges from 2 μm to 400 nm size and rods of 2 μm size are prepared successfully. The wide applicability of this strategy has been demonstrated by preparing ZrO 2 features via the same method.

595.prez_name: Coercivity Model for (Co, Ni)-based Soft Nanocomposite Magnets
595.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
595.prez_authors: Jonathan  Healy, Bowen  Dong, Song  Lan, Billy Chad Hornbuckle, Gregory B. Thompson, Maria  Daniil, Matthew A. Willard
595.prez_abstract: (Co1-xNix)88Zr7B4Cu1  nanocrystalline alloys have shown promise for soft magnetic applications due to their low coercivity (< 50 A/m).  The coercivity variation with composition in the nanocomposites indicates a plateau when 0.50 ≤ x ≤ 0.75.  The composition dependence of the magnetostriction and magnetocrystalline anisotropy across the alloy series have been modeled to phenomenologically explain the coercivity. (Co, Ni)-based nanocomposites with this composition are prepared by melt spinning followed by isothermal annealing, following the same procedure previously used. Room temperature magnetic hysteresis and temperature dependent magnetization have been studied. Coercivity data from this work will be used to validate our proposed coercivity model.  This study will focus on an alloy with composition (Co0.316Ni0.684)88Zr7B4Cu1which is modeled to have a coercivity less than 10 A/m.

596.prez_name: Designing Functional Organic Nanomaterials for Advanced Energy Technologies
596.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
596.prez_abstract: Nanostructured materials have become critically important in many areas of technology, ranging from renewable energy, electronics, and photonics to biology and medicine, because of their unusual physical/chemical properties due to confined dimensions of such materials. This talk will present a new class of polymeric materials we developed recently: nanostructured conducting polymer gels (nCPGs) that are hierarchically porous, and structurally tunable in size, shape, composition, hierarchical porosity, and chemical interfaces. nCPGs as functional organic building blocks offer an array of advantageous features including intrinsic 3D nanostructured conducting framework, excellent electrical conductivity and electrochemical activity to store and transport ions, tunable structures and chemical interface, and they have been demonstrated powerful for a number of applications in energy and environment technologies. Several examples on nCPGs-enabled advanced energy and electronic devices including high-energy lithium batteries, supercapacitors, and self-healing electronics, will be discussed to illustrate ‘structure-derived multifunctionality’ of this special class of materials.

597.prez_name: Development of Nanocrystalline Magnetic Material for High Current Inductors
597.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
597.prez_authors: Anthony M Martone, Bowen  Dong, Song  Lan, Matthew  Willard
597.prez_abstract:
As inductor technology advances, greater efficiency, smaller components demand a new core material. With recent developments of nanocrystalline magnetic materials, soft magnetic properties of these cores can be greatly improved. A novel nanocrystalline soft magnetic material, Fe77Co5.5Ni5.5Zr7B4Cu1, has been developed by Willard and his research group in 2015. While this nanocrystalline alloy having iron substituted with equal percents of cobalt and nickel has resulted in small coercivity and high Curie temperature, magnetostriction persist as the main source of losses. This investigation focuses on increasing the nickel to cobalt ratio in these alloys. Through alloy development, low coercivities and high Curie temperatures can be achieved with eliminated magnetostrictive losses to create an improved magnetic material for high current inductors.    
Knipling, Keith E. et al. “Nanocrystalline Fe88-2xCoxNixZr7B4Cu1 alloys:  Soft magnets for vehicle electrification technologies (invited)” Journal of Applied Physics 117, 172611(2015); doi: 10.1063/1.4914118.

598.prez_name: Dislocation Aided Orientation Alignment during Initial Stages of Crystal Growth
598.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
598.prez_authors: Amit  Samanta, Andrew   Lange, Tammy  Olson, Selim  Elhadj
598.prez_abstract: The oriented attachment of molecular clusters and nanoparticles is a commonly reported mechanism of crystal growth in many materials, yet the microscopic mechanisms associated with the alignment of nanoparticles during coalescence has not been established. We studied the coalescence of prototypical gold and copper nanoparticles using in situ electron microscopy coupled to atomic level simulations. At variance with the oriented attachment hypothesis, alignment of nanoparticles post-contact irrespective of their initial misorientation is driven by extensive dislocation activity that is followed by twinning or surface diffusion aided neck growth and subsequent surface diffusion aided shape evolution. Our atomistic simulations suggest that the dislocation-aided alignment of nanoparticles in vacuum happens much faster than diffusion aided processes such as neck growth, or shape. The fact that many nanoparticles with different orientation coalesce to form single crystal aggregates suggests a revision of the scope of oriented attachment during crystal growth by nanoparticle aggregation.

599.prez_name: Electrospun Fabrication of Nanocomposite PVC/TiO2 Fiber for Air Filtration
599.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
599.prez_authors: Zhuoying  Jiang, Anna Cristina  Samia, Xiong (Bill)  Yu
599.prez_abstract: As people spend most time inside building, indoor air quality control plays an essential role on human’s exposure to environmental contaminations. Here we present a nanocomposite fiber for air filtration to improve indoor air quality. Polyvinyl chloride (PVC) nanofiber membrane was fabricated using electrospun technique, and further loaded with functional nanoparticles TiO2 on the fiber surface. PVC nanofiber has potential to adsorb floating pollutants due to its excellent filter function associated with its large surface areas. TiO2 is well known as a photo-catalyst to break down harmful pollutants energized by ultraviolet lights, thus assisting improving filtration efficiency with nanofiber. Nano TiO2 particles have been transferred to fiber surface through direct-dispersing, post-dipping and post-electrospraying method, respectively. The photocatalytic functionality of TiO2 by these three different means are tested and discussed.

600.prez_name: Ferret: an Open-source Code for Simulating Thermodynamical Evolution and Phase Transformations in Complex Materials Systems at Mesoscale
600.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
600.prez_abstract: Ferret is an open-source highly scalable real-space finite-element-method (FEM) based code for simulating materials systems with coupled physical properties at mesoscale. It is built on MOOSE, Multiphysics Object Oriented Simulation Environment, and is being developed by a team of collaborators at UConn and ANL. In this presentation we provide an overview of computational approach utilized by the code, as well as its technical features and the associated software. We also highlight some of the code applications including (a) evaluations of size- and microstructure-dependent properties of core-shell nanoparticles, including Zn/ZnO and ZnO/TiO2 core/shell material combinations; (b) modeling of the influence of shape, size and elastic distortions of monolythic ZnO and Zn/ZnO core/shell nanowires on their optical properties; (c) studies of the properties and domain-wall dynamics in perovskite-ferroelectric films, nanowires and nanoridges, and (d) investigation of transitional behavior and topological phases in ferroelectric nanoinclusions embedded in a dielectic matrix.

601.prez_name: Flame Synthesis of Carbon and Metal Oxides Nanomaterials for Energy Storage, Conversion and Harvesting
601.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
601.prez_abstract:
Many forms of energy utilization, conversion and storage and generation are dominated by interfacial chemistry.  Therein nanomaterials as an interfacial modifier can play a critical role in these processes. Specific energy applications we have explored include the following:
1)  Storage: Increased energy density in Li ion batteries and supercapacitors using carbon nanotubes.
2)  Conservation: Lightweight polymer composites incorporating nanotubes.
3)  Control: Gas sensors based on nanoscale metal oxide semi-conductors for process control and monitoring.
4)  Harvesting: Catalysts and photocatalysts using nanostructured oxides for accelerated charge transfer and minimize recombination losses.
Highlights in each application will be presented. Scalable flame synthesis will be illustrated for both carbon and oxide materials for these applications.

602.prez_name: Growth Direction Control of ZnO Nanorods on the Edge of the Patterned ITO/AZO Bi-layers
602.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
602.prez_abstract: In this study, ZnO nanorods were grown radially on the edge of ITO/AZO bi-layers by hydrothermal method since the mask ITO layer covered on the AZO seed layer.  By etching the ITO/AZO bi-layers with the dilute HCl solution, the under-cut space is created under the ITO layer which is the key for the vertical growth direction of ZnO nanorods on the etched-edge of ITO/AZO bi-layers.  Interestingly, the ZnO nanorods grew laterally on the etched-edge of ITO/AZO bi-layers prepared with 400 ºC substrate temperature.  It’s the higher crystallinity of AZO seed layer (400 °C) causes the etched-edge microstructure different from that of AZO seed layers (room temperature and 150 °C).  By manipulating the under-cut etching space dimension and the surface microstructure on the etched-edge of ITO/AZO bi-layers, the growth direction of ZnO nanorods can be controlled.  The more detail would be discussed during this talk as well.

603.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
603.prez_abstract: Despite the success of imprint lithography method to transfer arrays of patterned features onto pure polymers and polymer/metallic nanoparticle composites, it has never been achieved on the sub-micron scale with polymer-oxide particle hybrids. This study patterns ZnO-PMMA (poly(methyl methacrylate)) hybrids via imprint lithography from co-suspensions of PMMA and ZnO nanoparticles in anisole from 1 vol% to 20 vol% ZnO solids loading. ZnO nanoparticles are functionalized with nonanoic acid to disperse the nanoparticles in anisole with dissolved PMMA. Even at the lowest feature fidelity, all ZnO contents result in usable features with line edge roughness (LER) and inverse circularity (IC) below 10% of the feature size. The surface roughness (SR) of the features also increases with the ZnO solids loading. ZnO nanoparticles enhance the photoluminescence (PL) intensity of the patterned arrays. This method of lithographic patterning of nanoparticle-polymer suspensions can be applied to a wide variety of hybrid devices.

604.prez_name: In-situ Characterization of Growth and Performance of Nanostructured Materials for Energy Conversion and Storage
604.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
604.prez_abstract: Nanostructured materials help circumvent mass and electron transport kinetic limitations associated with room temperature function of electrochemical batteries.  Innumerable examples of enhanced performance stemming from nanostructured electrodes exist in the published literature.  However, few commercial examples exist.  This results from several factors, most important of which are the cost of high volume nanomaterial synthesis and the inherent instability and reactivity of many nanostructured electrodes that can cause them to degrade during long-term cycling.  This work describes efforts to develop an inexpensive and scalable approach to oxide nanowire growth, and highlights the importance of in-situ TEM characterization in determining the growth mechanisms.  The talk will also highlight how in-situ AES and XPS characterization can be important for understanding the nature of surface reactions that tend to degrade nanomaterials in battery applications.

605.prez_name: in-situ Synthesized CdS Nanowire Photosensor for Chemiluminescence Biosensors
605.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
605.prez_abstract: In this work, a chemiluminescence biosensor was developed based on a hyper sensitive CdS nanowires photosensor which was fabricated by in-situ synthesis of nanowires directly on the interdigitated electrodes with pulsed laser deposition (PLD) system. The density of CdS nanowires on the in-situ fabricated photosensor could be far enhanced in comparison with the conventional methods. The in-situ synthesis condition of CdS nanowire was optimized such as density, diameter and resistance performance could be controlled to have maximum photo-resistive response. The CdS nanowire photosensor was applied to detect the chemiluminescent signal band of a lateral flow immunoassay (LF-immunoassay). In this work, the feasibility of the chemiluminescence biosensor based on the in-situ synthesized CdS nanowire photosensor and the chemiluminescent LF-immunoassay was demonstrated by the detection of human hepatitis B surface antigen (hHBsAg).

606.prez_name: Incommensurate Van der Waals Epitaxy of Low-dimensional Halide Perovskite
606.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
606.prez_abstract: The emergence of hybrid organic-inorganic halide perovskites has been widely recognized as a huge boost to the existing semiconductor family, enabling an upsurge of device performance in photovoltaic field which soon proceeds to the electro-optics and optoelectronics like photo detector and lasers. Nanostructured halide perovskite would broaden the present horizon and introduce interesting physics absent in the bulk scale. By incommensurate van der Waals epitaxy, we successfully obtained aligned ultrathin two-dimensional sheets and one-dimensional horizontal nanowire arrays. As a step forward, epitaxial double heterosturcture was received via optically controlled spinodal decomposition and nucleation/coarsening. Via optical spectroscopy, reduced electron-phonon interactions are revealed which uniquely exist in these low dimensional structures. Our results promise a new approach on developing optically high quality halide perovskite morphology with designed physical properties.

607.prez_name: Integration of Dissimilar Nanophase Materials in 3D Nanocomposites: Applications in Magnetism
607.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
607.prez_abstract: The high concentration of interfaces in nanocomposites offer extensive opportunities for property manipulation. However, integrating the desired phases with the nanoscale control necessary is a major challenge. We discuss processing strategies for obtaining relatively large 3D materials through powder consolidation. The processes leverage differences in processing/reaction kinetics to find suitable kinetic windows. We will present results on the integration of metal-oxide/metal as well as oxide/oxide composites. The nanocomposites have increased magnetic performance such as high coercivity and increased magnetic energy product.

608.prez_name: Low Temperature Conventional Sintering of Nanograined Ceramics via High Green Density Processing
608.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
608.prez_abstract: Nanograined ceramic oxide powders can be produced or acquired via multiple routes. However, to date, there does not exist a universal way of shaping, processing, and sintering these powders to retain their nanograined structure without the application of large external pressures (>1 GPa). Therefore, in this work, novel low pressure shaping coupled with high pressure cold isostatic pressing (CIP) (dry processing and without binders) was employed to shape and consolidate the nanograined ceramic oxide powders to high green densities (>55%) prior to sintering. With these high green densities, the pellets were sintered at 100s of ⁰C  lower temperatures (100s of ⁰C below conventional firing) than conventional firing while retaining the nanograined structure. Final grain sizes of sub-35nm can be achieved without any externally applied pressure or chemical binders. This approach opens up a new avenue for nanoparticle sintering that can be transitioned to industrial applications.

609.prez_name: Magnetic and Structural Properties of Ball-milled Nanocrystalline Fe77Co5.5Ni5.5Zr7B4Cu1 Soft Magnetic Powders
609.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
609.prez_authors: Anthony M Martone, Bowen  Dong, Som  Thomas, Donglu  Shi, Matthew  Willard
609.prez_abstract:
The development of nanocrystalline magnetic ribbons with improved soft magnetic properties has met the demand in inductor applications for smaller components that operate at higher frequencies and greater temperatures. However, the applications of these ribbons are greatly restricted by their geometry. By ball milling ribbons into powders, geometry is no longer a major restraint. Processing conditions can be optimized based off the resulting powder’s magnetic and structural properties.  A high temperature nanocrystalline soft magnetic material, Fe77Co5.5Ni5.5Zr7B4Cu1, has been developed by Willard and his research group in 2015. The present investigation has studied powders of this composition to optimize crystallization annealing conditions, milling conditions, and stress-relaxation annealing conditions.
Knipling, Keith E. et al. “Nanocrystalline Fe88-2xCoxNixZr7B4Cu1 alloys: Soft magnets for vehicle electrification technologies (invited)” Journal of Applied Physics 117, 172611 	(2015); doi: 10.1063/1.4914118.

610.prez_name: Magnetic Properties and Phase Evolution of Iron Powders after High−temperature Nitridation
610.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
610.prez_authors: Song  Lan, Zhiyao  Feng, Parivash  Moradifar, Frank   Ernst, David H Matthiesen, Matthew A. Willard
610.prez_abstract:
A metastable iron nitride phase, α''−Fe16N2, is a magnetic compound with potential to replace rare−earth permanent magnets in some applications. This study examines austenite formation in iron −nitrogen system with sufficient nitrogen concentration to form the most desirable magnetic iron nitride phase, α''−Fe16N2. Moderate−temperature nitridation (at ≈ 650°C) has been performed on iron powders using a custom nitridation furnace with flowing ammonia/hydrogen gas. A processing window of nitridation for near−single−phase nitrogen austenite, γ−(Fe,N), has been determined by vibrating sample magnetometry (VSM) and confirmed by X−ray diffractometry (XRD). Further processing results in nano−scale laths of disordered martensite α'−(Fe,N), a precursor to the ordered martensite α''−Fe16N2, as observed by transmission electron microscopy (TEM). The phase evolution of nitrogen austenite, γ−(Fe,N), upon heating will be reported from VSM and XRD data. Proceedings Inclusion? Undecided

611.prez_name: Mist Deposition and Lift-off Patterning of Nanocrystalline Quantum Dots Films
611.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
611.prez_authors: Ala Hamza J Sabeeh, Jared S. Price, Jerzy  Ruzyllo
611.prez_abstract: Nanocrystalline quantum dots (NQD) represent unique properties making them of interest in the range of potential applications such as displays and UV detection between others. This presentation is concerned with patterning of ultra-thin CdSe/ZnS nanodot films using conventional lift-off process in combination with mist deposition technique. The lift-off process allows creating designated patterns using a sacrificial layer, while the mist deposition technique offers a precise control on the NQD film thickness using a colloidal solution. Process characterization employed in this study is based primarily of Atomic Force Microscopy (AFM) and fluorescence microscopy. The results obtained demonstrate effectiveness of the lift-off process in creating well-defined patterns in mist deposited NQD films with 1 μm resolution. The effect of both lift-off patterning and mist deposition process conditions resulting in the formation of homogenous, low surface roughness NQD films in 10-40 nm thickness regime are identified.

612.prez_name: Multi-Scale Mechanics and Electrical Transport in a Free-Standing 3D Architecture of Graphene and Carbon Nanotubes Fabricated by Pressure Assisted Welding
612.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
612.prez_authors: Pranjal  Nautiyal, Leslie  Embrey, Benjamin  Boesl, Arvind  Agarwal
612.prez_abstract: A free-standing, three dimensional nanohybrid material is fabricated by welding 2D graphene (Gr) and 1D carbon nanotubes (CNT) by localized Joule heating under high pressure. Multi-scale mechanical properties and electrical transport behavior of the hierarchical nanostructure are investigated. Nanoindentation invesigation revealed anisotropy in mechanical properties with respect to the orientation of the graphene layers. CNTs were found to act as anchors between graphene layers during in situ indentation, enhancing the material’s resistance to failure. Due to its hierarchical structure, Gr-CNT is characterized by excellent damping capability, with loss tangent values as high as 0.8. A two-fold increase in electrical conductivity is observed (~108 S/cm) as compared to pure graphene monolith (~55 S/cm). CNTs act as conduction pathways and compensate for resistance at interfaces. Development of a large-scale 3D architecture with strongly bonded nano-constituents and excellent electrical transport behavior opens up scope for numerous structural and functional applications.

613.prez_name: Nanocrystalline Metal Grain Stabilization by Carbon Nanotube Aerogel Cages
613.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
613.prez_authors: Siyuan  Liu, Yeon Joo  Jeong, Mohammad  Islam
613.prez_abstract: The moduli and strength of metals can be considerably enhanced through grain refinement to nanosizes (≤ 100 nm) but exhibit drastic degradation due to rapid grain growth. Empirical alloying approaches have provided limited success but often lead to unpredictable thermodynamic phases with poor thermal stability. We demonstrate that nanoporous carbon nanotube (CNT) aerogels, constituting a percolated inclusion network, greatly suppress the growth of nanocrystalline copper grains fabricated within the nanopores at least up to 600 °C. We attribute the highly restrained grain growth to energetic and/or geometric effects of confinement imparted by the aerogel nanopores. The extraordinary stability of nanocrystalline copper grains caged within the nanoporous aerogels will contribute to further study on thermal stability of various nanocrystalline metals in confined spaces for eventual use as structural or functional materials.

614.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
614.prez_abstract: Electrospun preceramic Polymethylhydrosiloxane (PMHS) with either Poly (methyl methacrylate) (PMMA) or Polyvinylpyrrolidone (PVP) as the carrier polymer were fabricated followed by pyrolysis  to make nanoporous silicon oxycarbide fibers (SiCO). Their fiber morphologies and atomic compositions differed due to their thermal behaviors and decomposition pathways of each carrier polymer. The chemical compositions and structures of the ceramic fibers were characterized by XRD and FTIR and the average pore size, cumulative pore volume, and the BET surface area were measure by Porosimetry. The superhydrophobic property of the fibrous mats was studied and showed their potential ability to absorb oils and organic chemicals, which can be used for the application such as marine oil-spill recovery and environmental remediation.

615.prez_name: Nanostructured TiO2 - Hydrotalcite Composites for Vanillin Photocatalytic Decomposition
615.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
615.prez_authors: Andrei  Jitianu, Anhay  Hernandez-Mujica, Naphtali  O'Connor, Ravnit  Kaur-Bhatia, Nicoleta  Apostol, Mihaela  Jitianu
615.prez_abstract: Various organic compounds can be decomposed in aqueous solution by titanium dioxide (TiO2) under near ultraviolet light into carbon dioxide and water.  When TiO2 absorbs ultraviolet radiation, it will produce pairs of electrons and holes.  The key for an ongoing photooxidation process is to avoid accumulations of the electrons on particles to ultimately avoid their recombination with the holes.  This goal is achieved by creating composites with hydrotalcite, a lamellar mixed hydroxide with the general formula [Mg(II)1-xAl(III)x(OH)2]x+(Ax/m)m-nH2O, where Am- is a compensating anion. The sol-gel process was employed to synthesize the hydrotalcite–enhanced TiO2 nanocomposites, the precursor for the TiO2 Titanium (IV) isopropoxide, whilst the hydrotalcite constituent was generated starting from the corresponding nitrates, in situ, using urea.  The photocatalytic test reaction was performed under visible light (575 nm), using vanillin as a phenol-model compound. The nanosized composites have been found very effective, displaying high decomposition rates of vanillin.

616.prez_name: Phase Change Nanoparticles for Biosensing, Barcoding and Enhanced Cooling
616.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
616.prez_abstract: Existing nanomaterials are studied for their electronic, magnetic, mechanical, and chemical properties. This abstract describes a new type of nanomaterials, i.e., phase change nanoparticles, which has been studied for their unique thermal properties. This group of materials is conveniently called nano-PCM (nanoscale phase change materials) which may have any chemical nature, as long as there is a solid-liquid phase transition when temperature is changed. Metallic nano-PCMs and organic nano-PCMs have been made with precise thermodyanmic properties (melting temperature and enthalpy) based on phase diagram knowledge. The nano-PCMs have been used to enhance heat transfer capability of a variety of fluids, to detect multiple molecular biomarkers of diseases, to create cover barcodes that can be added into objects, to prevent catalytical reactors from thermal runaway, and to achieve cooling effect.

617.prez_name: Porous Silicon Oxycarbide (SiCO) Materials and Environmental Applications
617.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
617.prez_authors: Susana I Aguirre-Medel, Jared  Enriquez, Peter  Kroll
617.prez_abstract:
We report synthesis of porous silicon oxycarbide (SiCO) materials, their microstructural characterization and performance in environmental applications.  One of processes consists of reacting siloxane precursors containing Si-H bonds with cross-linkers bearing vinyl groups using a platinum catalyst. The reaction in diluted solutions (80-95 vol%) converts the siloxanes into aerogels after supercritical drying in carbon dioxide. The other synthesis method involves hydrolysis and condensation reactions to obtain a cross-linked gel which is slowly dried at 45 °C to obtain a porous material. 
Porous SiCO materials are transformed via thermal treatment in controlled atmospheres into SiCO ceramics. We characterize the porous SiCO materials’ specific surface area, nanoparticle size, pore size distribution, average pore size and total porosity. We also study the potential applications of these materials, specifically the effects of different microstructures on their properties

618.prez_name: Process Dependent Morphologies of Nano-particulate Superstructures
618.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
618.prez_authors: Kaushik Sridhar  Vadari Venkata, Nicole  Ray, William  Petuskey
618.prez_abstract: We report on the facile and rapid synthesis of superstructures from nanoparticulate magnetite (Fe3O4). These structures were deposited onto polymer substrates using spin spray deposition- a process that involves hydrolysis of precursor salt solutions at low temperatures (90°C) and is surfactant-free. Scanning Electron Microscopy (SEM) and High Resolution Transmission Electron Microscopy (HR-TEM) reveal hierarchical self-assembly of nanoparticles (typically 5-15 nm) into 3-D, 2-D and even 1-D superstructures that scale from tens of nanometers to a few microns. The morphology of the obtained superstructures could be modified through solution chemistry and process parameters. The effect of post-deposition heat treatment on the stability of the superstructures will also be discussed.

619.prez_name: Reaction Intermediate Induced Vapor-Liquid-Solid Growth of Amorphous Silicon Oxide Nanowires
619.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
619.prez_abstract: Vapor-liquid-solid (VLS) process is the most popular vapor-phase method for the controlled growth of various one-dimensional (1D) microstructures and nanostructures with the assistance of catalyst particles. In a typical VLS process, catalyst particles, such as noble metal particles, are introduced intentionally prior to the growth to promote the formation of 1D nanostructures. In this study, we report a new VLS growth mode induced by the reaction intermediate. In the nanowire growth of a compound semiconductor, ZnTe, besides the expected ZnTe nanowire arrays, an interesting growth of “jellyfish-like” SiOx nanowires has been observed. Growth mechanism study reveals that the intermediate Te vapor species promoted the growth by producing Si vapors. The mechanism will promote the attentions in composition control for the growth of compound semiconductor nanowires, and the growth mode can be applied to realize lower temperature growth of other nanomaterials.

620.prez_name: Synthesis of Nanocrystalline Ultrahigh Temperature Ceramic Powders via Rapid Single-step High Temperature Spray Pyrolysis
620.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
620.prez_authors: Zhe  Cheng, Junheng  Xing, Paniz  Foroughi, Andres  Behrens
620.prez_abstract: Many transition metal carbides, borides, and nitrides are considered as ultrahigh temperature ceramics (UHTCs) with melting points above ~3000°C. Here, the authors report the synthesis of nanocrystalline UHTCs powders using a single-step high temperature spray pyrolysis (HTSP) process. Soluble oxides and carbon precursors are dissolved in non-aqueous solvents and atomized into micron-sized droplets using a nebulizer.  The fine droplets are then transported by a carrier gas (e.g., Ar) into a furnace preheated to temperature as high as ~1700 °C and go through a series of reactions including solvent removal, pyrolysis, and then in situ carbothermal (CTR) reaction all in one single pass within a few minutes.  The HTSP process incorporating in situ CTR is expected to be low cost, continuous, and scalable.  Preliminary results on systems such as tantalum carbide (TaC) will be presented, and the learnings on the composition-processing-structure relationship and the directions for future development will be discussed.

621.prez_name: Synthesis of Nanomaterials in Extreme Environments
621.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
621.prez_authors: , Catherine  Johnson, Vadym  Mochalin, Martin  Langenderfer, Sergeii  Chertopalov
621.prez_abstract: The high pressure, high temperature environment produced by detonation of explosives has been used to synthesize nanomaterials.  Commercially, nanodiamonds are produced by detonation of mixtures of TNT and RDX in an enclosed blast chamber.  When using oxygen-deficient explosive blends, nanodiamonds with diameters in the range of 5 to 10 nm are produced.  Currently, nanodiamonds are only produced in commercial quantities outside of the U.S.  The goals of our project are to establish research capabilities necessary to produce nanodiamonds and other nanomaterials using detonation synthesis at the Missouri University of Science and Technology.  This presentation will describe the configuration of the detonation chamber, validation experiments to determine charge size/shape necessary to produce the desired conditions, and initial attempts to synthesize nanodiamonds.  In addition, extension of this method to other nanomaterials will be discussed.

622.prez_name: Tailoring of Rutile&Anatase Hybrid Structure by Supersaturated Precursor Solution
622.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
622.prez_abstract: TiO2 (rutile) nanorods have been used as the anode material in various photovoltaic devices. However, the efficiency for bare rutile nanorods system is very limited due to its low surface area and relatively onefold band gap structure. Here we use hydrothermal methods to study hybrid structures consisting of two different titania phases: anatase and rutile. Because of their band potential energy difference, Rutile- anatase hybrid structure is expected to avoid electron-hole recombination via leading electrons to pass through their interface. Through systematically controlling supersaturation, reaction temperature and time, and the ratio of different phase inducing anion, we obtained rutile nanorod microstructures embedded with various amount of porosities and also covered with nanostructured anatase with different orientations and surface morphologies. Variation of hybrid microstructures are the focus of this study and influences on dye-sensitized solar cell are highlighted.

623.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
623.prez_authors: Hyo-Soo  Lee, Jae-Ha  Kim, Tae-Hoon  Park
623.prez_abstract: It was investigated that thermal diffusivity of Cu-Cu/RGO composites was varied with a volume fraction of Cu/RGO powders. The Cu/GO powders, which were dispersed by graphene oxide on copper powder, were prepared by mechanical alloying and then the Cu/RGO powders were obtained by a hydrogen reduction process. The Cu-Cu/RGO composites were fabricated by spark plasma sintering processes after mixing Cu powders and Cu/RGO powders.. It could be convinced from these results that the heat flow path for increasing a thermal diffusivity was supplied by the graphene dispersed composite powers after sintering, and the thermal diffusivity of Cu-Cu/RGO composites showed higher values than that of pure copper. It could be mentioned that the dispersion of graphene in the copper matrix was main role of providing the heat flow path in Cu-Cu/RGO composites, which let the thermal diffusivity increased.

624.prez_name: Thermodynamic Stabilization of Nano-scale Nickel Catalysts for Energy Conversion
624.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
624.prez_abstract: Thermal coarsening through Ostwald ripening represents an important limitation to the lifetime and performance of high temperature metallic catalysts at nano-scales.  A mechanism is proposed that supports microstructural stabilization by “diffusion caging” where sub 10 nanometer alumina decorations on the surface of nickel catalyst particles constrain nickel atom transport at high temperatures.   Through the addition and thermal reaction of aluminum oxide dopant, electron microscopy reveals a decorated nickel microstructure upon reduction of secondary reaction phases.  Electro-chemical energy and high temperature electrolysis testing at 800 degrees C support enhanced performance of nickel catalyst infiltrated initially at 30 – 90 nanometers.  Atomic Force Microscopy in addition to complementary characterization establishes depressions in the nickel surface that facilitate thermodynamic driven stabilization that serves to limit thermally induced coarsening of the catalysts.

625.prez_name: Ultrathin Nanosheets of Functional Oxide Materials
625.symp_name: Controlled Synthesis, Processing, and Applications of Structural and Functional Nanomaterials
625.prez_abstract: We demonstrate that surfactant monolayers could serve as a soft template supporting the nucleation and growth of 2D nanomaterials in large area beyond the limitation of van der Waals solids. Through this approach, 1 to 2 nm thick, single-crystalline free-standing ZnO nanosheets with sizes up to tens of microns were synthesized at the water-air interface. This technique was denoted as the Ionic Layer Epitaxy (ILE).  The nanosheet thickness was controlled by the initial ion concentrated zone formed underneath the negatively charged surfactant monolayer. ILE vastly broadens the range of 2D nanomaterials from layered van der Waals solids to oxides, ceramics, and metals, opening up opportunities for discoveries of exciting transport, photonic, and catalytic properties. In addition to ZnO, we have showed successful results from Pd, NiO, and CoO. The new 2D nanomaterials enabled by ILE will lead to extraordinary performance gain or new functionalities in many scientific and technology disciplines.

626.prez_name: ZrO2 Nanofiber Reinforced Si3N4 Structural Ceramic Sintered by SPS
