643.prez_name: A Data-driven Stochastic Multiscale Analysis Framework for Design of Microstructural Material Systems
643.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
643.prez_abstract: Uncertainty quantification in multiscale materials is a significantly challenging task because the uncertainty arises from various sources at different scales. Investigation of role that microstructural features and randomness play on the macroscopic property and performance has been the focus of many works. Such efforts are largely hampered by the lack of methods that enable the characterization of spatial microstructure correlations as well as efficient multiscale modeling considering spatial variations of material properties. We propose a data-driven framework for materials analysis and design by (i) explicitly modeling spatial variations of microstructural features and properties via additive Gaussian processes, and (ii) replacing expensive multiscale simulations via supervised learning models by building a training dataset in an off-line and parallelizable stage. Such an approach would, collectively, results into a stochastic constitutive law that bridges the material scales and can be used for materials design and conducting statistical analyses considering various sources of uncertainties.

644.prez_name: A Data Laboratory for Materials Design: A New Paradigm for a Materials Information Infrastructure
644.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
644.prez_abstract: We explore the challenges of how one can transform the traditional role of databases as repositories of known information into a “Data Laboratory” for accelerated materials design and discovery.  This presentation will expand on this paradigm in the context of a new NSF initiative  led by the newly established Department of Materials Design and Innovation (MDI) in collaboration at the University at Buffalo,  with the UB Center for Unified Biometrics and Sensors and the UB Center for Computational Research. The “Materials Data Engineering Laboratory” (MaDE@UB Lab) aims to   incorporate a computational system with the cognitive skills for scientific interpretation of text, graphs and images. This will permit one to automatically and intelligently survey and extract massive amounts of  experimental and computational data embedded in scientific publications, handbooks, databases that can be augmented by large scale materials modeling and simulation

645.prez_name: A Paradigm Shift in Advanced Manufacturing and System Life Management
645.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
645.prez_abstract: For decades the United States Air Force (AF) has pushed the envelope of advanced materials and manufacturing research in maintaining air superiority over our adversaries.  However, a revamped AF strategy for Future Operating Concepts in 2035 is prompting a paradigm shift in system life management from Science and Technology (S&T) research through operations/sustainment and retirement.  The focus on “operational agility” in a multi-domain environment is driving revolutionary transformations in design and manufacturing. Today’s turbine engine community is adopting a new Enterprise Architecture to achieve these goals.  Leveraging Digital Thread/Digital Twin approaches precipitates agile design, enabling technologies such as Additive Manufacturing to transition directly from the lab to the field.  These technologies are critical to manufacturing Uninhabited Aircraft Systems (UAS) characterized by low production rates and high variation.  Development time must be compressed and complexity reduced in the future to achieve affordability for the AF to achieve future mission objectives.

646.prez_name: An Analytical Micromechanical Model Solution for Twin Nucleation in Hexagonal Close-packed Metals
646.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
646.prez_authors: Yub Raj  Paudel, Christopher D. Barrett, Mark A Tschopp, Kaan  Inal, Haitham  El Kadiri
646.prez_abstract: Twin nucleation has a critical role in full-field plasticity models determining mechanical behavior of hexagonal close-packed metals, including anisotropy, asymmetry, damage, and fatigue. This capability pertains more to understanding the stress patterning mechanisms driving twin spacing than knowing a site-specific nucleation event. We develop an analytical model based on micromechanical formulation that can pinpoint where second twin must nucleate in an idealistic single twin variant scenario within a single crystal. The model was compared to the twin patterns in three-point in-situ bending of sharp textured AZ31 Mg alloys. The analytical solution to the stress field was obtained for a spherical oblate twin domain with uniform eigenstrain in homogenous, isotropic, and half-infinite space. The results show that the twin spacing depends upon the height of the twin domain, and the maximum stress relaxation from twin domain depends upon the thickness of the twin domain. The results compared well to experimental results.

647.prez_name: An Integrated Collaborative Environment for ICME
647.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
647.prez_authors: Charles H. Ward, Matthew D. Jacobsen
647.prez_abstract: The success of a materials information infrastructure is dependent on the availability of local nodes at the level of the researcher that can lower the barrier to capturing, processing, analyzing, storing, sharing, discovering, and publishing information.  The Integrated Collaborative Environment (ICE) is an ICME cyberinfrastructure that provides a web-based, federated software architecture supporting group and project spaces within which researchers can easily organize and collaborate on their experimental and computational efforts. It seamlessly connects researchers with resources for easy generation, collection, and storage of digital data. ICE uses a robust Application Programming Interface (API) to federate applications and repositories in a secure, efficient, and scalable manner.  The architecture is designed to be modular and agile for rapid deployment and expansion across organizations.  A number of open-source, commercial, and non-commercial software packages provide specific functionality needed to meet the large number of system requirements.

648.prez_name: Analyzing Trends and Correlations in Structure-property Relationships Using Canonical Correlation Analysis
648.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
648.prez_authors: Sudipto  Mandal, Jacky  Lao, Vahid  Tari, Anthony D. Rollett
648.prez_abstract: Successful modeling of a material’s deformation behavior is dependent on the development of realistic constitutive models. In-depth knowledge about the parameters in a constitutive model will lead to a better understanding of the relationship between flow stress and deformation conditions and will eventually aid in better design of the deformation process. Curve fitting is generally employed to train constitutive models using experimental data. However, relative impact of constitutive model parameters and microstructural features on the mechanical response has not been explored much. In this study, both local and global sensitivity analysis methods are used. Canonical correlation analysis (CCA) has been used to understand the effect of constitutive model parameters on the flow stress behavior of titanium alloys. It has been shown that CCA provides a measure of both individual variable’s contribution and the effectiveness of the parameter set as a whole.

649.prez_name: Application of Data Science to the Study and Design of 9-12% Cr Steel
649.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
649.prez_authors: Amit Kumar Verma, Jeffrey  A.  Hawk, Laura  Bruckman, Vyacheslav   Romanov, Roger  H.  French, Jennifer L. W.  Carter
649.prez_abstract: The development of 9-12% Cr ferritic/martensitic steels is necessary to meet the energy efficiency and lower carbon dioxide emission standards required of advanced ultra-supercritical (A-USC) coal-fired power plants in the 21st century. To accomplish this, data science approaches are being explored to determine if they can provide design guidance for new alloy development, now that intuitive design choices are focused on ppm alloy additions. Heritage data for 9-12% Cr-steels was investigated to explore a variety of alloy/processing design questions, with a focus towards expanding the present operating temperature range of 610 to 650 °C. In particular, network models were used to map multivariate, interdependency, correlations of different strengthening mechanisms on the design of high strength and creep resistant alloys. The approach explores multiple data science tools for rapid qualification of new alloys, while setting up generic methodologies to explore similar questions for other alloy families.

650.prez_name: Applications of Data Science and Machine Learning in Computational Materials Science
650.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
650.prez_authors: Elizabeth  Holm, Brian  DeCost, Ankita  Mangal
650.prez_abstract: Computer science has advanced rapidly in the internet era, primarily due to the availability of very large data sets. However, materials science has not yet fully capitalized on these advances. In this talk, we will discuss two approaches to utilizing data science in computational materials studies. The first involves using machine learning to gain scientific insights from large and complex data sets. As a case study, we demonstrate a data science approach to study stress hotspot formation in polycrystalline microstructures. We find expected and unexpected correlations that illustrate the power and the limitations of the machine learning approach. The second application uses computer vision and transfer learning concepts to autonomously find relationships in large and diverse microstructural image data sets. The results offer a new way to extract knowledge in order to design new materials, optimize material processes, and tailor material properties.

651.prez_name: Approaching the Fundamental Speed Limit of Materials Innovation
651.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
651.prez_abstract:
The Materials Genome Initiative’s well-known target of a 2x acceleration in materials development raises tantalizing question: How fast can we actually go?
As materials innovation is an iterative process amenable to optimization, the requirements for maximizing speed are (1) minimizing the number of iterations needed to achieve a desired result; and (2) minimizing the time involved in executing each iteration. In this talk, I will present a vision for approaching the fundamental speed limit of materials innovation by driving (1) and (2) to logical endpoints. To address (1), we must harness signal across all available data when designing experiments; and to address (2), we must use software and robotics to automate away mechanical, tedious tasks that encumber day-to-day materials work. I will assess where we are now on the path to realizing this vision, and argue that within just a few years its benefits will be widely available.

652.prez_name: Bellerophon Environment for Analysis of Materials (BEAM), A High Performance Computing Link to Understanding Material Properties
652.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
652.prez_authors: Alex  Belianinov, Eric  Lingerfelt, Stephen  Jesse
652.prez_abstract: The Bellerophon Environment for Analysis of Materials (BEAM) is an open source software system that brings the computational power of ORNL’s Compute And Data Environment for Science (CADES) to national user centers in order to perform near real-time data analysis of experimental data using a web-deliverable, cross-platform Java application. At the core of this new system is a web and data server enabling multiple, concurrent users to securely access uploaded data, execute materials science workflows, and interactively engage analysis artifacts. This talk will focus on strategies to employ machine learning, hyperspectral analysis, and data co-registration techniques to paint a clearer picture of material composition and chemistry at the nanoscale. Data from multimodal spectral and imaging techniques such as Raman, Nano-IR, TOF-SIMS as well as electron, ion, and probe microscopies will be presented and discussed in the framework of creating and utilizing integrated libraries of structure-property relationships through BEAM.

653.prez_name: Combining Hi Throughput Computations and Hi Throughput Experiments to Accelerate Discovery and Development of Structural Alloys
653.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
653.prez_authors: Dan  Miracle, Bhaskar  Majumdar, Katelun  Wertz, Stephane  Gorsse
653.prez_abstract: High throughput, combinatorial computations and experiments dramatically accelerate the discovery and development of functional materials, where properties depend primarily on composition. In structural materials, many properties depend sensitively on sample dimensions and microstructural length scales, complicating high throughput tools used for functional materials. Here we develop a new strategy to accelerate the exploration of structural alloys by combining high throughput computational methods with new high throughput experiments. This new strategy places new demands on high throughput computations in terms of accuracy, reliability and the ability to link to high throughput experiments. This strategy will be described and the implications for high throughput calculations will be discussed.

654.prez_name: Comparison of Single-sensor Differential Thermal Analysis (SSDTA) and Dilatometry in CCT Development in Grade 22 Steel
654.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
654.prez_abstract: Grade 22 steel is a 2.25Cr-1Mo steel commonly used in weld overlays in the Oil and Gas and Petrochemical industries. An important step in characterizing this material is the development of a continuous cooling transformation (CCT) diagram. The determination of the transformation temperatures necessary to build a CCT diagram traditionally involves locating inflection points on Dilation vs. Temperature plots for various cooling rates. Single-Sensor Differential Thermal Analysis (SSDTA) can identify heat dissipation due to phase transformations, and allow more precise transformation temperatures to be determined. SSDTA could also allow individual phases that form near the same temperature to be differentiated (e.g. differentiating between martensite and bainite formation). Results on the potential formation of ferrite in the Inter-Critical HAZ will also be discussed, with analysis using SSDTA and dilatometry.

655.prez_name: Data-driven Search and Design Strategies for the Development of Novel Magnetocaloric Materials
655.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
655.prez_abstract: Materials Informatics is a majorly evolving field that can wield, visualize, and analyze materials data; and has shown the potential to enable decision making in today’s cutting-edge materials research. Magnetocaloric materials—a class of magnetic materials that undergo a significant change in certain thermodynamic properties under an external applied magnetic field—have potential application as magnetic refrigerants. Past hypothesis-driven research has shown challenges and, the data-driven computer-aided materials design is expected to alleviate the existing challenges as well as provide future research directions in this class of materials. This work is focused on generating a comprehensive database of magnetocaloric materials, to identify variables/property sets which are highly correlated, and utilize the variable sets to obtain unique interpretations of data sets to support suitable substitutes and/or outliers to facilitate the development of novel magnetocaloric materials.

656.prez_name: Data-driven Selection, Design, and Optimization of Hard Magnetic Materials
656.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
656.prez_abstract: Hard magnetic materials are ubiquitous and, are used in myriad of applications including, but not limited to computers, green energy technologies, and defense systems. Over the years a variety of hard magnetic materials have been developed adopting several of the processing techniques, in various forms, to meet the imminent technological demands. It is imperative to integrate materials informatics to enable efficient and high-throughput screening and designing of novel magnetic materials. In this work a combination of—various multiple attribute decision making (MADM) methods, cluster expansion, principal component analysis (PCA), and partitioning were adopted for magnetic materials selection, design, and properties optimization. The magnetic materials—hard and soft —were evaluated using various MADMs. Shannon’s entropy model was adopted to evaluate the relative weights of various properties (attributes). Pearson correlation among the properties were calculated and, hierarchical clustering was adopted for classification. A decision-tree based model was developed using PCA and partitioning.

657.prez_name: Data Analytics for Mining Process-Structure-property Linkages for Hierarchical Materials
657.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
657.prez_abstract: Although the core connections between the material’s structure, its evolution through various manufacturing processes, and its macroscale properties are widely acknowledged to exist, establishing this fundamental knowledge base has proven effort-intensive, slow, and very expensive for most material systems being explored for advanced technology applications. It is anticipated that the multi-functional performance characteristics of a material are likely to be controlled by a relatively small number of salient features in its hierarchical internal structure. However, cost-effective validated protocols do not yet exist for rapid identification of these salient features and establishment of the desired core knowledge needed for the accelerated design, manufacture and deployment of new materials in advanced technologies. We will present novel data science algorithms and computationally efficient protocols capable of mining the essential linkages from large ensembles of disparate materials datasets and building robust knowledge systems.

658.prez_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design: The Materials Innovation Infrastructure
658.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
658.prez_abstract: Since its inception in 2011, the  progress of the Materials Genome Initiative has been marked by the ongoing development of the materials innovation infrastructure.  In this talk,  progress towards deploying these infrastructures will be discussed, as well as this infrastructure's influence on the way materials discovery, design, development, and deployment have progressed. I will also provide a high level review the status of the MGI, how the agencies across the federal government are coordinating this effort, and how NIST is supporting the Initiative.

659.prez_name: Design Optimization of Fractal Metamaterials with Distributed Gaussian Process
659.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
659.prez_abstract: Hierarchical cellular materials are ubiquitous in nature and have attractive characteristics of high strength and low density. Yet, the challenge of designing the hierarchical architecture of such materials to possess desirable mechanical behavior is not well understood. In this work, we propose a data-driven computational design framework for fractal metamaterials, using distributed Gaussian process and Bayesian optimization to account for model-form uncertainty associated surrogates throughout the optimization process. Different from classical Gaussian process regression, the proposed approach enables optimization with both continuous and discrete variables as well as dimensionality reduction for efficient computation for large-scale problems.

660.prez_name: Developing Infrastructure for High Quality Data of Materials Properties
660.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
660.prez_authors: Zi-Kui  Liu, Richard  Otis, Brandon  Bocklund
660.prez_abstract: For most cases, individual phases can be considered as the building blocks of materials (Integr. Mater. Manuf. Innov. 2014, 3, 12). In this presentation, the current infrastructure for properties of individual phases will be discussed along with associated challenges and opportunities. Particular emphases include high throughput computational and experimental approaches and tools (J. Open Res. Softw. 2017, 5, 1), uncertainty quantifications (JOM 2017, http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s11837-017-2318-6), automated database improvement (Magnesium Technology 2010; pp. 617–622), and anomaly prediction (Sci. Rep. 2014, 4, 7043).

661.prez_name: Development of the NIST Materials Resource Registry as a Means to Advertise, Find, and Use Materials-related Resources
661.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
661.prez_authors: Chandler A. Becker, Alden  Dima, Raymond L Plante, Sharief  Youssef, Andrea  Medina-Smith, Laura M Bartolo, Robert J Hanisch, James A Warren, Mary C Brady
661.prez_abstract: The NIST Materials Resource Registry (NMRR) system is being developed to facilitate the announcement, discovery, and use of materials-related resources such as repositories, data collections, organizations, projects, services, and software by researchers and engineers.  We envision the emergence of an international network of participating institutions and organizations, such as  professional societies, who maintain their own resource registries.  These participants would make their resource metadata available through a federated system that supports resource discovery and access, and which is built from software components such as the NMRR.  In addition to the development effort at NIST, we are working with partners (e.g., CHiMaD) and through an international Research Data Alliance working group to develop consensus on terminology, improve NMRR usability, and demonstrate its feasibility.  Here we will discuss the NIST effort’s goals and primary focus, technical development of the NMRR and its related materials vocabulary, and how other researchers and institutions can become involved.

662.prez_name: Efficient Protocols for Ranking the Transition Fatigue Performance of Polycrystalline Materials
662.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
662.prez_authors: Noah H. Paulson, Matthew W. Priddy, David L. McDowell, Surya R.  Kalidindi
662.prez_abstract: Increasing the rates of development and deployment of novel materials requires the use of high-throughput tools for the evaluation of properties. This is especially challenging for fatigue performance, where existing experimental and computational techniques are both time consuming and expensive. In this work, the materials knowledge system (MKS) for homogenization is extended to rank-order polycrystalline microstructures’ resistance to transition fatigue. In this framework, microstructures are quantified using 2-point spatial statistics for orientation and then represented in a reduced dimensionality space using principal component analysis (PCA). The linkage is calibrated with the representations of example microstructures and fatigue responses in the form of extreme value distributions of fatigue indicator parameters (FIPs). These data-driven linkages are many orders of magnitude faster than traditional methods. The efficiency, robustness and simplicity of the resultant linkages are well suited to materials optimization efforts.

663.prez_name: Estimating Thermal Expansion with Intrinsic Quantum Thermodynamics
663.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
663.prez_authors: Ryo  Yamada, Michael R. von Spakovsky, William T. Reynolds
663.prez_abstract: Mechanics and equilibrium thermodynamics are powerful scientific disciplines that overlap in computational materials science. However, there are well-known conceptual incompatibilities between the two frameworks that arise from their different origins. Intrinsic Quantum Thermodynamics (IQT) is one intriguing approach to reconcile the incompatibilities. We demonstrate the use of IQT to estimate the thermal expansion of face-centered-cubic silver not only at stable equilibrium states but also along a path from non-equilibrium to stable equilibrium states. The eigenstructures (eigenvalues and eigenfunctions) of anharmonic oscillators determined from band calculations were employed to determine the temperature dependence of the lattice parameter of Ag. The thermal expansion of Ag calculated using two different exchange-correlation functionals was in good agreement with experimental values. Analysis of the pair interaction potential derived from the band calculations allowed us to infer the origin of errors in the thermal expansion calculation.

664.prez_name: Facilitating Discovery of Materials Resources with NIST’s Federated Registry System
664.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
664.prez_authors: Laura M. Bartolo, Chandler A. Becker, Benjamin J Blaiszik, Ian T. Foster
664.prez_abstract: Materials data, organizations, services, and software are essential to grow advanced materials development and commercial adoption.  Finding materials datasets, software packages, data services, and tools to meet your needs amid the proliferation of resources can be daunting.  To support discovery and encourage collaborations, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) has launched its Materials Resource Registry (MRR) system.  To support international materials alliances, NIST and its collaborators are building a federation of MRRs for discovery of global materials data resources.  As an illustration, we will discuss an MRR instance the NIST Center of Excellence for Hierarchical Materials Design (CHiMaD) and its Materials Data Facility (MDF) have established that MDF will operate as part of the NSF Midwest Big Data Spoke on Integrative Materials Design, connecting the MRR with Materials Big Data resources.  Deeper search services provided by MDF to enable materials discovery and development will also be discussed.

665.prez_name: High-throughput and Machine-learning Diffusion Modeling with the MAterials Simulation Toolkit (MAST)
665.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
665.prez_authors: Dane  Morgan, Tam  Mayeshiba, Henry  Wu
665.prez_abstract: We have developed the MAterials Simulation Toolkit (MAST) to support high-throughput screening of materials properties with ab initio methods. MAST Workflow (MAST-WF) allows easy management of complex workflows, produces well-organized output data, and is highly stable, even after multiple interruptions. We demonstrate MAST on a complex workflow with dozens of steps, which has been used to predict over 300 dilute impurity diffusion coefficients in host metals. This large, consistently calculated database enables us to extract novel insights into how impurity diffusion trends with multiple factors, including size, atomic number, host structure, and magnetism. MAST Machine Learning (MAST-ML) is being developed to enable efficient application of machine-learning tools to materials problems. Here we show how MAST-ML will be used to develop accurate machine-learning models for diffusion coefficients, allowing us to predict thousands of new diffusion systems without any significant additional computation.

666.prez_name: High-throughput Identification and Characterization of Two-dimensional Materials Using Density Functional Theory
666.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
666.prez_authors: Kamal  Choudhary, Ryan   Beams, Irina   Kalish, Francesca  Tavazza
666.prez_abstract: We introduce a simple criterion to identify two-dimensional (2D) materials based on the comparison between experimental lattice constants and lattice constants mainly obtained from Materials-Project (MP) density functional theory (DFT) calculation repository. Specifically, if the relative difference between the two lattice constants for a specific material is more than 5%, we predict them to be good candidates for 2D materials resulting in at least 521 such 2D materials.  We manually create single layer systems and calculate their energetics, structural, electronic, and elastic. To validate our criterion, we calculated the exfoliation energy of the suggested layered materials with 88.9% agreement. We also performed X-ray diffraction and Raman scattering experiments to benchmark our calculation data for molybdenum telluride as a test case. We have 427 bulk and 252 single layer materials in our database but many more calculations are currently underway. The data is publicly available at the website http://www.ctcms.nist.gov/~knc6/JVASP.html .

667.prez_name: High-throughput Materials Discovery and Development: Computational Tools for Data Generation and Advanced Characterization
667.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
667.prez_abstract: High-Throughput Quantum-Mechanics computation of materials properties by ab initio methods has become the foundation of an effective approach to materials design, discovery and characterization. This data driven approach to materials science currently presents the most promising path to the development of advanced technological materials that could solve or mitigate important social and economic challenges of the 21st century. Enhanced repositories such as AFLOW.org open novel opportunities for structure discovery and optimization, including uncovering of unsuspected compounds, metastable structures and correlations between various properties. The practical realization of these opportunities depends on the the design of efficient algorithms for electronic structure simulations of realistic material systems beyond the limitations of the current standard theories. I will review recent progress in theoretical and computational tools, and in particular, discuss the development and validation of novel functionals within Density Functional Theory and of local basis representations for effective ab-initio tight-binding schemes.

668.prez_name: Identifying Structural Motifs in Disordered Materials
668.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
668.prez_authors: Jason J Maldonis, Arash Dehghan Banadaki, Srikanth  Patala, Paul M Voyles
668.prez_abstract: Even with an atomistic structural model, understanding the structure of disordered materials is complicated by the lack of long-range order and the distribution of orientations of structural units. We have developed a method to identify structural motifs in disordered systems, starting from short-range order (SRO) units, such as an atom and its nearest neighbors. Given two such units, we first remove the trivial rotational and translation degrees of freedom to best map the two structures onto one another. Then, we can calculate atom-by-atom structure similarity metrics such as the sum of the rms distances between matched pairs of atoms. Repeating this calculation for all pairs of SRO units in a material forms a similarity matrix amenable to machine learning. Clustering algorithms then group the SRO units into structurally similar categories, learning prototypical structures from the model. Application of this method to identify prototypes in bulk metallic glasses will be presented.

669.prez_name: Machine Learning Strategies to Guide Materials Discovery
669.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
669.prez_abstract: Data-to-knowledge ideas are beginning to show promise within materials science. Among these ideas is “machine learning”, a branch of artificial intelligence pertaining to the creation of models that can effectively learn from past data, and make rapid predictions and decisions when confronted with new situations. In this talk, I will provide a general background to this topic, and discuss the example of screening for superior or new dielectric materials through accelerated property predictions. The challenges that remain and the need for additional methodological developments necessary to further strengthen this design concept will also be discussed.

670.prez_name: Materials Discovery and Design at Finite Temperatures
670.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
670.prez_authors: Jan  Janssen, Albert  Glensk, Blazej  Grabowski, Tilmann  Hickel, Jörg  Neugebauer
670.prez_abstract: The behavior and performance of a material at T=0K and at technologically relevant temperatures can differ considerably. To account for temperature effects in simulating and predicting materials properties all excitation mechanisms (vibrational, electronic, magnetic and their couplings) have to be included. In the past years, tremendous progress has been made in computing these contributions on a fully ab initio level. However, the computational effort, as well as the complexity of the developed simulation protocols, are significantly more demanding than conventional T=0K calculations.  As a consequence, such calculations have been mainly restricted to a few selected materials. To enable high-throughput calculations of materials properties at finite temperatures we have systematically explored routes to identify computationally efficient yet accurate approaches to compute these contributions and implement them in our highly automated framework PyIron. Examples of the performance of this approach will be given with respect to the design of high-strength light-weight materials.

671.prez_name: Materials Informatics and Big Data: Realization of 4th Paradigm of Science in Materials Science
671.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
671.prez_abstract: In this age of “big data”, large-scale experimental and simulation data is increasingly becoming available in all fields of science. Our ability to collect and store this data has greatly surpassed our capability to analyze it, underscoring the emergence of the fourth paradigm of science, which is data-driven discovery. The need to use of advanced data science approaches in materials science is also recognized by the Materials Genome Initiative (MGI), further promoting the emerging field of materials informatics. In this talk, I would present some of our recent works employing state-of-the-art data analytics for exploring processing-structure-property-performance (PSPP) linkages in materials, both in terms of forward models (e.g. predicting property for a given material) and inverse models (e.g. discovering materials that possess a desired property). I will also demonstrate some online web-tools we have developed that deploy machine learning based forward models to predict materials properties.

672.prez_name: Materials Informatics Discovery Platform & RESTful API
672.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
672.prez_abstract:
Historically, materials discovery is driven by a laborious trial-and-error process. The growth of materials databases and emerging informatics approaches finally offer the opportunity to transform this practice into data- and knowledge-driven rational design—accelerating discovery of novel materials exhibiting desired properties. 
By using data from the AFLOW repository for high-throughput ab-initio calculations, we have generated Quantitative Materials Structure-Property Relationship (QMSPR) models to predict seven critical material properties. To enable these calculation, we have developed novel materials descriptors such as universal property-labelled fragments (PLMF).[1] We have established that the accuracy of predictions obtained with machine learning models approaches that of GGA DFT functionals yet model development requires a minute fraction of computational time as compared to ab initio calculations. Notably, due to the representation of materials with PLMF the QMSPR models are broadly applicable to virtually any stoichiometric inorganic materials. 
[1] O. Isayev, et al. arXiv:1608.04782

673.prez_name: Methods for Discovery and Design of Advanced Materials Across Length Scales
673.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
673.prez_abstract: The discovery and design of advanced materials has occurred for thousands of years and accelerated dramatically in the last 100 years with the development of ever more sophisticated methods for material characterization. The application of computational methods to the process is comparatively new but potentially impactful. This presentation will discuss methods that enable the discovery and design of advanced materials within computational materials science and the role of databases and datamining algorithms. Applications include algorithms for the discovery of 2D materials with desirable structure-property relationships through the identification of bonded atomic clusters within the unit cells of 3D materials and determining the way in which these bonded clusters scale with the size of the unit cell, the utilization of electronic structure methods to design new 2D materials and heterostructures, and the development of reactive empirical potentials (reactive force fields) to discover and design material interfacial structures at the atomic scale.

674.prez_name: Microstructural Variability Constrained Uncertainty Propagation in the Hierarchical Multiscale Modeling of Cartridge Brass
674.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
674.prez_authors: Aaron E. Tallman, Joseph E Bishop, Laura P Swiler, Yan  Wang, David L McDowell
674.prez_abstract: Mechanisms physically described at one length scale can affect materials performance at higher length scales. In deterministic macroplasticity models, the uncertainty of mechanical response that arises from microstructure variability in ductile metals is often neglected. Stress concentrators can exacerbate this limitation. The microstructure-sensitive stress-strain response of cartridge brass is approached with a hierarchical multiscale model. A crystal plasticity model and monotonic tensile and microstructural data inform an internal state variable (ISV) model for cartridge brass, including variability arising from underlying microstructure. Microstructure instantiations are generated using Dream3D. Comparisons are made with a classical homogenization scheme. The new approach informs the ISV model element-wise with an ensemble of statistical volume element (SVE) simulations. Macroplasticity finite element size is tied to SVE simulation size; both are varied. The trade-off between discretization error and SVE size related bias is explored. The use of scale-bridging in passing multiple types of uncertainty is discussed.

675.prez_name: NIST Alloys Thermophysical Property Data Development
675.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
675.prez_authors: Erik  Pfeif, Boris  Wilthan, Vladimir  Diky, Scott  Townsend, Andrei  Kazakov, Kroenlein  Kenneth
675.prez_abstract: Efforts at the NIST Thermodynamics Research Center (TRC) focus on improving the thermophysical property data infrastructure through the collection, curation and dissemination of critically evaluated property data.  With the increased use of ab-initio or experimentally-based predictive approaches adopted by the Integrated Computational Materials Engineering (ICME) community, the need for the tools, databases, and communication standards developed by the TRC abounds. Community use of data standards provides a means for a common interface between data producers and data consumers. In these standards, standard methods for communication of metadata, such as: measured uncertainties, purity information, and processing history; will afford material scientists with the ability to curate their own high quality databases - i.e. allowing for the scientists to supplement their own database, or specifically exclude suspicious or ill-defined data. An overview of the alloy data curation efforts at TRC will be presented.

676.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
676.prez_abstract: A goal of accelerated materials discovery is finding materials with targeted properties using as few experiments as possible. Machine learning and statistical design methods, used in industry for solving complex problems, are increasingly being adapted for the design of new materials by learning from past data. However, the number of well characterized samples available as sources of data to learn from is typically small; as a result, uncertainties associated with the predictions from model fits, or even those from measurements, become large and important. The choice of the next experiment or calculation solely based on the machine model predictions is prone to be suboptimal. Thus, optimization or experimental design schemes are needed for decision making to guide experiments using uncertainties to explore the vast material descriptor space. I will discuss how an active learning framework that iteratively combines inference and design offers a promising approach.

677.prez_name: Prediction of Microstructure Evolution in Phase-field Simulations Through Data Analytics and Time Series
677.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
677.prez_authors: Yuksel  Yabansu, Linyun  Liang, Long-Qing  Chen, Surya  Kalidindi
677.prez_abstract: Phase-field simulations have proven to be successful in modeling and capturing the salient features of microstructures and their evolution through a processing history for several material systems and phenomena. However, the conventional phase-field simulations are computationally effort-intensive resulting in a slow and expensive exploration of microstructure space for the process-structure-property relationships. For the first time, a templated workflow is implemented for learning the physics involved in microstructure evolution in phase-field simulations through data analytics and time series. This study depicts the reduced order statistical representation of entire microstructure evolution in phase-field simulations through two-point statistics and principal component analysis (PCA). It will be shown that the reduced order representation of microstructure can be effectively and efficiently used in a time-series approach to capture the physics of microstructure evolution in a compact metamodel with high reusability for future microstructures.

678.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
678.prez_abstract: Experimental and multi-scale computational methods generate increasingly large data sets of thermal, mechanical, and chemical material properties. To capture the key physics and chemistry of the material, mathematical models relate material properties to parameters such as temperature, pressure, and composition. High quality models are comprehensive, robust, precise, accurate, and predictive. Given the complexity of the data and the advent of high throughput experiments and computations, creating quality models in near-real time becomes a challenging task, which can be accomplished with support from supervised or unsupervised machine learning algorithms.  In this study, we evaluate the quality of several material models and examine popular model development methodologies and “best practices.”

679.prez_name: Quasi-Coarse-Grained Dynamics to Unravel the Behavior of Materials at the Mesoscales
679.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
679.prez_abstract: One of the long standing problems in materials design is the gap in the modeling capability of behavior at the scales between the atomic scales and the continuum scales i.e. at the mesoscales. A computationally efficient modeling method called “quasi-coarse-grained dynamics” (QCGD) is developed that expands the capabilities of molecular dynamics (MD) simulations to model behavior of materials at the mesoscales using scaling relationships for atomic scale interatomic potentials. The QCGD method uses a reduced number of atoms and improved timesteps and is able to retain the atomic scale processes related to plastic deformation, phase transformation and heat generation and transfer as observed in MD simulations. The capability to bridge the mesoscale gap between the current atomic scale simulations and the continuum simulations to model the deformation and phase transformation behavior will be discussed. This work is funded by the US Army Research Office under grant # W911NF-14-1-0257.

680.prez_name: The Effective Use of Data in Materials Research
680.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
680.prez_abstract: Rapid advances in information technology have made it possible to generate, analyze, and distribute large data sets of material properties. One of the great challenges in materials research is to effectively make use of these data sets to accelerate the design and development of new materials. To this end, I will discuss how data can be leveraged in two ways. I will demonstrate how machine learning, in the form of genetic programming, can be used to identify descriptors for material properties, facilitating rational materials design. I will also demonstrate how informatics can be used to rapidly generate highly efficient k-point grids. Our group has developed a publicly accessible k-point grid server backed by a database of hundreds of thousands of k-point grids, and we estimate that for a broad range of computational methods the use of this server can nearly double the average speed of electronic structure calculations for materials.

681.prez_name: The Role of Infrastructure in Materials Informatics
681.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
681.prez_authors: C.  Campbell, I.  Foster, G.  Olson, L.  Bartolo, J.  de Pablo, Peter  Voorhees
681.prez_abstract: Materials data lies at the core of any materials development effort.  It provides the foundation for the models that are used to compute the properties of hierarchical materials.  A classic example is the central role played by CALPHAD free energy functions in simulations of microstructural evolution in hierarchical materials. Another is identifying compounds with unique properties through mining databases created by density functional calculations.  However, challenges remain.  In many cases it is unclear how to share data and discover existing databases.  While many materials databases exist, their long-term sustainability is often unclear. In addition, there is no community-wide consensus on the proper metadata for a given dataset. An approach to handling large materials data, CALPHAD protodata databases for hard and soft materials, methods for creating schemas for materials data, and the challenge of long-term sustainability of databases will be discussed.

682.prez_name: Thermodynamic Modeling with Uncertainty Quantification and Its Implications for Additive Manufacturing
682.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
682.prez_abstract: CALPHAD-based thermodynamic modeling is now routinely used to predict and understand the observed properties of multi-component alloy systems. While these thermodynamic predictions are often in qualitatively good agreement with experiments, we show that there are significant limitations in the commercially available thermodynamic databases. These limitations are due to the cumbersome task of maintaining complex multi-component databases. This work describes new software architecture, with a particular focus on uncertainty quantification, for improving these databases for additive manufacturing applications. This approach requires little input from the user, making it possible to be integrated into automated, high-throughput modeling infrastructure. With a more robust and efficient method for generating multi-component thermodynamic databases based on the latest available data, thermodynamic studies of materials systems for additive manufacturing will become more predictive and accurate.

683.prez_name: Using the Materials Commons in Integrated Computational Materials Science Workflows
683.symp_name: Data and Tools for Materials Discovery and Design
683.prez_authors: Brian  Puchala, Glenn  Tarcea, Terry  Weymouth, Tracy  Berman, John  Allison
683.prez_abstract: New materials data infrastructure tools promise to increase the pace of materials design and discovery by increasing collaboration, increasing access to data, and making data more easily used and re-used. The Materials Commons is a collaboration platform and information repository for the global materials community developed by the PRedictive Integrated Structural Materials Science (PRISMS) Center at the University of Michigan.  A key feature of the Materials Commons is the seamless and "automatic" capture of data provenance.  Initial set-up for a particular computational or experimental process requires modest planning to determine the data and metadata to be stored, and how it will be represented, extracted, and uploaded.  This enables the Materials Commons to capture data from the computational or experimental process and use it to describe processing-structure-property relationships in materials. We describe this process, challenges, and lessons-learned by reviewing examples drawn from experience integrating PRISMS Center software with the Materials Commons.

900.prez_name: An Innovative Pathway to Nanostructured Sapphire Optical Fiber for Sensing in Harsh Environments
900.prez_authors: Hui  Chen, Jiri  Kanka, Zsolt L. Poole, Paul  Ohodnicki, Henry  Du
900.prez_abstract: Single-crystal sapphire (α-Al2O3) optical fiber holds excellent promise for sensing in harsh environments such as those encountered in advanced high efficiency, near-zero emission energy generation systems due to its high optical transmission (UV-mid IR range), high melting point (~2040°C), excellent mechanical strength, and superior chemical stability. Development of high-quality commercially viable cladding on sapphire fiber has remained elusive despite numerous efforts, which hampers its exploration and exploitation under service conditions. We report an innovative and scalable strategy of transforming a commercial unclad sapphire optical fiber to an all-alumina nanostructured sapphire optical fiber (NSOF) that overcomes decades-long challenges faced in sapphire fiber optics. The strategy entails fiber coating with metal aluminum followed by subsequent anodization to form anodized alumina oxide (AAO) cladding of highly-organized pore channel structure. We, through experiments and numerical simulation, demonstrate the utility and benefit of NSOF for evanescent-field surface-enhanced Raman scattering (SERS) measurements at high temperatures.

901.prez_name: Broadband Tunable Emission of Glasses for Single-phase Multi-Chromatic/White Light Phosphors
901.prez_authors: Ruilin  Zheng, Qi  Zhang, Wei  Wei
901.prez_abstract: Superior optical properties of phosphors are very important in the applications of solid-state lighting. Glass phosphors have simple manufacture procedure, easy formation of any shape and high transparency, except the lower quantum efficiency of rare earth ions. Therefore, if a glass phosphor could show high CRI and QE, it will be a great potential multi-chromatic/white light phosphor for the LEDs. A series of broadband tunable emission of glasses (BTE) for single-phase multi-chromatic phosphors have been investigated, which have highly color rendering index (over 90) and quantum efficiency (over 85%). Continuous tunable emission from blue to red can be obtained by changing doping concentration. Moreover, by combining with commercially available LED chips directly, the CIE coordinate (x=0.32, y=0.33) and correlated color temperature (5620 K) are close to the standard white-light illumination. BTE glasses are promising candidates as alternative single-phase multi-chromatic/white light phosphors for use in solid state lighting and display devices.

902.prez_name: Comparison of Hot Pressing and Spark Plasma Sintering in the Densification Behavior of Indium Tin Oxide – Borosilicate Glass Composites
902.prez_abstract: The goal of this study was to fabricate ITO-borosilicate glass composites with high optical transmittance and conductivity by forming percolated segregated networks of ITO in the microstructure. ITO nanoparticles and borosilicate glass microspheres were mechanically mixed with ITO concentrations varying from 0-2.99 vol% and consolidated using either hot pressing (HP) or spark plasma sintering (SPS). Ac impedance spectroscopy (IS), SEM, and EDS indicated the successful formation of a grain-like microstructure of the sintered glass, with the ITO particles segregated to the boundary regions, in all samples. IS results indicated percolation threshold values below 0.764 vol% ITO in all samples, with resistivities approaching 101 Ωcm at 2.99 vol% ITO. Contrary to conventional belief, it was found that samples made using SPS required far higher temperatures to fully densify, with all other processing conditions being the same, compared with HP. The cause of this behavior is still under investigation.

903.prez_name: Crystallization Kinetics and Microstructural Development in a Complex Borosilicate Glass-ceramic for Waste Vitrification
903.prez_authors: Paul  Porter, Nicholas  Roberts, Richard  Brow, Jarrod  Crum
903.prez_abstract:
We have studied the effects of thermal history on the evolution of the microstructure of a complex borosilicate glass-ceramic developed for nuclear waste vitrification.  Glass melts were quenched from 3°C/sec to 50°C/sec, using a melt-wedge technique, and other melts were quenched in a roller cooler (~100°C/sec) and in furnaces cooled as slowly as 0.01°/sec.  Analytical scanning electron microscopy was used to characterize the development of microstructural features, including the formation of Mo-rich droplets from which powellite nucleates and grows, and the development of rare-earth containing oxyapatite crystals. In a second set of experiments, melts were cooled at fixed rates and isothermally held using a hot thermocouple system to characterize the onset of microstructural features.
This work was supported by the US Department of Energy (NEUP 15-8112).

904.prez_name: Design and Characterization of Glass-Ceramic Layered Composites with Enhanced Mechanical Properties
904.prez_authors: Raul  Bermejo, Peter  Supancic, Franz  Aldrian, Robert  Danzer
904.prez_abstract: The strength variability, brittleness and environmental assisted cracking of glass-ceramic composites may compromise their use for structural applications. In this work, novel glass-ceramic layered architectures designed with surface compressive residual stresses are investigated. As an example, Low Temperature Co-fired Ceramic (LTCC) materials, used as substrates in electronic circuits, are analyzed. The magnitude of the (in-plane) residual stresses is tailored combining two LTCCs with different microstructures, varying the volume ratio between the two materials. Experimental findings based upon ball-on-three-balls (B3B) biaxial bending tests show a significant increase in the LTCC strength, associated with the compressive residual stress in the surface layer. In addition, the strength distribution in dependence of the surface stresses in the outer layer shows a “threshold strength” (i.e. minimum strength) for the composite material. Analogue, it is demonstrated that the use of compressive residual stresses can yield a threshold intensity factor, below which no environmental assisted cracking occurs.

905.prez_name: Effects of Microstructure on the Corrosion Behavior of Borosilicate Glass-ceramics for Waste Vitrification
905.prez_authors: Nicholas  Roberts, Richard  Brow, Jarrod  Crum, Paul  Porter
905.prez_abstract: Spent nuclear fuels will be reprocessed into several secondary waste products, as described by the Advanced Fuel Cycle Initiative (AFCL). The secondary waste products are intended to be vitrified into environmentally acceptable waste forms. One form developed by Pacific Northwest National Laboratories (PNNL) is a borosilicate glass-ceramic. Borosilicate glasses provided by PNNL were re-melted and quenched at various rates using a wedge-cast technique to produce samples with a range of microstructures. Analytical scanning electron microscopy provided information on the phase separation and crystallization processes behind the microstructural development.  Corrosion tests were performed to understand how the individual phases in the glass-ceramic affect its overall chemical durability. This work was supported by the US Department of Energy (NEUP 15-8112).

906.prez_name: Functionalizing a Glass Surface with Nanostructures for Nanophotonic and Optoelectronic Applications
906.prez_authors: Cheng  Zhang, Henri Joseph Lezec, Wenqi  Zhu, Amit  Agrawal
906.prez_abstract: In this talk, I will present our recent investigation of nanostructures built on glass for nanophotonic and optoelectronic applications. Examples include flat lenses with a negative index of refraction, structural colors with an angle-insensitive response, metamaterials with a hyperbolic dispersion, surface-plasmon lasers, and transparent conductive electrode using an ultra-thin silver film.

907.prez_name: Glass-ceramic Composite for Wavelength Tunable Light Source
907.prez_abstract: Functional luminescent materials that show wavelength-tunable and broadband luminescence are of great interest for various applications, including broadband telecommunication and tunable lasers. Glass materials have some incomparable advantages such as high transparency and easy elaboration. However, it still remains a significant challenge to construct active glass with wavelength-tunable and broadband luminescence. Here, we present an in-situ strategy for controlling the optical properties of glass via simultaneous tailoring of the evolution of phases and the distribution of dopants in the glassy phase. We show that the controllable precipitation of nanocrystals (e.g., Ga2O3, Ga2O3:In/F, Mg2SiO4, Ba0.808(Al1.71Si2.29)O8, and LaF3) inside glassy phase and the selective incorporation of dopants (e.g., Ni2+, Er3+) into them can be achieved. The obtained highly transparent glass-ceramic materials show unique multicolor visible and broadband near-infrared emission. The results suggest that the strategy could be applied to fabricate multifunctional light sources with a broad range of important host/activator combinations.

908.prez_authors: Frank  Wessely, Dennis  Braeuhaus, Gerrit  Scheich, Nils Christian  Nielsen
908.prez_abstract: We are introducing a novel, black silica-composite material. The black appearance of HBQ is achieved by embedding elemental Silicon particles in a densely sintered, pure silica matrix (>99.9%). Material properties, such as low thermal conductivity, thermal shock resistance, low coefficient of thermal expansion and chemical inertness, are governed by the silica matrix. The temperature dependent high emissivity of HBQ results from the indirect band-gap of the incorporated elemental Silicon. The absence of carbon in the material yields a high resistance against oxidizing and reducing atmosphere at temperatures up to as high as 1300°C. Combined with the availability in a wide dimensional range and the ease of machining, HBQ is suitable for a wide field of applications and is already in use where emissivity, purity and thermal stability are essential.

909.prez_name: Improved Characterization of Cell Phone Glass by SEM/EDS with an Updated Silicon Drift Detector
909.prez_abstract: Cell phone display cover glasses pose special problems for SEM/EDS because they are nonconductors. Some of them change composition under the influence of the electron beam. Newer Silicon Drift x-ray Detectors can measure x-rays much more quickly and with less beam current than the traditional Si(Li) x-ray detector did. Rather than do the same analysis more quickly, analysts should use the same analysis time as before to perform more detailed analyses that provide a richer understanding of the sample. Time series data makes visible, and documents, any changes in a sample over time and provides a guide for making a safe analysis of a challenging sample. Analysis of multiple areas reveals sample homogeneity. Groups of analyses reveal trends and outliers that provide insight that would be missed by relying on a single spectrum. Analysis of glass from several popular cell phones illustrate these points.

910.prez_name: Luminescence Properties of Rare Earth Doped Chalcogenide Glass Ceramics and Quantum Dots/Chalcogenide Glass Composite
910.prez_authors: Jihong  Zhang, Lingchao  Meng, Chao  Liu, Xiujian  Zhao, Jong  Heo
910.prez_abstract: In first part, the upconversion, and near, mid-infrared luminescence properties of rare earth doped chalcogenide glass and glass ceramics will be investigated. The effect of glass compositions on the local environment and emission properties will be discussed. The dependency of local surroundings on the energy transfer processes will be studied. The luminescence were enhanced due to the formation of nano-crystal in chalcogenide glass matrix, by heat-treatment process control. The local surrounding changes at the early stage of crystallization will be analyzed. In second part, PbS/PbSe quantum dots and As2S3 glass composite were prepared by mixing, pressing, and consolidation processes. Near infrared from the composite were observed. The effect of processing parameters on the luminescence properties of composite will be discussed. In addition, ultra-broad near infrared emission from mixed PbSe quantum dots and chalcogenide glass composite were obtained. The quantum dots in As2S3 glass matrix were proved by XRD,TEM and others.

911.prez_name: Microstructure Effects on the Dynamic Tensile (Spall) Strength of Titanium-based Bulk Metallic Glass In-situ formed Composites
911.prez_abstract: The influence of microstructure on the dynamic tensile (spall) strength of Ti-based metallic glass composites with varying volume fractions (0-80%) of in-situ formed crystalline dendrites will be presented. Plate-impact experiments were performed using the 80-mm single-stage gas gun over impact stresses up to 18 GPa. VISAR interferometry was used to obtain rear free-surface velocity profiles revealing the velocity pullback spall failure signals. The influence of microstructure on the spall strength is established by correlating quantitatively determined microstructural parameters including volume fraction, inter-dendritic spacing, and mean linear intercept with the constants of the power law fit, to the dependence of spall strength on the decompression strain rate. The microstructure with neither 100% glass nor with very high crystalline content, provides the most tortuous path for fracture and therefore highest spall strength. The results allow projection of spall strength predictions for design of in-situ formed metallic glass composites.

912.prez_name: Nanocrystal-glass Composite Electrolytes with Superior Ionic Conductivity and Stability for Na-ion Batteries
912.prez_authors: Ruilin  Zheng, Hanqing  Dai, Wei  Wei
912.prez_abstract: All solid-state sodium-ion electrolytes have attracted increasing attention due to their wide range of applications in secondary batteries. Chalcogenide electrolytes with high ionic conductivities have been extensively studied for room-temperature sodium-ion batteries. Nevertheless, suffering from the high cost of the raw materials and poor ambient stability, they are far from practical use. Oxide electrolytes have much better chemical stability, simple preparation processes, and easy availability and low cost of the raw materials. Here, a new NaTi2(PO4)3 nanocrystal-glass composite electrolyte, (Na2O+NaF)-TiO2-B2O3-P2O5-ZrF4 (NTBPZ), has been proposed and synthesized. Due to a low activation energy of 13.9 kJmol-1 and reduced resistance at the grain boundaries, the NaTi2(PO4)3-NTBPZ nanocrystal-glass composite has a room-temperature ionic conductivity as high as 10-4 Scm-1. In addition, the NaTi2(PO4)3-NTBPZ electrolyte has excellent thermal and chemical stabilities under ambient conditions. These outstanding performances make the NaTi2(PO4)3-NTBPZ a promising electrolyte for all-solid-state sodium-ion batteries.

913.prez_name: Photoelectric Properties of Nano-crystallized Chalcogenide Glass-ceramics
913.prez_authors: Xianghua  Zhang, Ilia  Korolkov, Michel  Cathelinaud, Hongli  Ma, Laurent  Calvez, Jean-Luc  Adam
913.prez_abstract: Selenide glasses are generally poor electric conductors. The conductivity can be greatly increased by controlled crystallization in order to generate appropriate semiconducting crystalline phases inside the glass matrix. The nanostructure of the glass ceramics is the key to adjust its photoelectric properties. In this presentation, the GeSe2-Sb2Se3-CuI glass forming system will be particularly studied. The influence of the composition and the crystallization on the photoelectric properties will be studied in relationship with the nanostructure. The potential applications of these innovative composite materials for photo-catalysis and photovoltaic will be discussed.

914.prez_name: Recent Development of China Nuclear Waste Vitrification
914.prez_abstract: China nuclear power plants are expected to provide at least 58 GW of capacity by 2020, then up to 150 GW by 2030. With such rapid growth of nuclear power, huge amount of high-, intermediate- and low-level radioactive wastes will be soon generated. The high-level waste in China is going to be immobilized in the borosilicate glass before the long-term geological disposal, while, vitrification of intermediate- and low-level wastes is an option. This talk will review the recent development of China nuclear waste vitrification. The main works include (i) investigation of glass formulation for kinds of wastes, (ii) development of the vitrification technology, including cold-crucible induction melter and plasma torch melter, and (ii) development of the waste-form for the waste from Thorium-based fuel.

915.prez_name: Sintering Behavior and Phase Transition of ZnS-CaLa2S4 Composites
915.prez_abstract: In the present research, commercial calcium lanthanum sulfide (CaLa2S4, CLS) powder was mixed and ground with lab-synthesized zinc sulfide (ZnS) nano powder via high-energy ball milling. The milled composite powder was then consolidated by field assisted sintering at different temperatures to form ZnS-CLS composite ceramics. XRD analysis revealed that the composite ceramics were composed of sphalerite and wurtzite-phase ZnS, and thorium phosphate-phase CLS. TEM observations of the composite ceramics reveal that the sphalerite-wurtzite phase transition of ZnS is accompanied by the formation of stacking faults and twins. Through sintering curve analyses and microstructural observations, it was determined that grain boundary diffusion is the main mechanism controlling the grain growth of both the ZnS and CLS phases of the composite ceramics during sintering at 800-1000 ºC. In addition, it was determined that the addition of CLS to ZnS improved the indentation hardness of the ceramics relative to pure ZnS.

916.prez_name: Tuning Different Crystalline Phases via Composition Design in Ge-Ga-S Chalcogenide Glass-ceramics
916.prez_abstract: We prepared Ge-Ga-S glasses and annealed them at a temperature to create chalcogenide glass-ceramics with an aim at tuning the formation of the different crystals in chalcogenide glass-ceramics. Through systematic characterisation of the structure using X-ray diffraction and Raman scattering spectra, we found that, GeS2 and GeS crystals only can be created in S-rich and S-poor glass-ceramics, respectively,  while all GeS, Ga2S3 and GeS2 crystals exist in chemically stoichiometric glass-ceramics. Moreover, we demonstrated the homogeneous distribution of the crystals can be formed in the S-rich glass-ceramics from the surface to the interior via composition designing. The present approach blazes a new path to control the growth of the different crystals in chalcogenide glass-ceramics.

917.prez_name: Vector Soliton Polarization Dynamics in Anisotropic Silica Glass Optical Fiber Based Ultrafast Laser
917.prez_authors: Chengbo  Mou, Sergey  Sergeyev, Raz  Arif, Aleksey  Rozhin
917.prez_abstract: The recent developed silica glass optical fiber based ultrafast laser offers great potential in various applications including micromachining, metrology, biomedical imaging and telecommunication. With the advances of carbon nanomaterials, such lasers can now benefit from more compact and robust design. Various properties including pulse energy, repetition rate, timing jitter have been widely studied in conventional ultrafast lasers. In an anisotropic silica optical fiber based ultrafast laser, due to the unbalanced cylindrical symmetry of the glass fiber, the whole laser could behave as a dissipative isotropic/anisotropic cavity. Therefore, the output ultrashort pulses would exhibit polarization precessing in the time scale of tens of thousands roundtrips. In this paper, we will review the recent investigation on the polarization dynamics of vectorial soliton from a carbon nanotube mode locked ultrafast silica glass fiber laser. Various polarization trajectories along the Poincare sphere will be presented under different mode locking regimes.

1128.prez_name: In-situ Experimental Measurement and Numerical Simulation of Translational Friction Welding of Titanium Alloy
1128.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1128.prez_authors: Kaiwen  Zhang, Wei  Zhang, Michael  Eff, Samuel  Kuhr, Hamish  Fraser, Thomas  Broderick
1128.prez_abstract: Translational or linear friction welding is a solid-state welding process that is increasingly used to join titanium alloys in the aerospace industry. The TFW process is highly-transient, rapid heating and cooling, severe plastic deformation and microstructure evolution (dynamic recrystallization). To gain a better understanding of the process transients, specially-designed TFW experiments were performed in the present study.  Rectangular coupons of Ti-6Al-4V were painted with a speckle pattern, which was used to map the surface deformation strains by digital image correlation in-situ during TFW.  The same surface was also measured for temperature distribution using an infrared camera and thermocouples.  For numerical modeling, a series of thermal-stress models of TFW were developed based on DEFORM, a commercial finite element analysis code. The accuracy of 2-D longitudinal, transverse and full 3-D models was discussed by comparing the simulated results with the measured temperature and strain fields in the region near the joint interface

1129.prez_name: A Computational Modeling Approach to Predict the Interfacial Characteristics Obtained in High Velocity Impact Welding of Metals
1129.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1129.prez_authors: Varun  Gupta, Xin  Sun, Kyoo Sil  Choi, Anupam  Vivek, Yu  Mao, Glenn  Daehn
1129.prez_abstract: The high velocity impact welding has been well recognized by the automotive sector for the assembly of lightweight structures using multi-material combinations. It is typically categorized as solid state joining not requiring the traditional fusion based welding process. The presented work focuses on a specific impact welding process, known as Vaporized Foil Actuator Welding (VFAW), of dissimilar metals. A high fidelity thermo-mechanically coupled computational model is developed to quantitatively capture the weld interface characteristics resulting from this process. The identified interface morphology coupled with the predicted temperature field from this process-structure model can then be used to estimate the post-weld microstructure and joint strength. The computational model is used to study the effect of different process parameters like impact pulse characteristics, buffer materials, stand-off distance and geometrical set-up, on the joint properties.

1130.prez_name: Brazing of Inconel 600 by a Newly Designed Multi-Principal-Component Alloy Filler Foil
1130.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1130.prez_authors: Zhenzhen  Yu, Minrui  Gao, Stephen  Liu
1130.prez_abstract: A new multi-principal-component (MPC) alloy was designed for brazing of Inconel 600. Theoretical analysis was performed to optimize the composition for a desired microstructure of FCC phases with a balanced strength and ductility. DTA test confirmed that the MPC alloy has a solidus temperature of 1080˚C and liquidus temperature of 1150˚C. The optimum brazing temperature was determined to be 1200˚C through wetting angle tests at various temperatures. The effects of foil thickness (50 - 300 µm) and brazing time (15 - 120min) on the shear strength of the brazed joints were evaluated. A maximum shear strength of 530MPa was achieved with a foil thickness of 300µm and brazing time of 90min. Microscale digital image correlation method was used to map localized strain distribution at the brazed joints during shear test. Metallurgical characterization including OM, SEM and EDS was performed at the interface to explain the observed mechanical behavior.

1131.prez_name: Brazing of Nickel Superalloys Using High Entropy Alloy Bulk Material and Nanopaste
1131.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1131.prez_authors: Denzel Aaron Bridges, Suhong  Zhang, Minrui  Gao, Zhenzhen  Yu, Zhili  Feng, Anming  Hu
1131.prez_abstract: Inconel 718 is a popular precipitation-hardened, corrosion-resistant nickel superalloy that is widely used in aerospace turbines, liquid fueled rockets, and other high temperature applications. To better match the high temperature stability of Inconel 718, a MnCoCrNiFe high entropy alloy (HEA) bulk material and nanoparticle paste (nanopaste) were developed. Two brazing techniques were investigated for this brazing material: laser brazing and vacuum brazing. Laser brazing produces a small heat affected zone and very short brazing time. For vacuum brazing, transient liquid phase bonding is employed for brazing Inconel 718 to exploit a lower processing temperature by heating above the solidus line of HEA in conjunction with the size-dependent melting point depression behavior of nanoparticles. The mechanical properties and microstructural evolution of the brazed joints were determined to build a fundamental understanding of HEA brazing filler metals and the difference in behavior of the bulk brazing filler metals and the brazing nanopaste.

1132.prez_name: Brazing of Steel 304 and Inconel 718 Using Ni Nanoparticle Paste
1132.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1132.prez_authors: Suhong  Zhang, Denzel  Bridges, Zhili  Feng, Anming  Hu
1132.prez_abstract: Because of the large specific surface area, nanoparticles process great potential of providing high-strength at a low brazing temperature due to their reduced melting and sintering temperature with respect to the corresponding bulk materials. In our research vacuum brazing of 304 stainless steel and Inconel 718 alloy was conducted by using Ni nanoparticles as filler material. Ni nanoparticles were synthesized through a wet-chemistry. The bonding can be acquired at a minimum temperature of 800 °C. In addition to low temperature brazing, the bonding strength was remarkably improved by inducing transit liquid phase bonding (TLPD) process. The element distribution, mechanical feature like hardness and the microstructure of the joint area were investigated to analyze the mechanism of nanoparticle-induced joining.

1133.prez_name: Characterization of Cracking in Nickel-based Alloy Overlays
1133.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1133.prez_abstract: Cracking in nickel-based overlays has been observed in several recent studies, and the mode of this cracking needs clarification. Liquation cracking (LC) and ductility dip cracking (DDC) are the primary suspects. It is also posited that LCs can serve as nucleating points for further damage via DDC. The crack surfaces in low-angle sections of a sample overlay were characterized to identify the mode of cracking. Focused-ion beam sections were removed from crack openings to expose their interior for further analysis. Smooth, dendritic surfaces showing evidence of liquid films are indicative of LC and intergranular surfaces are more likely to be DDC. The crack surfaces were examined in an SEM to determine their morphology, and therefore their origin. Understanding the cracking mechanism precisely is expected to aid in developing more effective mitigating solutions in the future.

1134.prez_name: Characterization of Dissimilar Metal Welds between Grade F65 Steel and Low Alloy Steel Overlays Using Alloy 625 Filler Wire
1134.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1134.prez_abstract: Dissimilar metal welds (DMWs) are used regularly in the oil and gas industry to join high strength steels in order to eliminate the need for post weld heat treatment (PWHT) following field welding. Previous research has found nickel based overlays to be susceptible to hydrogen assisted cracking during subsea service while under cathodic protection. Low alloy steel (LAS) overlays have been used in place of nickel based overlays in order to mitigate the detrimental effects of carbon diffusion during PWHT. The goal of this research was to perform metallurgical characterization of low alloy steel (LAS) overlays welded to F65 steel pipes using nickel based Alloy 625 filler wire. Three different multi pass welding procedures were compared, none of which included a final PWHT. Optical microscopy, scanning electron microscopy (SEM), energy dispersive spectroscopy (EDS), electron backscatter diffraction (EBSD), hardness testing and computational modeling were used to characterize the dissimilar joints.

1135.prez_name: Characterization of Explosively Clad Steel-titanium and Steel-titanium Systems
1135.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1135.prez_authors: M.J.  Perricone, C.M.  Hefferan, K.E.  Wagner, M.S.  Potter, B.R.  Bandli
1135.prez_abstract: Originating during the turn of the previous century, explosion cladding has served as a novel method for the joining of two otherwise incompatible materials.  The technique is advantageous for creating a composite material that borrows from the beneficial traits of the component metals without reliance on melting.  Here, we compare differences in two explosively welded systems, with one consisting of steel-titanium and the other composed of steel-nickel. The characterization places emphasis on microstructural differences in the grain morphology, crystallographic orientation, and phase distribution at the near-interface using metallographic techniques including electron backscatter diffraction microscopy (EBSD).

1136.prez_name: Characterization of Fiber Laser Welded TC4/SS 304 Joints Using Cu Interlayer
1136.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1136.prez_authors: Seyed Reza  Elmi Hosseini, Zhugou  Li
1136.prez_abstract: The fiber laser welding of Ti64 alloy to AISI 304 stainless steel by a pure Cu interlayer was developed. The microstructure and fracture characteristic of the joints were analyzed by OM, SEM, EDS and X-ray diffraction.
