The phases formed at SS side and Ti side of the joints studied by EDS results combined with phase diagrams. To evaluate the mechanical resistance of the cross section of the joint, the microhardness experiment performed. The cross-weld tensile strength of the joints was up to 213 MPa, recovering 32% of titanium alloy strength. The intermetallic compounds were observed in the Ti/weld interface, and the joints all fractured at the Ti/Cu interfaces. The strong links between the microhardness result and the intermetallic formation and then with joining strength were found and discussed by the experimental studies.

1137.prez_name: Characterization of the Solidification Process in Dissimilar Welds
1137.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1137.prez_abstract: During welding of dissimilar metals by fusion processes, both the liquidus and solidus temperature are completely different due to the chemical composition, which changes the solidification mode of each alloy involved specifically in the fusion boundary region where microstructural features are result of the dilution rate. In this research different experimental alloys were prepared by button melting with chemical composition simulating the different dilution grades, therefore the solidification curves were characterized and analyzed. On the other hand, dissimilar welds were performed by GTAW spot weld controlling the dilution rate to match and compare the solidifications with the buttons and determine the influence of the chemical composition as a result of the dilution and therefore solidification.

1138.prez_name: Computational Modeling for Optimization of Temperbead Welding
1138.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1138.prez_abstract: Dissimilar metal welds (DMWs) of low alloy steel components overlayed with Ni-base filler metal are common in the Power Generation, and Petrochemical industries. Post-weld heat-treatment (PWHT) is typically used to temper martensite that forms in the steel heat-affected zone (HAZ). There are multiple phenomena-based issues associated with PWHTing, it’s expensive, and impractical for field use. A temper bead welding (TBW) procedure eliminates the need for PWHT. The current practice for developing TBW procedures is trial-and-error based, requiring a lot of material and time; therefore, it is often not employed. The objective is the development of an efficient methodology for selection of TBW parameters, resulting in reduced production cost of DMWs. The approach involves modeling the gaps between DoE extremes and finding a TBW operating window for DMW overlays. Running full sized experiments with thermocouples in the HAZ provides model validation.

1139.prez_name: Development of Additive Manufacturing of Ultraviolet Laser Lithography to Create Bulky Ceramic Components with Micro Geometric Patterns
1139.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1139.prez_abstract: In additive manufacturing of ultraviolet lithography, 2D cross sections were created through dewaxing and sintering by high power laser drawing on spread resin paste including ceramic nanoparticles, and 3D composite models were sterically printed by layer lamination and micro joining.  The lithographic system has been developed to obtain bulky ceramic components with functional geometries. As the row material of the lithography, nanometer sized ceramic particles were dispersed in to liquid resins at 50 % in volume fraction. The resin paste was spread on a glass substrate at 100 μm in layer thickness by a mechanically moved knife edge. The ultraviolet laser beam of 355 nm in wavelength was adjusted at 50 μm in diameter and scanned on the pasted resin surface. The irradiation power was changed automatically from 1 to 10 W for enough dewaxing and sintering depth for layer bonding.

1140.prez_name: Development of Laser Welding Process for Parts of Orthodontics
1140.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1140.prez_authors: Jeng-O  Kim, Jae-Hoon  Lee, Seung-Woo  Lee
1140.prez_abstract: Orthodontics is exactly the right set of teeth. Bracket is a product  which is attached to the surface of the teeth for straightening the teeth of the corrective wire on the teeth. The brackets are used for metal, ceramic, resin, and so on. Bracket are made up of powder injected bodies and bases and most of them are manufactured from brazing processes. Brazing are complex, many reject rates are generated and consume lots of energy. In this study we want to produce a bracket on the new laser technology. The optimum conditions were identified laser power 100W, pulse width 3 mS, pulse rate 50Hz. Especially parts used in humans, This part obtained the approval on the KFDA(Korean Food and Drug Administration). Thus, it was given the proper judgement in every part of the oral mucosa test as requested an official contribution for proofing safety.

1141.prez_name: Effect of Alloying Elements on the Weldability of Austenitic Stainless Steel SA 240 Type 304L
1141.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1141.prez_authors: Muhammad  Kamran, Ayyaze  Aslam, Tahir  Ahmad, Muhammad Umer Manzoor, Fahad  Riaz, Faraz  Hussain
1141.prez_abstract: Austenitic stainless steel, due to its resistant to corrosion is an ideal material for surgical instruments, industrial equipment, automotive and aerospace parts and in food, dairy, and beverage industries. Welding is the major fabrication process to shape different equipment used in these industries, so, welding and weld ability of stainless steel plays an important role. In order to check the effect of alloying elements on the weld ability of austenitic stainless steel, three plate samples of 8mm thickness of SA 240 Type 304L stainless steel were welded by GTAW process using three different alloy filler wires. Spectroscopic examination was performed to determine the exact alloying composition in the weld metal, metallography was performed to determine the microstructure of weldment. Tensile testing was performed to determine tensile strength, yield strength and elongation of weld metal. Similarly hardness testing was performed on Rockwell and Vickers Hardness testers.

1142.prez_name: Effect of Electrode Material on Dissimilar Joints between Grade 70 SA-516 and Grade B SA-517 Carbon Steels
1142.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1142.prez_authors: Fahad  Riaz, Muhammad  Kamran, Atif  Makhdoom, Faraz  Hussain, Faran  Bilal
1142.prez_abstract:
The present research involves detail investigation of dissimilar weld joints in terms of microstructure and mechanical properties. SA-516 grade 70 and SA-517 grade B carbon steels have been selected and joined using three different kinds of electrodes through Shielded Metal Arc Welding (SMAW) process. 
By varying the electrode material, chemistry of the weldment and in them mechanical properties got changed. 
Such variations have been evaluated using different characterization techniques that is optical, SEM, tensile bend and impact tests.
The welded samples were also subjected to Post Weld Heat Treatment (PWHT) process to reduce the residual stresses in the welded and Heat Affected Zone (HAZ).
Results of as welded samples and the samples subjected to PWHT were obtained and compared.

1143.prez_name: Effect of Post Weld Heat Treatment Temperature on Hydrogen Assisted Cracking of Heat Resistant Stainless Steel Dissimilar Metal Welds
1143.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1143.prez_abstract: The delayed hydrogen cracking test (DHCT) method developed at The Ohio State University was utilized to evaluate effects of post weld heat treatment (PWHT) temperature on KHR35CT heat resistant stainless steel to ASTM A335 Gr.P11 dissimilar metal welds to hydrogen cracking.  This material combination is often found in petrochemical refining in hydrogen reformer service which can experience failures due to hydrogen assisted cracking.  PWHT of such dissimilar metal welds is required to improving the microstructure and resistance to hydrogen assisted cracking of the steel side of the weld.  Study of the effect of various PWHT temperatures/times allows for optimization in fabrication as well as improved lifecycle of the reformer tube assembly.  This study uses field experience as well as previous DHCT results for other dissimilar metal welds to gauge susceptibility to hydrogen assisted cracking of these welds as well as correlation of laboratory results to expected field life.

1144.prez_name: Effect of Secondary Phases on the Corrosion Resistance of Hyperduplex Stainless Steel
1144.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1144.prez_abstract: In this study, the microstructural change at low temperature in a hyperduplex stainless steel was investigated. Samples of 32Cr-07Ni in the as received condition were aged at 475C for 1, 10, 20, 60 and 120 minutes in order to promote the formation of secondary phases. All samples were analyzed through optical microscopy and scanning electron microscope. Tensile and hardness tests were performed in order to evaluate the mechanical properties and samples were immersed in natural sea water in order to study the corrosion behaviour. Results showed that the alloy was significantly degraded after the aging at different temperatures due to the formation of secondary phases, which formed after 10 minutes of exposition and increases hardness. After immersion, all samples were attacked by pitting corrosion.

1145.prez_name: Effect of Selective Element Evaporation on the Solidification and Cracking Response of 304L Stainless Steel Alloys with Controlled Levels of Manganese
1145.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1145.prez_authors: Jason E Berger, Jeff M Rodelas, João P Oliveira, Antonio J Ramirez
1145.prez_abstract:
Past research has correlated selective element evaporation during autogenous laser rework/repair welding of 304L stainless steel with a shift from primary ferrite to primary austenite solidification mode and an increase in solidification cracking susceptibility. In the present work, custom heats of 304L stainless steel with systematically varying levels of manganese are subject to various reweld cycles to understand selective element evaporation during laser welding.  Bulk and local compositional analysis (optical emission spectroscopy and electron microprobe) is used to quantify the effect of starting manganese level on relative evaporation rates of other alloying species and solidification mode evolution during rewelding.  An analytical model that predicts solidification cracking susceptibility by using welding parameters and starting alloy composition will also be presented.
*Sandia is a multiprogram laboratory operated by Sandia Corporation, a Lockhead Martin Company, for the United States Department of Energy’s National Nuclear Security Administration under contract DE-AC04-94AL85000.

1146.prez_name: Effects of Pinned and Clamped Loading Conditions on Fatigue Test Results of Similar and Dissimilar Welds in Lap-shear Specimens
1146.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1146.prez_abstract: Lap-shear specimens are commonly used to evaluate the fracture and fatigue strengths of similar and dissimilar welds.  The stress intensity factor solutions are useful to correlate with the fatigue lives of these welds.  The stress intensity factor solutions for similar and dissimilar welds in lap-shear specimens of equal and unequal thickness under pinned and clamped loading conditions are examined by computational and analytical solutions.  Both computational and analytical solutions indicate that the bending moments and the transverse shear forces at the clamped edges can reduce the stress intensity factor solutions for a given specimen geometry by about 7% for similar welds and by about 20% for dissimilar aluminum/steel and magnesium/steel welds when compared to those under pinned loading conditions.  The analytical and computational stress intensity factor solutions suggest that the fatigue lives of the welds in lap-shear specimens under clamped loading conditions are higher than those under pinned loading conditions.

1147.prez_name: Effects of Supercritical CO2 on the Mechanical Behavior of Dissimilar Metal-weld
1147.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1147.prez_authors: Sajedur R. Akanda, M.  Kapoor, K. A. Rozman, Ö. N.  Doğan
1147.prez_abstract: This study focuses on the effects of supercritical CO2 (sCO2) on the mechanical behavior of a dissimilar metal-weld of P91 and 347H steels under monotonic and cyclic stresses. The global mechanical behavior of the metal-weld is a result of the synergistic interaction of the local mechanical property of each constituent. Among all the constituents, the heat-affected-zone (HAZ) is the most critical because it has varying mechanical property due to its microstructure variation generated by weld thermal cycles and post weld heat treatment. This results in non-uniform plastic-strain accumulations in the softer HAZ making it susceptible to failure under mechanical loading. To capture such a complicated interaction of the local mechanical properties, a finite element model is developed. The inputs of the model are the local mechanical properties which are determined by indentation tests. The model is found to successfully simulate the tensile and fatigue responses of the sCO2 exposed metal-weld.

1148.prez_name: Evaluation of Ductility-dip Cracking Susceptibility in Alloy 690 Laser Multipass Weld Metal by Cross-bead Longitudinal-Varestraint test
1148.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1148.prez_authors: Tomo  Ogura, Yusuke  Morikawa, Kazuyoshi  Saida
1148.prez_abstract: In order to synthesize a ductility-dip crack in the laser multipass weld metal, the cross-bead longitudinal-Varestraint test with laser welding was applied under the various welding speed. Ductility-dip temperature range (DTR) was increased with an increase in P and S contents in the weld metal, and S was more effective to enhancing the DTR compared with P. A numerical simulation of grain boundary segregation of P and S revealed that the segregated concentrations of P and S at grain boundaries were increased with an increase in the P and S contents in the weld metal, and that those were slightly decreased with an increase in the welding speed due to the rapid heating and cooling rates. It follows that the changes in ductility-dip cracking susceptibility with the filler metal composition and welding speed were consistent with the grain boundary segregation behaviours of P and S during laser multipass welding process.

1149.prez_name: Fatigue and Tensile Performance of Friction Stir Welded AM60
1149.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1149.prez_authors: Sara  Richmire, Pouya  Sharifi, Meysam  Haghshenas
1149.prez_abstract: In this paper, an experimental research approach has been used to assess friction stir behavior of cast AM60 magnesium alloy.  Friction stir welding tests were performed at different feed rates of 114, 219, and 422 mm/min and at tool rotational speed of 635 and 1200 rpm.  This paper then aims at assessing the effect of the main processing parameters, including transverse travel rate (mm/min) and rotation speed (rpm), on the joint efficiency in terms of the mechanical properties and fatigue properties of the joint.  Since AM60 is a cast alloy, it is expected that friction stir welding modify the grain structure/morphology and eliminate casting defects such as shrinkage and porosity. This in turn enhances mechanical performance, assessed through tensile testing and instrumented indentation testing, as well as fatigue life of the alloy. To assess the nature of fatigue failure, fracture surface is also studied through scanning electron microscopy.

1150.prez_name: Femtosecond Laser Peening without a Sacrificial Overlay under Atmospheric Conditions for Improving Fatigue Properties of Laser-welded and FSWed 2024 Aluminum Alloys
1150.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1150.prez_authors: Tomokazu  Sano, Takayuki  Eimura, Akio  Hirose, Seiichiro  Tsutsumi, Yousuke  Kawahito, Seiji  Katayama, Kazuto  Arakawa, Hisashi  Hori, Kiyotaka  Masaki, Ayumi  Shiro, Takahisa  Shobu
1150.prez_abstract: We have succeeded in improving fatigue properties of laser-welded and FSWed 2024 aluminum alloys compared to each as-welded specimen using femtosecond laser peening in the air, which was not covered with any sacrificial overlay such as protective coating, nor using water as a plasma confinement medium during the peening treatment. Increment of fatigue strength and life of femtosecond laser-peened FSWed joint was larger than that of femtosecond laser-peened laser welded joint. The reason causing the difference of the peening effects will be discussed based on changes of microstructures, hardness and residual stress of each joint.

1151.prez_name: Friction Stir Welding of Dissimilar in Thickness Al-5Mg Alloy Butt Joints
1151.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1151.prez_authors: Anton A. Naumov, Evgenii V. Chernikov, Fedor Iu. Isupov, Oleg V. Panchenko
1151.prez_abstract: The use of dissimilar in thickness welds, especially for the thin aluminium sheets, has been increasing in automobile and civil ship building industries due to its potential for energy saving. The purpose of the present  research is to develop the technology of friction stir welding for dissimilar in thickness Al–5Mg alloy butt joints. The thicknesses of the sheets for FSW were 1 mm and 2 mm. The FSW was provided on the 5-axis FSW-machine in horizontal plane with the constant tilt angle equals to 2 degree, tool rotation speed equals to 700 RPM and welding speed equals to 5 mm/s. The probe high equals to 1; 1,15 and 1,3 mm and dissimilar thick angle in the range from 4 to 6 degree were taken for the investigation. The macrostructure of the welds was analyzed in order to select defect free welds. The mechanical tests of the selected welds were done.

1152.prez_name: HDPE High-density Polyethylene Pipe Systems Welding Process
1152.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1152.prez_abstract:
Piping made from polyethylene is a cost effective solution for a broad range of piping problems in municipal, industrial, marine, mining, landfill, duct and agricultural
applications. It has been tested and proven effective for above ground, surface, buried, sliplined, floating, and sub-surface marine applications. High-density polyethylene pipe (HDPE) can carry potable water, wastewater, slurries, chemicals, hazardous wastes, and compressed gases. Polyethylene is strong, extremely tough and very durable. Whether when looking for long service, trouble-free installation, flexibility, resistance to chemicals or a myriad of other features, high-density polyethylene pipe will meet all needed requirements. Considering the features of leak free. Corrosion, abrasion, and chemical resistance. Excellent flow characteristics. Lightweight, and flexible. This paper discusses the butt welding process being used in HDPE High-Density Polyethylene Pipe Systems, as an integral part of any pipe system is the method used to join the system components.

1153.prez_name: High Frequency Linear Friction Welding of Aluminum Alloys
1153.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1153.prez_authors: Hideo  Mogami, Tomoki  Matsuda, Tomokazu  Sano, Akio  Hirose, Ryo  Yoshida, Hisashi  Hori
1153.prez_abstract: We have been developing High Frequency Linear Friction Welding (HFLFW) that works at 250 Hz, which is more than fifth times as high as the frequency of the conventional LFW process, aiming to weld high thermal conductivity materials such as aluminum alloys. In our previous study, it was found that sound welds were achieved for 6063 and 5052 Al alloys with this process and that difference of material properties gave some influence on welding process. However, the tensile strength of 6063 Al alloy was slightly weaker because of the heat affect. Therefore, the purpose of the present research is to reduce the heat affect by investigated influence of friction pressure on microstructure and mechanical properties of HFLFW. As a result of tensile test, higher tensile strength was achieved when lower friction pressure was applied. Further consideration about influences of friction pressure will be addressed in the talk.

1154.prez_name: Improvement of Fatigue Properties of Friction Stir Welded 7075-T73 Aluminum Alloy Using Femtosecond Laser Peening
1154.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1154.prez_authors: Terumasa  Kawashima, Tomokazu  Sano, Akio  Hirose, Seiichiro  Tsutsumi, Kiyotaka  Masaki, Hisashi  Hori
1154.prez_abstract: We succeeded in improving fatigue properties of friction stir welded 7075-T73 aluminum alloy using femtosecond laser peening without a sacrificial overlay under atmospheric conditions. Femtosecond laser pulses with a wavelength of 800 nm, a pulse duration of 130 fs at full width at half maximum, and a pulse energy of 0.6 mJ were focused on the surface of the specimen using a lens with a focal length of 70 mm. Results of plane bending fatigue tests with a stress ratio of R=-1 showed that femtosecond laser peening increased the fatigue strength at 10<sup>6</sup> cycles and the fatigue life under cyclic loading at a stress amplitude of 200 MPa by about 35 MPa and 24 times, respectively. Effects of femtosecond laser peening without a sacrificial overlay under atmospheric conditions on surface hardness and residual stress were also investigated.

1155.prez_name: Improvement of Reliability of Metal-to-Metal Joints Bonded Using Redox Reactions of Ag2O-CuO-Mixed Paste
1155.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1155.prez_authors: Takafumi  Yao, Tomoki  Matsuda, Tomokazu  Sano, Akio  Hirose
1155.prez_abstract: Bonding method utilizing redox reactions of metallic oxide microparticles achieves metal-to-ceramics direct bonding in the air, which can be alternative to lead-rich high melting point solder. Joints bonded using silver oxide paste consisting of Ag<SUB>2</SUB>O microparticles and reducing solvent has a sound bondability, whereas silver has a low tolerance against electrochemical migration. Joints bonded using copper oxide paste consisting of CuO microparticles and reducing solvent has a worse bondability than that of joints bonded using silver oxide paste, whereas copper has a higher tolerance against electrochemical migration than that of silver. The purpose of this study is to improve both the bondability and reliability of metal-to-metal joints bonded using Ag<SUB>2</SUB>O-CuO-mixed paste, aiming to offset each demerit by each merit. As a result, improvement of both bondability and reliability was achieved under an optimized condition. Detail results and mechanism will be addressed in the talk.

1156.prez_name: Influence of Titanium on Microstructures and Toughness in Simulated Coarse Grained Heat Affected Zone for Titanium Micro-alloyed Steel with Different Heat Inputs
1156.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1156.prez_authors: Junsheng  Cao, Mujun  Long, Wenjie   He, Tao  Liu, Lintao  Gui, Dengfu  Chen, Huamei  Duan, Xinhong  Du
1156.prez_abstract: Microstructure at coarse grained heat affected zone (CGHAZ) has great effect on the welding properties. The effect of t8/5 on the microstructure at CGHAZ for micro-alloyed steels with different titanium content was studied using Gleeble 3500. The microstructure, hardness, and impact toughness of the samples were analyzed. Results indicated that the structures of CGHAZ for high Ti steel (HTS) were lath-shape bainite and martensite when t8/5 was less than 15s, and acicular ferrite would form if the t8/5 reached 60s. The impact toughness was less than 10J once the t8/5 was more than 15s. The variation of microstructure for low Ti steel (LTS) resembled with HTS. Meanwhile, The influence of Ti content on microstructure, phase transformation temperature, mechanical properties was discussed. Increasing Ti would reduced the temperature range of phase transformation. Acicular ferrite and finer crystal grains would be facilitated owing to the addition of titanium.

1157.prez_name: Interfacial Characterization of Brazed Hexagonal Boron Nitride (h-BN)
1157.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1157.prez_abstract: The new Brazilian synchrotron light source accelerator project includes components of advanced metal al-loys and ceramic materials, such as hexagonal boron nitride (h-BN). This work investigates chemical inter-action of h-BN brazed joint, which has low surface wettability. Brazing process variables such as tempera-ture and diffusion play an important role for metallurgical stable interface formation. The main characteris-tic analyzed refers to h-BN wettability at high temperature and vacuum environment. The sessile drop tests were performed to simulate brazing process conditions using Ticusil alloy. The results show good wetting and spreading on ceramic surface. It was possible to observe that the formed liquid exhibits good agreement at the interface. Nevertheless, good wetting by liquid constituent of filler alloy on h-BN shows average con-tact angle of Ɵ=40°. This effect in semi-liquid state is beneficial since it allows reducing process tempera-ture. Therefore, results show so far that it promotes good interaction at h-BN surface.

1158.prez_name: Joining of Dissimilar Materials by Friction Bit Joining and Friction Self-pierce Riveting
1158.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1158.prez_authors: Yong Chae  Lim, Michael   Miles, Xun  Liu, Yongbing  Li, Zhili  Feng
1158.prez_abstract: Multi-materials lightweight auto body structure has been mandated to increase fuel efficiency and decrease green gas emission. The mixed car body structure must utilize the lightweight materials, such as high strength aluminum alloys, magnesium alloys, advanced/or ultra-high strength steel, and composite polymers at the right place in the vehicle without safety and performance concern. Because of difference in chemical and physical properties of each material, joining of dissimilar materials is a critical issue for multi-material vehicle application. In this talk, two recently developed solid-state joining processes, friction bit joining (FBJ) and friction self-pierce riveting (F-SPR) techniques, will be presented and discussed for various dissimilar material combinations. Mechanical joint strength, microstructure at joint interface, microhardness profiles in specimens made by FBJ and F-SPR will be presented. Also, corrosion performance of Al/steel specimens by FBJ with and without adhesive will be further discussed.

1159.prez_name: Joining of Dissimilar Materials Using Friction Stir Scribe Technique
1159.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1159.prez_authors: Piyush  Upadhyay, Timothy J Roosendaal, Yuri   Hovanski, Xiujuan  Jiang
1159.prez_abstract: Joining of dissimilar materials can allow effective utilization of materials which in turn can enable truly multi-material design and assembly in high volume industrial application such that parts are tailor made to suit design needs with right material at the right place. As a solid state joining technique Friction stir scribe (FSS) welding have been demonstrated to be effective in producing linear continuous in-situ joint between dissimilar materials like aluminum and steel without the need for third material or predrilled hole. This has been demonstrated at a competitively high speed with the use of low-cost tooling. In partnership with several automotive manufacturers, Pacific Northwest National Laboratory has been actively involved in developing this capability. Current state of the art, progress made and challenges in joining dissimilar materials utilizing FSS techniques in different grades of steels, mechanical properties of the produced joints and nature of the joint interface will be presented.

1160.prez_name: Laser Sintering of Al Nanoparticles for Al-air Batteries
1160.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1160.prez_abstract: Metal-air batteries become a promising choice for electrical vehicles, smart grid energy storage and powerful energy sources for portable electronics. Compared to Li, aluminum provides a similar specific energy density and compelling volumetric energy density. In this work, we printed Al nanoparticle electrode with 3D printing. We further employed two kinds of laser for preparing electrodes. A high power diode laser is used for sintering aluminum nanoparticles at a temperature higher than 400oC in vacuum and a femtosecond laser is used for welding aluminum electrode to plastic substrates and carbonizing an air electrode. The developed Al-air batteries display superior battery performance.

1161.prez_name: Liquid Metal Embrittlement of Zn Coated Advanced High Strength Steel Welds
1161.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1161.prez_authors: Andrew  Macwan, Elliot  Biro, Y. Norman  Zhou
1161.prez_abstract: Currently, advanced high strength steels (AHSS) used in automotive structural components are commonly protected via zinc (Zn) coatings. However, the steel/Zn system creates the potential for liquid metal embrittlement (LME) during welding, since Zn exists in liquid phase between 419-906°C, which is well below the melting point of conventional AHSS. LME has a deleterious effect on the properties of steel since the onset of premature crack initiation and propagation along grain boundaries leads to a significant reduction in strength and ductility. Therefore, the purpose of this study was to evaluate LME susceptibility during resistance spot welding of Zn-coated AHSS. The susceptibility to LME was analyzed using key variables such as base metal microstructure, coating types, and weld process variables. It was identified that susceptibility to LME increased when austenitic microstructures were present. Furthermore, LME cracks were more sensitive to welding current than welding time.

1162.prez_name: Local Mechanical Properties Estimation of Friction Stir Welded Al-Mg-Si Joints
1162.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1162.prez_authors: Oleg V. Panchenko, Sergey Yu. Ivanov, Anton  A. Naumov, Iurii  A. Golubev
1162.prez_abstract: Microstructure and mechanical properties of friction stir (FSW) welded joints of 4 mm thick 6082-T6 Al-Mg-Si alloy were studied. Welded joints have a distinct heterogeneity of microstructure and mechanical properties. The asymmetry of peak temperature field and microhardness distribution in heat affected zone (HAZ) was revealed. The welded joints efficiency in terms of yield stress was about 72%. Elongation of welded joints in 5.3 times lower than base metal due to strain concentration in the zone of minimum hardness. The prolonged dwell time of the HAZ metal at high-temperature leads to the dissolution of the β'' hardening particles and therefore to a significant decrease of the hardness in HAZ. The dependence between yield strength and hardness of 6082 alloy was obtained, which makes it possible to estimate local mechanical properties in a welded joints.

1163.prez_name: Low–temperature Sintering Joining Techniques through Reduction of Metallic Oxides
1163.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1163.prez_abstract: Lead-free assembly technologies have been an indispensable issue in microelectronics fields for several tens years. Although lead-free soldering in middle temperature range has been put to practical use, that in high temperature range which is applied to such as power devices has not been developed yet. To this end, we proposed low-temperature sintering joining processes using nanoparticles as alternative to Pb-rich high-temperature solders in the early 2000s. Then to improve bondability and reduce cost, we have developed a novel joining technique using reduction reaction of metallic oxides, such as Ag2O and CuO. Since nanoparticles form through the reduction of metallic oxides by organic reducing agents, joining is achieved by sintering of nanoparticles at a low temperature ranging from 300 to 400℃. Metal-to-ceramics joining as well as metal-to-metal joining has been achieved using this joining process. Their bonding behaviors and mechanisms will be addressed in the presentation.

1164.prez_name: Manufacturing of Assembled Aluminium-steel Gearwheels by Lateral Extrusion
1164.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1164.prez_abstract:
This paper focuses on manufacturing of an assembled gearwheel through cold forging and simultaneous joining of an aluminium gearwheel body and a steel gear ring. Multicomponent process for production of high performance gearwheels combines both high power density and high lightweight potential. 
This study presents FEM and experimental results of joining aluminium gearwheel bodies with steel gear rings. The forging process is performed by lateral extrusion of an aluminium blank, placed between shaft and pre-hardened steel gear ring. The gear ring is equipped with a non-uniform inner profile in order to enable both a form- and press-fit joint in radial and axial direction. Furthermore, this study figures out differences in required press forces, achieved form filling, lubrication effects and occurring roundness deviations. Finally, this paper faces a novel manufacturing strategy in reducing material cost, lightweight design and reduction of inertia of torque of assembled gearwheels in automotive applications.

1165.prez_name: Mechanism Study of Resistive Switching Memory Devices in Perspective of Nanojoining
1165.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1165.prez_authors: Ming  Xiao, Kevin P  Musselman, Walter W Duley, Norman  Y  Zhou
1165.prez_abstract: Nanojoining as a way of integration of nanoscale devices and systems is attracting increasing attention. Furthermore, engineering of nanojoining process could affect the electrical performance of obtained nanodevices. For resistive switching memory devices as the next-generation non-volatile memory devices, the formation and rupture of conductive filament, which is widely studied as the switching mechanism theoretically and experimentally, could be regarded as the nanojoining process between conductive atoms such as cations (such as Ag ions) or anions (such as oxygen vacancies) and the top or bottom electrodes. We demonstrated that the structure and reliability of the joint would directly determine the resistive switching performance. A weak joint between the conductive filament and electrode leads to threshold switching behavior, while a robust joint results in bipolar resistive switching. However, if the joint is too strong to be broken via negative voltage or thermal dissolution, an inerasable memory device is obtained.

1166.prez_name: Micro-joints Formed between Cu-Cu Wires by Using Low-temperature Lead-free Nanosolder Particles
1166.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1166.prez_authors: Edward  Fratto, Evan  Wernicki, Yang  Shu, Fan  Gao, Zhiyong  Gu
1166.prez_abstract: As the electronics tend towards smaller, more delicate devices with progressively more sophisticated components, micro-/nano-scale joining becomes increasingly important. In this work, we show that micro-scale solder joints were formed between Cu-Cu wires by lead-free nanosolder pastes. Sn-In nanoparticles were synthesized by a surfactant-assisted chemical reduction method. The size, structure and thermal property of the nanosolders were characterized by SEM, TEM, XRD and DSC. The nanosolders were dispersed in flux and melted to join Cu wires of varying diameters as small as 25 um. Electrical measurements were conducted for evaluation of joint quality and performance. Cross-section of the micro-joints was examined by SEM imaging to characterize their interfacial structure, and tensile strength was tested with an Instron machine. The results were compared to the joints formed using commercial micro-sized solder pastes. This investigation shows that lead-free nanosolders offer the next level of precision deposition control and smaller scale joining.

1167.prez_name: Microstructure and Characterization of Interfacial Phases of Sapphire/Sapphire Joint Bonded Using Bi2O3–B2O3–ZnO Glass
1167.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1167.prez_abstract: Bismuth borate zinc glass, 50Bi2O3–30B2O3–20ZnO (mol.%), was used as a braze intended to join sapphire. Thermal properties of the glass were all experimentally determined. The wettability of the glass on sapphire was investigated. The contact angle not greater than 11.3° was obtained in air at temperatures of ≥700 °C. Subsequently, sapphire was successfully joined to themselves at 700 °C for 20 min. The microstructure of the joint was studied and the interfacial phases were characterized. The results showed that the ZnAl2O4 phase was formed as a result of the reaction between the sapphire substrate and ZnO from the glass. The mechanical integrity of the joints was investigated. The joints with an average room shear strength of 70 MPa were achieved. The fracture analysis indicated that the fracture occurred within the glass interlayer rather than at the sapphire/glass interface, hence indicating a good bonding of the glass with sapphire.

1168.prez_name: Microstructure Evolution during Air Bonding of Al2O3 to Al2O3 Joints Using an Amorphous Bismuth–borate–zinc Glass
1168.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1168.prez_abstract: Alumina ceramics with 95 wt.% purity were joined to itself using a bismuth based glass, 40Bi2O3–40B2O3–20ZnO (mol.%). The wettability of the glass on the Al2O3 substrate was investigated. The results showed a contact angle of ≤36.5°was achieved when the temperature was ≥630 °C.Subsequently, joining cycles were performed at temperatures of 520-700 °C for 30 min. The dependence of microstructure evolution of the joints on temperature was investigated. Bi24B2O39 was detected to be the product in the joints bonded at 530-580 °C, while ZnAl2O4 was identified to be the main product at temperature of ≥650 °C due to the reaction between the Al2O3 substrate and ZnO from the glass. The influence of dwelling time at 700 °C on microstructure evolution of the joints was also studied. The results showed that the size of ZnAl2O4 increased with increasing holding time.

1169.prez_name: Microstructure Evolution of High Cr-Ni-N Superalloy Welded Joints Submitted to Heat-treatment
1169.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1169.prez_authors: Julio Cesar Spadotto, Ivan Guillermo  Solórzano
1169.prez_abstract: Properties and performance of superalloys welded joints can be significantly affected by second phase precipitation resulting from high-temperature exposure of the joint. The material used in this study was a high Cr-Ni-N superalloy (Cr-Fe-Ni-Mo-Cu-Si-N-C), known as Alloy 33, which has been subjected to GTAW fusion welding process, followed by heat treatment schedules ending with aging at 700 °C.  SEM and TEM observations show that the microstructural evolution of the welded joint, resulting from aging with and without previous homogenization treatment, present different characteristics. While the homogenization treatment followed by isothermal aging resulted in conventional precipitation (grain-boundary heterogeneous precipitation and homogeneous precipitation), the direct-aging of the welded joint led to the formation of discontinuous precipitation colonies in the weld metal zone. Both modes of intergranular precipitation are of great interest due to influence on the materials properties and the later is rarely reported in the literature.

1170.prez_name: Microstructure, Toughness and Cold Cracking Tendency of 1100 MPa Weld Metal
1170.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1170.prez_authors: Yun  Peng, Xingna  Peng, Zhiling  Tian
1170.prez_abstract: High strength C-Mn-Ni-Mo alloyed welding wires were used to weld 1500 MPa QT steel. The tensile strength of welded joint can reach 1100 MPa with CVN impact energy of 30 J for MAG joint and 60 J for TIG joint. Analysis indicates that the microstructure of fine martensite and bainite ensures the high strength and good toughness. TIG joint has much higher toughness because of less oxide inclusions and more residual austenite content. With the increase of heat input, tensile strength of welded joint decreases little but the toughness deteriorates remarkably. Slit type cracking test was carried out. The effect of temperature, relative humidity, and heat input on cold cracking tendency of the high strength welding joint was investigated. It is found that welding wires with higher Ni content shows better welding cold cracking resistance because the weld metal has lower Ms temperature and more residual austenite content.

1171.prez_name: Multiple Self-exothermic Reactions for Room-temperature Aluminum Bonding via Instantaneous Melting
1171.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1171.prez_authors: Tomoki  Matsuda, Makoto  Takahashi, Tomokazu  Sano, Akio  Hirose
1171.prez_abstract: We propose a room-temperature multiple-reaction bonding method combining the thermite reaction and self-propagating high-temperature synthesis with no external heat source. The use of multiple reactions enables aluminum alloy bonding through the formation of a composite structure, due to pore filling by the produced compounds and molten base metal, unlike conventional techniques. Dissimilar bonding between the composites is achieved by the lattice defects, such as ledges and lattice disordering, which contribute to relieving the interfacial misfit. It is concluded that appropriate reactant design plays a significant role in controlling the microstructure and formation of a sound joint. The further consideration of reactant design and the influence on the bondability will be addressed in my presentation.

1172.prez_name: Numerical Prediction of Penetration Shapes in MIG Welding of Aluminum Alloy Joints
1172.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1172.prez_authors: Hisashi  Serizawa, Shingo  Sato, Fumikazu  Miyasaka
1172.prez_abstract: As one of the methods for simulating the molten droplet from filler wire in metal insert gas (MIG) welding, a new line-type heat source has been developed and it was added in the three-dimensional, non-stationary thermal model which can demonstrate both molten pool and penetration shape in gas metal arc welding (GMAW) process.  Through the serial computations varying the values for parameters in the model, it is found that the finger type penetrations, which is typically obtained in bead-on MIG welding of aluminum alloy, can be demonstrated by using the new line-type heat source and selecting the appropriate values for the parameters.  In addition, the penetration shape in butt welding can be reproduced by employing the same parameters except for only the arc pressure radius.  Moreover, it is revealed that the penetration shapes in lap and joggled joints also can be predicted with taking oxide layer effect into account.

1173.prez_name: Numerical Simulation and Experimental Investigation on Impulse Friction Stir Welding of 6082-T6 Aluminum Alloy
1173.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1173.prez_authors: Iurii  Golubev, Iuliia  Morozova, Anton  Naumov, Cord  Hantelmann, Nikolay  Doynov, Vesselin  Michailov
1173.prez_abstract: The series of impulse friction stir welding (IFSW) experiments for aluminum alloy 6082-T6 butt joints was performed to obtain micrographs, tensile and hardness test samples and to receive the validation data for a numerical model of the process. Impulse force and frequency were varied to determine the effect of individual process parameters on microstructure evolution and mechanical properties of the welded butt joints. A three-dimensional model was established to simulate temperature distribution, heat generation and contact state between the tool and the workpiece during IFSW. Based on the numerical simulation the influence of the impulses on heat input, maximum weld temperatures and contact state was found. The combination of impulse force and frequency effects the grain refinement, the increase of elongation and hardness of the welded joints during IFSW were determined.

1174.prez_name: Numerical Simulation of Hydrogen Distribution during Multi-pass Welding for Reduced Activation Ferritic/martensitic Steel F82H
1174.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1174.prez_authors: Hiroaki  Mori, Kohei  Hatoya, Kento  Kawauchi, Taichiro  Kato, Takanori  Hirose, Hiroyasu  Tanigawa
1174.prez_abstract: Reduced activation ferritic/martensitic steel F82H has been developed for one of the construction material of blanket modules set on the inner wall of nuclear fusion reactors. When the steel is welded, cold cracking in heat affected zone (HAZ) has to be considered, because martensite is prone to form in HAZ as well as 9Cr-1Mo steel. Especially, in the case of multi-pass welding, its susceptibility should be remarkably higher than that in single-pass welding. Therefore, hydrogen concentrations in welds, which is well known as a cause of cold cracking, was evaluated by numerical analysis with combination of thermal elastic-plastic analysis and the developed simulation code to calculate hydrogen distribution. As dynamic calculation, tensile stress, which is closely equivalent to its yield stress, mainly occurred around fusion line. From calculation of hydrogen distribution, considering stresses and strains generated in multi-pass welds, hydrogen was concentrated at along fusion line.

1175.prez_name: On the Role of Wetting and Reactivity during Joining Of Ceramics by Brazing Alloys at High Temperature
1175.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1175.prez_abstract: Interfacial reactions between liquid metals and ceramics are of technological importance in many fields of materials engineering such as joining of ceramics by brazing alloys, manufacturing of metal/ceramic composites, casting of metals, etc. This presentation will be mainly focused on the following points: (i) Thermodynamics analysis of reactive brazing and relationship between wettability and brazability. (ii) The crucial role of geometrical confinement in brazing which can lead to a major difference between interfaces obtained in sessile drop and brazing experiments. (iii) Analysis of the main thermodynamic and kinetic factors governing the interfacial reactions. In particular, some physicochemical aspects which can affect, or even control, the morphological evolution of the interfacial region will be presented. These points will be discussed by using and analysing different examples of interactions between oxide or non-oxide ceramics and reactive liquid alloys.

1176.prez_name: Optimization of Electron Beam Welding Parameters for Ti-6Al-4V Alloy by Using Taguchi Method
1176.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1176.prez_abstract: The present work on electron beam welding was successfully applied to join Ti-6Al-4V alloy which will eliminates “trial and error” method by providing a reliable model which can predict the right combination of weld parameters to achieve a high-quality weld. Electron beam welding parameters such as accelerating voltage, beam current and welding speed was selected with the objective of full weld depth penetration with minimum weld bead width. For the optimization of welding parameters Taguchi approach was used as statistical design of experimental technique. From the experimental results it is found that the effect of welding parameters on the welding quality decreased in order of welding speed, beam current and accelerating voltage. The optimal combination of welding parameters is the accelerating voltage 50kV, beam current 60mA and welding speed 1000mm/min. One more set of experiment at same parameters was conducted to validate the optimized parameters.

1177.prez_name: Optimizing Dissimilar Metal Welds via Pillar Compression and TEM Analysis
1177.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1177.prez_authors: Daniel  Sorensen, Jason  Myers, Bernard  Li, Wei  Zhang, Eric  Hintsala, Douglas D Stauffer, Antonio  Ramirez
1177.prez_abstract: The mechanical properties of a weld are often difficult to determine. this is especially true for micro-resistance welds as used in microelectronic and medical device applications. These devices are often subjected to loading, fatigue, and corrosive environments which can lead to failure. Therefore, valid modeling parameters are required. For the dissimilar metals tested here, the material in the fusion zone  may contain nonequilibrium phases with features ranging from sub-20nm to the micron scale. Nanomechanical testing in the form of pillar compression was performed to investigate the yield and fracture behavior across the heat affected zone.  The results from the pillar compression testing was then used as an input parameter for the design of experiments to optimize the toughness of the weld using the electrode force, current, and weld time as parameters.

1178.prez_name: Rapid Formation of Intermetallic Joint during Ultrasonic-assisted Soldering of Sn-based Composite Solders
1178.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1178.prez_abstract: With the dramatic requirements of high power and high integrity in field of power devices, the study of novel interconnection materials and packaging methods has been paid an extremely attention. Presently, the most candidates for the chip bonding are noble metal solders ,nanometal particles and TLP bonding. An enhanced and low cost auxiliary energy is necessary. Ultrasonic-assisted soldering has been proven able to solder dissimilar metals at low temperatures within a very short time. Therefore, the sandwich structure of die/Sn+Ni paste/Ni substrate and the ultrasonic-assisted bonding principle were investigated. High remelting temperature joint consisted of nearly sole Ni3Sn4 with a high shear strength of 43.4MPa was achieved with Sn+24wt.%Ni composite solder at 250℃ for ultrasonic time of 10s and power of 500W in air. This rapidly formed intermetallic joint was phase stable as isothermally aged at 300℃ for 72h in air and its shear strength was 33.4 MPa.

1179.prez_name: Scalable Writing of High Performance Ultraminiature Graphene Micro-supercapacitors
1179.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1179.prez_authors: Daozhi  Shen, Guisheng  Zou, Lei  Liu, Walter W. Duley, Norman Y. Zhou
1179.prez_abstract: Miniaturization of energy storage devices can significantly decrease the overall size of electronic systems. However, this miniaturization is limited by the reduction of electrode dimensions and the reproducible transfer of small electrolyte drops. This paper reports a simple scalable direct writing method for the production of ultraminiature micro-supercapacitor (MSC) electrodes using femtosecond laser. These pads, separated by 2 μm spacing, are 100 μm long and 8 μm wide. A second stage involves the accurate transfer of an electrolyte microdroplet on top of each individual electrode. Abundant in-plane nanopores in fsrGO induced by femtosecond laser together with ultra-short interelectrode spacing enables MSCs to exhibit a high specific capacitance (6.3 mF cm-2 and 646 F cm-3), low equivalent series resistance (0.2 Ω cm2) and ~ 100% retention after 1000 cycles. This new hybrid technique easily enables scalable production of high-performance ultraminiature MSCs for powering micro/nano electronic systems that require high power/energy density.

1180.prez_name: Simulation Model for Laser Beam Welding of Steel-aluminum Lap Joints
1180.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1180.prez_authors: Anton  Evdokimov, Katrin  Springer, Nikolay  Doynov, Ralf  Ossenbrink, Vesselin  Michailov
1180.prez_abstract: Recent developments for laser beam welding between steel and aluminum structures are based on the partial mixing between both materials. Successful implementation of those techniques in real industrial lines requires developing new simulation models of the process. In this paper, a numerical model for prediction of the structural behavior of dissimilar overlap joints with respect to welding distortions and residual stresses under consideration of specific mechanical properties of the weld zone is introduced. For simulation of a thermal load from welding process, a developed volumetric heat source was applied. Base metals, heat affected zones, and welds were characterized and mechanical properties as a function of temperature were experimental determined. The obtained data were transferred to the developed model. Simulation results were compared with experimental measurements during welding trials and good correlation was achieved.

1181.prez_name: Solid State Joining of Steel to Aluminum with Refractory Metal Tools
1181.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1181.prez_authors: Martin M McDonnell, Ashish K Dasgupta
1181.prez_abstract: The current research is to join armor grade steel and aluminum utilizing friction stir welding with thermal control and refractory metal tools.  The joining of aluminum and steel can be a challenging task by conventional fusion welding techniques due to the difference between each material’s melting points.  Also the development of intermetallic compounds (IMC’s) in the interface pose a problem when joining aluminum to steel at high temperatures.   A design of experiments (DOE) approach for comparison between various FSW parameters and FSW tool design and tooling materials.  Process parameter variation experiments, which included inductive pre-heating, tool design geometry, plunge and traverse rates, tool offset, spindle tilt, and rotation speed, were conducted to develop a parameter set which yielded a defect free joint.  Testing of welded sections has demonstrated the ability to produce stabilized weld properties and an ability to increase strength based on interface geometry and tool design.

1182.prez_name: Synthesis and Nano-joining of Multi-segmented Metallic Nanowires
1182.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1182.prez_authors: Jirui  Wang, Fan  Gao, Zhiyang  Li, Zhiyong  Gu
1182.prez_abstract: Nanowires have shown great promise in a variety of applications such as nanoelectronics, nanophotonics, sensors, energy conversion devices, and biomedical engineering. However, joining and interconnecting nanowires is still a challenging issue in fabricating complex nanodevices. In this work, we show the joining and bonding of metallic nanowires by using lead-free nanosolders. Pure tin (Sn) nanowires and multi-segmented Sn-based metallic nanowires such as tin-gold-nickel-gold-tin (Sn-Au-Ni-Au-Sn) nanowires were successfully synthesized through a template assisted electroplating method. The polycarbonate membrane or AAO membrane with nanosized pores was used as a template. The length of each segment was controlled by varying the electrodeposition current and time. These multi-segment nanowires with two solder ends can be connected into ordered structures with good electrical connection by using self-assembly method such as magnetic-assisted assembly, and effective soldering method such as oven reflow or IR heating. These joined nanowires can find various applications such as nanoelectronics or sensors/biosensors.

1183.prez_name: Technologies for Joining Titanium to Steel: Overview and New Development
1183.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1183.prez_authors: Yu-Ping  Yang, Jerry  Gould, Bradley  Fingland
1183.prez_abstract: For lightweight applications, titanium and its alloys are often welded to steels to achieve high performance and cost efficiency. However, it is difficult to produce robust and reliable Ti/steel joints due to the notable mismatch in physical properties and poor metallurgical compatibility between these two dissimilar materials. The major metallurgical problem of joining titanium alloys to steels is the formation of hard and brittle intermetallic phases which could lead to cracking and reduce the joint strength.  In the past 15 years, there have been some notable advances in joining and welding of titanium alloys to steels. This paper reviewed the technology status and identified technology gaps for joining processes: explosive welding, diffusion bonding, friction welding and friction stir welding, vacuum furnace brazing, and high-energy beam welding. This paper also introduced the recent development of following processes for automotive and aerospace applications: magnetic pulse welding, Upset welding, and mash welding.

1184.prez_name: The Influence of Stabilizing Element of Austenite on UND S32707 Hyperduplex Stainless Steel Welded by TIG Process
1184.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1184.prez_authors: André Rocha Pimenta, Marilia Garcia Diniz, Guillermo  Solorzano Naranjo
1184.prez_abstract: The interest for hyperduplex steel comes from their good mechanical properties and corrosion resistance. However, when submitted to welding the balance of your phases can be modified, as well as, deleterious phases can appear. This study aimed to investigate the efficiency of nitrogenous addition into the shielding gas of autogenous TIG welding on hyperduplex UNS S32707 in the maintenance of the equilibrium of phases and possible desirable effects were also analyzed. Shielding gas used on was argon and nitrogenous, which nitrogenous was added in different quantities for each specimen, 1.5%, 2.5%, 3.5%, 4.5% and 5.5%. The techniques employed were optical microscopy, scanning electron microscopy, atomic force microscopy, X-Ray Energy Dispersive Spectroscopy, Digital Image Processing and microhardness Vickers measurements. Fusion zones obtained with higher N2 concentration, resulted in increasing of austenite content, 39% to 57%, using 1.5% and 5.5% nitrogen, respectively. Elevated N2 concentration contributed to better corrosion resistance.

1185.prez_name: Transient Liquid Phase Bonding of Ni-based-alloy-H230 for Compact Heat Exchangers for Application in Supercritical CO2 Power Cycles
1185.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1185.prez_authors: Monica  Kapoor, Omer  Dogan, Jeffrey  Hawk
1185.prez_abstract: This work focuses on transient-liquid-phase bonding (TLPB) of Ni-based alloy H230 for application in compact heat exchangers operating at 700°C-800°C and 20-30 MPa in supercritical CO2 power cycles.  TLPB uses a low-melting coating on the surfaces which are to be joined.  This coating melts at the bonding temperature and enhances diffusion processes to form a bond across the two surfaces.  This bond should have a uniform microstructure without any deleterious second phases in order to have uniform mechanical properties across the structure.   Tensile testing on these TLP bonded stacks shows that fracture occurs through the joint region and that the plastic strain is constrained in the vicinity of the fracture region.  Creep testing of the stacks at 800°C has been performed and compared to bulk H230.  Scanning and transmission electron microscopy of the creep tested samples to understand the failure mechanisms in the stacks has been performed.

1186.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1186.prez_abstract: In high strain-rate deformation, as in ultrasonic joining, excess vacancies may impact material behavior through their effects on diffusion, thermodynamic stability and dislocation motion. Ultrasonic joining experiments with aluminum and copper sheets have shown a possible five-orders-of-magnitude increase in diffusivity over the normal value. Scanning transmission electron microscopy (STEM) has revealed evidence of high-rate dynamic recovery and recrystallization indicative of excess vacancies in aluminum fabricated by ultrasonic powder consolidation (UPC), a new, low-temperature powder consolidation technique which can produce full-density, metallurgically intact consolidates just in seconds. Systematic experiments with copper have revealed the mechanism of UPC. Bimetallic and hybrid bimetallic-thermite reactive composites fabricated by UPC can be used as heaters for microjoining with controlled heat outputs. UPC also provides a means for the consolidation of oxidation-susceptible nanoparticles. Sn-In nanosolder particles pre-consolidated into sheet has successfully been used to solder copper plates.

1187.prez_name: Utilizing Site Specific Shear Punch Testing to Evaluate Friction Stir Welded Al-2139 T8 Plate
1187.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1187.prez_authors: B. Chad Hornbuckle, Heather A Murdoch, Anthony J Roberts, Laszlo J Kecskes, Mark A Tschopp, Kevin J Doherty, Jian H Yu, Kris A Darling
1187.prez_abstract: Friction stir welding (FSW) is of interest to the Army for joining of high strength aluminum alloys to replace heavier steels in automotive applications. While FSW has been shown as an effective method for welding such materials, the key is the evaluation of the mechanical properties of these welded regions. Site specific shear punch testing was shown to be a valuable tool to site specifically assess the weld properties of a butt joint of Al-2189 T8 plate by generating two-dimensional color enhanced property maps. The underlying microstructure responsible for the variation in mechanical properties seen in the two-dimensional property maps were characterized via SEM and TEM to provide a direct properties to microstructure relationship. This talk will describe the advantages of shear punch testing and results of this particular study.

1188.prez_name: Utilizing Ultrasonic Thermometry to Monitor Friction Stir Welding Temperature Profiles
1188.symp_name: Joining of Advanced and Specialty Materials (JASM XIX)
1188.prez_abstract: Friction stir welding (FSW) is a solid state welding process that thermo-mechanically joins two parts together by plunging a rotating tool into the work material and plastically deforming and heating the material by stirring it together.  FSW quality is dependent on maintaining a constant temperature during the weld.  Since the temperature is only indirectly controlled by the process parameters, maintaining a constant weld temperature can be difficult. Ultrasonic thermometry is both non-invasive and can be used to obtain spatial resolution of the weld zone temperature.  Using the change in elastic modulus caused by change in temperature and relating it to a time of flight change in an ultrasonic echo, a real time temperature profile can be determined during the FSW. Making the transducer move with the tool translation removes the transient factor.  This study explored the use of ultrasonic thermometry in monitoring the real time temperature in a FSW.

1189.prez_name: Alloying Effects on the Microstructure and Mechanical Properties of Ti-Fe-Al Based Lower Cost Cast Titanium Alloys
1189.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1189.prez_authors: Jiashi  Miao, Zhi  Liang, Anil K.  Sachdev, Alan A.  Luo, James C.  Williams
1189.prez_abstract: Titanium alloys with excellent mechanical properties and corrosion resistance have attracted increasing interests for applications in the aerospace, automotive and biomedical fields. However, additional applications of commercial titanium alloys often have been limited, by their high cost.  In this work, lower cost cast titanium alloys based on Ti-Fe-Al system were developed. Microstructure evolution including features such as grain size, alpha phase fraction and morphology, and phase transformation kinetics during heat treatment was characterized using quantitative metallography in combination with scanning electron microscopy and transmission electron microscopy. Mechanical properties of the alloys were tested on miniature specimens. Small additions of boron can significantly refine the grain size of as-cast microstructure of Ti-Fe-Al alloys.  The additions of other alloying element such as Mn and Zr for solid solution strengthening were also investigated in this work.

1190.prez_name: Aluminum Intensive Ultra-lightweight Automotive Door Structure
1190.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1190.prez_authors: Randy  Beals, Tim  Skszek, Miguel  Merino, Tim   Reaburn, Mari    Chellman
1190.prez_abstract: The Ultralight Door Project developed by Magna International, FCA US LLC, Grupo Antolin and Corning is a result of a US Department of Energy project DE-EE0007306. The project is opening new doors to light weighting by demonstrating an innovative lightweight car door solution which includes functional integration of the door structure, door module, latch, glass and interior trim subsystems, achieving a 15.5kg mass reduction associated with a driver’s side door, while maintaining performance, occupant safety and functionality of the baseline 2017 production vehicle.  Production intent prototype doors have been manufactured and limited full vehicle and component level testing is being conducted by FCA. The Ultralight driver’s side door, comprised of commercially available materials and production processes, realized a 15.5kg (40%) mass reduction. When applied to a 4-door vehicle, with a proportionally downsized engine, an estimated 50kg full vehicle mass reduction will be realized, resulting in an 8 g/mile reduction in CO2. The higher cost associated with lightweight materials is offset by the design-enabled procurement of DIW and Door Module subassemblies resulting in a significant reduction in assembly labor and floor space requirements. The estimated incremental cost associated with the Ultralight Door is $2.59 per pound saved.

1191.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1191.prez_abstract: Aluminum usage in the automotive industry is projected to increase annually due to its attractive strength-to-weight ratio and aesthetic benefits. However, the sustainability of this demand increase is under speculation due to a misunderstood recycling rate for automotive aluminum. This study proves the feasibility of aluminum beyond use phase and into the realm of recyclability. A grave-to-gate process material flow analysis system has been developed based upon surveys delivered to auto-dismantlers, downstream separation systems, and recovery processors. A holistic and detailed understanding of the processes, technologies and their effectiveness, from each tier, regarding the extraction of aluminum from end-of-life automobiles, and the resulting material flows are reported. All processors in the secondary aluminum industry pay careful attention to their respective landfill flows and this allows for the recycling rate of automotive aluminum to maintain its competitive nature.

1192.prez_name: Boon for the Injured and Elderly: Optimization of Laser Processing Parameters to Improve Bio-Wettability of Ti-6Al-4V Alloys
1192.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1192.prez_abstract: Due to an increase in orthopedic injuries, an increasing demand for hard tissue replacements such as bone exists. The Ti-6Al-4V alloy is commonly used in such replacements. Recently, however, there has been great concern over the dissolution of aluminum and vanadium debris into the body fluid, thereby causing a toxic result due to poor integration with the human environment. Without the ability to surround biomaterials with osteoblast cells, the surrounding tissue will recede from the material, release debris, and thereby require immediate revision surgery. Laser surface processing creates a physical surface texture on Ti-6Al-4V alloys and has been hypothesized to improve bone integration for metallic implants. This form of engineering will be used to find the optimal laser processing parameters to improve Ti-6Al-4V alloy’s bio-wettability. Contact angle, surface energy, and roughness measurements were conducted to test for improved wettability. Through Taguchi method-based response surface analysis, the optimal parameter was concluded.

1193.prez_name: Comparison of Microstructure and Tensile Property of Silafont-36 and Mercaloy 367 in a Rear Cross Member Prototype Casting Using HPDC Process
1193.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1193.prez_authors: Kumar  Sadayappan, Gabriel  Birsan, Xiaochun  Zeng, Sumanth  Shankar
1193.prez_abstract: An automotive structural casting was manufactured through high-pressure die casting process using two Al-Si alloys Silafont 36 and Mercalloy 367.  The objective was to compare the two alloys using the dependant parameters such as, filling and solidification, microstructure and uniaxial tensile properties of casting at various critical locations.  The analysis includes simulations of mould filling and solidification using Flow3D software.  The two Al-Si based alloys lend themselves to structural castings because of their low Fe content; resulting in an increase in the component ductility.  The drawback of reducing the Fe content in these alloys were the high susceptibility to die tool soldering of Al which was alleviated by increasing levels of Mn in Silafont-36 and Sr in Mercaloy 367.  This report presents the process details, characterization and properties of these two alloy components.

1194.prez_name: Complexities in the Assessment of Melt Quality
1194.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1194.prez_authors: Martin  Riestra, Anton  Bjurenstedt, Toni  Bogdanoff, Ehsan  Ghassemali, Salem  Seifeddine
1194.prez_abstract: If high performance aluminium castings are to be produced, the melt quality needs to be properly assured. Multiple tests for melt quality assessment exist and have previously been analysed. In most studies the techniques were used separately. In this work, reduced pressure, fluidity, Prefil and tensile tests have been performed on the same melts. A commercial EN 46000 alloy was used as the base material with additions of 25 and 50 wt.% machining chips to degrade the melt quality. In reduced pressure and fluidity tests, oxides floated to the top of samples, decreasing the reliability. Bifilm index increased with addition level, but not correspondingly. Density index, Prefil and fluidity tests did not present significant variations and tensile properties only deteriorated with the 50 wt.% addition level. The investigated techniques provided information, but measuring melt quality reliably remains a challenge.

1195.prez_name: Computational Study of Competing Icosahedral Approximants in RS8009
1195.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1195.prez_authors: Joseph  Jankowski, Jonathan  Miorelli, Michael  Kaufman, Amy  Clarke, Mark  Eberhart, Krish  Krishnamurthy, Vladan  Stevanovic
1195.prez_abstract: RS8009 is a high performance structural Al alloy that retains its strength at temperatures well above 200 C. However, due to the use of rapid solidification to produce the alloy, several complex metastable phases can form. The α-phase and h-phase are two of the most important phases that form and are icosahedral approximants with similar compositions. The α-phase forms as favorable fine dispersoids and the h-phase forms as unfavorable coarse particles that create dispersoid-free regions in the microstructure. Density functional theory (DFT) calculations are performed in order to understand what factors lead to the formation of the α-phase and the h-phase in RS8009.

1196.prez_name: Constitutive Response of a Near-alpha Titanium Alloy as a Function of Temperature and Strain Rate
1196.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1196.prez_authors: Brian T Gockel, Anthony D Rollett
1196.prez_abstract: Modeling structures operating in extreme environment require a full understanding of material response under relevant loading conditions.  In this study the tensile constitutive response of titanium alloy Ti-6Al-2Sn-4Zr-2Mo-0.1Si (Ti-6242S) was investigated over a range of temperatures from 23 °C to 650 °C and two strain rates.  Test results indicated that dynamic strain aging was occurring between the temperatures of 260 °C and 482 °C at a quasi-static strain rate. This unexpected behavior was investigated further at appropriate temperatures and strain rates to verify that the dynamic strain aging behavior was repeatable.  The constitutive response was modeled within the viscoplastic, self-consistent code using the modified Voce model, Johnson-Cook model and mechanical threshold stress (MTS) hardening models.  Model parameters were developed for a range of loading conditions and the applicability and limitations of each model were explored.  Recommendations for future testing and investigation will be discussed.

1197.prez_name: Crack Propagation from a Notched Hole under Uni-axial Fatigue Loading of AA7075-T6 Sheet
1197.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1197.prez_authors: Malika  Khodja, Hamida   Fekirini, Ulyate   Curle , Gary   Corderley , Gonasagren   Govender
1197.prez_abstract:
Aluminium is the predominant material used in the manufacture of commercial aircraft. Fatigue cracks in aircraft skin commonly initiate from stress concentrations such as fastener holes and failure will occur in the mode that corresponds with the lowest load carrying capability of the material. 
Crack propagation from a notched hole under cyclic tension–tension mode was studied. Crack growth rates were obtained from load-controlled low cycle fatigue testing of aluminium 7075-T6. Specimens were loaded in parallel, perpendicular and at a 45° angle to the rolling directions respectively. In addition, material characterization and microstructural analyses were performed before and after failure of the material. Observations of the complex interaction between mechanical load and the metallurgical structure are discussed.

1198.prez_name: Development of the Multi-purpose High Shear Mixing Technology for Continuous Processing of Al and Mg Alloys
1198.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1198.prez_authors: Jayesh Bhimji Patel, Yijie  Zhang, Jaime Lazaro Nebreda, Zhongyun  Fan
1198.prez_abstract: Melt conditioning by application of intensive melt shearing of Al and Mg alloys has shown that oxide films that already exist in melts can be dispersed into individual particles which can act as potent nucleation sites. Due to this enhanced nucleation during solidification, significant grain refinement is achieved without any specific chemical inoculation. Current technology is limited to batch processing only, hence the need to further develop to a continuous multi-purpose high shear processing technology which can be used in conjunction with various conventional casting processes. The multi-purpose high shear device can be used for; physical grain refinement by dispersing naturally occurring oxides, for degassing of Al-alloy melts and for the preparation of metal matrix composites. Hence, the newly developed multi-purpose high shear technology can be integrated and implemented with ease to benefit various industrial casting processes such as ingot casting, sand casting, high pressure die casting and twin-roll casting.

1199.prez_name: Effect of Casting Porosity on Compressive Mechanical Property of as-quenched Al-Cu-Mn Alloy
1199.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1199.prez_authors: Ke  Ren, Gang  Wang, Wenguang  Wang , Yiming  Rong
1199.prez_abstract: The porosity, as one of common defects in casting parts, has a significant effect on the mechanical properties of as-quenched Al-Cu-Mn alloy. In this paper, the low-pressure casting and quenching processes were conducted to prepare Al-Cu-Mn alloy specimens with various porosity values. The porosity distribution of the sample blocks were characterized by using high precision densimeter. The relation between density and compressive properties was investigated by isothermal compression test. The experimental results showed that when density increased by 1.19%, yield strength (ε_p=0.10) of quenched samples increased by 19.6%, while yield strength (ε_p=0.30) of quenched samples increased by 20.61%. Finally, a porosity-based constitutive model was established to represent the yielding behavior of as-quenched Al-Cu-Mn alloy under compressive stress.

1200.prez_name: Effect of Co and Ni-Additions on the Microstructure and Mechanical Properties at Room and Elevated Temperature of an Al-7%Si Alloy
1200.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1200.prez_authors: Toni  Bogdanoff, Arne K. Dahle, Salem  Seifeddine
1200.prez_abstract: Increasing environmental demands is forcing the automotive industry to reduce vehicle emissions by producing more light-weight and fuel efficient vehicles.  Al-Si alloys are commonly used in engine applications because of excellent castability, high thermal conductivity, good wear properties and high strength-to-weight ratio. However, most of the aluminium alloys on the market exhibit significantly reduced strength at temperatures above 200°C. The mechanical properties of Al-Si alloys at elevated temperature can be improved by alloying of transition metal elements. This paper presents results of a study into development new Al-Si alloys with addition of transitions metal elements for high temperature applications. Tensile test specimens were produced by directional solidification in a Bridgman furnace to produce samples with microstructures comparable to ones obtained by die castings e.g. SDAS ~ 10 µm. Directional solidification ensures well-fed samples with low levels of defects. The result shows improved tensile properties up to 250 ° C.

1201.prez_name: Effect of Heat Treatment and Artificial Ageing on Al-5Mg-2Zn
1201.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1201.prez_abstract: Traditionally aluminium casting alloy 513 is not heat treated after permanent mould casting. Al-Mg alloys are generally not heat treatable but the higher Zn content in this alloy could render it heat treatable.  It could be expected that in its as-cast state (F temper condition) there should be non-equilibrium intermetallics remaining at grain boundaries after casting which could be detrimental to corrosion properties of the alloy. This study investigated the effect of heat treatment and artificial ageing of Al-5Mg-2Zn. The study showed intermetallic phases at the grain boundaries and a melting peak at about 476 °C for the F condition.  Solution heat treatment at 440°C for 4 hours dissolved the intermetallic phase thus increasing the melting point of the alloy. The results further showed an appreciable increase of mechanical properties after T6 heat treatment over the F-condition.

1202.prez_name:
Effect of Heat Treatment Conditions on Microstructure, Mechanical Properties
and Residual Stress in a Die-cast Al-Si Alloy
1202.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
