1202.prez_abstract: During a die casting process, aluminum alloy cast components experience considerable changes in their mechanical properties, which subsequently adversely affect the residual stresses and distortion in the cast parts. In the present study, the mechanical properties of aluminum-silicon alloy, AA365, undergoing heat treatment processes T4, T5, and T6 were investigated to see the effects of cooling rate on mechanical properties of AA365. The effects of different cooling rates on the mechanical properties of AA365 have been statistically analyzed, and the microstructures of the alloy, with different heat treatment conditions, have been investigated to understand the mechanisms of the mechanical property changes. In addition, the residual stresses with different heat treatment conditions have been measured and correlated with the microstructural behavior of AA365.

1203.prez_name: Effect of Isothermal Holding at Elevated Temperature on Metallurgically Bonded Bimetallic Castings
1203.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1203.prez_abstract: Local improvement of properties like wear resistance and stiffness can be achieved in aluminum castings by casting in ferrous inserts. The volume change associated with solidification causes a shrink-fit around the insert holding it in place. With proper control of the casting process a metallurgical bond between the insert and the casting can be formed which can improve both load and heat transfer across the interface. The growth of the bond is diffusional in nature and post manufacturing heat treatments activates diffusion causing defects such as Kirkendall voids to form. Growth kinetics and microstructure of the metallurgical bond is temperature and time dependent and thus needs to be characterized before industrial application. The results of a study on growth kinetics and microstructural development of metallurgically bonded bimetallic castings will be presented and discussed.

1204.prez_name: Effect of Mn/Cu Content Ratio on Microstructure and Mechanical Properties of Al-Cu-Mn Alloys
1204.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1204.prez_authors: Soban Muddassir Dar, Heng Cheng Liao, Guang Jin Li
1204.prez_abstract: Al-Cu-Mn alloys are used in components in automotive and aircraft industry which work at high temperature. Recent research is focused on Al-Cu-Mn alloys to promote the formation of Mn-rich (T-phase) particles. This phase has high thermal stability and has potential to improve the high temperature strength of these alloys. In this study, the effect of Mn/Cu ratio on microstructure and mechanical properties of two Al-Cu-Mn alloys (Mn/Cu ratio = 0.2, 0.4) is investigated by optical microscopy, scanning electron microscopy, energy dispersive spectroscopy and high temperature tensile testing. Results reveal that as-cast microstructure of both the alloys consists of trunks of α-Al dendrites surrounded by Cu-rich interdendritic region. After solution treatment, a great amount of Al-Cu-Mn intermetallic compound particles are found to precipitate adjacent to this region. Alloy with high Mn/Curatio exhibits high strength at high temperature due to relatively high amount of Al-Cu-Mn (T-phase) particles.

1205.prez_name: Effect of Processing Method on Thermal Conductivity of Mg-Ce-Zn-Zr Alloy
1205.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1205.prez_authors: Lingfei  Hu, Guangxin  Wu, Jieyu  Zhang
1205.prez_abstract: Magnesium alloys have been widely used in automobile and 3C industries, however detailed studies of its thermal properties are still lacking. In order to investigate the effect of processing method on thermal properties, the Mg-Ce-Zn-Zr alloys were prepared in the state of as-cast, with homogenization treatment at 713K for 12h and through extrusion at 623K with an extrusion ratio of 10.24: 1. Thermal conductivity tester was used to measure the thermal conductivity. Optical microscope (OM), scanning electron microscope (SEM) equipped with energy dispersive spectrometer (EDS), X ray diffraction (XRD) and were used for microstructural characterization. The experimental results revealed that after homogenization treatment, the materials exhibited higher thermal conductivity than as-cast state, which may be attributed to the reduction of (Mg, Zn)12Ce volume. Meanwhile the thermal conductivity of extrusion alloys was better than alloys after homogenization treatment due to the decrease of defects.

1206.prez_name: Effect of Strain Rate on Mechanical Behaviour of Commercial Die-cast Magnesium Alloys
1206.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1206.prez_authors: Hua Qian  Ang, Trevor Bruce Abbott, Suming  Zhu, Mark  Easton
1206.prez_abstract: The tensile properties of high-pressure die-cast Mg-4Al-4RE (AE44), Mg-6Al-0.3Mn (AM60), and Mg-9Al-1Zn (AZ91) under strain rates ranging from 10<sup>-6 </sup> to 10<sup>-1 </sup> s<sup>-1 </sup> have been investigated.  It was found that AE44 is highly strain rate sensitive, followed by AM60, whilst AZ91 has little strain-rate sensitivity, fitting with previous observations about a correlation between strain-rate sensitivity and the aluminium content. Ductility is improved at lower strain rates in AE44 and AM60, but it appears to be independent of strain rate in AZ91. Microstructural examinations by electron backscattered diffraction (EBSD) revealed that deformation twinning is more active in AZ91 and AM60 than AE44. The difference in strain-rate sensitivity among these alloys is considered to be related to dynamic strain aging (DSA) from interactions between the aluminium solute and dislocations.

1207.prez_name: Effect of Titanium Levels on the Castability and Abnormal Grain Growth after Heat Treatment of Al-Zn-Mg-Cu Alloys
1207.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1207.prez_authors: Xiaochun  Zeng, Kumar  Sadayappan, Cassandra  Ferguson, Sumanth  Shankar
1207.prez_abstract: In this paper, the castability of Al-6wt.%Zn-2wt%.Mg-2wt.%Cu alloy with different titanium levels was investigated with a constrained rod casting (CRC) mould.  About 0.06 wt%Ti seem to be the optimum at which the hot tearing sensitivity (HTS) index is minimum while it increases to about 17 at 0wt%Ti and 13 at 0.24wt%Ti.  The grain sizes and grain morphologies for F and T4 tempers of samples were analyzed; grain size decreased with the increasing Ti levels in the as cast samples, and the grain morphology was changed from dendrite to globular.  After T4 treatment, abnormal grain growth occurred only in samples with less then 0.1wt.% of Ti.  The uniaxial tensile properties were measured for samples cast with various levels of Ti using the tilt pour casting process;  notably, the abnormal grain growth had negligible effect on tensile properties.

1208.prez_name: Effects of Heat-Treatment on the Microstructure of TiAl-Nb Produced with Laser Metal Deposition Technique
1208.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1208.prez_authors: Monnamme  Tlotleng, Thabo  Lengopeng, Mandy  Seerane, Sisa  Pityana
1208.prez_abstract: Ti and its intermetallic alloys are light-weight and have good creep properties. Materials of this nature are desired for the manufacturing of parts for the aerospace, automotive and power plants. Titanium aluminides, in particular, are preferred due to their lightness and excellent creep properties when compared to nickel super-alloys. This paper looked into the production of titanium aluminide microstructures, the so-called ordered α2-Ti3Al-Nb, making use of the in-situ laser metal alloying additive manufacturing approach, and the impact of heat treatment on microstructural evolution and hardness measurements. Ti-33Al-8Nb alloy was produced by melting the elemental powders in a laser melt-pool. The resulting microstructure was characterised for composition and hardness measurements before and after heat treatment. The As-produced sample was dense and had lamella with the observed grains. Micro-hardness of 5550.5 was reported. Heat treatment at 1200°C, as oppose to other heating profiles, resulted in a homogeneous structure with refined lamella observed inside the preserved grain structures. Contrary, non-homogeneous structure with coarsened lamella inside elongated grains was observed at 1400°C. Micro-hardness of 4520.5 was reported. These results are summarised in Figure 4.

1209.prez_name: Enhancing Aluminum Scrap Recycling through the Implementation of Optoelectronic Sorting Technologies
1209.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1209.prez_abstract: Optoelectronic sorting systems, namely x-ray transmission (XRT), x-ray fluorescence (XRF), and laser-induced breakdown spectroscopy (LIBS), are poised to shift the metallic recycling industry. These enabling technologies will aid in the broadening of the secondary aluminum alloy spectrum, prolong the threatening shredded scrap surplus, and increase domestic utilization of aluminum auto-shred in the United States. Characterization studies and sorting-criteria development are required to extract the full potential of these systems. This work explores the efficiencies, capabilities, and limitations of these technologies and discusses the ideal route for implementation into an inflexible industry.

1210.prez_name: Exploring Magnesium Alloys for Lightweighting in Transportation
1210.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1210.prez_authors: Frank  Czerwinski, Amjad  Javaid, Kumar  Sadayappan
1210.prez_abstract: Magnesium, being the lightest structural metal, is seen as the primary candidate for substantial weight reduction in modern aerospace and ground transportation. However, the high strength-to-weight ratio, along with other unique properties, offered by magnesium alloys, are overshadowed by their high surface reactivity, processing challenges, cost and competition by conventional  materials.  Research activities at CanmetMATERIALS aim at removing some of these barriers that prevent the widespread use of magnesium. The study of magnesium reactivity in solid and liquid states concluded that at high temperatures the oxidation, ignition, evaporation and flammability are controlled by the nature of the oxide film formed on the metal surface.  This finding opens opportunities for development of ignition resistant alloys through chemistry modification with additions of rare earths and other elements having high affinity to oxygen. Additions of rare earths were also used to improve formability of alloys through modification of their deformation textures. The detrimental effect of oxidation on processing was examined through industrial scale experiments of high pressure-die casting, semisolid casting, twin roll casting and high temperature forming. Opportunities to increase use of magnesium in transportation are discussed using recent projects with industrial partners.

1211.prez_name: Formability of Tailor Welded Blanks Made by Friction Stir Welding: Effect of Heat Input and Flow Profile
1211.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1211.prez_authors: Ronit  Dey, Amit  Arora, Jyoti  Mukhopadhyay
1211.prez_abstract: In view of increasing concerns about fuel economy and reducing carbon emissions in the automotive sector, the use of lightweight materials along with relevant technologies has developed huge popularity in the recent times. Tailor welded blanks technology is one of them, it has gained lot of importance due to its vast applications in automotive and aerospace industries.Friction stir welding has been effectively used in the production of TWBs and the forming characteristics are found to be much better than other welding techniques. This paper aims at further optimizing the formability of TWBs by utilising different tool pin profiles and offsetting of tool pin which creates a pulsated flow in the weld pool. Various tool rotation and welding speeds have been used to control the heat input during welding which causes changes in dynamic recrystallization and grain growth during welding.

1212.prez_name:
Fracture and Fatigue Crack Growth Behavior of As-cast vs. Forged 
Ti-43Al-4Nb-1Mo
1212.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1212.prez_authors: Matthew  Dahar, Sesh  Tamirisakandala, John  Lewandowski
1212.prez_abstract: Ti-43Al-4Nb-1Mo (TNM) is being investigated as a potential material for low-pressure turbine blades in high performance gas turbine engines. This study summarizes mechanical behavior of third generation TNM in the as-cast and post-processed conditions (e.g. cast + HIP, HIP + forged). Tension, creep, and bend bar samples were machined from the longitudinal and transverse and tested at various temperatures. In addition, fatigue crack growth tests were conducted over a range of load ratios, R, at room temperature in order to determine the load ratio dependence of the fatigue threshold, Paris slope, and stress intensity at overload (Kc) in fatigue. Characterization of the microstructures and fracture surfaces were also performed with SEM and other surface science techniques. The effects of post processing on the microstructure and the resulting mechanisms of fracture and fatigue will be discussed in order to develop a micro-mechanistic model

1213.prez_name: Heat Treatment of Steel-Aluminum Hybrid Components
1213.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1213.prez_abstract: Recent research efforts aim at transferring the concept of tailored properties (known from tailored blanks) to massive steel-aluminum hybrid components under the term “Tailored Forming”. The specific feature of the employed process chain is that the dissimilar metals are joined before the forming process to allow for a modification of the joining zone properties by adapted forming operations. To improve and adapt the mechanical properties of the hybrid components, heat treatment of the steel and aluminum parts have to be carried out. However, this is challenging due to the different solidus temperatures and the growth of brittle intermetallic compound layers. Hence, adapted heat treatment techniques have been developed and employed for surface hardening of the steel part and T6-treatment of the aluminum part. The work addresses the approaches to deal with the aforementioned challenges and the resulting microstructural and mechanical properties of the heat treated hybrid components.

1214.prez_name: Hot Deformation Behavior, Microstructure and Mechanical Properties of Mg-8Zn-1Al-0.5Cu-0.5Mn Alloy
1214.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1214.prez_authors: Yuansheng  Yang, Shaozhen  Zhu, Tianjiao  Luo
1214.prez_abstract: The hot deformation behavior of a new Mg-8Zn-1Al-0.5Cu-0.5Mn alloy was studied by hot compression tests at temperatures of 200°C-350°C and strain rates of 0.001/s - 1/s. The flow stress model was developed to predict the flow behavior during hot compression, and processing maps were established according to the dynamic materials model. The processing maps show that the increase of strain enlarges the instability domains, and the alloy has good hot workability at higher temperature and lower strain rate. Completed DRX occurred when the alloy was extruded at 290°C and the grains grew obviously after solution/aging treatments. Finer and far more densely dispersed precipitates were in the alloy with double aging treatment and the tensile properties were enhanced remarkably with the yield strength, tensile strength and elongation were 298MPa, 348MPa and 18%, which was attributed to the combined effects of fine recrystallized grains and the uniform distribution of fine precipitates.

1215.prez_name: Hot Deformation/Forging and Mechanical Behavior of 3rd Generation Al-Li Alloy
1215.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1215.prez_authors: Henry J Neilson, David  Schwam, John J. Lewandowski
1215.prez_abstract: Since their initial development in the 1920s, both research and application of aluminum-lithium alloys has greatly expanded.  The higher stiffness (~6% increase per 1.0% Li addition) and lower density (~3% decrease per 1.0% Li addition) compared to their lithium-free counterparts is desirable for aerospace applications.  These alloys are commonly deformation-processed at high temperatures (T > 300C) over a moderate range in strain rates (0.01/s < strain rate < 0.1/s) in various forming operations, including forging. This project characterizes the mechanical and deformation behavior of a new Ag-free aluminum-lithium alloy.  The degree of anisotropy of both forged and unforged specimens is analyzed via tension, compression, and Charpy impact tests.  Acoustic measurements are conducted to analyze the anisotropy of elastic constants.  The effects of changes in temperature, strain rate, and strain on the flow stress evolution are determined on the MTS Advanced Deformation Simulator at Case Western Reserve University.

1216.prez_name: In-situ Manufacturing Techniques for Aluminum Matrix Nano-composites
1216.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1216.prez_authors: Iñigo  Anza, Jeremy  Michael Fedors, Eunkyung  Lee, Brajendra  Mishra
1216.prez_abstract: Two distinct technologies are being pioneered for the cost competitive and scalable manufacturing of metal matrix nano-composites. One of them, the Rotating Impeller Gas-Liquid In-situ method (RIGLI), has been successfully developed for aluminum master alloys with two different reinforcement chemistries: Al-AlN and Al-TiC nanocomposites. A progress update will be given in regards to several aspects: kinetics enhancement, particle size control, rheology increase and loading, scale-up strategies, master alloy incorporation in the melt and treatment thereof. Finally, the mechanical properties will be revisited and other potential reinforcement chemistries explored. A second method, the self-propagating high temperature synthesis (SHS) currently in its initial development stage, has been conceived to specifically overcome the obstacles encountered in the RIGLI process for carbide reinforcement synthesis. An introductory description and preliminary results will be presented.

1217.prez_name: Influence of Metallic Coatings on the Microstructural Development of the Metallurgical Bond for Cast-in Ferrous Inserts
1217.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1217.prez_authors: Carl  Soderhjelm, Chiara  Bertuccioli, Lorella  Ceschini, Diran  Apelian
1217.prez_abstract: Properties of cast aluminum components can be improved by strategically placing ferrous inserts to locally improve properties such as wear resistance and stiffness. A cost-effective production method is to cast-in the insert using the solidification of the molten aluminum as a joining method. Metallurgically bonding between the metals could potentially improve both load and heat transfer across the interface. Formation of a continuous defect free bond is inhibited by the wetting behavior of aluminum which can be modified by application of sacrificial low melting point metallic coatings. Modern metal powder coating technologies such as cold spray provide tools for application of a wider selection of materials allowing for interfacial engineering to combat multi-material diffusion phenomena like Kirkendall void formation. The results of a study on the suitability of hot-dipped zinc, tin, and cold sprayed titanium coatings for cast-in inserts will be presented and discussed.

1218.prez_name: Investigating Effect of Thermal Parameters on Properties of Al-4%Cu Alloy Squeeze Cast under a High Applied Pressure
1218.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1218.prez_abstract: In squeeze casting process melt is forced into die cavity under a directly applied pressure thus reducing fluidity concerns for the process. Two distinctly different levels of superheat were investigated that were expected to give different cooling rates and hence varying mechanical properties. Effect of the superheat level can be influenced by die temperature, which was selected to maximize cooling rate. Squeeze pressure was selected to be higher than the critical value for aluminum alloys above which there is little or even deteriorating effect on properties. Effect of superheat was found to be not significant and this was evaluated against microstructural evidence to postulate the findings of present research. Increase in die temperature at lower superheat level resulted in heat being initially removed inwards into undercooled melt ahead of the solidifying front. Coarsening effect of pressure was observed in run with highest properties that also showed evidence of age hardening.

1219.prez_name: Joining Automotive Steel and Aluminum Alloys with Vaporizing Foil Actuator Welding
1219.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1219.prez_authors: Anupam  Vivek, Bert  Liu, Yu  Mao, Glenn Steven Daehn
1219.prez_abstract: Vehicle weight reduction, by creating multi-material structures consisting of high strength-to-weight ratio materials, is one the strategies of the automotive industry to meet its fuel economy targets. Multi-material assembly raises issues of joining and corrosion and, currently, the standard solution in the industry is using fasteners and adhesives. Vaporizing foil actuator welding (VFAW) is a solid state welding technique, which enables joining of dissimilar materials without a third body. It utilizes a large pulsed current to turn a thin conductor into a highly kinetic gas, which launches one sheet of metal into another and creates an impact weld. Aluminum alloys type 5052 and 6111-T4 were welded to DP 980 and 22MnB5 steels. High pressure cast aluminum alloy Aural 2 was also welded to HSLA 350 steel. During mechanical testing, failure occurred in parent aluminum. Results of mechanical testing, corrosion and advanced characterization will be discussed in light of the structure-property relationships. The stages of technology development for commercial implementation will also be presented.

1220.prez_name: Laser Welding Characteristics for Joints of Secondary Cell Made of Aluminium and Nickel
1220.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1220.prez_abstract: The purpose of this study is to make the experimental basis for the development of the laser-assisted micro welding technology. The basic experiments are carried out on the melting of the thin aluminium and nickel sheets in order to secure the micro laser welding process technology for manufacturing the secondary cell. The micro laser welding joints are lap joints. The welding specimens are made from the aluminium and nickel plate. The thickness of metal sheet is 0.15 mm. The quality of welding specimens is tested by observing the shape of the beads on the plate after the laser welding and the cross-section of the welded parts is observed by using metallography method. The mechanical tensile test is carried out for analyzing the performance of welding strength. The monitoring method by using UV and IR sensor is used for finding the correlation with the results of the mechanical and metallurgical test.

1221.prez_name: Light Metal Activities in USA – A Retrospective and Prospective View
1221.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1221.prez_abstract: In a nutshell, the activities in light metals in USA point out that light metals are not taken lightly.  There is much active work in Al, Mg, Ti in both process development as well as alloy development, and also in the development of resource recovery and recycling. In this presentation, we will give an overview of the vast network of work ongoing in light metals at the Metal Processing Institute and all its partners – industry, academia, and national laboratories, as well as at LIFT, one of the Institutes of NNMI (National Network of Manufacturing Institutes).

1222.prez_name: Lightweight Aluminum Foams – Tailoring Compressive Property through Relative Density Variation
1222.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1222.prez_abstract: Metal foams are lightweight structural materials possessing high specific mechanical properties and good thermal properties. Metal foams finds applications in aerospace, automotive and oil&gas sectors as heat exchangers, foam core in sandwich structures and energy absorbing crash structures. Open-cell aluminum foams are porous lightweight material owing to their cell shape and inherent low density of aluminum. Foams relative density depends on pores per inch, strut thickness and material. In the present work, effort is made to vary relative density of open-cell aluminum foam through rolling and the foams are studied for compressive response. The relative density of the foams are varied by controlling the thickness to which they are compressed. The developed foams are evaluated for compressive properties under varying strain rates (10^-4/s – 10^3/s) and compared with as-cast open cell foams and existing literature data. Effort is also made to establish strain rate sensitivity in foams compressive behavior.

1223.prez_name: Lightweight Designs: A Balance of Density, Material Properties, Processing Capabilities, and Cost
1223.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1223.prez_abstract: In materials selection, trade-offs occur on a variety of parameters.  Although ferrous metals are not typically considered to be amongst the light weight metals, ductile iron is ten percent lighter than steel.  In addition, if cost is a significant consideration, austempered ductile iron (ADI) is considered to have the best combination of strength:weight:cost ratio making it appropriate for use in many circumstances, particularly for automotive applications.  In the past its use has been limited due carbides frequently occurring below 6.35 mm thicknesses.  Much research including ongoing efforts by the LIFT consortium (Lightweight Innovations For Tomorrow) have been expended into production methods of thin walled ductile iron.  Existing methods in lost foam casting currently exist that prevent carbides with standard metallurgy practices.  Several production examples are reviewed.  In addition, details of trials that have been conducted achieving thicknesses down to 1.90 mm and prototypes for use as a replacement for stampings are covered.

1224.prez_name: Low Temperature Thermal Conductivity of Pure Mg and Binary Magnesium Alloys
1224.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1224.prez_authors: Tao  Ying, Hang  Chi, Mingyi  Zheng, Zitong   Li, Ctirad  Uher
1224.prez_abstract: The thermal conductivity of pure Mg, Mg-Al, Mg-Zn and Mg-Mn binary magnesium alloys were measured in the temperature range of 2 – 300 K. The thermal conductivity decreased with the increasing alloying content in each binary alloy system. The low-temperature thermal conductivity was understood using κ = (A/T + BT2)-1 + CT2, which is found to be applicable in various binary and/or multi-component alloy systems. The parameters A, B, and C were determined through numerical fitting of the experimental data. Significant differences were found in the effect of three solute atoms on the thermal conductivity of Mg. The reasons for large differences in the thermal conductivity of the three binary magnesium alloy systems are discussed. Variations in the atomic volume and the valency are believed to play an important role on the thermal conductivity of magnesium alloys.

1225.prez_name: Manufacturing Challenges for Aluminum Sheet in the Automotive Industry
1225.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1225.prez_abstract: Aluminum sheet is used in the automotive industry for body applications such as hoods, decklids, liftgates, and doors, as a way to achieve mass reduction and improve fuel economy.  This presentation will outline technical challenges in manufacturing aluminum sheet metal components and describe new alloys and new technologies that are being explored to overcome these challenges.  This presentation will also discuss practical implementation hurdles such as developing design guidelines, formability analysis material data cards, manufacturing plant readiness, and training.

1226.prez_name: Metal Injection Moulding of Ti6Al7Nb Using a CSIR Custom Feedstock
1226.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1226.prez_abstract: This paper reports on the metal injection moulding of prealloyed Ti6Al7Nb using a CSIR developed MIM feedstock. The preliminary debinding and sintering studies were performed at 1300oC the Mercury Centre at the University of Sheffield to demonstrate feasibility and versatility of the developed MIM feedstock. XRD analysis and microstructural and mechanical properties of the of the sintered materials were established. The results demonstrate that the CSIR-developed binder system can be cost-effectively used to fabricate MIM components of acceptable mechanical performances. The sintered samples achieved relative density values and mechanical properties typically higher than some recently reported powder metallurgy Ti6Al7Nb alloy but comparable to the wrought alloy.

1227.prez_name: Microalloyed Magnesium Alloys with High Complex of Properties
1227.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1227.prez_authors: Sergei  Belikov, Vadim  Shalomeev, Eduard  Tsivirko, Nikita  Aikin, Sergei  Sheyko
1227.prez_abstract: This study presents a theoretical analysis and justified choice of alloying elements for the development of new magnesium alloys with higher levels of properties. It was shown the effect of microalloying on the macro- and microstructure, morphology and topology of intermetallic phases of magnesium alloy MЛ5 (Standard of Ukraine). It was found an optimal amount of the alloying elements that improves the structure as well as the mechanical properties of the magnesium alloy.

1228.prez_name: Microstructural and Physical Properties of Laser Cladding of Ti-Al Coatings on Ti6Al4V
1228.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1228.prez_abstract: Today, Titanium and its alloys are widely used in the marine, aerospace and chemical industries due to their excellent corrosion resistance, low density, and high strength. However, under contact loading, titanium and its alloys show poor oxidation and wear resistance. Laser cladding is an emerging material processing technique which is an efficient and cost effective technique for improving the surface properties of general metallic materials. Ti–Al coatings with 20, 25 and 30 wt.% Al contents were laser cladded on Ti6Al4V substrate by laser cladding. The Microstructure of the laser cladded coatings were characterised with scanning electron microscope (SEM) and X-ray energy dispersive spectroscopy (EDS). The results showed a defect free coatings were produced with improvement in hardness and wear resistance compared to the substrate.

1229.prez_name: Microstructure And Surface Finish Evolution During Single Point Incremental Forming
1229.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1229.prez_authors: Maya  Nath, Erika  Salem, Jaekwang  Shin, Timothy  Odykirk, Mihaela  Banu, Alan  Taub
1229.prez_abstract: Single Point Incremental Forming is a die-less manufacturing process where metal sheet is locally deformed by a rigid tool that moves along a pre-defined tool path. It serves as an alternative processing method to conventional stamping and deep drawing, offering cost savings for small volume production. Sheets of AA 7075-O were incrementally formed into cones and characterized for grain structure, texture and surface finish evolution by a combination of electron and optical microscopy techniques. Strain history of several locations along the wall was tracked during forming using finite element analysis. As equivalent strain increased, grains elongated along the cone wall. Both grain length and width evolved linearly with strain, indicating that the grains elongated proportionally to the equivalent deformation of the sheet. The <111> texture variant was strong with respect to the elongation direction. Surface cracks and other tribological features increased in size and density with increasing strain.

1230.prez_name: Microstructure and Texture Evolution of Micro-alloyed Magnesium-Zinc-Neodymium Alloys
1230.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1230.prez_authors: Yang  Liu, Jing   Su, Amjad  Javaid, Stephen  Yue, Tim  Skszek
1230.prez_abstract: The application of wrought magnesium (Mg) alloys was expanded by the addition of rare-earth (RE) elements due to the enhancement of formability, which can be attributed to the formation of non-basal texture components. Most previous studies on RE containing Mg alloys employed considerable amounts (above 0.5 wt.%) of RE elements. To economize on RE resources, two Mg-1Zn-xNd (wt.%) alloys with reduced amounts of Nd, i.e. x= 0.1 and 0.5 wt.%, were designed for the present work. The two alloys were subjected to hot rolling at 450℃ to a total reduction of 45% in two passes. Post-deformation annealing was then employed on the as-rolled specimens at various temperatures to generate microstructures and textures by static recrystallization. The addition of 0.1% Nd did not have a strong impact on the alloy.  However, strong recrystallization suppression was observed with 0.5 wt% addition of Nd. A texture with basal poles splitting toward transverse direction (TD) was obtained after rolling of the Mg-1Zn-0.5Nd alloy. The texture was further modified after annealing and a non-basal texture with RD and TD splitting was achieved.

1231.prez_name: Microstructure Evolution during High-temperature Tensile Testing of 5083 Aluminum Alloy
1231.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1231.prez_authors: Mizuguchi  Takashi, Tsutomu   Ito, Tokiko   Kurisaka, Hiroaki  Ohfuji
1231.prez_abstract: The stress–strain relationship and microstructural evolution of a fine-grained 5083 aluminum alloy produced via friction-stir processing (FSP) during high-temperature tensile deformation were investigated. It was found that the 5083 aluminum alloy exhibited a large elongation, especially above 693 K. The data of stress exponent and the activation energy for deformation suggest that grain boundary sliding accommodated by the solute drag motion of dislocations was the rate-controlling process in the early stages of deformation. The largest elongation of 350% occurred at 743 K and an initial strain rate of 0.001 /s. In this case, the grain aspect ratio increased with increasing nominal strain, which indicated that equiaxed grains continuously elongated along the tensile axis during high-temperature deformation because of dislocation creep. The value of the stress exponent increased with increasing strain. From our experimental results, the dominant deformation mechanism was determined to change during the tensile test.

1232.prez_name:
Microstructure, Mechanical Properties and Deformation Behavior of 
Mg-Gd-Y-Zn-Zr Alloy
1232.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1232.prez_abstract: We describe here the microstructure, mechanical properties, and deformation behavior of Mg-Gd-Y-Zn-Zr alloy. On the addition of element Y, the Mg-rare earth alloy forms Mg12Zn(Y, Gd) phase with 18R-long period stacking ordered (LPSO) structure. The long period stacking ordered (LPSO) structure in Mg-RE alloys enhances both strength and elongation at ambient and elevated temperature because of the excellent thermal stability and ability of plastic deformation. LPSO phase in the grain boundary ensures strength of the alloy at room and elevated temperature by effectively preventing grain boundary sliding.

1233.prez_name: Molecular Dynamics Simulations of the Twinnability of Al Alloys with Different Vacancy Fractions
1233.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1233.prez_abstract: Nanocrystalline materials (NCMs) have received a great deal of interest due to their superior strength, but this is achieved at the expense of ductility. Mechanical twinning has a significant effect on the ductility of NCMs.  Twinnability of materials can be evaluated by calculation of four extrema on generalized planar fault energy (GPFE) curve. While measuring accurate extrema by experiment is very challenging, molecular dynamics (MD) simulation offers a powerful tool to that end. To the best of the author’s knowledge, no completed research has so far been published for studying the effect of combined vacancy and Mg, Cu and Si impurities on the twinnability of pure Al by using modified embedded-atom method (MEAM) MD simulations. Here, we present the twinnabilities of the different concentrations of impurities including Mg, Cu, and Si with different vacancy fractions in the Al matrix. The results also compared with existing first-principle calculations.

1234.prez_name: On the Influence of CaO, Gd, Nd and Y on the Corrosion and Mechanical Properties of ZK40 Alloy
1234.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1234.prez_authors: Ricardo Henrique Buzolin, Chamini L Mendis, Marta  Mohedano, Domonkos  Tolnai, Carsten  Blawert, Karl Ulrich Kainer, Norbert  Hort
1234.prez_abstract: The effect of individual additions of CaO, Gd, Nd and Y on the microstructure, mechanical properties and corrosion resistance of the as-cast ZK40 alloy was investigated. The microstructural features were analysed using optical, scanning electron microscopy, x-ray diffraction and Scanning Kelvin Atomic Probe Force Microscopy. The compressive and tensile be­ha­vi­our of the as-cast alloys at room temperature were investigated. Hydrogen evolution under immersion in 0.5 wt.% NaCl solution were used to evaluate the corrosion behaviour. Results of mechanical and corrosion tests were correlated with microstructures. The addition of Gd and Y enhanced the ductility, while the Nd addition resulted in deterioration of mechanical properties. CaO addition did not cause enhancement in mechanical properties. The corrosion behaviour was enhanced with the addition of CaO and Gd. Modification of ZK40 with Gd opens up new perspectives in the development of Mg-Zn based alloys.

1235.prez_name: Optimisation of Injection Moulding Process Parameters: Orthogonal Array Approach
1235.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1235.prez_authors: Mandy  Seerane, Ronald  Machaka, Filipe  Pereira
1235.prez_abstract: Metal Injection Moulding (MIM) is the name associated with the process of producing near net metal components by injecting the particular metal feedstock into a mould. Injection moulding the green part sets the tone for a successful debinding as well the final process of sintering of the metal component. To obtain a defect-free green part, the injection moulding processing parameters should be optimised. A Ti6Al4V feedstock is studied to obtain optimum moulding parameters that yield maximum ‘green density’. An orthogonal array approach is presented whereby the green density is used as a quality characteristic indicator to measure the signal-to-noise ratio pattern of the experimental sets. Archimedes’ principle is used to measure the green density, and the pore concentration and pore distribution are analysed through X-ray tomography. The results are presented in the paper. Key words: Injection moulding, green density, Archimedes’ principle, X-ray tomography

1236.prez_name: Optimization of Thermal Balance of HPDC Tooling by Lubro-refrigeration and Quality Improvement of Castings
1236.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1236.prez_abstract: The work is focused to the optimization of the HPDC process for aluminum alloy, to improve the reliability of the process and the quality of casting with economical and environmental benefits. In particular the work done has been related to the thermal balance of the die trough a suitable control and setting of the lubricant application with contemporaneous refrigerating effects. In fact, a well done control of the temperature distribution trough the die resulted in a considerable  reduction of dimensional defects of castings together with a better control of possible residual porosity.

1237.prez_name: Post-forming Mechanical Properties of Double-sided Incrementally Formed Sheet Alloys
1237.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1237.prez_authors: Ravi  Verma, Eric  Thomas, Brian  Martinek, Alan  Gillard, Vijitha  Kiridena
1237.prez_abstract: Double-sided incremental forming (DSIF) of typical automotive sheet alloys, DDQ, AA 5754-O and AA 6111-T4, and age hardenable aerospace aluminum alloys AA 2024-O and AA 7075-O, in to a truncated pyramid shape was conducted. This paper will report mechanical properties of these DSIF panels in the as formed condition and, in case of age hardenable alloys, also in the post-forming age-hardened condition. The properties in the formed regions (areas deformed by stylus tools) will be compared with those in the unformed regions (parent metal). Effect of post-forming heat treatments on the property differential between formed and unformed regions and between sheet rolling and transverse directions will also be reported.

1238.prez_name: Precipitation Strengthening Behavior of Al-Cu-Mn Alloys With the Effect of Casting Segregation
1238.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1238.prez_authors: Yisen  Hu, Gang  Wang, Qing  Jiang, Wenfeng  Xiao, Yiming  Rong
1238.prez_abstract: Al-Cu-Mn is one of typical heat-treatable cast alloys with high strength which has been widely used in aerospace and automobile industries. The complete manufacturing process for Al-Cu-Mn components includes low pressure die casting, T6 heat treatment and machining. It has been found that the property in former process has been transferred to the sequent step with considerable effect. In this paper, a detailed study has been conducted on precipitation strengthening behavior of Al-Cu-Mn alloy under effects of casting macro-segregation. A plate of 60 mm thickness was prepared by using low pressure die casting. The remarkable segregation was observed in the position close to the sprue. The results showed that the composition of Cu decreased from 5.1 % to 3.8 % through the thickness, which led to a decrease of the yield strength and an increasing time for aging, while the elongation appeared as a parabolic.

1239.prez_name: Process Model for Hardness Prediction in Friction Stir Aluminum Welds
1239.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1239.prez_authors: Olga  Gopkalo, Brad J. Diak, Michael  Booth, Adrian  Gerlich
1239.prez_abstract: Welding is one of the major joining techniques used in the fabrication of vehicles. One of the common welding problems in age hardenable aluminum alloys is the strength loss in the heat affected zone (HAZ). The welding thermal cycle has the greatest effect on the HAZ of the material. The present work focuses on understanding the evolution of the HAZ microstructure of an age hardenable Al-Mg-Si alloy joined by friction stir welding (FSW). The Shercliff-Ashby model [1990] was used to fit the hardness evolution associated with isothermal aging.  An analytical thermal model was applied to describe the thermal history of the FSW. Measured parabolic thermal cycles were modeled in terms of an equivalent isothermal treatment and coupled to the Shercliff-Ashby model to predict the hardness profile and microstructure across a weld. Model prediction will be compared to experimental measurements of FSW aluminum alloy 6022-T4 thin plate.

1240.prez_name: Recent Advances in Designing Al and Ti Light Metal Alloys Based on ICME Technologies
1240.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1240.prez_authors: Greg  Olson, James  Saal, Jason  Sebastian, Aziz  Asphahani
1240.prez_abstract: Computational materials design with Integrated Computational Materials Engineering (ICME) technologies is fast becoming a necessity to accelerate the development of novel, high-performance alloys for demanding applications. QuesTek Innovations applies its ICME technologies to produce Materials By Design™, from steels to superalloys and light metal alloys. Two examples will be discussed: a high-strength Al alloy with superior resistance to stress corrosion cracking (SCC), and a highly-castable Ti alloy. Furthermore, applicability and design of these alloys for additive manufacturing (AM) will be detailed.

1241.prez_name: Revisit of Al–Si–Mg (Cu) Cast Alloys for Gravity Casting and High Pressure Die Casting: Microstructure and Mechanical Properties
1241.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1241.prez_authors: Shouxun  Ji, Xixi  Dong, Zhongyun  Fan
1241.prez_abstract: The requirements of light weighting structures in automotive industry and other transport applications drive the improvement of mechanical properties of aluminium alloys in conventional manufacturing process. The microstructure and tensile properties of cast Al–Si–Mg (Cu) alloys were investigated for the improvement of mechanical properties. With optimized condition, the Al-Si-Mg alloy can provide a yield strength over 300MPa and a UTS over 350MPa and an elongation over 8% using gravity casting and high pressure die casting. The optimization of alloy composition, microstructure characterization and mechanical properties under as-cast condition and under heat treated conditions were introduced in the paper. The strengthening mechanism and the improvement of mechanical properties in comparison with the conventional Al-Si-Mg (Cu) casting alloys are discussed in association with the defect formation.

1242.prez_name: Sensitivity of Ti-6Al-4V Components to Oxidation during Out of Chamber Wire Arc Additive Manufacturing
1242.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1242.prez_authors: Michael John Bermingham, Jordan  Thomson, David  StJohn, Matthew  Dargusch
1242.prez_abstract: Wire Arc Additive Manufacturing is a promising manufacturing process for producing large ribbed titanium aerospace components.  Based on welding technology, the process is highly affordable, has a very high deposition rate and is not limited by chamber size. However, given titanium’s extreme reactivity, an ongoing challenge is to prevent atmospheric contamination (oxidation) during out of chamber deposition. This is especially important during additive manufacturing where surface oxides in previous layers are readily absorbed during deposition of subsequent layers. This work explores the sensitivity of Ti-6Al-4V components to oxidation contamination during out of chamber Wire Arc Additive Manufacturing. Several components are produced under various argon trailing shield configurations and the changes in alloy chemistry (oxygen pickup) and mechanical properties are investigated, along with other techniques including bead blasting that can reduce oxide contamination. This work provides useful insights for determining acceptable levels of oxide contamination during out of chamber additive manufacturing.

1243.prez_name: Sensitization Effects on Tensile Behavior in 5XXX Series Aluminum Alloys: Environmentally Enhanced Cracking
1243.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1243.prez_abstract: The desirability of 5XXX series Aluminum-Magnesium alloys for Naval use is tempered by their propensity to sensitize in the application environment. A contributor to this is the β phase (Al3Mg2) and non-equilibrium variants that preferentially precipitate at grain boundaries upon thermal exposure. These phases are anodic with respect to the matrix and can corrode and/or provide a path for environmentally enhanced cracking. However, the mechanisms behind this cracking and the morphology it takes are less well known. In this study, interrupted tensile tests, microscopy, and tomography are used to observe how damage development in tensile specimens is affected by sensitization in samples from the Short-Transverse (ST) direction of 5083-H131 rolled plates.

1244.prez_name: Shear Band Corrosion Susceptibility in Al 6061 Extruded by Equal Channel Angular Extrusion (ECAP)
1244.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1244.prez_abstract: Formation of adiabatic shear bands during processing of Al 6061 by ECAP is common and difficult to avoid. It can be considered as a new interface or boundary between the refined equiaxe grains and the elongated grain along the shear direction. Our research investigates the influence of adiabatic shear bands in the spreading and propagation of intergranular corrosion of Al 6061 after ECAP and post ageing. The intergranular corrosion susceptibility of the shear bands was assessed by the standardized test ISO 11840 Method B, coupled with Secondary Electron Microscopy (SEM) images and Secondary Ions Mass Spectroscopy (SIMS) analysis.

1245.prez_name: Solid Silver Embrittlement of Ti-6Al-2Sn-4Zr-2Mo Alloy
1245.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1245.prez_authors: Jingjing  Qing, Mario  F. Buchely, David C.  Van Aken, Michael  A. Walker, Royle W Juusola, John E Goethe
1245.prez_abstract: Silver plated fasteners are commonly used throughout the aircraft/aerospace industry due to its lubricating properties and aesthetics.  However, it is usually avoided due to the potential for solid metal embrittlement(SME) in many structural materials. SME of Ti-6Al-2Sn-4Zr-2Mo alloy due to silver at high temperatures was investigated in this study.  Experiments were designed and conducted to obtain time/temperature/failure data for Ti-6Al-2Sn-4Zr-2Mo alloy.  Transverse and longitudinal directions of rolling direction of Ti alloy were compared. High purity silver was pressed against the Ti specimen with two steel plates held together by two pressure bolts. Effect of torque applied on the pressure bolts on failure time was studied. Intergranular grain boundary decoherence was observed next to the silver on the fracture surface, indicating brittle failure of the Ti alloy. Microvoids observed in the area away from silver contact side on the fracture surface implied ductile failure of the material.

1246.prez_name: Solution Heat Treatment on Mechanical Properties and Corrosion of Extruded Mg5Gd Compared To Pure Mg
1246.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1246.prez_authors: Petra  Maier, Maximilian  Bechly, Norbert  Hort
1246.prez_abstract: This study focuses on the influence of solution heat treatment on mechanical properties and corrosion by immersion of extruded Mg5Gd. The results are compared to pure Mg. Since Mg5Gd can be considered as a biodegradable magnesium alloy, Ringer solution has been chosen for immersion tests. Hardness, tension and compression tests reveal a loss in strength by solution heat treatment resulting from strong grain growth and dissolved second phases. The addition of the alloying element Gd improves the corrosion behavior, there is no pitting corrosion found. The pure Mg extrusion bars in comparison have a higher corrosion rate and show strong pitting. The corrosion morphology is described by the pitting factor. Even there is less anodic-cathodic microgalvanic coupling because of dissolved second phases, solution heat treatment does not improve the corrosion behavior of Mg5Gd much, making the strong grain growth responsible for that. However, also Mg5Gd-T4 is free of pitting corrosion.

1247.prez_name: Strain Hardening in Beta Annealed Ti-6Al-4V Alloy
1247.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1247.prez_authors: Stephen  Masete, Kalenda  Mutombo, Roelf  Mostert, Charles  Siyasiya
1247.prez_abstract: A combination of high strain hardening exponent, strain hardening rate as well as a high uniform plastic strain is needed for performance and formability of aerospace parts. This work reports the strain hardening properties of the beta annealed (solution treated above the beta transus temperature) Ti-6Al-4V alloy. The alloy was solution treated above the β-transus temperature and either water quenched or furnace cooled, and subsequently aged. The tensile strain hardening properties were determined through tensile testing. The strain hardening rate and the strain hardening exponent of the specimens that were solution treated and water quenched were higher than those of the solution treated and furnace cooled specimens. However, ageing of the solution treated and furnace cooled specimens produced the highest strain hardening exponent and strength coefficient. The increase in the volume fraction of the β-phase was found to increase the strain hardening exponent and the strain hardening rate.

1248.prez_name: Strain State Effects of Sensitization-induced β Precipitates in AA5456
1248.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1248.prez_abstract: Aluminum alloys in the 5xxx series are known to sensitize at relatively low temperatures due to the precipitation of the anodic β and β' phases at the grain boundaries. Sensitization results in the increased susceptibility to stress corrosion cracking, as well as a general degradation of mechanical properties. Understanding how these precipitates contribute to the overall strain state will allow for a fuller understanding of the modes of failure in these alloys. Samples of AA5456 with the H116 temper were aged at low temperature (100°C) to grow the metastable, semi-coherent β' phase, and at high temperature (250°C) for the incoherent β-equilibrium phase. Precession electron diffraction was then utilized to map the matrix strain surrounding both types of precipitates, as well as other features such as dislocations, in order to form a general picture of the strain state in these alloys after sensitization.

1249.prez_name: Structure and Properties Of Consolidated Gas-atomized Magnesium Alloy Powders
1249.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1249.prez_authors: R  Sadangi, D  Kapoor, T F Zahrah
1249.prez_abstract: Powder Metallurgy (PM) processed conventional magnesium alloys show properties that exceed those obtained by conventional ingot metallurgy. Starting with commercially available gas-atomized powders, the two-step consolidation process comprises of (a) Hot Isostatic Pressing (HIP), and (b) Extrusion. The HIP-ed materials show prior-particle boundaries and inhomogeneous microstructure, essentially retaining the solidification-induced segregation of the atomized powder. The as HIP-ed materials display inferior mechanical properties because the prior-particle boundaries provide path for easy crack propagation. Extruded structures show improved microstructure homogeneity via redistribution of prior particle boundaries. Significant improvements in both strength and ductility is observed in the extruded material. This paper describes the structure and properties of PM- processed magnesium alloys.

1250.prez_name: Study of Constant and Variable Blank Holding Force Techniques in Hydroforming of Cryorolled Al-Mg Alloy Sheets by FE Simulation
1250.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1250.prez_authors: Fitsum Taye Feyissa, Ravi Kumar Digavalli
1250.prez_abstract: Cryorolling is a severe plastic deformation technique to enhance strength of Al alloys but it leads to reduction in ductility and formability. Hydroforming is an important manufacturing process to enhance formability of lightweight materials such as Al alloys. Process parameters affect product quality in hydroforming. This study mainly focuses on comparison of constant and variable blank holding force techniques by finite element analysis and their effect on formability of high strength cryorolled Al-Mg alloy (AA 5083) sheets in hydroforming of square cups. Experimentally determined material properties of cryorolled and annealed Al-Mg alloy have been used in simulations. Effect of coefficient of friction has also been studied. By using constant and variable blank holding force techniques, strain distribution, percentage of thinning and geometrical accuracy have been analyzed. Keywords: Cryorolling, Hydroforming, Lightweight metals, Formability, Blank Holding Force.

1251.prez_name: Study on Microstructure and Properties of Low Concentration Al-V Alloy
1251.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1251.prez_abstract: As a vital alloying element, the Vanadium not only can improve the hardness and tensile strength of aluminum alloy, but also can improve the corrosion resistance. So the Vanadium added as a alloying element to the pure aluminum is studied in this article. The smelten aluminum works as liquid reduction agent to produce Al-V alloy which containing small amount of V. The influence of V on the microstructure and mechanical properties of the alloy is studied by optical microscopy (OM)、 Scanning electronic microscopy (SEM)、 mechanical properties testing.

1252.prez_name: Study on Refinement and Homogenization of Microstructures of Aluminium Alloys Billet by Pulse and Magnetic Treatment
1252.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1252.prez_authors: Kyunghyun  Kim, Mykola  Slazhniev, Hyunsuk  Sim, Sewon  Kim
1252.prez_abstract: The high strength aluminum alloys is necessary to develop the lightweight of automobile parts for fuel efficiency and CO2 reduction. This alloys are poor in formability because heterogeneous microstructure and casting defects by addition of many solute elements. The microstructure should be fined and homogeneous to improve extrudability of this alloy. Billet by DC process shows the dendrite and heterogeneous microstructure and it is difficult to produce high quality billet because defects and segregation occurs during casting process. The microstructures and intermetallic compound becomes fine and homogeneous when pulses and magnetic process are applied to molten aluminum. Researching application the direct pulses and magnetic processing of the Al-Zn-Mg-Cu of this alloy allowed perform the reducing of the microstructure grain size from 550μm up to 90μm. This processing aluminum alloys are increased extrusion speed without crack and it is possible to improve the productivity of high strength aluminum alloys.

1253.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1253.prez_authors: Anthony J Barnes, David  Edwards, Simon  Miller-Jupp
1253.prez_abstract: Although used in production for more than forty years superplastic forming (SPF) continuous to advance with stronger, stiffer and lighter structures. SPF's remarkable ability to form complex single piece components that defy the capabilities of other more 'conventional' forming techniques yields both functional and cost competitive benefits. These attributes are leading to ever increasing use of this remarkable technology in both the automotive and aerospace industries, where the 'light weighting' advantages of SPF aluminum, magnesium and titanium alloys results in elegant solutions to other wise obdurate design challenges. This presentation highlights recent advances in SPF technology including alloy developments, process improvements through the application of robotics and automation and the prospect of greater use of superplastic magnesium alloys.

1254.prez_name: Tensile Behavior  and Microstructural Characteristics of Friction Stir Welded Butt joints of Titanium Alloys
1254.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1254.prez_authors: Laxminarayana  Pappula, Kapil    Gangwara, Ashok Kumar  Uppari, Ramulu  M
1254.prez_abstract: The work deals with FSW of three titanium alloys i.e., ATI-425, TIMET-54M, and Ti-6Al-4V with typicalα and β phases in base metal. Parameters were rotational and traverse speeds. Defect free welds were obtained under processing conditions at 300 RPM and 100 mm/ min. FSW produced Widmanstätten morphology in the weld nugget (WN) for all cases except Ti-6Al-4V, demonstrating the temperatures reaching par β transus in WN. All the monotonically loaded tensile test revealed that the fracture occurred in the WN, for ATI-425; in the base material for TIMET-54M; and in the retreating side HAZ/TMAZ forTi-6Al-4V in this study. The HAZ and TMAZ for TIMET-54M, and Ti-6Al-4V consist of refined bimodal, and equiaxed α grains. HAZ, for ATI-425 results in refined equiaxed α infused with β. Hardness increased in WN for all cases; presence of HAZ is marked by the drop in the hardness values because of recrystallized grains in HAZ.

1255.prez_name: The Role of Zn Additions on the Microstructure and Mechanical Properties of Mg-Nd-Zn Alloys
1255.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1255.prez_authors: Serge  Gavras, Domonkos   Tolnai, Tungky   Subroto, Ricardo  Buzolin, Norbert  Hort
1255.prez_abstract: Mg-rare earth (Mg-RE) alloys have improved yield strength and creep resistance compared to commercial alloys such as AZ91, AM60 or AS21. The combination of RE and Zn additions further enhances the mechanical properties. However, the influence of Zn additions on intermetallic phases and the resulting changes in the macroscopic mechanical behaviour of the materials, specifically Mg-Nd alloys, is not fully understood yet. The aim of this work is to identify the effect of Zn additions on the nature of the intermetallic phases and on the mechanical properties in a Mg-5Nd(wt.%) alloy. The mechanical properties of the alloys have been investigated by room- and elevated-temperature tensile and compression tests. Two intermetallic phases, a quasi-binary Mg3(Zn,Nd) and ternary Mg50Nd8Zn42, have been identified by the means of synchrotron diffraction and electron microscopy. These results indicate there are some discrepancies in the current thermodynamic calculations, suggesting an update to the databases might be required.

1256.prez_name: TiO2 and ZrO2 Controlled Crystallization and Microstructure in SiO2-MgO-Al2O3-B2O3-K2O-F Glass
1256.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1256.prez_abstract: The crystallization concert and microstructural evolution of SiO2-MgO-Al2O3-K2O-B2O3-F glasses with excess nucleating agent CeO2, TiO2 and ZrO2 content (5 mol%), were studied. Opaque mica glass-ceramics were prepared from such glasses by controlled heat-treatment at 1050°C; and the evolved phases are identified as fluorophlogopite mica, KMg3(AlSi3O10)F2 by XRD study. The flurophlogopite mica crystallization is improved in presence of TiO2 and ZrO2 nucleating agents. As observed from FESEM study, the glass-ceramic morphology with hexagonal card like mica-flake crystals restructured to be interlocked in presence of ZrO2 content. Nanocrystalline microstructure is obtained in presence of CeO2 content. As obtained from dilatometry, highest thermal expansion coefficient (greater than 12 x10-6/K, at 50-800) is observed in ZrO2 containing (5 mol%) glass-ceramic, and it is compatible with other SOFC components. So, ZrO2 containing SiO2-MgO-Al2O3-K2O-B2O3-F glass can be useful for SOFC sealing application.

1257.prez_name: Ultrafine-/Nano-laminated Structure Improving Mechanical Properties in an Al-Mg Alloy
1257.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1257.prez_authors: Yaojun  Lin, Zhibo  Liu, Zhigang  Yan
1257.prez_abstract: Recently, ultrafine-/nano-laminated microstructures have attracted considerable interest due to its ultra-high strength. In this talk, we present mechanical properties of an Al-Mg alloy 5083 (Al-4.5Mg-0.7Mn-0.15Cr, wt.%) containing ultrafine-/nano-laminated microstructures. The ultrafine-/nano-laminated 5083 Al was produced by cryogenic rolling plus subsequent annealing. Our results indicate that the as-rolled materials entirely comprise ultrafine-/nano-laminated microstructures with lamellar width from 20 to 150 nm. After annealing, recrystallization occurred in a portion of lamellae, forming nanostructured and ultra-fine grains of 80 to 250 nm, but the lamellar structure was still retained in the other portion of lamellae. The as-rolled 5083 Al exhibits the tensile yield strength and ductility comparable to those in nanostructured 5083 Al produced by consolidation of nanostructured powders. After annealing, the 5083 Al achieves a combination of high strength and ductility: tensile yield strength 435 MPa and uniform elongation 11%. The mechanisms underlying the high strength and ductility are discussed.

1258.prez_name: Ultrasonic Vibration Assisted Laser Surface Melting Of Al 2024 Alloys and Its Influence on Microstructural Evolution
1258.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1258.prez_authors: Sourabh  Biswas, Seyyed Habib  Alavi, Sandip P. Harimkar
1258.prez_abstract: Laser surface melting (LSM) of Al-alloys and its implications on the microstructural evolution has been extensively studied. It has often been reported that LSM results in a highly refined but dendritic microstructure. In this study, influence of ultrasonic vibrations (USV) in dendrite fragmentation during LSM of 2024 Al alloys was investigated. It was observed that USV results in significant improvement in grain refinement of both the primary α and intermetallic θ phases. The microstructural investigations also confirmed that USV results in shift in resolidified grain morphology post laser processing. The LSM specimen processed without USV was observed to exhibit cellular grains while the USV-LSM specimen exhibited dendritic grains. Finally, the reduction in texturing was also reflected in the x-ray diffraction analysis indicating marked reduction in preferred orientation of the grains in the USV assisted LSM specimen compared to the textured grains observed in the non-vibrated counterpart.

1259.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1259.prez_abstract: The grain refinement of aluminum by adding Al-Ti-B type master alloys is discussed in view of heterogeneous nucleation of alpha-aluminum grains. Proposed mechanisms are summarized in addition to the findings of this research. It is generally agreed that alpha-aluminum grains formed through heterogeneous nucleation on stable TiB2 particles that are covered by Al3Ti. However, a consensus is yet to be reached due to the lack of observation of a thin layer of Al3Ti on TiB2 particles after grain refinement reactions. Our findings lead to a balanced mechanism, in which a dynamic layer of Al3Ti forms in cooling and causes the nucleation of alpha-aluminum grains. This dynamic nucleation mechanism explains the heterogeneous nucleation of aluminum grains and, in the same time, avoiding the formation of large blocky Al3Ti-TiB2 compounded particles. The findings have broad implications from the casting of aluminum to other processes of aluminum alloys containing titanium and boron.

1260.prez_name: Understanding Homogenous Nucleation Mechanisms in Solidification of Aluminum by Million-atom Molecular Dynamics Simulations
1260.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1260.prez_authors: Avik  Mahata, Mohsen  Asle Zaeem, Michael  Baskes
1260.prez_abstract: Homogeneous nucleation from undercooled fcc aluminum (Al) melt is investigated by million-atom molecular dynamics simulations utilizing the second nearest neighbor modified embedded atom method interatomic potentials. Both isothermal and quenching processes are applied to study the nucleation process. The maximum nucleation rate is found to be 5.74x 1035 m-3s-1 at the critical temperature of nucleation of 475 K. Three different thermal nucleation regimes are identified: i) unstable nucleation (> 730 K), ii) stable nucleation (700-730 K), and iii) nuclei growth (< 700 K) regions. The Al atoms solidify as fcc/hcp crystals directly from the melt and the solidified fcc Al exhibits hcp staking faults.  By slowing down the cooling rate, the volume fraction of hcp and amorphous phases decreased. After the box was completely solid, grain growth was simulated for 4500 ps. The grain growth exponent was determined for different annealing temperatures, and results show good agreement with experimental data.

1261.prez_name: Vertical Section Phase Diagram of  Mg (1-X) Sr0.5 ZnX Alloy Using Solidification Cooling Curves
1261.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1261.prez_abstract: Among the Magnesium based alloys, the mechanical properties of the Magnesium (Mg) - Zinc (Zn) based alloys can be effectively improved through heat treatment due to their pronounced age hardening effect. Strontium (Sr) is one of the major micro alloying addition to the Mg-Zn alloys, to obtain the promising high temperature and creep properties. However, creep resistant of an material also depends on the types of precipitates or compounds  and the stability of precipitates or compounds and phases present over the range of operating temperatures. Here we present the novel vertical phase section diagram of Mg (1-X) Sr0.5 ZnX (X = 0 - 18 at.%), constructed using cooling curve measurements. Different phases which are not reported in the past is experimentally identified and corroborated with Differential Scanning Calorimetry, X Ray Diffraction analysis for crystal structure identification and Scanning electron microscopy equipped with an energy-dispersive spectroscope for microstructural and compositions identification.

1262.prez_name: Warm Temperature (170-280°C) Uniaxial Compression of SiC Reinforced 2124-Al MMCs
1262.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1262.prez_authors: Zizo  Gxowa, Lesley H. Chown, Gonasagren  Govender
1262.prez_abstract: This work evaluates the effect of warm temperature (170-280°C) uniaxial compression on the deformation behaviour of SiC reinforced Metal Matrix Composites (MMCs). Green and sintered compacts (d=8mm, h=12mm) were produced by blending 2124-Al with SiC (10 or 15 vol. %) powders in a high energy ball mill, cold (i.e.ambient temperature) compaction and sintering at 490°C for 1hr. Warm temperature uniaxial compression tests were performed on a Gleeble 3500® at strain rates of 0.01s<SUP>-1</SUP> and 5s<SUP>-1</SUP> and constant strain of 0.3. Engineering stress-strain curves showed that the best deformation was achieved when sintered MMC compacts were uniaxially compressed at 280°C and strain rate of 5s<SUP>-1</SUP> using a soaking time of 20min.The best deformation was achieved in the 2124-Al with 10%SiC compact since it plastically deformed at a higher, constant stress of ~153MPa up to the maximum strain of 0.3.

1263.prez_name: X-Ray Computed Tomography – An Enabling Tool for Casting Process Cognition Development and Improvement
1263.symp_name: Light Metals Alliance: Light Metals Technology 2017
1263.prez_authors: Ning  Sun, Chen  Dai, Vijay  Alreja, Diran  Apelian
1263.prez_abstract: Modern foundries are striving to find ways to use vast amounts of production data to support knowledge-based systems that can provide closed-loop feedback to enhance the cast product quality by elimination of casting defects.  Detection of internal defects, such as porosity, by NDE techniques is a critical element in the process to provide rapid product quality feedback to the system.  Advanced computed tomography (CT) have greatly improved the capability and efficiency of detection and reconstruction of defects in Al castings. In this study, porosity in a HPDC was investigated using 3D X-ray CT imaging technology. The impact of critical operation parameters on data output, such as size, volume fraction, and spatial distribution of porosity is demonstrated. These data, along with floor operation and processing details, and models of the casting and solidification processes, will be integral components of a data fusion framework for continuous process learning to mitigate casting defects.

1376.prez_name: Hot Rolling Effect upon the High Temperature Johnson-Cook Strength and Failure Models for a 15V38 Grade Steel
1376.prez_authors: Mario  Buchely, David  Van Aken, Ronald  O'Malley, K.  Chandrashekhara, Simon  Lekakh
1376.prez_abstract: A commercially produced 15V38 grade steel (0.38C, 1.3Mn, 0.57Si, 0.13Cr, 0.08V) was studied in the cast and hot-rolled condition. Mechanical testing was performed using a hydraulic load frame specifically adapted to perform tensile tests at different temperatures (up to 1300C) and different strain-rates (up to 20s-1). Plastic flow behavior and the strain at failure of the steel were modeled using the Johnson-Cook Strength model and the Johnson-Cook Failure model. The material’s model was implemented in ANSYS-AUTODYN to replicate the tensile experiments. The accuracy of each material curve was determined by comparing the experimental data with the FEA results. It was found that FEM simulation predicts the deformation of the material during the tensile test at medium strain-rates and temperatures; therefore, these models can be implemented to simulate deformation processes, such as hot metal rolling. Hot-rolled material shows higher properties and more consistent failure data comparing to the as-cast material.

1434.prez_name: A Study on High Energy Ball Milling and Spark Plasma Sintering of Fe-9Cr Model Alloys
1434.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1434.prez_abstract: Iron and chromium powders are milled together for different durations (2, 5, 8, 10, 12, 15 and 20 h) at varying %Cr. Powder characteristics such as crystallite size, lattice strain and powder size are evaluated. The 10 h milled powder was consolidated via spark plasma sintering at 850, 950 and 1050 oC for different dwell times. Consolidation was done on hybrid mixtures for creating a bimodal distribution of grain size.  Effects of sintering parameters on densification, hardness and grain size are evaluated. The grain size increased with increasing sintering temperature and dwell time. This work is first expected to lead to understanding of a simple Fe-Cr system and will then be expanded to more complex oxide dispersion strengthened alloy systems keeping the Fe-9Cr as the base matrix. The work is supported by the Idaho National Laboratory and the Center for Advanced Energy Studies.

1435.prez_name: Alane by Mechanochemical Metathesis: Reaction Control by Inert Solids, Liquids and Gases
1435.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1435.prez_authors: Shalabh  Gupta, Ihor  Hlova, Takeshi  Kobayashi, Jennifer  Goldston, Marek  Pruski, Vitalij  Pecharsky
1435.prez_abstract: Solid-state mechanochemistry is a successful and efficient way to synthesize alane (AlH3). However, the commonly used ether-free version of Schlesinger reaction (SR), in which alkali-metal hydride or alanate undergoes an exchange reaction with aluminum halide, present some interesting sensitivities to the reaction conditions such as  temperature and intensity of milling, and presence of “process control agents”. Unlike SR, the solvent-free reaction produces adduct-free alane, but the reaction must either be carried out at cryogenic temperature or at considerably reduced rate to prevent any parallel reactions. These side reactions can be effectively prevented by applying pressure from inert gases like He and Ar without compromising the reaction rate. Furthermore, similar results are achieved when the reaction is performed at ambient pressure with small amounts of inert liquids such as hexane. Such nuances, and the results of investigation of other metathesis reactions potentially leading to alane will be discussed in this presentation.

1436.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II

1437.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1437.prez_abstract: Mechanocatalysis or facilitation of catalysis through the application of mechanical force in a ball mill offers the potential for realizing increased catalytic rates and novel reaction pathways. The implementation of catalysis in a mechanochemical reactor requires an understanding of the mechanical behavior of a catalyst as well as the desired surface reactions. Very high transient pressures (upwards of 6000 bar) and high shear facilitate catalysis through defect formation and limited heating. Defects can be introduced into h-BN, MoS2, and δ-MoN forming dh-BN, d-MoS2, and dδ-MoN through grinding. We found good olefin hydrogenation rates over dh-BN, production of methanol from syngas over unpromoted d-MoS2 and the potential for ammonia synthesis over dδ-MoN. Challenges to scale-up are mitigated in a mechanocatalytic reactor since reactions only occur at each impact. These reactions are really massively parallel microreactions with the thermal control achievable on a small scale and the throughput desired for industrial implementation.

1438.prez_name: Developing a Better Understanding of Mechanochemical Reactions
1438.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1438.prez_authors: James  Mack, Kendra  Leahy, Rebecca  Haley, Joel   Andersen
1438.prez_abstract: Solvent has been considered a necessity in chemical reactions since the days of Aristotle. Even today it is believed that reactions conducted in solution are faster, more efficient and show greater reproducibility than those in the solid state. Because of this, chemists have been trained to use solution phase chemistry in organic synthesis to such an extent that solvent-free chemistry is not considered. However, due to increasing interest in environmental protection and waste minimization, solvent-free chemistry has recently gained momentum. Ball milling or mechanochemistry has been developed as a solvent-free technique that is a viable alternative to solution phase chemistry. Mechanochemistry has been demonstrated to be equally fast, efficient and as reproducible as solution phase chemistry. The seminar presentation will uncover some of the mysteries of mechanochemistry, where some chemical reactions are the same as in solution and some quite different.

1439.prez_name: Effect of Ball Milling on the Hydrogen Storage Properties of TiFe Alloy Doped with 4wt.% ZrMn2 Additive
1439.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1439.prez_abstract: In this paper, we report the microstructure and hydrogen storage properties of TiFe+4  wt.%ZrMn2 alloy before and after high energy milling. Milling times were 15, 30, and 60 minutes. The as-cast alloy is made of two phases: a TiFe matrix and a zirconium and manganese–rich secondary phase. We found that, after 15 minutes of milling there is an important reduction of particle size but further milling has minimal effect. In the same way, crystallite size was reduced after 15 minutes of milling time but no further reduction for higher milling time. Hydrogenation measurement showed that milling for 15 minutes leads to s slightly faster absorption kinetics but was detrimental to the hydrogen capacity. Further milling had for effect of making the sample totally inert to hydrogen. Possible reasons why prolonged milling is detrimental to hydrogen absorption for this system will be discussed.

1440.prez_name: Electrical Properties of  Lnx Y0.04 Zr0.96-x O2-δ Ceramics Synthesized by Mechanical Milling
1440.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1440.prez_authors: Carlos A.   Durón-Sifuentes, José Alonso  Díaz-Guillén, Madelyne  Salazar-Zertuche, María Elena   Bazaldua-Medellín, Oswaldo   Burciaga-Diaz, Nayeli M.  Cepeda-Sanchez, Antonio   F. Fuentes
