1440.prez_abstract: This work reports results of mechanochemical synthesis and electrical properties of phases with general formula LnxY0.04Zr0.96-xO2-δ  (Ln = Er and Dy, x = 0.02, 0.05 and 0.1) on views to be applied as solid electrolytes in Solid Oxides Fuel Cells. Samples were synthesized by mechanical milling, by using a planetary mill and zirconia containers and balls, and starting from mixtures of corresponding oxides. Evolution of samples with milling time was followed by XRD at different time intervals; reactions were considered completed when no traces of the starting reagents were evident by this technique. Synthesized powders were also characterized by SEM and thermal analysis, among others. Ionic conductivity and activation energies for oxygen ion diffusion were determined by impedance spectroscopy. Results show that these materials can be successfully obtained after 20 hours of milling, and after be fired at 1500°C, show good electrical properties, similar to those obtained for ionic conductors.

1441.prez_name: Electrical Properties of LaPO4/La2Zr2O7 Composites Synthesized by the Molten Salt Method Assisted by Mechanical Milling
1441.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1441.prez_authors: Madelyne  Salazar-Zertuche, José Alonso  Díaz-Guillén, Carlos A.   Durón-Sifuentes, Oswaldo   Burciaga-Diaz, María Elena   Bazaldua-Medellín, Antonio   F. Fuentes
1441.prez_abstract: This work reports results of synthesis and evaluation of electrical properties of a new group of composites with general formula LaPO4/La2Zr2O7 (weight ratios 100-0, 75-25, 50-50,25-75  and 0-100) on views to be applied as components in Solid Oxide Fuel Cells (SOFC). Each composite was synthesized (phosphate and zirconate in the same process) by the molten salt method, preceded by a metathesis reaction induced by mechanical milling, by using a planetary mill and starting from nitrates of involved elements and Na2HPO4. Synthesized powders were characterized by XRD, SEM and thermal analysis, among others. Ionic conductivity and activation energies for oxygen ion diffusion were determined by impedance spectroscopy. Results show that these materials can be successfully obtained after 1 hour of milling followed by a molten salt process at 500°C during 3 hours. Analysis of electrical properties reveals that these materials show interesting electrical properties, similar to those obtained for ionic conductors.

1442.prez_name: Forced Mixing and Nanostructuration in Metallic Alloys Subjected to Severe Plastic Deformation
1442.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1442.prez_authors: Pascal  Bellon, Robert S Averback, Nisha  Verma, John  Beach, Nirab  Pant, Qun  Li, Xuekun  Shang, Juilia  Ivanisenko
1442.prez_abstract: Severe plastic deformation (SPD) has become an important route for the processing of materials, in particular for synthesizing nanostructures. In moderately immiscible alloy systems, e.g., Cu-Ag, plastic co-deformation results in forced chemical mixing, which, at elevated temperature, competes with the decomposition driven by thermodynamic forces. This competition results in the stabilization of self-organized nanostructures. In other alloy systems, e.g., Cu-Mo, severe plastic deformation fails to fully mix these elements into solution, even at low temperatures where thermal diffusion is negligible. We investigate the origins of this limitation by subjecting Cu-base binary and ternary alloy systems, with varied heats of mixing and mechanical properties, to severe plastic deformation by ball milling and high pressure torsion at low temperature. We show that the high heat of mixing in these alloys is the determinant factor limiting solubility, but surprisingly, that SPD still leads to self-organized, nanoscale patterns of composition.

1443.prez_name: Formation of Refractory Metal Borides during Mechanical Alloying
1443.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II

1444.prez_name: From Molecules to Hybrid Materials by Ball-milling
1444.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II

1445.prez_name: Information on the Mechanism of Mechanochemical Reactions Based on Detailed Studies of the Reaction Kinetics
1445.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1445.prez_abstract: Mechanochemical synthesis takes place in a ball mill, where the heavy walls of the milling container make in situ process monitoring and testing very difficult. However, some information on mechanism and microscopic parameters can be obtained by carefully analyzing and modeling the macroscopic kinetics obtained under suitable control of the mechanical processing conditions and combining the results with a the ex-situ characterization of the processed material. Quantities such as the average amount of powder caught and processed between the colliding milling tools and the minimum impact energy required to induce structural and chemical changes in the impacted powder can be deduced. The kinetic parameters of the reaction can be determined and used to infer the reaction mechanism. The ignition time of mechanically induced self-propagating reactions and its variation with material properties and milling conditions can also provide clues about the reaction mechanism.

1446.prez_name: Investigation on Mechanochemical Behaviour of the Al-Ti-Nb System
1446.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1446.prez_abstract: This work investigates the mechanochemical behaviour of aluminium-titanium-niobium powder mixture. The Nb-Ti-Al alloy was prepared by mechanical alloying. Milling was performed in a high-energy planetary ball mill under Ar atmosphere. The phase transformation and structural evaluation were investigated by means X-ray diffractometry and scanning electron microscopy (SEM). The thermal behavour was determined by differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) technique. In addition, the mechanical property of the Nb-Ti-Al alloy is also investigated.

1447.prez_name: Kesterite Cu2ZnSnS4: Mechanochemical Synthesis of Solar Cell Absorber in Scalable Amounts
1447.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1447.prez_authors: Peter  Baláž, Matej  Baláž, Marcela  Achimovičová, Michal  Hegedüs, Matej  Tešínsky, Nina  Daneu, Erika  Dutková, Mária  Kaňuchová
1447.prez_abstract: Until now, chalcogenide solar cell absorbers have been prepared by numerous processes such as electrochemical deposition, sol-gel, electron beam evaporation, etc. However, mechanochemical solid-state approach proves to be faster, eco-friendly, and low-cost in contrast to other processes. The present study demonstrates a scalable approach towards the pure kesterite (Cu2ZnSnS4) phase using elemental precursors (Cu, Zn, Sn and S). Pure kesterite was obtained after 360 minutes in an industrial vibration mill. The kinetics of reactions was analyzed by a Soxhlet extraction of unreacted sulfur. The results of the XPS analysis showed the presence of Cu2+, Zn2+, Sn4+ and S2- species.  Based on UV-Vis measurements, the bandgap Eg = 1.15 eV was calculated, which is acceptable for application in solar cells.The applied mechanochemical approach can produce 100-500 grams of product in one batch mode experiment, which is 10-100 times higher amount in comparison with the same product obtained in laboratory planetary mills.

1448.prez_name: Magnesiothermic MASHS of Zirconium and Hafnium Diborides
1448.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1448.prez_abstract: Materials based on diborides of zirconium and hafnium s(ZrB2 and HfB2) are promising for ultrahigh-temperature applications such as leading edge in hypersonic vehicles and electrodes of MHD generators. Self-propagating high-temperature synthesis (SHS) is attractive for the fabrication of such materials because of low energy consumption, short process times, high purity of products, and low cost of equipment. SHS of ZrB2 and HfB2 from elements is well known, but it is not suitable for large-scale fabrication because of high costs of raw materials. Magnesiothermic SHS involves reduction of their oxides by magnesium and it is more economically viable. However, the reacting mixtures are low-exothermic and it is difficult to ignite them. Also, it is hard to achieve full conversion of oxides to borides. Here, we report the results of using mechanical activation for improving magnesiothermic SHS of ZrB2 and HfB2.

1449.prez_name: Magnetic Behavior of Nanostructured Oxides Prepared by Mechanochemical Synthesis
1449.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1449.prez_abstract:
Surface effects are of course crucial in governing the functional properties and potential applications of nanostructures, including those prepared by mechanochemical synthesis. In the present work, selected examples of the magnetic behavior of nanostructured oxides prepared by mechanosynthesis are presented, which are discussed in terms of a competition between the effects of spin canting and nonequilibrium cation distribution in the near-surface layers of nanoparticles. Based on comparative spectroscopic (Mössbauer, NMR, Raman, XPS) studies of oxide nanoparticles of various chemical compositions and the corresponding bulk counterparts, an attempt is made to separate surface effects from bulk effects in oxide nanoparticles.
The work is supported by the DFG (project SE 1407/4-1), the VEGA (2/0097/14) and the Visegrad Group (V4)-Japan Joint Research Program “Structure – function relationship of advanced nanooxides for energy storage devices (AdOX)” granted from the Visegrad Fund and the Japan Science and Technology Agency.

1450.prez_name: Mechanochemical Activation in the M-Si-Al-O-N System: Advantages and Drawbacks
1450.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II

1451.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1451.prez_authors: Oleg S Lagoviyer, Mirko  Schoenitz, Edward  Dreizin
1451.prez_abstract: Nitration of toluene is necessary to produce TNT, a popular energetic material.  The conventional nitration process uses a mixture of concentrated sulfuric and nitric acids as nitrating agents and multiple solvents.  The chemicals are corrosive and require special handling and disposal procedures. Undesired byproducts are generated.  This work is aimed to develop a mechanochemical process of producing nitrotoluene with environmentally benign solid precursors and without solvents.  The focus is on preparing mononitrotoluene (MNT).  MNT was synthesized by milling toluene with sodium nitrate and molybdenum trioxide as a Lewis acid catalyst.  While byproducts were generated, the selectivity of the MNT production was controlled by milling conditions. The selectivity also increased at higher yields of MNT.  Parameters affecting the desired product yield and selectivity were identified and varied, including milling intensity and temperature.  Experimental results will be presented and possible mechanisms of the mechanochemical reaction of nitration of toluene will be discussed.

1452.prez_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Characterization of Digenite, Cu1.8S
1452.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1452.prez_authors: Matej  Baláž, Anna  Zorkovská, Nina  Daneu, Erika  Dutková, Jaroslav  Briančin, Mária  Kaňuchová, Zdenka  Bujňáková, Peter  Baláž
1452.prez_abstract: In the present study, an effort to synthesize non-stoichiometric copper sulfides from elemental precursors was made. However, it was possible only to obtain digenite, Cu1.8S, despite milling Cu:S mixtures with different stoichiometries. The reaction proceeds in an explosive manner, when milled on air and the product is formed within a second range. In addition to digenite, also a small amount of covellite impurity is formed. The most pure digenite was obtained immediately after the explosion and further milling favors the formation of covellite. After 15 minutes of milling, 76% of digenite and 24% of covellite was present. The obtained final product was characterized by a vast number of characterization methods (XRD, SEM, EDS, TEM, SAD, N2 adsorption, UV-VIS, PL, ZP measurements, PCCS and XPS) and its nanocrystalline character was confirmed.  The present work is a contribution to the expanding field of copper sulfides applied as photothermal agents in medicine.

1453.prez_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis of Lanthanide Hafnates: Influence of Different Cation Substitutions on the Structural Characteristics and Electrical Properties of Gd2Hf2O7
1453.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1453.prez_authors: Nayeli M. Cepeda-Sánchez, José Alonso Díaz-Guillén, Miroslaw  Maczka, Ulises  Amador,
1453.prez_abstract: Lanthanide hafnates Ln2Hf2O7, crystallize either with the fluorite or the pyrochlore structures; they belong to a group of oxides, showing a rich variety of intriguing physicochemical properties of fundamental, and practical interest; indeed, such properties are very much affected by defects and disorder. Furthermore, defect concentration in any particular phase is determined by both, intrinsic (e.g., bonding character, size mismatch), and extrinsic factors (e.g., processing conditions). This contribution presents a systematic study of the structural characteristics, and electrical properties of different samples with the general formula Gd2-yLnyHf2-xBxO7 (B = Ti, Zr, Sn; Ln = Eu, Sm), and obtained by mechanically milling stochiometric mixtures of the corresponding elemental oxides. As-prepared samples as well as powders milled and fired at different temperatures, were analyzed by using XRD (Rietveld method) and Raman spectroscopy; whereas, electrical properties were analyzed by using impedance spectroscopy, as a function of temperature and frequency.

1454.prez_name: Mechanochemically Initiated Polymerizations: Solvent-free Enolate-mediated Reactions of Cellulose in a Ball Mill
1454.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1454.prez_abstract: In the present work, we primarily focus our efforts on a solvent-free nucleophilic addition reaction in a ball mill. We demonstrate that the reaction can proceed with high efficiency and selectivity on the structure of cellulose as a consequence of the enolization. Alkali metal hydroxides are used to catalyze the enolization reaction of cellulose and a model compound of D-glucose in a lab-scale planetary ball mill. Then, a series of model compound of electrophiles having saturated aliphatic hydrocarbons are utilized to fulfill the reaction. With the support of FTIR, NMR, XPS and TGA techniques, we will describe solvent-free procedures, mechanisms and characterization of obtained products. For example, using FTIR, results led us to identify characteristic bands of methyl, aliphatic hydrocarbons and the imine bond in the conjugated systems. In turn, thermogravimetric analysis of the product has shown a notable thermal stability in comparison with raw materials.

1455.prez_name: Mechanochemistry under Hydrogen Gas: Synthesis of Efficient Materials for Hydrogen Storage and Electrochemical Applications
1455.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1455.prez_authors: Fermin  Cuevas, Junxian  Zhang, Michel  Latroche
1455.prez_abstract:
Mechanochemistry under dihydrogen gas is a powerful technique for the synthesis of metallic and complex hydrides. In this presentation, the synthesis of binary metal hydrides, solid solution BCC hydrides, non-miscible metal hydrides, complex magnesium hydrides, alanates and imides/amides is surveyed. Some particular phenomena such as ball-milling induced amorphisation, formation of metastable phases and multi-step reactions are reported. Influence of mechanical deformations and temperature effects on compound synthesis are discussed. The obtained hydrides are nanostructured powders exhibiting fast reaction kinetics and deserve increasing interest in the fields of hydrogen storage [1] as well as electrochemical systems [2]. 
[1] J. Huot, D. B. Ravnsbæk, J. Zhang, F. Cuevas, M. Latroche, T. R. Jensen, "Mechanochemical synthesis of hydrogen storage materials", Prog. Mater. Sci., 58 (2013) 30
[2] S. Sartori, F. Cuevas, M. Latroche, "Metal hydrides as negative electrodes for Li-ion batteries", App. Phys. A, 122 (2016) 135

1456.prez_name: Mechanochemo Approaches to Lignocellulosic Biomass and Its Isolated Polymers
1456.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1456.prez_authors: Michael P Wolcott, Jinwen  Zhang, Jinwu  Wang, Mohammadali  Azadfar, Jinxue  Jiang, Yalan  Liu
1456.prez_abstract: Lignocellulosic materials have long been a source of feedstock for energy, fuels, chemicals, and materials. Use of these renewable materials benefit from the relative abundance and low-carbon input. However, their use is also challenged by complex and chemically intensive conversion processes. Mechanochemo processes are used to alter the ultrastructural and molecular morphology of the lignocellulosic material; specifically Douglas-fir wood (Pseudotusga menziesii). Efforts have been made to scale the process in an energy efficient manner. The consequences of this pretreatment allowed the resulting micronized wood to be easily hydrolyzed with cellulase enzymes to liberate simple sugars for industrial processes. Unlike common thermochemical pretreatment methods, the isolated sugars are clean of contaminating organic compounds that render the sugars difficult to use in bioconversion processes. In addition, have been used to modify the isolated lignin and cellulosic components for use in polymer applications.

1457.prez_name: Metastability and Electrical Properties of Fluorite and Pyrochlore Phases in the Ln2Zr2O7:Ln2Ti2O7 systems (Ln = Yb, Ho): Cations Size Mismatch Effects
1457.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1457.prez_authors: , Goretti Carolina Fraustro-Castañeda, Nayeli M. Cepeda-Sánchez, José A. Díaz-Guillén
1457.prez_abstract: Lanthanide titanates and zirconates Ln2B2O7 with the pyrochlore or fluorite structures, display a rich variety of exciting, and potentially useful physical properties such as high ionic conductivity and low thermal conductivity. Moreover, they are interesting component materials for energy conversion and storage devices or for thermally insulating coatings. Some properties are mediated by subtle electronic differences or by the presence of structural defects, and disorder, which occur easily in this family of oxides. Moreover, they offer a unique playground to examine the interplay between defect chemistry, and properties in multicomponent oxides. This contribution analyzes the stability of pyrochlore and fluorite structures, in two Ln2Zr2O7:Ln2Ti2O7 systems (Ln = Yb, Ho) using samples obtained via mechanochemical reactions between the corresponding elemental oxides; special emphasis is focused to study the cations size effects on the post-milling thermal stability and ionic conduction of both systems.

1458.prez_name: Multiscale Theory for Mechanochemistry and Its Applications
1458.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1458.prez_abstract: High pressure mechanochemistry studies the effect of large plastic deformation on phase transformations and chemical reactions in rotational diamond anvil cell (RDAC), high pressure torsion, and during ball milling. Atomistic simulations are used to determine the effect of multiaxial loading on lattice instability conditions.  At the nanoscale, a model for strain-induced nucleation at the tip of a dislocation pile-up is suggested and studied analytically and using developed phase field approach. At the microscale, simple strain-controlled kinetic equation for the strain-induced transformations is thermodynamically derived. It depends on the ratio of the yield strengths of phases. Macroscale model for plastic flow and strain-induced transformations in a sample in RDAC is developed and finite element solutions are found. Results are applied for the prediction and description of multiple mechanochemical phenomena, search for new phases, and significant (by a factor of 3-10) reduction of the transformation pressure. Many of them are confirmed experimentally.

1459.prez_name: Phase Evolution during the Synthesis of Manganese Germanides
1459.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1459.prez_authors: Vamsi M  Meka, Tanjore V. Jayaraman
1459.prez_abstract: Transition metal germanides, known to have an interesting combination of electronic and magnetic properties, are suitable for applications in magnetoelectronic devices. In this work the phase evolution during the synthesis of metastable manganese-germanides, during mechanical alloying, is presented. Mechanical alloying of manganese and germanium elemental powder blends were carried out as a function of milling time. Characterization of various evolving phases, during milling, was performed by x-ray diffraction and scanning electron microscopy. At the initial stages of milling, supersaturated solid solutions were formed, followed by various metastable phases. With the increase in milling time, gradual variation in the amounts of various metastable phases was observed at different intervals. Milling was continued until the desired intermetallic metastable manganese-germanide was obtained. The magnetic properties of the metastable phase were characterized and, compared with other transition metal germanides available in the literature.

1460.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1460.prez_abstract: Mechanical alloying and mechanochemcial processing of powders is known to produce a variety of stable and metastable phases. These include supersaturated solid solutions, intermetallics, quasicrystalline phases, nanomaterials, and amorphous alloys. Such metastable effects in alloy systems can also be achieved by other non-equilibrium processing methods such as rapid solidification processing. But, there are significant differences in the effects observed in a system by different processing methods. This presentation will critically examine the data on phase selection in different alloy systems processed by different techniques and discuss the differences and the mechanisms responsible for them.

1461.prez_name: Real-time Observations of Impact-induced Melting and Adhesion
1461.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1461.prez_authors: Mostafa  Hassani-Gangaraj, David  Veysset, Keith A. Nelson, Christopher  A.  Schuh
1461.prez_abstract: While it is well known that mechanical work can cause heating and promote chemical reactions, mechanically-induced melting can open significant new opportunities in mechanochemistry.  For example, localized melting has been always viewed as a facilitating factor, if not the main mechanism, for bonding of metallic microparticles to substrates in kinetic deposition. Here, we conduct in-situ supersonic impact studies of microparticles to explicitly study impact-induced deformation and melting. We employ an in-house-designed microscale ballistic test platform to accelerate individual metallic microparticles up to ~1 km/s, have them impact a substrate, and study the potential melting, reaction, and bonding processes in real time. We find that under some conditions melting is disadvantageous and hinders impact-induced bonding, and develop an argument to explain this counter-intuitive observation.

1462.prez_name: SMACS: Surface Mechanical Attrition of Cold Spray Composite Coatings
1462.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1462.prez_authors: Heather  Murdoch, Blake   Barnett, Jonathan  Ligda
1462.prez_abstract: Surface Mechanical Attrition Treatment (SMAT) is a severe plastic deformation process that produces a grain size gradient in a substrate material, with surface grains on the nanocrystalline or ultrafinegrained scale. This grain refinement has been seen in a variety of pure metal and alloy substrates; here we demonstrate the effect of SMAT on a thick film system where copper-nickel has been deposited on 6061 aluminum alloy via gas dynamic Cold Spray (CS), a solid state powder deposition technique. We show that the grain refinement continues through the several hundred micron thick coating into the substrate material. Furthermore, the cold spray coating was comprised of discrete copper and nickel components; after SMAT, the coating was well mixed. Additionally, while the as-sprayed interface between the cold spray coating and the substrate showed evidence of cracks or delamination, the post-SMAT interface appeared continuous.

1463.prez_name: Structural Evolution of Molybdenite during Severe Milling Process; The Effect of Addition Alumina Particles
1463.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1463.prez_authors: Arman  Hoseinpur, Malihe  Mohammadi Bezanaj, Maryam Sadat  Marashi, Jalil  Vahdati Khaki
1463.prez_abstract: Easy, economic, and extendible production of 2D molybdenite (MoS2) nanosheets is necessary for practical applications like in next generation anodes for Li-ion batteries. There are some promising reports for production of MoS2 nanosheets from its bulk material with the milling process. This research is an effort to unveil the structural evolution of MoS2 during milling process. In this study the morphology evolution of molybdenite during the milling process and the effect of adding alumina particles to the initial mixture is studied. The structural investigations were performed by XRD and TEM characterizations. Results showed that when MoS2 was milled alone 2D nanosheets, nanobars, and nanotubes were formed at the first step of the process and then structural destruction occurred when milling was prolonged. However, when MoS2 was milled in presence of alumina particles, destruction initiated from the beginning of the milling process leading to provide a high degree of activated structure.

1464.prez_name: Surface Characterization of Activated Chalcopyrite Particles via the FLSmidth ROL Process. Part 2: Surface Spectroscopy Investigations
1464.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1464.prez_authors: , Anne Juul  Damø, Jytte Boll  Illerup, Sara S. Rocks, Kim  Dam-Johansen, David  Chaiko
1464.prez_abstract: Due to its semiconductor properties, the world’s most abundant copper mineral, chalcopyrite (CuFeS2), is refractory with respect to atmospheric leaching using traditional acidic ferric sulfate lixiviants. FLSmidth® has developed a novel Rapid Oxidative Leach (ROL) process that (a) manipulates the lattice and (b) mechano-chemically processes chalcopyrite with a Stirred Media Reactor (SMRt).  This combination yields the benefit of increasing chemical reactivity and dissolution kinetics. By reducing surface passivation, this process is typically able to achieve copper recoveries exceeding 95% in under 6-8 hours. An important factor contributing to this extraordinary performance is a mineral preconditioning step, which uses 0.1-5 mol% of copper(II) to dope the lattice and thereby "activate" chalcopyrite. Previously, we reported the relationship between doping and deformation of the chalcopyrite lattice using electron microscopy. Now, we draw further insights into the electrochemical properties of the activated chalcopyrite particles through a variety of surface spectroscopy studies.

1465.prez_name: Surface Mechanical Alloying for Specialized Heterogeneity (SMASH)
1465.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1465.prez_authors: Heather  Murdoch, Joseph  Labukas, Chad  Hornbuckle
1465.prez_abstract: Current surface treatments to impart desired surface chemistry and morphology on a metallic substrate, such as the anodizing of aluminum alloys, entail intensive multi-step chemical processing systems that generates a significant amount of hazardous waste. This work extends the severe plastic deformation of Surface Mechanical Attrition Treatment to include the alloying capability of mechanical milling to develop a surface layer of alumina that is well integrated into the aluminum alloy substrate. In addition to the surface alloying, a grain size gradient subsurface structure is formed which may provide additional corrosion protection and improved mechanical properties. The plastic deformation engenders grain refinement and a redistribution of precipitates both of which have impacts on corrosion response. The SMASH process of alumina powder stock onto an aluminum alloy may provide an alternative to chemical anodizing.

1466.prez_name: Synthesis and Photoluminescence of Single-crystal Silicon Nitride Nanowires via Nitriding of Cryomilled Nanocrystalline Silicon Powder
1466.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II
1466.prez_authors: Fei  Chen, Zhifeng  Huang, Qiang  Shen, Lianmeng  Zhang, Enrique J. Lavernia
1466.prez_abstract: The preparation of high-purity Si3N4 nanowires (SNNWs) is challenging partly as a result of the poor nitriding and oxidation kinetics by traditional solid-phase synthesis methodologies. In this work we developed a novel synthetic methodology to fabricate dimensionaly controllable SNNWs by nitriding of cryomilled nanocrystalline silicon powder. The SNNWs consist of single-crystalline α-Si3N4, and are 30-100 nm in diameter. The formation of Si–N–Si surface passivation during cryomilling process promotes the subsequent synthesis of SNNWs. The growth mechanism for SNNWs appears to be a vapor–solid reaction. Moreover, we describe doping control methods for SNNWs using doping elements selected in the order of valence electron at different blocks in the periodic table to realize control of its photoluminescence wavelengths (380-620 nm). Finally, combining first-principles simulation and optical measurements, we have established the relationship between band structures and photoluminescence properties, which reveals the photoluminescence mechanisms of SNNWs with doping elements.

1467.prez_name: Synthesis of Solid Solution Phases by Mechanochemical Processes: New Perspectives for the Design of Advanced Materials
1467.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II

1468.prez_name: The Energy Consumed in Ball Mills
1468.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II

1469.prez_name: The Influence of Non-equilibrium Defects on the Reactivity of Mechanically Activated Composites Based on Transition Metal Oxides
1469.symp_name: Mechanochemical Synthesis and Reactions in Materials Science II

1470.prez_name: Advances on Fabrication of Al-based Nanocomposites Assisted by Ultrasonic and Electromagnetic Processing
1470.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1470.prez_abstract: Al-based nanocomposites were fabricated in this study by using ultrasonic cavitation (UST) and induction melting and stirring technologies. The required ultrasonic parameters to achieve the required cavitation for adequate degassing and refining of the A356 alloy as well as the fluid flow characteristics for uniform dispersion of the SiC nanoparticles into the A356 alloy matrix were investigated in this study by using a magneto-hydro-dynamics (MHD) model and an UST cavitation model. The MHD model accounts for turbulent fluid flow, heat transfer and solidification, electromagnetic field as well as the complex interactions between the solidifying alloy and nanoparticles.  The MHD and UST models were coupled with a stochastic microstructure model to predict the formation of the microstructure during the molten metal and solidification processing of the A356-based nanocomposites. Fine globular grain structures and uniform distribution of nanoparticles were observed in the cast samples obtained via UST during solidification.

1471.prez_name:
Anisotropy and Thermal History Effects on the 
Tensile Behavior of a 3D Printed Polymer Matrix Composite via In Situ Synchrotron X-ray Tomography
1471.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1471.prez_abstract: The tensile behavior of an additively manufactured (AM) polymer matrix composite (PMC) was studied by in situ synchrotron x-ray computed microtomography (CT) and digital volume correlation (DVC). The effects of recycled material content and print direction on the selective laser sintered (SLS) material’s mechanical response were explored. The PMC samples were printed in a tensile specimen geometry with gage lengths parallel to all three orthogonal, primary sintering directions. In situ tensile-CT experiments were conducted at Argonne National Laboratory’s Advanced Photon Source 2-BM beamline. Analysis of the AM PMCs tensile response, failure, and strain evolution was analyzed using the load-displacement data and from a microstructural standpoint by applying DVC analysis to the reconstructed volumes. Significant variations on both strength and ductility were observed with respect to print direction and the recycled material content in the printed parts. The effects of addition of recycled source material will be discussed.

1472.prez_name: Boron Nitride Nanotube Reinforced Aluminum Composite via Solidification Processing
1472.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1472.prez_authors: Pranjal  Nautiyal, Benjamin  Boesl, Arvind  Agarwal
1472.prez_abstract: Boron Nitride Nanotube (BNNT) reinforced Aluminum composites are fabricated by solidification route. The nanotubes survive high temperature and reactive conditions involved in melting of Aluminum. Microstructure investigation reveal limited interfacial reactions, resulting in the formation of AlN, AlB<SUB>2</SUB> and AlB<SUB>10</SUB> in trace amounts. AlN is the principal reaction product at Al/BNNT interface. Theoretical calculations show improved work of interfacial adhesion due to AlN formation. BNNTs are found to be well integrated in the aluminum matrix, attesting AlN induced excellent wetting. In addition, capillary filling of BNNT by molten Al is also observed. The cast Al-BNNT composite was rolled to ~60% thickness reduction. The nanotubes survived severe plastic deformation involved in rolling. Mechanical properties are evaluated by nanoindentation, microhardness and tensile tests. Enhancement of elastic modulus, hardness and ultimate tensile strength is observed due to BNNT. This study establishes the suitability of casting route for developing high strength Al-BNNT composites.

1473.prez_name: Cellulose Nanocrystals: An Approach toward Lightweight Sheet Molding Compound (SMC) Composites
1473.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1473.prez_authors: Amir  Asadi, Robert J. Moon, Kyriaki  Kalaitzidou
1473.prez_abstract: The focus of this study is making lightweight hybrid sheet molding compound (SMC) composites by replacing the heavier components, i.e. glass fibers (GF), with a small amount of cellulose nanocrystals (CNC) with no penalty on mechanical performance. SMC, which are materials consist of short GF impregnated between two layers of thermosetting resin, are composites used mainly in automotive structural applications. CNC are cellulose-based whisker shaped, high surface area, high mechanical properties, surfaces with accessible hydroxyl side groups (e.g. –OH) and low toxicity make them an attractive candidate for reinforcement in polymers and polymer composites. We report that using a scalable technique, introducing 1 and 1.5 wt% cellulose nanocrystals (CNC) in the epoxy matrix of short GF/epoxy SMC composites allows removing 10 wt% glass fibers (GF) from a typical SMC composites containing 35 wt% glass fibers (35GF/epoxy), producing ~8% lighter composites with no compromise in tensile and flexural properties.

1474.prez_name: Composite Fiber Orientation Analysis Utilizing X-ray Micro-Computed Tomography
1474.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1474.prez_abstract: Well-aligned fibers are critical for composite material behavior, especially for tensile loading. Fiber orientations can deviate from desired angles, however, due to material processing methods such as hand lay-up, and it is difficult to measure the specific fiber orientations within the bulk material. X-ray micro-computed tomography (micro-CT) allows for the non-destructive evaluation of materials to obtain microstructural information of a full 3D volume. High resolution micro-CT scans can segment fibers from the matrix if there are distinctly different densities between the material constituents. In this work, fiber orientations were quantified from micro-CT scans for carbon fiber epoxy matrix composites, and histogram responses of the orientation relative to specific viewing planes were generated. These results were compared with optical images to independently validate the orientation results which showed good agreement. Micro-CT was shown to be a viable method for quantifying fiber orientation and advantages and disadvantages of this technique are discussed.

1475.prez_name: Effect of Melon Shell Particles on the Microstructure and Mechanical Properties of Epoxy/Melon Shell Particulate Bio-composites
1475.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1475.prez_authors: Suleiman Bolaji Hassan, Victor Sunday Aigbodion, C U  Atuanya
1475.prez_abstract: Particle filled polymer composites have become attractive because of their wide applications and low cost. Increased environmental awareness throughout the world have developed an increasing interest towards the use of natural particles such as melon husks (MHs) as reinforcement which are now considered as alternative to synthetic particles in various fields. MHs are shells that are discarded after processing of melon seeds. The MHs were carbonized and used to produce the composites by varying the carbonized MHs particles from 5-30 wt%. The microstructure and mechanical properties were determined using standard methods. The result shows that increased in MHs reinforcement, increased the mechanical properties of the composites. The carbonized MHs particles in the epoxy matrix as reinforcement gave better mechanical properties than the uncarbonized MHs particles. The work has established that MHs particles can be used to enhance the properties of epoxy resin matrix composites for indoor and outdoor structural application.

1476.prez_name: Electrical and Mechanical Properties of Copper Metal Matrix Composite Containing Polydopamine Derived Nanocarbon
1476.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1476.prez_authors: Yao  Zhao, Bosen  Qian, Haoqi  Li, Dmitriy A Dikin, Fei  Ren
1476.prez_abstract: Copper metal matrix composites containing nanocarbons may possess improved mechanical and physical properties compared to pure copper. In this study, a new processing method was developed to fabricate copper-nanocarbon composite. Uniform PDA layers that were tens of nanometer thick were coated onto copper powder particles, which were then converted to carbon coatings during sintering. The resultant composite materials exhibited higher electrical conductivities than the pure copper samples sintered under the same conditions. Meanwhile, the hardness values were comparable between materials with and without PDA addition. Microstructural characterization using SEM, TEM, and other techniques indicated the copper-PDA composite exhibited better sintering behavior leading to higher mass densities, which may contribute to their improved electrical conductivity.

1477.prez_name: Fabricating Process for Nano-particle Enforced Metal Matrix Composites with Rotational Friction Extrusion Method
1477.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1477.prez_abstract: The characteristic of the interface between the metal matrix and CNTs, uniformity of the composites, effect of the fraction of CNTs on tensile strength and wear resistance of the composites were investigated. The results indicated that the CNTs/Al composites are fabricated undergoing severe plastic deformation, mixture, breaking of bulk metal matrix, the mixing of metallic particles with CNTs, the welding of metallic particles embed with CNTs, and recrystallization. Thus a homogeneous distribution of CNTs in the metal matrix composites with fine grains is formed. The tensile strength of composites significantly improved with increasing of the fraction of CNTs. There was a sharp variation in the wear resistance of the composites at a certain CNTs fraction with the increase of the CNTs addition. Rotational Friction Extrusion process is mostly a potential technique to fabricate the super strength metal matrix composites in which the CNTs is dispersed uniformly.

1478.prez_name: Instrumented Depth-sensing Nanoindentation of a Magnesium Metal-matrix Nanocomposite (AZ31-0.33wt% CNT)
1478.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1478.prez_authors: Meysam  Haghshenas, Robert  Klassen, Sathish   Kannan, AZM  Islam, Manoj  Gupta
1478.prez_abstract: Magnesium metal-matrix nanocomposites (Mg MMNCs), the addition of nano-size reinforcement with different volume fractions, can well address the structural limitations of magnesium and the alloys through improving wear resistance, damping properties and mechanical properties (i.e. tensile strength, yield stress, hardness), possibly, without scarifying the ductility and no noticeable weight gains. In this study, length-scale mechanical properties of a Mg-based nanocomposite containing carbon nanotubes (CNT), AZ31-0.33wt%CNT, were studied through an instrumented nanoindentation system at room temperature. To this end, using a Berkovich pyramidal indenter, multiple indentation hardness tests at six average indentation strain rates (0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1.0, and 2.0 /sec) were performed to assess indentation force-displacement response along with average indentation stress, average reduced elastic modulus, and indentation strain rate sensitivity of the material. The microstructure of the nanocomposite was also studied through optical and scanning microscopy (SEM) to find the microstructure/property correlations in the tested AZ31-0.33wt% CNT composite.

1479.prez_name: Lightweight Self-lubricating Aluminum Matrix Composites Reinforced by Graphene
1479.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1479.prez_authors: Emad  Omrani, Afsaneh  Dorri Moghadam, Pradeep K. Rohatgi
1479.prez_abstract: Graphene possess unique electrical, mechanical, and thermal properties. Owe to their lubricious nature, graphene has attracted researchers to synthesize lightweight self-lubricating metal matrix nanocomposites with superior mechanical and tribological properties. In the present investigation, aluminum matrix nanocomposites reinforced by graphene nanoplatelets were synthesized by powder metallurgy method. To investigate the tribological behavior of aluminum matrix composites reinforced by graphene nanoplatelets and pure aluminum, pin-on-disk experiments were conducted. In the experiments, the influence of reinforcement volume fraction and normal load on the tribological performance was investigated. It was found that the graphene nanoplatelets reinforced nanocomposites showed superior tribological properties and demonstrated the ability of the self-lubricating nature of the composite during tribological conditions. The mechanisms involved for the improved mechanical and tribological behavior is discussed.

1480.prez_name: Multiscale Synergistic Damage Mechanics Model for Progressive Damage and Durability Analysis of Laminated Composite Structures
1480.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1480.prez_abstract: Despite four decades of intense research on damage development and failure initiation, industry designs for composite structures are overly conservative, mainly due to the lack of a comprehensive progressive damage and failure analysis tool for their structural analysis and performance prediction. Here, we will present the progress of multi-year model development of a multiscale synergistic damage mechanics approach as a comprehensive tool for industrial design and damage tolerance predictions for practical composite structures. This approach can predict damage initiation, its progression and degradation in stiffness properties for multidirectional laminated structures under multiaxial loading conditions with good reliability. The application of this method to conduct multiscale progressive failure analysis of wind turbine composite structures and airplane fuselase under quasi-static and fatigue loading will be presented.

1481.prez_name: Nano-damping Behavior of 3D Graphene Foam Reinforced Polyurethane Composites
1481.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1481.prez_authors: Adeyinka  Idowu, Luiza  Fontoura, Marcus  Herndon, Pranjal  Nautiyal, Archana  Loganathan, Benjamin  Boesl, Arvind  Agarwal
1481.prez_abstract: 3D Graphene foam (GrF), a state of the art material, portrays to be a more robust nano-reinforcement in polymers compared with other carbon-based nano-reinforcements. In this work, 3D graphene foam reinforced polyurethane composites (PU-GrF) are fabricated using electrostatic spray deposition. The thermal and damping properties of 3D graphene foam reinforced polyurethane (PU) composites are investigated. DSC study showed significant increase of 150C and 280C in the glass transition temperature of PU-GrF at 1.95 vol% and 3.32 vol% graphene foam within the PU matrices. Furthermore, the DMA analysis, at both low and high load regimes, revealed that loss tangent values of PU-GrFs displayed appreciable increase than PU. The results indicate high energy absorption and thermal stability of PU-GrF composites compared with PU. The study suggests that PU-GrF nanocomposites have the potential to act as high dampener in vibrating systems.

1482.prez_name: Nanomechanical and Nanotribological Studies of BNNP Reinforced UHMWPE Coating for Biomedical Applications
1482.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1482.prez_authors: Archana  Loganathan, Pranjal  Nautiyal, Dillon  Watring, Leslie  Embrey, Benjamin  Boesl, Arvind  Agarwal
1482.prez_abstract: Boron nitride nanoplatelets (BNNP) was dispersed in ultra-high molecular weight polyethylene (UHMWPE) using centrifugal mixer and deposited onto Ti-6Al-4V substrate via electrostatic spray deposition. The addition of BNNP in the UHMWPE resulted in a dense coating with a thickness of ~ 100 µm. Fracture surface showed a uniform dispersion of BNNP in the UHMWPE coating. XRD and DSC studies on the UHMWPE-BNNP coating revealed a significant drop in crystallinity compared to the pure UHMWPE coating. Nanoindentation studies showed that the hardness improved by 17% by the addition of BNNP to the UHMWPE coating. Plasticity index for UHMWPE + 1 wt.% BNNP coating was about 4.2% lower than the pure UHMWPE coating. Further, nanoscratch test was performed on the coatings and BNNP reinforced coating showed an 18% decrease in coefficient of friction compared to the pure UHMWPE coating indicating the superior frictional properties of BNNP due to interlayer sliding.

1483.prez_name: Particle Brush Materials – Building Blocks for Multifunctional Nanocomposites With Engineered Properties
1483.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1483.prez_abstract: Polymer-grafted particulates (aka ‘particle brush materials’) are of interest both from a fundamental as well as applied perspective because structural frustrations that are associated with the tethering of chains to a curved surface imply a sensitive dependence of structure and interactions on the architecture of the particle brush. The opportunity to control chain conformation in hierarchically organized hybrid materials with precisely controlled microstructure renders particle brush materials intriguing building blocks for innovative material systems that could have a transformative impact on a range of ‘soft material’ technologies. This presentation will discuss experimental results that illustrate the role of polymer graft modification on the interaction between brush particles in the solid state as well as the assembly characteristics of particle brushes in the solid state. The application of particle brush based composites in areas such as dielectric barrier materials or phononic crystals will be discussed.

1484.prez_name: Prediction of Modulus of Polymers and Composites at Different Strain Rates by Integral Transform of DMA Data
1484.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1484.prez_authors: Steven E Zeltmann, Keerthana  A Prakash , Nikhil  Gupta
1484.prez_abstract: Dynamic mechanical analysis (DMA) has for long been used to characterize thermal transitions and activation of chain motions in polymers. However, the frequency domain results obtained from DMA have found little utility in constitutive modeling of materials. A method is presented for transforming the results of a combined frequency- and time-sweep in DMA to the material time domain relaxation function, which is then used to predict the linear viscoelastic response of the material to different strain rates. Validation of the technique is presented for high density polyethylene (HDPE) and syntactic foams containing fly ash cenosphere hollow particles in a HDPE matrix. The predictions from the technique are shown to have excellent agreement with the results from tensile testing of the materials at a wide range of strain rates.

1485.prez_name: Quantitative Evaluation of Composite Materials Using In Situ Microscopy
1485.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1485.prez_abstract: Metal matrix composites have been of interest for many decades, however there remains some question regarding local deformation around particles. In this talk, Ni-B4C and Al-B4C composites will be discussed as model systems to study deformation using quantitative in situ microscopy techniques. In particular, particle-dislocation interactions will be analyzed using quantitative diffraction methods coupled with in situ SEM and TEM, providing an evolution of this relationship. Local and global strain measurements will also provide a view of the role of particle distributions in these materials, which will be analyzed in both film and bulk (from powder) form. The combination of mesoscale and nanoscale in situ techniques provides a platform for further developing composites in a predictive manner with respect to matrix-particle interactions.

1486.prez_name: Recent Developments in Self-healing Metallic Materials and Mechanics of Self-healing Composites
1486.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1486.prez_authors: Nathan Picchietti Salowitz, Volkan  Kilicli, Xiaojun  Yan , Pradeep K. Rohatgi
1486.prez_abstract: Self-healing materials, inspired by biological materials, can heal from damage. Incorporating self-repair functionality into inorganic systems has received a lot of interest in recent years. Most studies have focused on polymers, concretes, and ceramics because they are easier to synthesize than metallic materials.  Multiple significant challenges remain to increase the technology readiness level of self-healing materials including: a) bonding between components, b) multicycle healing, c) autonomous healing, d) understanding influence and interaction of sub-components, and e) properties of materials after self-healing. Metal matrix self-healing materials reinforced with shape memory alloys can provide engineering grade material properties capable of healing multiple times. Similarly, the fabrication process can control the mechanics of self healing. Recent studies have been performed on self-healing metal matrix composites consisting of tin-bismuth alloys to ensure bonding between subcomponents.  Simultaneous work was performed to create crack closing loads capable of resisting external loading with theory and experimental validation.

1487.prez_name: Structural Modification of Polyethylene Using Dialium Guineense Particles
1487.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1487.prez_abstract: This work,used Dialium guineense shell particles (DSPs) as filler in recycled low density polyethylene (RLDPE) for the production of new polymeric composites indoor applications. The RLDPE/DSP composites were produced by compounding and compaction. The DSP addition was varied from 4 to 10 wt. % . The morphology and tensile property of the composites were studied. Results indicated homogenous structure and grain refinement as the wt. % of DSP increased. About 3 and 29 % enhancement in Young’s modulus were observed at 4 and 6 wt. % addition of DSP respectively above which there was no significant improvement in the Young’s modulus. This enhancement in Young’s modulus is attributable to grain refinement and good interfacial adhesion.

1488.prez_name: Synthesis and Characterization of Biomimetic Composites for Dental Applications
1488.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1488.prez_authors: Rashmi Reddy Mallu, Isabel K Lloyd, Yang  Yang, Karan  Mohan, Ayush  Thapa, Joe  Marchese, Kai-wen  Chang
1488.prez_abstract: Our study seeks to mimic the structure of natural enamel by adding nano and micro fillers to acrylic monomers. To determine the effects of filler type and size, glass fibers, silica microrods, TiO2 nanorods, TiO2 nanoparticles, and silica nanospheres were silanized and added to 50:50 BisGMA:TEGDMA matrix, respectively. The microstructure and the organization of the rods and fibers were characterized by SEM. Three point bend tests were used to determine flexural strength, elastic modulus, and toughness. Vicker’s microhardness and degree of curing were also measured. Because the composite is intended for use in the mouth, samples were characterized in the as-cured and water aged state. Aging did not lead to significant swelling but did effect mechanical properties. Toughness was enhanced by the addition of fibers or rods to the filler mix. The fibers and rods could be organized by centrifuging, settling and packing. Packing was the least effective approach.

1489.prez_name: The Development and Mechanical Characterization of Aluminium Copper-carbon Fiber Metal Matrix Hybrid Composite
1489.symp_name: Metal and Polymer Matrix Composites III
1489.prez_authors: Muhammad Umar Manzoor, Muhammad  Feroze, Tahir  Ahmad, Muhammad  Kamran, Rafiq  Ahmad, Muhammad Taqi Zahid Butt
1489.prez_abstract: Metal matrix composites (MMCs) come under advanced materials that can be used for a wide range of industrial applications. MMCs consist of a non-metallic reinforcement incorporated into a metallic matrix which can enhance advantageous properties over base metal alloys. Copper-Carbon fiber reinforced aluminium based hybrid composites were prepared by compo casting method. 4 weight % copper was used as alloying element with Al because of its precipitation hardened properties. Different weight compositions of composites were developed and characterized by mechanical testing. A significant improvement in tensile strength and micro hardness were found, before and after heat treatment of the composite. The SEM analysis of the fractured surfaces showed dispersed and embedded Carbon fibers within the network leading to the enhanced strength.

1490.prez_name: Thermophysical and Thermochemical Property Measurement and Simulation of Liquid Metal Alloys for Additive Manufacturing Simulation and Materials Design
1490.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control

1491.prez_name: A-14: A Computer Vision Approach to Defect Analysis in Additive Manufacturing Build Components
1491.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1491.prez_authors: Andrew  Kitahara, Brian  DeCost, Elizabeth  Holm
1491.prez_abstract: This work demonstrates the application of computer vision and machine learning techniques to defect analysis for components made with additive manufacturing (AM) methods. Computer vision techniques offer objective identification and quantification of defects, including pores and microstructural inhomogeneities, in a more general and higher throughput framework than traditional quantitative metallography. The methods we present employ open source computer vision toolkits to define keypoint descriptors and to search for descriptor matches on an image with high accuracy. For example, using a gradient of thresholding, pore size distribution is straightforward to determine even in micrographs that are poorly suited for segmentation and measurement. Machine learning algorithms can then be applied to the image data and processing conditions to find correlations between pores and pore formation mechanisms. Future work in defect characterization techniques will enable further optimizations in AM build quality.

1492.prez_name: A-15: Research on Structure Optimization of Cooling Channel of Copper Staves
1492.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1492.prez_abstract: In this paper, a structure optimization model of copper cooling stave was established based on ANSYS. With this model, the temperature distribution field and stress distribution of the copper cooling staves with different structure was calculated. The heat transfer effect of each cooling stave with certain structure was analyzed and the influence rule of each structure parameter was observed, then the structure of the cooling stave was optimized automatically by ANSYS optimizer. The optimizing result shows that the newly designed cooling stave has better heat transfer effect and the ANSYS optimizer works well on structure optimization of copper cooling stave.

1493.prez_name: Accessing and Managing Materials and Process Data for Additive Manufacturing (AM) Simulations and Managing AM Process Life Cycle Data
1493.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1493.prez_authors: Najib  Baig, Stephen  Warde, John  Twerdok, Will  Marsden
1493.prez_abstract: To ensure accurate simulations for Additive Manufacturing (AM), there is a need for a consistent way of delivering and applying materials and process data in simulation codes. Furthermore, to fully leverage simulations and understand the effect of process parameters on part quality, simulation results needs to be managed in a systematic way allowing data traceability, mining and comparison with physical (test) data. This is underpinned with the science of managing Additive Manufacturing data across its life-cycle with full maintenance of the complex relationship between the part geometry, material, and individual processes used to create the final part. This can make a difference between parts that can be reliably reproduced to the level of required fidelity. In this paper, challenges related to AM simulations, available codes and an approach for managing entire AM process including applying, analyzing and comparing simulation data will be discussed.

1494.prez_name: An Atomistic Study of Nanoscale Sintering: Application to Additive Manufacturing
1494.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1494.prez_authors: Jesse M. Sestito, Fadi  Abdeljawad, Tequila A. L. Harris, Yan  Wang
1494.prez_abstract: Solid-state sintering within direct ink write applications has become a key focus area for researchers in additive manufacturing seeking to understand processing of metallic and ceramic powders. In this study, atomistic simulations are leveraged to examine sintering dynamics of Nickel, where simple two and three particle geometries are used to examine the role of particle misorientation angles on grain boundary (GB) formation, rigid body rotations, and pore shrinkage. For the two particle geometry, a wide range of misorientation angles and particle diameters are explored with the aim of examining their roles on GB formation and neck growth. For the three particle geometry, pore shrinkage and associated dynamical scaling are examined as a function of misorientation angle at a constant particle diameter of 20 nm. Simulation results highlight the role of GBs and their anisotropy on the sintering behavior.

1495.prez_name: Analysis of Mechanical Behavior of Components Produced By Fused Filament Fabrication
1495.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control

1496.prez_name: Compression Behavior of 3D Printed Polymer Lattice Structures
1496.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1496.prez_authors: Mohammed  Al Rifaie, Sagar  Sangle, Ahsan  Mian, Raghavan  Srinivasan
1496.prez_abstract: Sandwich panel structures have high specific compressive stiffness, flexural stiffness, and strength, good vibration damping characteristics, and low through thickness thermal conductivity. These structures consist of solid face-sheets and low density cellular core structures, which are often based upon honeycomb topologies. Additive manufacturing or 3D-printing allows the fabrication of complex core lattice configurations, which have been redesigned to provide targeted improvements in certain properties, such as specific energy absorption. The goal of this research is to design, model through FEM, fabricate and test different lattice core structures. Starting with a 5x5x5 mm cubic cell, four designs of 25x25x20 mm core structures were created by varying the arrangement of vertical and diagonal struts, and then printed with ABS using fused deposition modeling.  FE and compression test results showed that the designs with vertical struts have significantly higher failure loads and higher specific energy to failure than the basic cubic design.

1497.prez_name: Computational Simulation of Additively Manufactured Marine Structures
1497.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1497.prez_abstract: The present study is part of an ICME thrust to expand the use of computational simulations for additive manufacturing (AM) components.  Previously, finite-element analysis of AM components was not able to include distortion and residual stress of the entire build, yielding uncertainty in the computational models.  To address this, recently developed computational tools are under a validation investigation for laser powder-bed fusion (L-PBF) builds.  The on-going investigation includes physical validation to better understand how modification of the build plans can improve build efficiency and reduce instances of failed builds due to distortion and cracking.  Additionally, the thermal modeling of the build process will likely influence the developed microstructure, thereby giving insight into how to modify build processes in order to obtain designed alloys (i.e. graded structures).  The project goal is to validate the computational tools to determine best practices for insertion of AM simulation into the greater Naval enterprise.

1498.prez_name: Distortion Analysis and Reduction for Layerwise Additive Manufacturing Processing by a Laminated Layerwise Analytical Model and Tool
1498.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1498.prez_abstract: It is well-known that the distortion of additive manufactured part is one of the essential issues for its application in industry.  In order to reveal the initiation of the distortion in AMed part and overcome the computation limitation of existing computational tools, a laminated layerwise analytical tool is developed to realize the quick emulation of the thermomechanical response for the additive manufacturing track-by -track and layer-by-layer deposition procedure based on a laminated analytical model  after the full-scale temperature field, temperature gradient  and cooling determined by Layerwise Additive Manufacturing Predictions and Simulation (L.A.M.P.S. ©) software. In terms of the developed laminated layerwise analytical tool and LAMPS software, a correlation map among the AMed part distortion, material properties and processing parameters , such as scan speed, power input, laser beam diameter and deposition path/strategy etc was established as the reference to optimize the processing  parameters for controlling and reducing the part distortion.

1499.prez_name: Experimental Validation of Phase-field Predictions for Rapidly Solidified Microstructures of Metallic Alloys
1499.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control

1500.prez_name: Fast Finite Element Predictions of Distortion, Residual Stresses, and Strength of Additively Manufactured Ti-6Al-4V
1500.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1500.prez_authors: Ayman A. Salem, Daniel P Satko, Joshua  Shaffer, Luke  Wuertemberger
1500.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing is increasingly attractive for producing complex metallic parts. However, part performance is dependent on processing parameters, such as laser speed and power, scanning strategy, and build direction. Anisotropic thermal history results in residual stresses, distortion, and anisotropic microstructure and mechanical properties. In this talk Materials Resources (MRL) demonstrates a case study for successfully building Ti-6Al-4V parts by laser powder bed fusion by employing an Integrated Computational Advanced Additive Manufacturing framework (ICAAMTM) that links our database for processing parameters, microstructure, and material properties with finite element software Simufact.additive for predicting distortion, residual stresses, and strength of a Ti-6Al-4V bracket accounting for thermal and microstructure anisotropy.

1501.prez_name: From High-fidelity to Reduced-order: A Comparison of Heat Transfer Models for Toolpath Design and Microstructure Prediction in AM
1501.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1501.prez_authors: Alex  Plotkowski, Yousub  Lee, Naren  Raghavan, Ryan  Dehoff, Sudarsanam Suresh Babu
1501.prez_abstract: A variety of models have been developed to predict the heat and mass transfer phenomena relevant to metal additive manufacturing. However, inclusion of all possible physical effects increases the computational expense of these models to the extent that they are not suitable for simulating full layers or complete builds. To understand longer length and time scale effects, some sacrifice must be made to model fidelity. In this presentation, three different continuum heat transfer models will be compared. The first is a finite-volume model that considers solidification and fluid mechanics, the second is a finite-element model that considers only conduction, and the third is a reduced-order semi-analytical model for conduction. Computational expense, scalability, and physical fidelity, particularly in relationship to their ability to simulate complex scan patterns and the development of solidification microstructure, will be evaluated. Applications based on relative advantages and disadvantages will be discussed.

1502.prez_name: Heat Transfer and Fluid Flow during Fabrication of Overhang Structure in Laser-Powder Bed Fusion Additive Manufacturing
1502.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1502.prez_authors: Yi  Li, Yousub  Lee, Ji-Cheng  Zhao, Wei  Zhang
1502.prez_abstract: Compared to directed energy deposition additive manufacturing processes, powder bed AM (such as laser-powder bed fusion) has distinct advantages in building complex structures such as overhangs. As overhangs sit on top of loosely-packed powder, the significantly reduced heat sink changes molten pool geometry. The present study aims to better understand molten pool evolution during fabrication of overhang structures. Discrete element model is used to calculate the arrangement of particles on the powder bed under the overhang. This arrangement is then imported into a transient heat transfer and fluid flow model to examine temperature evolution. For experimental validation, particle packing of AISI 316L powders are scanned by micron-resolution X-ray computerized tomography. Overhang structures are fabricated in a sensor laser test bed equipped with a high-speed video camera and a two-color infrared camera. The effects of processing parameters on overhang structure characteristics are discussed based on the computational and experimental results.

1503.prez_name: Investigation on Grain Structure Development of Ti-6Al-4V during Additive Manufacturing: An Integrated Phase-field and Finite-element Modelling
1503.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1503.prez_authors: Pengwei  Liu, Yanzhou  Ji, Alphons A.  Antonysamy, Long-Qing  Chen, Lei  Chen
1503.prez_abstract: The mechanism of grain structure development during additive manufacturing of Ti-6Al-4V is comprehensively investigated by an integrated phase-field and finite-element model. The thermal response at the macroscale is modeled using the finite-element method, and the grain growth at the mesoscale is simulated by a temperature-dependent phase-field model. The grain orientation is involved in the model to account for the strongly anisotropic grain structure and texture. Upon the experimental validation, the proposed model predicts the <001>β // NZ columnar grain structure aligned with the build direction in the bulk sections, as well as the inward columnar curved β-grain structure in the skin layer. The underlying mechanism of these behaviors is demonstrated to be related to the steep thermal gradient of highly elongated melt pool, the grain nucleation and growth during a layer-by-layer fabrication. A design map is proposed to tailor the manufacturing conditions to achieve site-specific grain structure control.

1504.prez_name: Mean-field Process-microstructure Modeling for Additive Manufacturing of High-quality Parts
1504.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1504.prez_authors: Yunhao  Zhao, Qian  Chen, Jian  Liu, Albert  To, Wei  Xiong
1504.prez_abstract: Due to complexity of laser processing on metal powders, a thorough understanding of microstructure evolution and its relations to processing and properties are critical for alloy design and quality control of additive manufacturing. In this work, case studies on process-structure simulation will be discussed demonstrating the state-of-the-art CALPHAD-based microstructure simulation for laser additive manufacturing. The phase transformation modeling and thermal modeling of Inconel 718 under direct metal laser sintering are coupled together. The thermal modeling takes the CALPHAD database as the input for the predictive science-based modeling of the temperature profile. A mean-field prediction of the constituent in the microstructure is performed using the combined Johnson-Mehl-Avrami-Kolmogorov and Scheil-Gulliver models. Processing diagrams of Inconel 718 are carefully analyzed for complex thermal cycle processes with mixed supercooling and rapid heating. Future research directions on process-structure-property modeling for additive manufacturing will be discussed.

1505.prez_name: Microstructure Modeling of Selective Laser Melting of Inconel 718
1505.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1505.prez_authors: Kubra  Karayagiz, Thien  Duong, Vahid  Attari, Luke  Johnson, Brian  Franco, Gustavo  Tapia, Ji  Ma, Alaa   Elwany, Ibrahim  Karaman, Raymundo  Arroyave
1505.prez_abstract: Selective Laser Melting (SLM) is a layer by layer additive manufacturing (AM) technique involving rapid heating-cooling cycles, which in turn results in a complicated thermal history in the fabricated part. It is well-known that the parts’ microstructures primarily depend on this thermal history. In the present work, we have developed a microstructure model based on the phase-field (PF) method to simulate the microstructure evolution during SLM of Inconel 718, which is approximated as a binary alloy. To this end, first the thermal history of the part is predicted in a finite element (FE) model which is then introduced into the PF model to predict the rapid solidification, particularly, dendritic structure and solute segregation. In addition, the effect of cooling rates and temperature gradients on the final microstructure is investigated through the simulations. Finally, the predictions are compared with the experimental observations.

1506.prez_name: Modeling of Laser Heat Input for Laser Powder Bed Fusion
1506.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control

1507.prez_name: Modeling of Phase Transformation and Transport Phenomena in the LENS Process via the Lattice Boltzmann-Cellular Automata Method
1507.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1507.prez_authors: Matthew  Rolchigo, Michael  Mendoza, Richard  LeSar, Peter  Collins
1507.prez_abstract: While additive manufacturing processes such as Laser Engineered Net Shaping (LENS) have gathered research interest, much remains to be understood about the complex relationships among process parameters, melt pool evolution, materials parameters, and microstructure formation. In particular, there is a need for modeling to play a role in the design of new alloys for additive manufacturing, predicting experimental conditions and guiding experiments toward favorable conditions for part creation. We present work in which a Thermal Lattice Boltzmann-Cellular Automaton (TLB-CA) model simulates coupled heat transport, melting, and fluid flow in the molten pool at the appropriate length and time scales for titanium alloys. A coupled solidification model then simulates grain growth and dendritic colony evolution as a function of the modeled thermal conditions. The coupling of the TLB-CA and solidification models will allow for investigation of process-melt pool-microstructure relationships, and microstructural trends will be examined and compared with experimental results.

1508.prez_name: Multi-scale Physics-based Modeling Framework for Additive Manufacturing of Metallic Components
1508.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1508.prez_authors: Yi  Zhang, Weng  Hoh  Lee, Yeon-Gil  Jung, Jing  Zhang
1508.prez_abstract: A longstanding scientific challenge is to optimize additive manufacturing (AM) process in order to reduce AM component failure due to excessive distortion and cracking. In this work, a multi-scale physics-based modeling framework is presented to understand the interrelationship between AM processing parameters and resulting properties. In particular, a multi-scale approach, spanning atomic, particle, to component levels, is employed. The predicted distortion due to residual stress is in good agreement with experimental measurements. In summary, the model framework provides a design tool to optimize the metal based additive manufacturing process.

1509.prez_name: Multivariate Statistical Calibration of a FEM Thermal Simulation Model for Selective Laser Melting of Ti6Al4V
1509.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1509.prez_authors: Mohamad  Mahmoudi, Gustavo  Tapia, Kubra  Karayagiz, Brian  Franco, Luke  Johnson, Ji  Ma, Raymundo  Arroyave, Ibrahim  Karaman, Alaa  Elwany
1509.prez_abstract:
Thermal models of SLM based on Finite Element Method (FEM) improve the understanding of the process by calculating thermal histories that the material undergoes given a combination of processing parameters. The analysis of temperature can be then employed in microstructure or mechanical properties assessment.
Nevertheless, thermal models normally depend in many physical constants of unknown value and either unmeasurable or extremely complicated to measure. Hence, misspecification of these constants will result in wrong calculations by the model.
This study presents a statistical calibration applied to a FEM thermal model developed for SLM of Ti6Al4V. The framework estimate the values of three influencing parameters given a limited number of simulations and experiments, which include melt pool characterization and temperature measurements through a pyrometer. A bayesian statistical approach with multivariate Gaussian Processes is used to infer those values of the constant parameters that bring the simulation model close to the real process.

1510.prez_name: Optimization of an Infill Pattern in Additive Manufacturing Accounting for Internal Stress
1510.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control

1511.prez_name: Optimization of Metal Additive Manufacturing Process Using a Computational Sequential Minimum Energy Design Approach
1511.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1511.prez_authors: Kai Wing Kelvin  Leung, Azadeh   Keshtgar, Nicole   Apetre, Nagaraja   Iyyer
1511.prez_abstract: Additive manufacturing technology offers rapid prototyping and large design freedom, however, part quality and mechanical performances of additively manufactured components are not comparable to that produced by traditional manufacturing techniques. To minimize experimental efforts for optimizing metal additive manufacturing process, a computational sequential energy design approach is proposed, consisting of multi-scale multi-physics additive manufacturing process simulation, sensitivity analysis and optimization. A finite-element based heat transfer model was developed to simulate multi-layer selective laser melting process of Ti-6Al-4V. The temperature history and melt pool shape were extracted to predict lack of fusion defects and microstructure evolution. Sensitivity analysis was carried out to identify and rank the most influential process parameters and the sequential minimum energy design algorithm was implemented to optimize the selective laser melting process for minimum defects and desired microstructure phase fraction. Validation of the computational approach with experimental studies will also be discussed.

1512.prez_name: Powderless Alloy Development Approach for Titanium Alloy Tailored for Additive Manufacturing
1512.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1512.prez_abstract: This study demonstrated a powder-free alloy design approach for a titanium alloy tailored to additive manufacturing processes.  Alloy design for AM is complicated by the need for small quantities of powder to examine any new composition.  In this study, a screening test was developed for a series of boron-modified Ti6Al4V-xB alloy(x = 0, 1, 2, 5, 10, wt%).
