Solid, arc-melted buttons of the above compositions were fabricated and single-pass & multiple-pass laser scanning tracks were made on the buttons over a wide range of laser power and beam travel speed. Microstructures were examined and microhardness measurements were made over the range of compositions and process variables. Optimal compositions and process variables were selected and the effect of boron on AM-processed titanium alloy were elaborated based on microstructural analysis. Initial comparisons to microstructure and properties of powder-based AM parts were also made.

1513.prez_name: Prediction of Powder Bed Fusion Micro Structures
1513.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1513.prez_authors: Christoph  Beetz, Salem  Mosbah, Mustafa  Megahed
1513.prez_abstract: Micro structures of material manufactured via powder bed fusion processes are complicated. The cooling rate is very high implying non-equilibrium rapid solidification and coaxed grain structures. However, in due course of creating the work piece the heat source travels near the solidified material several times implicitly heat treating the material and leading to an effective material cooling behavior that leads to columnar growth. The competition between the grains could lead to enclosures that weaken the material as a whole. This paper analyzes the cooling rate of powder bed fusion and applies an innovative grain growth model that allows a two way coupling between the melt pool model and the predicted grain structures. First the models are presented with corresponding validation data. Then process parameters are introduced before a layer by layer analysis is presented. Results will include powder characteristics, melt pool dimensions, thermal cycle and evolution of micro structure.

1514.prez_name: Quantitative Texture Prediction of Epitaxial Columnar Grains in Additive Manufacturing
1514.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1514.prez_authors: Jian  Liu, Qian  Chen, Yunhao  Zhao, Wei  Xiong, Albert C.  To
1514.prez_abstract: The goal of this work is to establish the link between the microstructure (texture) and the process parameters of metal AM (additive manufacturing) processes. A quantitative method based on the epitaxial growth of columnar grains within and across melt pools is proposed to predict the texture formation during a metal AM process. Both analytical modeling and FEM (finite element method) simulation have been used to predict the geometry and thermal profile of the quasi-steady melt pool. The thermal gradient distribution within the 3D melt pool determines the crystallography direction and growth direction of the columnar grains within each deposited single track. The single tracks with the predicted geometry are amalgamated together to represent the bulk part, and the epitaxial growth of grains across the boundary of neighboring tracks are quantitatively modeled. The proposed method is calibrated and validated by experimental studies of metal AM processed Inconel 718.

1515.prez_name: Rapid Alloy Screening: Tailoring Aluminum Alloy Composition for Additive Manufacturing
1515.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1515.prez_authors: Joe  Croteau, Davaadorj  Bayansan, Nhon  Vo, David  Dunand, David  Seidman
1515.prez_abstract: The very high cooling rate in additive manufacture of metals makes it a non-equilibrium process: opening new possibilities to design alloys specifically tailored for this process. NanoAl has observed a similar micro- and nano-structure in aluminum alloys fabricated from three different rapid-solidification processes: (i) melt-spinning, (ii) gas-atomization, and (iii) laser melting, and the alloys produced from each method have the same age-hardening potential. This is the foundation for our innovative method of rapid alloy screening (RAS), a high-throughput experimental approach to develop and optimize aluminum alloys for additive manufacturing. We will demonstrate that alloy properties measured during the cost-effective RAS method correspond to additively manufactured material of the same composition. This allows us to predict the performance of a newly developed alloy for additive manufacturing without having to produce powder or 3D-printing components for characterization, drastically reducing the resources needed to specifically tailor an aluminum alloy composition for additive manufacturing.

1516.prez_name: Thermal and elastic properties of δ-, γ”-, γ’- and γ-Ni3Nb at finite temperature and interfacial energy between precipitates and matrix from first-principles calculations
1516.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1516.prez_authors: Yi  Wang, Kevin   Mcnamara, Yanzhou  Ji, Zi-Kui  Liu, Rich  Martukanitz, Long-Qing  Chen
1516.prez_abstract: δ-, γ”-, and γ’-Ni3Nb are the major precipitate phases in Inconel 625 and Inconel 718 used for aerospace additive manufacturing. To simulate the process of the additive manufacturing of these alloys, the thermal and elastic properties in the wide temperature range together with the interfacial properties between precipitates and matrix are the key input data. In this work, first-principles quasi-harmonic calculations were performed to obtain the key properties, such as thermal expansion and elastic moduli, as functions of temperature. The lattice contributions have been accounted for based on the phonon theory, the electronic contribution have been accounted for based on the Mermin statistics, and the temperature dependence of the elastic moduli have been accounted for using the quasi-static approximation. It is found that the electronic contribution to the heat capacity can reach more than 10% and the major elastic moduli can be reduced by 30% at high temperature.

1517.prez_name: Thermo-fluid Modeling of Selective Laser Melting Considering Powder Particle Characteristics
1517.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1517.prez_abstract: In metal powder-bed fusion additive manufacturing such as selective laser melting (SLM), the variability in powder feedstock strongly influences the process performance and part quality. In this study, a 3D thermo-fluid model using the Volume of Fluid approach with powder particles incorporated was developed using ANSYS/FLUENT. A sequential addition-packing algorithm was utilized to generate randomly distributed particles in a powder bed. Temperature dependent material properties were specified and the laser beam scanning was modeled as a moving volumetric heat source. As a result of continuous melting and solidification, the temperature distribution, the melt flow and the deformed build surface can be obtained. The developed model was utilized to study the effect of the particle size, the size distribution and the packing density on the SLM thermal response and the build surface roughness.

1518.prez_name: Thermomechanical Analysis of Hot Cracking in Non-weldable Ni-based Superalloy
1518.symp_name: Modeling and Simulation in Additive Manufacturing: Materials Design, Property Prediction, and Process Control
1518.prez_authors: Yousub  Lee, Mike  Kirka, Naren  Raghavan, Alex  Plotlowski, Alfredo  Okello, Ryan  Dehoff
1518.prez_abstract: In electron beam melting (EBM), large numbers of Ni-based superalloy remain as non-printable (ex. MarM247 and CM247) due to high propensity to form cracks. Rapid formation of γ’ precipitate and existent of liquid γ/ γ’ eutectic make EBM difficult to print those alloys. The morphology of dendrite in EBM alloy 247, unlike in casting, is cellular structure. Also, the size is a couple of hundred times finer than in casting. Therefore, thorough understanding of solidification behavior is critical in determining formation of cracking during and after solidification. Cracking in alloy 247 is sensitive to process parameters and alloy selection. In this study, we focus on developing criteria based on theoretical and numerical thermo-mechanical analysis and correlate to cracking phenomena in various process conditions (i.e. power, speed, scan strategies and geometrical design etc.). Ultimately, we will suggest optimal process parameters to prevent the cracking in additively manufactured alloy 247 part.

1539.prez_name: Asymmetric Structure of 90° Domain Walls and Interaction with Defects in PbTiO3
1539.prez_abstract:
We investigate the atomistic structure of ferroelastic-ferroelectric 90° domain walls in PbTiO<SUB>3</SUB> with first-principles calculations and high-resolution scanning transmission electron microscopy. We find sharp discontinuities in the variation of lattice parameters across the domain walls. Unexpectedly, the two neighboring domains become asymmetric across the boundary, giving rise to primitive unit cells with large tetragonality ratios (c/a) of the order of 1.11 close to the boundary. The variation of the domain wall structure with respect to strain is demonstrated. We show that oxygen vacancies are attracted to the plane adjacent to the 90° domain wall. The mechanisms of domain wall pinning by oxygen vacancies are explained based on the energy landscape of the vacancies in the presence of the domain interface.

Reference [Chandrasekaran, A., Wei, X. K., Feigl, L., Damjanovic, D., Setter, N., & Marzari, N., Physical Review B, 93(14), 144102, 2016]

1540.prez_name: Atomistic Understanding of Interface Structures and Properties In Self-assembled Vertically Aligned Nanocomposite Thin Films by Advanced Scanning Transmission Electron Microscopy
1540.prez_authors: Ping  Lu, Lin   Zhou, Jon  Ihlefeld, Wei  Pan
1540.prez_abstract: The structural characterization up to atomic-scale plays a critical role in understanding the structure-property relationships. Self-assembled, vertically aligned nanocomposite (VAN) thin films, consisting of two immiscible components hetero-epitaxially grown on single crystals, offer the advantage of utilizing the functionalities of both components. The structure also provides the possibility of tuning the material’s properties by tailoring the volume ratio of two components, the interface-to-volume ratio, hetero-epitaxial strain and the interface properties. Here we describe several efforts of utilizing advanced scanning transmission electron microscopy (STEM) to quantify the interfaces of the VAN thin films including NiO:(La0.7Sr0.3)MnO3(LSMO),  ZnO:LSMO and  Sm-doped CeO2:SrTiO3. STEM imaging combining low-angle, and high-angle annular dark-field (LAADF, HAADF) detectors as well as atomic-scale elemental mapping using energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDS) and electron energy loss-spectroscopy (EELS) are used to study cation interdiffusion across the interfaces, dopant distribution within each component, and O vacancy and valence state of cations across/near the interfaces.

1541.prez_name: Black Titania by pp-MOCVD: Nanostructured Carbon-sensitised Titania Films with Visible Light Activity
1541.prez_authors: Catherine  Bishop, Aleksandra J. Gardecka, Andreas  Kafizas, Raphael  Boichot, Susan  Krumdieck
1541.prez_abstract: Photocatalytic titania-based materials are of interest for myriad applications including water purification, antimicrobial surfaces, solar cells, and water splitting. Existing materials are grown using diverse techniques, including solvathermal and CVD methods, and visible light activity has been demonstrated through doping, e.g. with N,  or formation of mixtures of materials, e.g. anatase nanoparticles with graphene oxide. Facet-engineered nanoparticles have been shown to yield excellent behaviour, but are not confined to a surface.  In this paper, conformal films of nano-structured titania/nanographite composites are grown from a single precursor solution by pulsed pressure MOCVD, a facile, scalable growth technique. Composites of textured, undoped, mixed-phase titania with nanographite obtain the benefits of nanoscale titania in intimate contact with nano-graphite in an adherent film on stainless steel and glass substrates that yields exceptional properties. The material’s visible light activity and photocatalytic performance are related to the nano- and micro-scale structure.

1542.prez_name: C-14: Multiferroic Behaviour and Magnetoelectric Coupling in Fe/Ni co-doped Bi3.15Nd0.85Ti3O12 Ceramics
1542.prez_authors: Sumit  Bhardwaj, Sanjev  Kumar, R. K.  Kotnala
1542.prez_abstract: Polycrystalline samples of Bi3.15Nd0.85(Ti3-xFex/2Nix/2)O12 (0 ≤ x ≤ 0.5) ceramics are synthesized by conventional solid state reaction method. X-ray diffraction reveals the formation of single phase upto x=0.3. Relaxation of distortion in TiO6 octahedron was conﬁrmed by Raman spectroscopy analysis. Microstructural studies reveals the plate like grain growth for x=0.0, whereas, increasing Fe/Ni content significantly influences the grain morphology and enhances the grain randomization. A good ferroelectricity and significant improvement in ferromagnetism are obtained simultaneously at room temperature. Magnetoelectric coupling coefﬁcient, α = 0.67 mV/cm Oe is obtained for x = 0.3 ceramic sample at room temperature. The observation of magnetoelectric coupling might be explained on the basis of binding effect of magnetic interactions on the migration of charged defects. Our results clearly demonstrate the lead-free, multiferroic behaviour of synthesized samples which find useful application in designing multiple state memory elements, data storage devices and sensors.

1543.prez_name: C-15: Optimization of Properties of Al2O3-spinel Castables for RH Snorkel Working Lining
1543.prez_abstract: Considering the Cr6+ pollution of magnesia-chrome bricks for secondary refining and ladle lining, Al2O3-Spinel castable is a potential choice to replace magnesia-chrome bricks, but the thermal shock stability needs to be optimized. Adopting tabular alumina, fused spinel and high purity spinel and fused zirconium corundum(ZrO2-Al2O3，hereinafter referred as ZA) as the main raw materials, Al2O3-spinel castables have been prepared with the introduction of ZA ( respectively adding 0, 2%, 4%, 6%,8%，10%).Thermal shock stability has been investigated by residual strength ratio. Slag resistance has been investigated by static crucible method and microstructure of specimens after slag test has been analyzed by SEM and EDAX. Results indicate that the castables with fused zirconium corundum cements (ZA) exhibit an excellent thermal shock stability and slag resistance. In this condition, the HMOR gets worse with the replacement of tabular alumina by ZA, all specimens tested are above 20 MPa. PLC remains between 0 to +0.5%.

1544.prez_name: Chemical Solution Deposition of Ferroelectric Oxide Thin Films and Nanocomposites
1544.prez_authors: Mads  Christensen, Trygve  Ræder, Mari-Ann  Einarsrud, Tor  Grande
1544.prez_abstract: Recent progress in ferroelectric and multiferroic thin films and nanocomposites have mainly been based on physical deposition techniques such as pulse laser deposition. Here, we report on an aqueous solution deposition platform to ferroelectric oxide thin films and nanocomposites. We report on deposition of polycrystalline as well as textured and epitaxial thin films of lead-free ferroelectric materials such as KNN and BNT. We also demonstrate that this synthesis platform is suitable for deposition of oxide nanocomposites, and we report on recent advances with focus on nanocomposites and strain engineering of ferroelectric barium titanate. We demonstrate the strength of this synthesis platform with respect to compositional engineering of thin films as well as nanocomposites. Finally, we discuss the processing-microstructure-property relationship of the oxide ferroelectrics prepared by aqueous chemical solution deposition.

1545.prez_name: Component-Customizable Porous Rare Earth-based Colloidal Spheres towards Highly Effective Catalysts and Bioimaging Applications
1545.prez_abstract: Multicomponent porous colloidal spheres are of interest because they not only show a combination of the properties associated with all different components, but also usually present synergy effect. However, combination of different components in a single porous sphere is still greatly challenged due to different precipitation behaviors of each component. In this talk, we develop a general synthetic route to prepare several categories of porous monodisperse rare earth (RE) based colloidal spheres with customizable elemental compositions and uniform element distribution. The two-step synthetic strategy is based on the integration of coordination chemistry precipitation of RE ions and subsequent ion-exchange process, which steers clear of obstacle from differences in solubility product constant in traditional co-precipitation methods. Taking advantage of their good dispersibility, porosity and customizable component, these porous RE oxide spheres show excellent catalytic activity for the reduction of 4-nitrophenol, and promising applications in single-phase multifunctional bioprobes.

1546.prez_name: Domain Specific Photoreduction of Ag+ on the Surface of Ferroelastic γ-WO3
1546.prez_authors: Ajay Sudhir Pisat, Paul A. Salvador, Gregory S. Rohrer
1546.prez_abstract: Ferroelectric photocatalysts can separate charge carriers and half-reactions to surfaces of specific domains, owing to their internal dipole moments. Though these separations increase efficiency, ferroelectrics have large band gaps and often photodegrade, limiting their use as solar photocatalysts. We are interested in understanding how other surface charge mechanisms can lead to spatially bifunctional surface properties of non-ferroelectrics. Here, we show ferroelectric-like domain specific photoactivity on the surface of bulk, polycrystalline, centrosymmetric, ferroelastic γ-WO<SUB>3</SUB>. Two out of three levels of hierarchical ferroelastic domains were found to be piezoresponsive for any orientation of the surface. Photodeposition of Ag<SUP>+</SUP> was carried out using UV light. The reactivity correlated with the same two levels of domains that were piezoresponsive. The results can be explained by surface flexoelectricity or a surface phase transformation, similar to prior reports for BiVO<SUB>4</SUB>.  We discuss these collected observations in light of the anti-ferroelectric natures of γ-WO<SUB>3</SUB> and BiVO<SUB>4</SUB> .

1547.prez_name: E-field Induced Giant Dynamic Magnetization Change in Self-assembled BFO-CFO/PMN-PT Heterostructures
1547.prez_authors: Xiao  Tang, Ravindranath  Viswan, Min  Gao, Jiefang  Li, Dwight  Viehland
1547.prez_abstract: We have deposited self-assembled BiFeO<SUB>3</SUB>-CoFe<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB> (BFO-CFO) thin films on (100) Pb(Mg<SUB>1/3</SUB>Nb<SUB>2/3</SUB>)<SUB>1-x</SUB>Ti<SUB>x</SUB>O3 (PMN-x%PT, x=33, 35.5 and 38) single crystal substrates. These heterostructures were used for the study of real-time changes in the magnetization with applied electric field (E). With increasing E, we observed a giant magnetization change along the out-of-plane direction, namely along the easy axis. For PMN-33PT and PMN-38PT, the induced magnetization changes were about ΔM=80%; and for PMN-35.5PT, ΔM was about 60%. By changing the electric field under different superimposed magnetic fields during measurement, we found several unique values of a stable magnetization, which were non-volatility on removal of the field. Based on the E-field induced changes in magnetization, a giant converse magnetoelectric (CME) coupling coefficient was calculated and determined to be about 2×10<SUP>-7</SUP> s/m. With increasing applied magnetic field (H), the coupling coefficient dropped significantly near the magnetic coercive field, reaching a plateau with further increase of H.

1548.prez_name: Electric-field Control of Tri-state Phase Transformation with Selective Dual-ion Switch
1548.prez_abstract: Electric-field control of phase transformation with ion transfer is of great interest in materials science with enormous and important practical applications, such as batteries, smart windows, fuel cells, etc. Although increasing the number of the transport ion species and the corresponding controllable crystalline phases can greatly enrich the material functionalities, studies have so far targeted mainly on the evolution of only single ionic species (e.g. O<sup>2-</sup>, H<sup>+</sup> or Li<sup>+</sup>, etc.). In this talk, I will report our recent progress on the reversible and nonvolatile electric-field control of dual-ion (O<sup>2-</sup> and H<sup>+</sup>) phase transformation associated with the discovery of the exotic tri-state electrochromic and magnetoelectric effects. These findings open up new opportunities for the electric-field control of multi-state phase transformation with novel crystalline structures and rich functionalities.

1549.prez_name: Emergent Structures and Properties in Ferroelectric Thin Films
1549.prez_abstract: Modern approaches to epitaxial thin-film growth have enabled unprecedented control of ferroelectric materials including the realization of enhanced polarization and transition temperatures, production of ordered domain structures, and improved properties. Today, however, we are looking beyond simple lattice mismatch control for new ways to manipulate and control ferroic response and to produce emergent phenomena. In this talk, we will explore one or more examples of such emergent phenomena including, but not limited to, leveraging various film orientations, compositionally-graded structures, superlattices, and other mesostructuring of ferroelectric and relaxor materials to understand the coupling between growth/defect formation and properties, routes to competition between energetically-degenerate “phases,” production of deterministic ferroelastic switching in clamped films, novel multi-state stability and neuromorphic-like function, exotic ferroelectric topologies, efficient waste-heat energy conversion, and more.

1550.prez_name: Exchange Coupling in Oxide Heterostructures Driven by Hidden Interface
1550.prez_authors: Aiping  Chen, Qiang   Wang, Michael   Fitzsimmons, Erik   Enriquez, Marcus  Weigand, Zach   Harrell, Brian   McFarland, Xujie  Lü, Paul   Dowden, Judith  MacManus-Driscoll, Dmitry   Yarotski, Quanxi  Jia
1550.prez_abstract: Recent advances in thin film synthesis enable unique opportunities to enhance and control the physical properties of oxide interfaces by controlling the interactions between adjacent layers. Interface layers intrinsic to oxide heterointerfaces have often been observed. However, the role of such an interfacial layer in controlling functionalities has not been fully explored. In this talk, we will focus on the role of buried interfaces on exchange couplings in the single-phase manganite heterostructures and we observed a clear exchange bias effect. Interestingly, the sign of exchange bias is controlled by the cooling field strength. The origin of such an exchange coupling is related to the pinned interfacial layer. Our results shed new light on using oxide interfaces to design functional spintronic devices.

1551.prez_name: First-principles Design of Two-dimensional Electron Gas in the Perovskite-Oxide-Based Interface Materials
1551.prez_abstract: The perovskite-based oxide heterointerfaces between two wide-band-gap insulators are attracting increasing interests because of their novel electronic properties such as the two-dimensional electron gas (2DEG) at the interface that have potential applications in the next-generation nanoelectronic devices. In this talk, I will present our recent work on the high-throughput design of the perovskite-based nonpolar/polar 2DEG systems based on polar catastrophe mechanism. Then I will show the possibility to produce 2DEG at the nonpolar/nonpolar and at the polar/polar perovskite heterointerfaces, separately, as well as their fundamental mechanisms. These research findings may provide some avenues to achieve 2DEG in the perovskite-oxide-based interface materials.

1552.prez_name: First Principle Study of Interfacial Structures and Properties of Perovskite Oxides
1552.prez_abstract: CaTiO3 thin film, which has a nonpolar orthorhombic perovskite structure, has become ferroelectric at experimentally accessible tensile strains. So it could be promising as components for sensors and capacitors. Density function theory (DFT) would be applied to analyze the strain effect in atomic scale at the interface. To achieve the biaxial tensile strain on CaTiO3, three different perovskite substrates were chosen in this project, including DyScO3 and La0.29Sr0.71Al0.65Ti0.35O3 (LSAT). These three substrates have larger in-plane lattice parameters and different octahedral tilting angles compared with CaTiO3. On the other hand, how the biaxial tensile strain in CaTiO3 thin film changes the octahedral tilts will be provided with a theoretical explanation. Eventually, a range of strain to tune CaTiO3 thin film with ferroelectric property hopefully could be acquired.  Based on this new technique, we could understand how the substrates could tune perovskite thin film and broaden the functionality of perovskite thin films.

1553.prez_name: Integration of High-k Metal Oxide Dielectrics with 2D MoS2 Materials
1553.prez_abstract: With the traditional materials, because of phonon scattering in the moderate electrical field, transistors with high-k metal oxide dielectrics show worse carrier mobility which is well below the universal mobility curve. This hampers the objective of device scaling using high-k dielectrics. Now, due to the large in-plane carrier mobility in MoS2, the above-mentioned problem will no longer be an issue with the integration of high-k metal oxide dielectrics with 2D materials, e.g. MoS2. To realize the huge potential of MoS2 in new revolutionary semiconductor technology, the knowledge of interfacial properties of MoS2 with metal oxide dielectric is greatly demanded. In this talk, I will present our recent research work on the integration of high-k metal oxide dielectrics with 2D MoS2 materials, with the emphasis on the interface engineering, device fabrication and characterization.

1554.prez_name: Magnetoelectricity of CoFe2O4 and Tetragonal Phase BiFeO3 Thin Films Prepared by Pulsed Laser Deposition
1554.prez_authors: Min  Gao, Ravindranath  Viswan, Xiao  Tang, Jiefang  Li, Dwight  Viehland
1554.prez_abstract: To investigate the coupling between the tetragonal phase BiFeO<SUB>3</SUB> (BFO) and CoFe<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>4</SUB> (CFO), bilayer structures of CFO (15nm, 30nm)/BFO (50nm) were fabricated on (001) LaAlO<SUB>3</SUB> substrates by pulsed laser deposition. The surface morphologies and crystal structures were determined by atomic force microscopy and x-ray diffraction. Although the CFO and BFO layers were deposited separately, after annealing at 725&#176C for 30min, the CFO on top developed a self-assembled platform-like morphology with BFO. Magnetic force microscopy images showed that each platform contained multiple magnetic domains, which could be tuned by applying a tip bias. Hysteresis loops measured by a vibrating sample magnetometer suggested a strong thickness effect of the CFO on coercivity, in particular along the out-of-plane direction, where the coercivity was enhanced from 629Oe to 2122Oe as the thickness of CFO increased from 15nm to 30nm. In addition, a weak exchange bias was found due to the ferrimagnetic CFO/antiferromagnetic BFO interface.

1555.prez_name: Nanoscale Tailoring of Oxygen Vacancy Distribution by Mechanical-loaded Scanning Probe
1555.prez_authors: BO  WANG, Saikat  Das, Ye  Cao, Sergei V. Kalinin, Tae Won  Noh, Long-Qing  Chen
1555.prez_abstract: The intriguing behaviors of metal-oxides in response to external stimuli at nanoscale have attracted extensive interest recently. In particular, manipulating ferroic orderings and electronic and ionic defects in oxides by a mechanically loaded scanning probe creates new possibilities for a mechanical control of multifunctional devices. However, the complicate physic couplings involved, e.g., the flexoelectric effect and the Vegard strain, bring challenges to a comprehensively interpretation of the experimental observations. Here, we employ phase-field modeling integrated with transport theories to explore the oxygen vacancy distribution under localized mechanical stress. On this basis, we demonstrate a controlled modulation of oxygen vacancy in a homoepitaxial SrTiO<SUB>3</SUB> thin film via a mechanical-loaded scanning probe. The locally tailoring of oxygen vacancies and the comprehensive understanding of its mechanisms may yield far-reaching implications on the development of novel multifunctional oxide devices.

1556.prez_name: Occupancy and Vacancy Correlation in Ternary Oxides: A Case Study of Lattice Chemistry in Ba1-xSrxNb2O6
1556.prez_abstract: Tungsten bronze structure is a variant of ABO<SUB>3</SUB> perovskite but with two A-sites, leaving a vast space for engineering of lattice chemistry. Ba<SUB>1-x</SUB>Sr<SUB>x</SUB>Nb<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>6</SUB> is model system, which could be made via either templated growth to form textured microstructures or molten salts to grow acicular micron-crystals. By developing a thickness-corrected EDS quantitative analysis in TEM, an accuracy and precision better than 5% for cation composition could be reached, while high-resolution HAADF imaging could not well differentiate Ba from Sr especially when they are competing for same sites. Such a local chemical analysis revealed that occupancy of two alkaline-earth cations over these A-sites are not only affected by low-valence alkaline cations from synthesis media, but also correlated to nonstoichiometric vacancy that is an inherent nature of this structure. Indeed, such vacancy is common even in ceramics to expose a hierachical chemical structure, opening new space for lattice chemistry engineering.

1557.prez_name: Polar Surface Domains on Non-polar Surfaces
1557.prez_abstract: Polar semiconductors have recently received significant attention because their internal fields separate photogenerated electron-hole pairs and reduce recombination.  On surfaces with polar domains, electrons are attracted to positively terminated domains where they promote reduction reactions and holes are attracted to negatively charged domains where they promote oxidation.  We have found that polar domains can be created on the surfaces of non-polar materials, including BiVO4, WO3, and SrTiO3.  In the cases of WO3 and BiVO4, polarity arises from the flexoelectric effect.  On SrTiO3, polarity arises from polar terminations on different terraces.  For SrTiO3, it is possible to control the fraction of the surface terminated by positive or negative charges by annealing the surfaces in environments with an excess or deficit of strontium. In this talk, the use of polar domains to control photochemical reactions on the surfaces will be described.

1558.prez_abstract: In multifunctional oxides, control over the orbital and lattice parameters are generally achieved through strain engineering imposed by heteroepitaxial film growth on non-lattice-matched substrates. This method involves perturbation in all three unit cell dimensions since the in-plane strain induced into a film’s lattice is accommodated by the Poisson effect along the out-of-plane direction. Recently, low energy, low dose He ion implantation into oxide films has been shown as an effective means of continuously controlling lattice expansion along only the out-of-plane axis while leaving the in-plane axes locked to the substrate. This opens a previously inaccessible phase space of crystal symmetry to experimental interrogation. We will focus on recent results demonstrating how this ability delivers never before possible control over functionality in a range of functionally important oxide materials. We will also discuss the implications of the ability to control a single order parameter in how we approach theoretical models.

1559.prez_name: The Development of Pseudocapacitance in Oxide Materials
1559.prez_abstract: This paper will review our work on identifying Li+ conducting materials in which charge storage occurs by pseudocapacitive mechanisms. Our research on Li+ insertion in Nb2O5 has established a basis for intercalation pseudocapacitance in which the rate of charge storage is determined by surface-like kinetics rather than semi-infinite diffusion as occurs with battery materials. Another important consideration with this mechanism is that the structure does not undergo a first-order phase transition upon Li+ insertion. However, even with materials that exhibit such phase transitions, nanostructuring the material can effectively suppress the structural change and lead to effective charge storage. The guide lines provided by these and other recent studies provide a basis for developing a wide variety of materials systems which exhibit pseudocapacitie responses.

1560.prez_name: Ultra-High-Resolution Transmission Electron Microscopy of the Relationship between Structural Defects and Local Electrical and Magnetic Properties in Metal Oxides
1560.prez_authors: Rafal  Dunin-Borkowski, Hongchu  Du, Lei  Jin, Xiankui  Wei, András  Kovács
1560.prez_abstract: Metal oxides exhibit fascinating electrical and magnetic properties and hold great promise for applications in information technology. However, their local properties are often influenced by the presence of structural defects and interfaces. Here, we use aberration-corrected transmission electron microscopy and off-axis electron holography to explore the atomic structures, compositions and electrical and magnetic properties of different perovskite oxide bulk crystals, thin films, nanostructures and devices. We determine domain wall structures and their conduction mechanism in ferroelectric Pb(Zr1-xTix)O3 and BiFeO3, characterize conducting filaments in Fe-doped SrTiO3 and reveal the evolution of magnetic properties in (La1-xSrx)MnO3 and Fe3O4. We correlate the presence of defects and interfaces with local variations in ferroelectric, ferromagnetic and resistive switching properties, both under ambient conditions and in the presence of applied voltages, applied magnetic fields and at reduced temperature. Our findings may have profound implications for the applications of local defects and interfaces in future devices.

1561.prez_name: Van der Waals Oxide Heteroepitaxy for Transparent and Flexible Electronics
1561.prez_abstract: In the diligent pursuit of low-power consumption, multifunctional, and environmentally friendly electronics, more sophisticated requirements on functional materials are on demand.  For example, flexible electronics represents a fast developing field and has a great potential to impact our daily life. In building up flexible electronics, the materials with controllable conduction, transparency, and good flexibility are required. Due to the interplay of lattice, charge, orbital, and spin degrees of freedom, correlated electrons in oxides generate a rich spectrum of competing phases and physical properties. However, a generic approach to build up flexible electronics based on functional oxides is yet to be developed. In this study, we use a 2D material as the substrate. And we take several functional oxides as model systems, including transparent conducting oxides, VO2, NiO, Fe3O4, Pb(Zr,Ti)O3, and oxide nanocomposites, to demonstrate a pathway to build up functional oxides for transparent and flexible electronics.

1562.prez_name: Weight Loss Mechanism of (La0.8Sr0.2)0.98MnO3±δ during Thermal Cycles
1562.prez_abstract: It is well known the weight loss is due to the intake and outtake of oxygen from LSM and the process is determined by the thermodynamics and kinetics combined effect. An integrated experimental and modeling approach was adopted to understand the mechanism for the weight loss observed during the thermal cycles. The TGA experiments at various condition were carried out on weight loss shows the thermodynamic and kinetic effect during the thermal cycles. The detail XRD and raman analysis has be carried out to understand the crystal structure and the internal bonds evolution. In addition, Quantitative Brouwer diagrams for LSM-20 in air and Ar was predicted in the range of 600-1400°C to show the concentration of the various species in A site, B site and oxygen site during thermal cycles. A new weight loss Mechanism of (La0.8Sr0.2)0.98MnO3±δ (LSM-20) was proposed based on the La-Sr-Mn-O thermodynamic database.

1680.symp_name: Non Beam-based Additive Manufacturing Approaches for Metallic Parts
1680.prez_abstract: The metal additive manufacturing paradigm assumes that metal components are obtained through various additive techniques using metal as the direct raw material.    There are a number of issues with current methods including porosity, variable and potentially unpredictable materials properties, limitations to use existing alloy powders, and time consuming processes which are limited in their scalability.  Additionally, processes using additive manufacturing to obtain molds in conjunction with casting are in use but are costly, time consuming, and result in poor dimensional accuracy (0.020”/inch are typical). Research is being conducted in an alternative method that uses metal casting as a post processing technique.  Additive manufacturing is used to construct a PLA form whose surface is a replica of the final desired component with minimal infill.  This is then used as a consumable pattern through evaporative casting in a process similar to lost foam casting. Examples produced and process details will be reviewed.

1697.prez_abstract: Engineers today are not limited to a career as an employee of a big manufacturing corporation. There are myriad opportunities for engineers to ply their skills starting and running new enterprises. For some, this path can be a highly-rewarding alternative to a long-term corporate career. Materials engineers have some unique opportunities in entrepreneurship. This presentation gives one engineer’s perspective on entrepreneurship as a career path. Advantages and disadvantages, resource requirements, and personal factors relating to starting and running a new business or small company will all be discussed.

1698.prez_name: Career Options in Patent Law for Materials Science Professionals
1698.prez_abstract: Materials science professionals have many career opportunities in patent law. These career opportunities can include becoming patent attorneys, patent agents, patent examiners, expert witnesses, inventors and patent owners. Material science professionals who enter these professions can work in law firms, consulting firms, private industry, government, and academia. This presentation will discuss the role of the various branches of government in applying patent law and how materials science professionals within these professions can interact with those branches of government.

1699.prez_name: Career Planning...Professionalism/Networking: Who is the Decision Maker?
1699.prez_abstract:
Dr. Schmidt, as have previous ASMI Presidents, has had a professional journey extravaganza. As a general proposition one must anticipate and embrace "change". The best strategy is to not allow one's career to move and stay in the direction of "Specialization". Rather, it is essential to
broaden, expand, and diversify your career. Topics discussed and illustrated: Horizon planning,acquiring credentials, certifications and resume building as lessons learned. 

The Life story of Herbert Hoover (e.g. Dam in Nevada) will be compared to Dr. Schmidt's current C S I forensic, investigative lifestyle.  One must "inventory" talent, assess relative areas of "weakness", be willing to take prudent risk and stay focused on accomplishing the "mission".

Note: The lecture will set the stage for the follow up "Outward Bound" panel discussion!
    
*Principal Engineer/Director of Technology, Advanced APPLIED Services, Inc, St. Charles, IL 60175

1700.prez_abstract: No company or organization can employ engineers of every possible expertise. In many cases, the fastest and most effective way to get the sort of engineer you need is to look outside your organization for an expert. Meeting this need is the role of technical consultants. A career in technical consulting offers many unique features and differs significantly from the role a PhD materials scientist might find in academic or government research as well as typical engineering roles in industry. This presentation will discuss some of these unique features from the perspective of a managing engineer at Exponent, Inc., a large technical consulting firm. Exponent provides an interesting vantage point to comment on careers in technical consulting since it is a global firm employing scientists and engineers from many disciplines, including many materials scientists, and provides engineering services widely to clients in industry and government.

1701.prez_name: Environmental Sustainability in the Material World
1701.prez_abstract: Today’s professionals have an increased awareness and interest in the area of sustainability and the impact of our decisions on the environment.  This presentation provides an overview of current sustainability issues pertaining to the material science and engineering community, and their potential impacts in an ever changing world.

1702.prez_name: Experiences and Thoughts on Professional Development
1702.prez_abstract: I will present experiences from graduate school and from my 10+ years at a DOE National Laboratory.  The presentation will include thoughts on co-op experiences, collaborative research projects, international opportunities, and professional societies.  These experiences have helped guide my career and personal development, and have provided many useful lessons.  This will be an interactive discussion with questions welcome.

1703.prez_name: Finding a Materials Engineering Position within the US Federal Government
1703.prez_abstract: The US federal government employs materials engineers in a variety of agencies and positions.  These positions range from senior researchers to entry-level engineers in agencies ranging from the Department of Defense to the Food and Drug Administration to the Department of the Interior.  Degreed materials engineers also work in program management, finance and budgeting, contracting, and oversight positions, among others.  The federal government uses the USAJobs website as its portal for posting vacancies and accepting applications.  This presentation will describe the speaker's experiences as a materials engineer with the Navy.  It will also explain some of the government-ese you may encounter when searching for federal jobs as well as how to search for and apply to these positions.

1704.prez_name: From Gator to Investigator: How I Became a Failure Analyst and How You Can Too
1704.prez_abstract: Ten years ago, with obstructed vision and an overheated body, it was hard for this then graduate student to see past his life on a football field, let alone beyond a dissertation and research project that never seemed close to completion. However, after a long college “career” including over three years as a mascot at the University of Florida, this Florida Man began a journey from late night perpetual graduate student to repairing Navy aircraft, to investigating all manner of transportation accidents for a small agency in Washington, DC. This talk will present a small slice of my life, and explain how to take advantage of opportunities as well as how to make those opportunities manifest during ones career and life.

1705.prez_name: From Undergraduate to Journal Editor:  A Professional Development Story
1705.prez_abstract: This presentation will review decisions that were made that have influenced my professional development over the past 30 years.  Starting as an undergraduate, I made choices to get involved with activities that helped establish my professional network and have benefited me in the years since.  As a young professional, I continued to stay involved with both technical and networking activities that contributed to my professional development.  These investments of time and effort led to opportunities that have allowed me to have a challenging and rewarding professional career.

1706.prez_name: International Experience: Preparing American Engineers with Global Perspective

1707.prez_name: Leadership Development: A 15 Minute Crash Course
1707.prez_abstract: This presentation is intended to assist those individuals with no formal professional development training who are looking to understand and build the skills necessary for long-term career advancement.  The author will share some lessons learned over the course of a nearly 30-year career and from his participation in various formal professional development training sessions.  The presentation will cover what the author believes to be the most important leadership and professional skills in the form of theme explorations and short story reviews.  The talk will cover not only the skills needed for career advancement, but also unproductive professional behaviors that can limit career progression.  The overlap between personal and professional behaviors will be considered as will the importance of engagement in activities that can contribute to professional growth and career advancement.  Finally, the presentation will be supplemented by a one-page professional development guide that will be provided to attendees.

1708.prez_name: Measuring Up My Career (So Far) at NIST
1708.prez_abstract: This presentation will focus my experiences in federal civil service as a Materials Research Engineer at the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST). I'd like to share some of the advantages I've found working at NIST, as well as some challenges of an 'early' career scientist at a national lab. In addition I'd like to highlight the importance of keeping a good work/life/family balance and tips and techniques I've learned on share your work with the public (or friends and family).

1709.prez_abstract: Mentoring is so critically important in one’s career, especially for employees just starting out; however, it is often overlooked and undervalued.  Some companies, noting the value of mentorship for a successful career, have instituted formal mentoring programs and may have a system setup to match employees with mentors.  Newbies to a company should seek out and take advantage of this opportunity if it exists; if not, one should take action to establish this crucial connection.  A mentor could be someone with a similar background, someone who’s taken a different career path to offer an alternative point of view, or even someone who’s started just a few years prior to offer some words of wisdom.  In this presentation, I will share the impact that mentoring has had on my emerging materials career, and will offer tips on how to find great mentors and get the most out of a mentoring relationship.

1710.prez_name:
My International Metal Career: 
Production, Equipment and 
Services – From Entrepreneur to Corporate Structures
1710.prez_abstract: This presentation outlines the different stakeholder of the metal industry on a global view. It will show the various tasks and career path of a materials engineer; gathered experiences are critically compared. It will show benefits of international corporation, mid-size, family and single entity companies.

1711.prez_abstract: One piece of advice commonly given to students and recent graduates is to network, network, network. But why? And with whom? While in school, professional societies are easy to find and cheap to join. Many societies have established networking groups designed for students and young professionals and these can be very helpful. As an example, the American Ceramic Society has the President’s Council of Student Advisors (PCSA), the Global Graduate Research Network (GGRN), and the Young Professionals Network (YPN). Joining groups like these can aid in making connections and staying involved with the overall society. This talk will aim to generate discussion on the advantages of professional society membership and professional networks for students and emerging professionals and how to get the most benefit from joining. It will also compare and contrast some of the materials-oriented societies open to students and young professionals and look briefly at online networking options.

1712.prez_name: New Challenges, New Connections and New Solutions
1712.prez_abstract: A materials engineer or scientist will wear many hats during his or her career, and this is especially true in the energy industry. From forensic analysis to cutting-edge material research, from cast iron to functionalized nanoparticles, or from Houston, Texas, to Cape Town, South Africa, engineers and scientists continue to bring expertise and skills to find solutions to efficiently bring energy to the customers who need it. Doing this well requires quickly adapting to new problems, connecting observation to fundamental material features, meeting new experts and effectively communicating your new understanding. Accomplishing these feats opens new challenges and new opportunities for continued scientific and career exploration. The presentation will share examples of these key points from an oil and gas materials scientist.

1713.prez_abstract: “It’s not what you know, it’s who you know.”  There is a lot of truth in this statement.  Obviously you need to have a strong technical base, but it is the network of friends and colleagues that push or pull you through your career.  Involvement in professional societies is a great opportunity to start a network outside of your company and develop leadership skills.  My involvement with professional societies means that I have a network of experts to call or email any time I have a question outside of my expertise, and I can solve the problem faster than my neighbor searching the internet.  My professional network has provided me job opportunities and travel opportunities.  This presentation will cover examples of networking success stories, as well as tips for starting and expanding your network.
