1802.prez_name: C-16: Effect of Silicon on Microstructure Development between Al2O3/SiO2/ZrO2  at 1450°C
1802.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1802.prez_authors: Yu-Hsiang  Chen, Kun-Lin  Lin, Chien-Cheng  Lin
1802.prez_abstract: Different kinds of ceramics were reacted to silicon in order to evaluate the suitable materials for crystal growth of silicon under the Czochralski process (CZ). Three types of Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>, SiO<SUB>2</SUB>, and ZrO<SUB>2</SUB> plates were reacted with silicon wafer at 1450°C/30 min in Ar. The interfacial characterization of the reaction between Si/ceramics was performed by using SEM, TEM, and EDS. The oxygen concentration of Si will be executed by FTIR. Among them, large amounts of dislocations were found in Si/SiO<SUB>2</SUB> joint due to the difference of coefficient of thermal expansion (CTE). Only one intermetallic compound, Zr-Si phase, was found in the Si/ZrO<SUB>2</SUB> joint caused by the diffusion of Zr from ZrO<SUB>2</SUB> into Si. In Si/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> joint, few dislocations at the interface, no any intermetallic compounds, and low oxygen dissolution was found and support that the Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> could be a suitable material for Si growth application.

1803.prez_name: C-17: Lamp Furnace for In-situ Diffraction and Total Scattering Studies in Controlled Atmospheres
1803.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1803.prez_authors: Pankaj  Sarin, Daniel  Lowry, Sanjit  Ghose
1803.prez_abstract: A novel lamp furnace has been developed to conduct X-ray diffraction and total scattering studies at high temperatures in user defined environments using synchrotron radiation. The furnace uses three halogen lamps with ellipsoidal reflectors positioned in a brass housing such that their second focal point is coincident. The sample is also positioned at this point, however it is inside a fused quartz flow cell. The atmosphere inside the cell can be controlled by flow of select gases. The sample can also be rotated during acquisition of X-ray diffraction and total scattering data. The furnace was successfully tested to study the short and long range structural changes occurring during oxidation of refractory diborides up to 1400 C.

1804.prez_name: Ca12Al14O33 Electride Formation in Hot-uniaxial Press
1804.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1804.prez_authors: John Robert  Salasin, Sabrina  Schwerzler, Claudia  Rawn
1804.prez_abstract: Ca<sub>12</sub>Al<sub>14</sub>O<sub>33</sub>,(C12A7), forms a cage framework containing Ca and Al cations and 32 of the 33 anions. The remaining anion is distributed within the six cages formed by the framework.  When processed in a reducing environment occluded O anions are substituted with localized electrons and the resultant compound forms an inorganic electride. The electronic conductivity can be tuned through process duration and temperature  and a insulator–semi–metallic conductor transition is observed. We attempt to process powder C12A7 into a fully dense electronic conductor through hot-uni-axial-pressing (HUP) to retain desired microstructural characteristics. At temperatures below 1100 °C no electride formation was observed and at 1200 °C the C12A7 structure decomposes. When the temperature is raised to 1250 °C the electride C12A7 is formed and near theoretical density is reached.  The origins of this temperature dependent electride formation will be discussed and the resultant electronic properties compared to other techniques.

1805.prez_name: Coexistence and Domain Dynamics of Ferroelectric Phases in Vicinity of the MPB
1805.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1805.prez_authors: Oscar  Torres, Edwin  Garcia, Catherine  Bishop
1805.prez_abstract: Pb-containing and Pb-free ferroelectrics are of great interest for electromechanical applications. It is well known that near the Morphotropic Phase Boundary (MPB) dielectric and piezoelectric properties are maximal, stimulating the identification and development of chemistries such as the BZT-BCT system. While field-induced phase transitions, appearance of metastable phases, and coexistence of ferroelectric phases across a finite temperature and compositional range have been reported, existing theoretical descriptions cannot describe the MPB directly or shed light on the structural state near this region of phase space. Other models couple the response of the adjoining phases in a contrived way. In this paper, we present a thermodynamically consistent phase field formulation that naturally integrates the properties of two ferroelectric phases to describe the local equilibrium close to the MPB. Two-phase coexistence as a function of applied and self-induced fields is explored and rationalized as the MPB temperature is approached for the BZT-BCT system.

1806.prez_name: Controlling Ferroelastic Phase Transformation in Rare-earth Ortho-niobates
1806.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1806.prez_abstract: Rare earth ortho-niobates undergo a reversible, pure ferroelastic phase transformation from a monoclinic phase at low temperatures to a tetragonal phase at high temperatures.  The presence of 6.5 to 7% of spontaneous strains in the room temperature phase, together with the second order nature of this transformation, has generated considerable interest in these materials. This study focused on controlling their ferroelastic transformation behavior.  Phase stability and transformation properties of a series of pure and doped rare-earth niobate compositions was investigated by thermal analysis methods and by -situ diffraction using synchrotron radiation. Our findings indicate that the size of the rare earth cation is an important parameter that can influence the transformation temperature, as well as the extent of substitution with an aliovalent cation. Co-substitution of the rare-earth and the niobium cations with aliovalent cation was found to have a significant effect on the spontaneous strains.

1807.prez_name: Crystal Structures, Phase Transformations and Properties of Ceramics
1807.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1807.prez_abstract: Here we review the studies of the crystal structure and phase transformation of some ceramic materials through in situ synchrotron X-ray and neutron diffraction measurements up to 1800 K. Hexagonal-monoclinic phase transition of calcium hydroxyapatite is accompanied by the occupational and orientational ordering of OH– ions, the tilting of PO4 tetrahedron and the Ca displacements [[J. Phys. Chem. C, Vol.115, 25077 (2011); Vol.118, 5180 (2014)]. We have determined the crystal structure of ferrielectric AgNbO3 (Pmc21) and found that the atomic displacements along the c axis in Pmc21 AgNbO3 are responsible for the spontaneous polarization, ferrielectricity and the paraelectric-to-ferrielectric phase transition [Chem. Mater., Vol.23, 3135 (2011)]. The atomic displacements are induced by the Nb-O and Ag-O covalent bonding. The strong (Bi,Pb)-O covalent bonding is responsible for the spontaneous polarization, ferroelectricity and paraelectric-to-ferroelectric phase transition of the high TC ferroelectric (PbTiO3)0.4(BiFeO3)0.6 with large tetragonality [Chem. Mater., Vol.23, 1643 (2011)].

1808.prez_name: Directions of Zero Thermal Expansion in Anisotropic Oxides
1808.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1808.prez_authors: Scott James McCormack, William  Wheeler, Waltraud  Kriven
1808.prez_abstract: Oxide materials tend to have anisotropic crystal structures, which results in material properties being dependent on direction. Typically, oxide materials have positive thermal expansion coefficients. However, it has been observed that some directions can have negative thermal expansion coefficients over certain temperature ranges. These oxide materials, which exhibit directions of positive and negative thermal expansion, will also have a particular direction in which the thermal expansion is zero. By using the Quadrupole Lamp Furnace (QLF) developed in the Kriven group, high temperature in-situ x-ray diffraction has been performed at the National Synchrotron Light Source II (NSLSII) X-ray powder diffraction beamline (XPD – 28-ID) to track these directions of zero thermal expansion in orthorhombic HfTiO4 and ZrTiO4. These measurements are important for identifying materials which will be dimensionally accurate at elevated temperatures.

1809.prez_name: Effects of Crystallographic Orientation and Pre-existing Defect on Mechanical Properties of Polycrystalline Yttria-stabilized Tetragonal Zirconia
1809.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1809.prez_abstract: In this work we study the effects of crystallographic orientation and pre-existing void on mechanical properties of polycrystalline yttria-stabilized tetragonal zirconia (YSTZ), as well as the corresponding atomic failure pattern. For this reason, molecular dynamics simulations are performed. Four typical YSTZ polycrystals with nanograins deformed by different dominant mechanisms including phase transformation, dislocation, combined-phase transformation-dislocation and the mixture of them, are generated. Our simulation results suggest that the crystallographic orientation of nanograins plays a significant role on mechanical behavior of polycrystalline YSTZ. Dislocation dominated YSTZ polycrystal shows the smallest yield stress, while phase transformation governed one leads to the highest strength. The amount of high strain atoms is found to be in proportion to the yield stress of specimen. With the introduction of nanovoid, dislocation and phase transformation are observed to nucleate around the void. Crack formation is identified in the YSTZ polycrystal that dominated by combined-phase transformation-dislocation after compression.

1810.prez_name: First-principles Phase Diagram Calculations for the Rocksalt-structure Quasibinary Systems TiN-ZrN, TiN-HfN and ZrN-HfN
1810.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1810.prez_authors: Zhi  Liu, Benjamin P. Burton, Sanjay V. Khare, Daniel  Gall
1810.prez_abstract: We have studied phase equilibria of ceramic quasibinary systems Ti1-xZrxN, Ti1-xHfxN and Zr1-xHfxN (0 ≤ x ≤ 1) with density functional theory, cluster expansion and Monte Carlo simulations. We predict consolute temperatures (TC) for Ti1-xZrxN to be 1400 K, for Ti1-xHfxN to be 700 K, and for Zr1-xHfxN to be below 200 K. The asymmetry of the formation energy ΔEf(x) is greater for Ti1-xHfxN than Ti1-xZrxN, with less solubility on the smaller cation TiN-side, and similar asymmetries were predicted for the corresponding phase diagrams. We also analyze two mutually partial-canceling energetic contributions and discuss their influence on the magnitude of TC and asymmetry of ΔEf(x) as well as phase boundaries. We conclude that the absence of experimentally observed phase separation in Ti1-xZrxN and Ti1-xHfxN is due to slow kinetics at low temperatures. The mixed thin films show consistency and stability with little phase separation, making them desirable coating choices.

1811.prez_name: Grain Boundary Phase-like Transformations and Their Roles in Activated Sintering and Beyond
1811.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1811.prez_abstract: Materials scientists have long recognized that grain boundaries (GBs) can undergo phase-like transformations, which can affect the fabrication and properties of a broad range of metals and ceramics. This talk will review our recent studies to extend the bulk CALPHAD methods to GBs to compute "GB diagrams" to predict the formation of nanometer-thick, premelting-like, intergranular films and related activated sintering and other properties [J. Am. Ceram. Soc. 95:2358 (2012)]. Recently, this work has been further extended to multicomponent alloys [Acta Mater. 91:201 (2015); Current Opinion, 20:268 (2016)], as well as from simpler metals to more complexion ceramics such as CuO-doped TiO2 [Nie et al., Acta Mater. in press (2017)]. More rigorous "GB phase (complexion) diagrams" with well-defined interfacial transition lines and critical points can also constructed.  In a broader perspective, these computed "GB (phase) diagrams" (as extensions to bulk phase diagrams) can be a generally useful materials science tool.

1812.prez_name: High-pressure Phase Transformation to Monazite Structure in Xenotime Rare-earth Orthophosphates
1812.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1812.prez_authors: Matthew A. Musselman, Taylor M. Wilkinson, Bianca  Haberl, Corinne E. Packard
1812.prez_abstract: Rare-earth orthophosphates (REPO4) are non-oxidizing, chemically stable ceramics that plastically deform more easily than other oxides with relatively high melting temperatures. In recent decades, they have shown potential as fiber coatings in oxide-oxide ceramic matrix composites (CMCs). In this application, a xenotime REPO4 composition consisting of a GdxDy(1-x)PO4 solid solution exhibited reduced fiber push-out stresses compared to monazite LaPO4. In this study, we characterize the phase transformation behavior of GdxDy(1-x)PO4 solid solutions and some neighboring xenotime REPO4s at ambient temperature under high pressures inside a diamond anvil cell with in situ Raman spectroscopy. The onset transformation pressure is reported at the formation of a new set of Raman peaks that corresponds with previous reports of the monazite-structured REPO4. Raman spectra collected throughout compression and decompression were analyzed for high pressure phenomena and reversibility of the phase transformations. The results are compared with previous research on other similar REPO4 materials.

1813.prez_name: High Temperature Behavior in Entropy Stabilized Oxide (Mg0.2Co0.2Ni0.2Cu0.2Zn0.2)O
1813.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1813.prez_authors: Kuo-pin  Tseng, Scott  McCormack, Waltraud  Kriven
1813.prez_abstract: The high entropy oxide, (Mg0.2Co0.2Ni0.2Cu0.2Zn0.2)O, exists as a single cubic phase at ~1100oC with components well distributed inside. At 2000oC, the oxide material is partially melted so that each oxide (e.g. CoO, NiO) in this compound tends to phase separate and melt. The dominant material above 2000oC is magnesium oxide, which has a melting point at around 2800oC. The synchrotron experiment at the Advanced Photon Source (APS) shows no significant difference in XRD patterns due to the similarity between the crystal structures of the high entropy oxide and magnesium oxide.

1814.prez_name: In Situ Determination of Phase Equilibria, Thermal Expansion and Phase Transformations in the Ternary Hafnia-Tantala-Titania System
1814.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1814.prez_authors: Scott J. McCormack, Waltraud M. Kriven, Sergey   Ushakov, Alexandra   Navrotsky, Richard  Webber
1814.prez_abstract: This research aims to demonstrate a new, efficient and highly accurate method to determine ternary phase diagrams using rapid, in-situ, in air, synchrotron instruments, coupled with accurate, quantitative data analysis by the Rietveld method. Two approaches are adopted: heating up of precisely fabricated compositions and melting of these compositions as beads and cooling so as to map out the liquidi of the oxide melts. In addition, thermal expansion coefficients and crystal structures are analyzed for any new phases discovered in the ternary phase diagram. The hafnia-titania-tantala ternary was selected as the model system. Both hafnia and tantala exhibit phase transformations.

1815.prez_name: Magnesium Oxychloride: Formation Kinetics Formation and Water Stability Enhancement
1815.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1815.prez_abstract: Magnesium oxychloride is a ceramic material with significant fire-resistant properties passive fire protection systems. The present study examined the cure reaction at temperatures from 35 to 55 C using time-resolved quantitative X-ray diffraction and DSC to monitor kinetics. A maximum crystallinity of 82–84% was achieved for each temperature. Assuming first-order kinetics for both MgO dissolution and MOC crystallization, a kinetic model predicts 42.4 and 26.1 kJ/mol for dissolution and crystallization activation energies, respectively. The Avrami model was fit to DSC data. This model predicts diffusion-controlled, one-dimensional growth with an activation energy of 72.4 kJ/mol. Additionally, water stability of this material was studied and was improved by the exposure to carbon dioxide to form chlorartinite, a protective semi-insoluble layer that forms around the crystals. Phosphoric acid has also been found to increase water stability, at the cost of a decrease in crystallinity.

1816.prez_name: Martensitic Transformation in Granular Shape Memory Ceramic Packings
1816.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1816.prez_authors: Hang Z. Yu, Hunter   Rauch, Mostafa   Hassani-Gangaraj , Zehui  Du, Chee Lip  Gan, Christopher   Schuh
1816.prez_abstract: Shape memory ceramics (SMCs), which are recently discovered with excellent shape memory and superelastic properties on the small scale, can be scaled up for bulk applications in the form of granular packings despite their intrinsic brittleness. In this talk, the fundamentals of stress and heat-induced martensitic transformation are explored for granular SMC packings.  In the shape memory regime, where dopant levels place the martensite finish temperature above the testing temperature, compaction results in load-dependent martensite reorientation. In the intermediate regime, where the testing temperature falls between the martensite start and austenite start temperatures, compaction causes an irreversible transformation that provides direct and quantitative evidence for stress-induced martensitic transformation in powder-die compaction. In the superelastic regime, where the testing temperature is above the austenite finish temperature, compaction and unloading result in forward and reverse martensitic transformations as supported by in situ phase characterization using neutron scattering.

1817.prez_name: Novel Microstructures and Innovative Processing in Cobalt Titanate
1817.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1817.prez_authors: Kevin P.  Anderson, Anit K. Giri, Richard P. Vinci, Helen M. Chan
1817.prez_abstract: Nanoscale ceramic matrix composites offer unique and exciting properties, but are limited by complex processing requirements.  Exploiting phase transformations such as eutectoid decomposition and partial reduction of mixed oxides presents a straightforward means of producing ceramic matrix composites with tunable microstructures.  These reactions were employed using powder compositions in the Co-Ti-O system, in which the CoTi<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>5</SUB> phase undergoes a eutectoid transformation to CoTiO<SUB>3</SUB> + TiO<SUB>2</SUB>.  Subsequently applying partial reduction to this composite produces a Co-TiO<SUB>2</SUB> composite with a novel microstructure.  By varying time and temperature both the eutectoid and partial reduction reactions can be controlled to yield composite microstructures of tunable scale, including nanocomposites.  The phase transformations and resulting microstructures will be discussed in reference to the morphology and scale of the composites, as well as the crystallographic relationships between the phases.  Microstructures were characterized through XRD, SEM, EBSD, and TEM.

1818.prez_name: Phase and Microstructural Evolution of Yttrium Disilicate in High-temperature High-velocity Water Vapor
1818.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1818.prez_abstract: Oxides are generally considered to be stable in high-temperature oxidizing environments; however, most oxides react readily with high-temperature water vapor present in oxidizing combustion environments to form gaseous metal hydroxides.  Surface phase evolution of complex oxides occurs in high-temperature steam as the component oxides have different stabilities towards reaction with the steam.  In this presentation, the reaction of yttrium disilicate with high-temperature water vapor to form yttrium monosilicate and gaseous silicon hydroxide will be described in detail.  Key aspects of the yttrium disilicate reaction include the nucleation of fine grained yttrium monosilicate and porosity.  The formation kinetics and microstructural evolution of the yttrium monosilicate will be presented.  In addition, the temperature dependent processes contributing to the observed microstructural evolution will be examined.  Implications of this reaction for the use of yttrium disilicate as an Environmental Barrier Coating will be discussed.

1819.prez_name: Phase Equilibrium in the 30% Al2O3 Plane of the Quaternary CaO-SiO2-MgO- Al2O3 System
1819.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1819.prez_authors: Lifeng  Sun, Junjie  Shi, Jiyu  Qiu, Bo  Zhang, Maofa  Jiang
1819.prez_abstract: With the purpose of providing new phase equilibrium data, phase equilibria in 30% Al2O3 plane of the CaO-SiO2-MgO-Al2O3 system at 1500°C were experimental investigated using the high temperature equilibration technique followed by x-ray diffraction (XRD), scanning electron microscope (SEM) and energy dispersive x-ray spectroscopy (EDX) analysis. The level rule was used to judge the equilibrium phases and the two-phase equilibration relations of liquid with CaO, liquid with 2CaO·SiO2 and three-phase equilibrium relation of liquid coexist with CaO and MgO was obtained based on the experimental result. The effect of MgO, CaO and SiO2 on 1500°C liquidus line have been discussed. The solubility of 2CaO·SiO2 and MgO at 1500°C were found to be higher in comparison with the existing phase diagram while the solubility of CaO was found to be somewhat lower.

1820.prez_name: Phase Transformation and Evolution of Ceramic-metal Composites with Unique Hierachical Microstructures
1820.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1820.prez_authors: Michael Robert Kracum, Kevin  Anderson, Christopher  Marvel, Mihaela  Albu, Martin P. Harmer, Ferdinand  Hofer, Helen M. Chan
1820.prez_abstract: Phase transformations involving complex oxides of the type AxByOz can result in unique ceramic-ceramic or metal-ceramic microstructures.  Recent work at Lehigh has used various complex oxides as precursors to form metal-ceramic composites. A partial-reduction phase transformation of the mixed oxides forms composites with structures at multiple length scales, structures that are otherwise difficult to achieve using traditional processing methods.  In particular, delafossite-structured CuAlO2 produces hierarchical composites of copper and alumina with ordered features on the nanometer and micrometer scales.  This talk will focus on the phase transformation and evolution of the composite microstructures, as well as strategies for microstructure control.  Cs-corrected HAADF-STEM was used to examine the reaction fronts and to elucidate nanoscale features of the composite.  Preliminary results on the mechanical properties of the composites, together with alternative bulk fabrication routes for this class of composite, will be presented.

1821.prez_name: Prediction of Diffusionless Phase Transformations in Complex Materials
1821.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1821.prez_authors: Randall  Hay, Pavel  Mogilevsky, Emmanuel  Boakye
1821.prez_abstract: Methods to predict diffusionless phase transformations in arbitrary complex crystal structures with ionic and iono-covalent bonding are in development. Transformation orientation relationships are predicted using near-coincidence site lattices (NCSLs). Transformations where all atom shuffles are less than 1/2 the bond length are diffusionless. The methods will be useful for prediction and design of complex binary, ternary, and quaternary oxides, carbides, nitrides, and borides for environmental barrier coatings, thermal protection systems, and other high temperature structures. The calculations are tested for transformations in rare-earth disilicates (Re2Si2O7), for which there are at least 13 polymorphs with approximately 30 feasible polymorphic phase transformations. Identified compositions are tested for softening by transformation plasticity.

1822.prez_name: Simulation and Experiments of Template-directed Eutectic Solidification for Nanophotonic Metamaterials
1822.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1822.prez_authors: Erik  Hanson, Julia  Kohanek, Ashish  Kulkarni, Runyu  Zhang, Katsuyo  Thornton, Paul  Braun
1822.prez_abstract: Photonic metamaterials are composite materials structured with a periodicity below the wavelength of light and can be used to create optical responses not possible in nature, such as negative refractive indices. Self-organization techniques, such as eutectic solidification, are being explored to fabricate large-area optical metamaterials. Solidifying a eutectic material through a non-reactive periodic template yields structures with more complexity and with different length scales than those of either the native eutectic material or the template alone. The effect of a template’s geometric confinement is investigated through both modeling and experiment. Phase-field simulations utilizing the smoothed boundary method (SBM) to include template-eutectic interactions are conducted, and the predictions are used to guide the design of template/eutectic combinations in experiments. The effect of material properties, processing parameters, and template geometries on the resulting nanostructures and optical responses are examined.

1823.prez_name: Structural Characterization of Nanoscale Phase Transitions: New Approaches
1823.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1823.prez_authors: Scott  Misture, Robert  Koch, Peter  Metz, Guangfang  Li, Hui  Wang
1823.prez_abstract: Oxide-metal core-shell nanoparticles represent useful precursors for hierarchically structured spongy nanoframes with morphologies tuned based on alloy composition and the choice and concentration of chemical etchant. Similarly hierarchical oxide systems can be built from nanosheet assemblies, where condensation reactions link adjacent sheets to form tunnel structures with porosity on the nanometer and micrometer scales. The phase transitions that occur in these systems define their final nanoscale morphologies, but the mechanisms by which these phase transformations occur have remained clouded by our inability to characterize materials with disorder on the nanometer scale. In-situ X-ray diffraction and synchrotron-based pair distribution function studies enable characterization of sub-milligram quantities of systems like Au-Cu2O core-shell nanoparticles and MnO2 nanosheet assemblies. The talk will highlight the use of subtle changes in diffraction peak shapes and PDF analysis to understand the phase transitions leading to hierarchical porosity in oxide nanosheet assemblies oxide-metal core-shell nanoparticles.

1824.prez_name: Thermodynamic Investigation on the Stoichiometry of PMN-PT Single Crystals
1824.symp_name: Phase Transformations in Ceramics: Science and Applications
1824.prez_authors: Hooman  Sabarou, Dehua  Huang, Yu Michael Zhong
1824.prez_abstract: A new thermodynamic approach on the structural evolution of Pb(Mg1/3Nb2/3)O3-xPbTiO3 (PMN-PT) single crystal has been carried out, and it is used to justify the inconsistency of the ferroelectric properties of single-crystal perovskite. A series of experimental tests under different temperatures and oxygen partial pressures has been applied to simulate the required working conditions of these materials. The phase stability and structural changes have been scrutinized via X-ray diffraction, Raman spectroscopy, and thermogravimetric methods. The involved mechanism explains how crystal structure transformation can contribute in the ferroelectric degradation. According to XRD and Raman spectroscopy, the defect chemistry of the PMN-PT with perovskite structure controls the crystal phase transition inside the material and subsequently changes the ferroelectric properties of the PMN-PT. The proposed mechanism can justify the ferroelectric degradation for other PMN-PT compositions.

1825.prez_name: A Look at Where We Stand on Addressing Technology Needs for Diversifying the Supply of Critical Materials for Clean Energy
1825.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1825.prez_abstract: Since 2013 the Critical Materials Institute (CMI) funded by the US Department of Energy has been developing technologies aimed at reducing the supply risk for five rare earth elements and several other elements. Within a shifting landscape, materials enabling clean, carbon-free production and utilization of energy include wind power, energy-efficient lighting, electric vehicles, photovoltaic solar panels, batteries, and nuclear power have been of greatest interest. This presentation will examine technology gaps in the supply chains for critical materials and the corresponding strategy within CMI for addressing those gaps. After over four years of effort, some significant strides have been made, and the key accomplishments will be presented. Results fall in three thrust areas: expanding supply by solving problems in metal recovery from primary sources, making processing more competitive, and driving the economics by finding new uses for co-products.

1826.prez_name: Advances in REE Metal Making Technologies – A Review
1826.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1826.prez_authors: Patrick  Taylor, Matt  Earlam, Fangyu   Liu
1826.prez_abstract: This paper reviews the technology that has been used, or studied, for the production of rare earth metals. The background covers work done in the past on various chemical routes that have looked at the production of metals from oxide, fluoride and chloride precursors. This will include descriptions of the various methods for oxides, chlorides and fluorides; metallothermic reduction; formation of intermediate alloys; lanthanothermy;  distillation; carbothermic reduction; and electrolytic production.  , This is followed by the current methods that are being used to produce these metals. This is followed by an overview of some of the current technologies’ being developed . Lastly, some conclusions and suggestions for additional developments are given.

1827.prez_name: Advances in Scalable Nano-manufacturing and Assembly Techniques  - Role of REEs
1827.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1827.prez_abstract: Here we will explore recent advances by IMS in the synthesis of crystalline rare earth materials, control of the many tunable properties and the technologies enabled by the advances in rare earth synthesis. The ability to produce high quality nanomaterials has advanced our understanding of these properties, opening the door for application across many areas of industry such as authentication, life science, quantum computing, transportation among others.  The tunable nature of these materials is becoming well established, specifically the optical properties which can be precisely controlled along various parameters such as emission, absorption and lifetimes (rise and decay).  Also, the development of new classes of host materials and rare earth doping strategies has improved the versatility of use by expanding the ranges of energy conversion from X-Ray to mid infrared to sonoluminescent and magneto-optic materials.

1828.prez_name: An Aluminum Alloy Containing Rare Earth Elements for Elevated Temperature Applications
1828.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1828.prez_abstract: Mechanical property advantages of a unique, dispersion-strengthened aluminum alloy, containing rare earth elements, gadolinium (Gd) and scandium (Sc) are described. The alloy, named Pandalloy® Gen2, has superior room and elevated temperature strength compared to conventional aluminum alloys such as AA2618-T61. The alloy also has a specific strength and elastic modulus that exceed those of Ti-6Al-4V.  Pandalloy® Gen2 uses rapid solidification to create fine, thermally stable intermetallic particles composed of Al, Gd, Sc, Ni and Zr, which provide exceptional elevated temperature strength up to 700 °F (371°C) and beyond. For demanding applications, such as race car pistons, Pandalloy® Gen2 offers high tensile and fatigue strengths, excellent thermal stability and resistance to cracking, which enables higher combustion cylinder temperatures, greater horsepower and increased durability. In addition to pistons, Pandalloy® Gen2 is a cost-effective alternative for high performance components such as turbocharger compressor wheels, auxiliary power turbines and other elevated temperature applications.

1829.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1829.prez_abstract: This presentation will outline the fundamentals of Rare Earth beneficiation with a focus on flotation. Examples will include bastnasite, xenotime, eudilayte, monazite and ancylite minerals.

1830.prez_name: Cost-effective Separation of Rare-earth Elements Using the RapidSX(TM) Process
1830.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1830.prez_authors: Gareth  Hatch, Darcy  Tait, Patrick  Wong
1830.prez_abstract:
The rare-earth element (REE) supply chain is currently dominated by China. The development of independent sources of REEs will require new, cost-effective methods of separating REE concentrates. The RapidSX process combines the time-proven chemistry of solvent extraction (SX), with a new processing platform. The approach significantly accelerates process kinetics, reducing the number of SX separation stages by 85% and time to equilibrium by 75%. Plant footprint, power, water and organic reagent consumption are also significantly reduced. These factors lead to dramatic reductions in projected operating and capital costs for REE separation, while avoiding the use of expensive resins or other chemistries unproven at scale for REEs. The RapidSX process has been used to separate REEs with 99.97% purities at the pilot scale, with >99% extraction rates from initial REE feedstock solutions. The process has also been shown to be effective for
the separation of a number of other metal concentrates.

1831.prez_name: Current Status and Future Challenges Facing Rare Earth Materials Industry
1831.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1831.prez_abstract: An overview of current status and future challenges facing the implementation of technologies promoting Rare Earth Elements and their compounds in various industrial applications will be reviewed.

1832.prez_name: Defense Logistics Agency – Strategic Materials (DLA-SM): Possible Actions Towards Mitigating the Risk of Rare Earths Shortfall
1832.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1832.prez_abstract: An overview will be provided on the role of DLA-SM, which is responsible for acquiring, upgrading, and disposing of strategic and critical materials according to policies set forth by the National Defense Stockpile. To perform this task, analytical tools, models, data from various sources and methodologies are used to assess the potential disruptions to supplies of critical materials. A brief discussion will be provided to explain how DLA-SM considers acquisition of material as a mitigation approach, and the importance of material specifications in the acquisition process. DLA-SM evaluates the possible supply interruptions that could occur in a national emergency and charts out a process to mitigate the risks at the critical failure points in the supply chain. Mitigation options under DLA-SM authority include stockpiling material, material recycle and recovery efforts, qualifications of alternate materials, new research and development (R&D) initiatives and coordination with other federal agencies for industrial base actions.

1833.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1833.prez_abstract: Rare earth and rare metal projects usually involve complex processing options to produce marketable products.   To generate reasonable financial returns, these projects require stable and sustainable product prices, and economies of scale which usually relates to large upfront capital expenditure. As a result, large complex projects will often rely on innovative funding solutions needing the support of national financial institutions such as Export Credit Agencies and / or specific strategic agencies or companies that understand the national significance of the metal supply. Minimising technical and financial risk is of primary importance and this requires a substantial commitment to pilot plant proving and distribution of products to consumers for certification and off-take agreements.   The latter is an added complication with the industry dominated by spot selling, or at best, short term contracts which are rarely satisfactory for normal financiers.

1834.prez_name: Experimental Characterization of Discarded Electronic Batteries
1834.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1834.prez_authors: Otavio  Fortini, Christian  Mutale, Igor  Kolomytsin
1834.prez_abstract: Discarded electronic batteries have been often considered as an alternative source of rare earth elements. While lead acid batteries have been recycled in large quantities over the years, discarded electronic batteries still present technological challenges due to their chemical complexity. This study presents the characterization of electronic batteries in a typical US waste stream with the purpose of validating literature descriptions regarding the potential metal values found in these batteries. The sample included batteries from computers, cellular phones, power tools, digital cameras, and remote controls. The samples were characterized for component mass distributions (shell, wiring, and power cells), elemental composition, and leachability in strong acid solutions. The results show that value metals are present in leachable form and suggest a selective dissolution mechanism where the energy storage layer is removed before any reaction of metal substrates takes place.

1835.prez_name: Historical Perspectives on Rare Earths, Critical Materials, and the Legacy of Karl Gschneidner
1835.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1835.prez_abstract: Many of the modern uses of rare earth elements are intimately linked to the scientific contributions made by Karl Gschneidner over his long and distinguished career. Karl began his professional career following the award of his Ph.D. in 1957, and advanced technical uses of the rare earths started in the 1960’s, which saw the development of new fluid cracking catalysts and efficient red light emitting phosphors.  Computer memories, permanent magnets, rechargeable batteries, lasers, magnetostrictive actuators, high-temperature superconductors, magnetocaloric materials, and many others emerged as the understanding of the rare earths grew.   We will trace some of the linkages between Gschneidner's contributions and the rare earth technologies, and also touch upon the Karl’s influence on the “critical material” status of the rare earths.

1836.prez_name: Investigation of Al-Sc Alloy for Lightweight Armor
1836.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1836.prez_authors: Eric M. Klier, Nhon Q. Vo, Denver B. Gallardy, Kevin J.  Doherty, David N. Seidman, David C. Dunand, Matthew S. Burkins
1836.prez_abstract: Additions of Scandium (Sc) to aluminum alloys have been shown to offer significant advantages which may be beneficial to lightweight armor.  In this work, Al-4.5 Mg-0.4 Sc-0.05 Zr wt.% (AA5024) plates were fabricated and optimized through rolling and heat aging process to maximize strength at a minimum elongation requirement of 8%.  Ballistic characterization of the AA5024 and similarly produced control Al-4.5 Mg-0.7 Mn-0.15 Cr wt.% (AA5083) alloy (H13 temper) was performed.  The V<SUB>50</SUB> ballistic limit for 1 inch thick plate was determined against 0.30 cal AP M2 and 0.50 cal FSP at 0<SUP>o</SUP> obliquity.  Optimized AA5024 displayed a 40% increase in yield strength and 25% increase in ultimate tensile strength, with a lower elongation of 8.7% versus 11.1%, as compared to the AA5083-H13.  The AA5024 exhibited a V<SUB>50</SUB> ballistic limit increase of 7% against AP and 11% against FSP versus AA5083-H13.  The effect of friction stir welding was also investigated.

1837.prez_name: Magnetocalorics: Rare Earths are Paving the Way to Efficient Cooling
1837.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1837.prez_abstract:
Now twenty years old, the discovery of the giant magnetocaloric effect in Gd5Si2Ge2 generated a broad interest in the magnetocaloric effect and magnetic refrigeration near room temperature in particular, and magneto-structural transitions in general.  Last decade has been also marked by rising interest in materials exhibiting strong electrocaloric, elastocaloric (a.k.a. thermoelastic), and barocaloric effects.  Common to all materials that exhibit the giant magnetocaloric effect is the coupling of magnetic and elastic effects.  In addition to the interplay between magnetic and lattice entropies, microstructure and nanostructure, play a role in controlling both the magnetostructural transition(s) and magnetocaloric effect.  The role of different control parameters and the potential pathways towards materials exhibiting strong magnetocaloric effects will be discussed.
Ames Laboratory is supported by the Division of Materials Science and Engineering of the Office of Basic Energy Sciences of the U.S. Department of Energy under contract No. DE-AC02-07CH11358 with Iowa State University.

1838.prez_name: Molecular Recognition Technology: A Green Chemistry, Economical Process for Separation and Recovery of Individual Rare Earth Metals
1838.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1838.prez_authors: Steven  Izatt, Ronald L Bruening, Neil E Izatt, Reed M Izatt
1838.prez_abstract: Molecular Recognition Technology (MRT) is a proven green chemistry process using SuperLig® products that enables selective recovery of individual rare earth elements (REE).  Separation from pregnant leach solutions (PLS) can be accomplished at 99% or higher levels.  Recoveries of 99% REE versus that in the PLS are achieved.  No solvents are used and minimal waste is generated.  The separation of Dy at 99.99% purity has been demonstrated at pilot scale.  Separation of Dy from neighboring REE was achieved at many fewer stages than is required for conventional technologies.  These achievements have significant implications regarding capital and operating expenses.  High metal selectivity of SuperLig® products using proprietary pre-designed ligands coupled with simplicity of MRT systems in design and operation result in significant reduction in capital and operating expenses for REE separations and recovery.  This disruptive MRT system points the way to restoring U.S. production of individual REE.

1839.prez_name: New Aluminum Alloys Based on Common Rare Earth Additives
1839.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1839.prez_abstract: Aluminum alloys containing cerium in near eutectic compositions have demonstrated high mechanical properties at temperatures over 250C. These alloys, which can contain magnesium, silicon, nickel or iron as secondary alloying elements, are suitable for all casting processes including high pressure diecasting, squeeze casting, permanent mold and sand casting. The alloys can be used in similar formulations for forging and extrusion. The Al-Ce alloy system can be used as a common template for wide-ranging alloy development, similar to the Al-Si system. The Al-Ce forms an intermetallic that is stable up to the melting point of the alloy. The near zero solubility of Ce in aluminum limits diffusion and Ostwald ripening. At cooling rates that are typical of some casting processes, the intermetallic formed is on the scale of 100-200 nanometers contributing to effective dispersion strengthening. This paper discusses the strengthening mechanisms, properties and applications of the Al-Ce-Mg alloy system.

1840.prez_name: On The Utility of Rare Earth Elements as Alloying Additions to Magnesium Alloys: Current Status and Considerations
1840.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1840.prez_abstract: Rare earth elements (REEs), namely Ce, La, Nd, Pr, Er, Y, Gd and Sc, are commonly employed as alloying additions to magnesium alloys. The role of individual REEs is unique. In a general sense, REEs are unique in the context of Mg-alloys, in that they present appreciable solid solubility in Mg (although the extent varies greatly depending on the specific element). Such solid solubility and its variation with temperature permits the development of age hardenable Mg-alloys, and is the basis of several well accepted commercial Mg-alloys. In the present work, the following aspects are discussed in a contemporary light; (i) high strength Mg-RE alloys, (ii) the role of minor RE additions in texture control of Mg-alloys, (iii) the role of REEs in Mg-Li alloys, and (iv) the emerging aspects related to the use of REEs in Mg alloys.

1841.prez_name: Opportunities and Challenges for the Rare Earth Magnet Industry
1841.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1841.prez_abstract: Three generations of rare earth magnets, Sm-Co 1:5, Sm-Co 2:17, and Nd-Fe-B 2:14:1, are commercially available today. Their high magnetic performance led to numerous applications including aerospace, medical, semiconductor, telecommunications, power generation, oil & gas exploration, and automotive industries.  There have been many new developments in recent years including high energy Nd-Fe-B magnets with no or less heavy rare earth elements, radially oriented anisotropic rings, and high energy Sm-Co magnets for high temperature applications. The search for new magnet materials has been very active for many years, but huge challenges still remain at the R & D front. Rare earth magnet market also faces a lot of challenges in recent years including volatile raw materials market, overcapacity problems in China, and Nd-Fe-B patent issues. This talk will discuss some of the opportunities and challenges for the rare earth magnet business.

1842.prez_name: Partial Substitution of Scandium with Rare-Earth Elements in Dilute Al-Sc-RE Alloys with Nanometric, Coherent Trialuminide Precipitates
1842.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1842.prez_abstract: are-earth elements (RE = Y, Sm, Gd, Dy, Er, or Yb) are added to binary dilute Al-Sc alloys to partially replace scandium, resulting in Al-Sc-RE alloys with modified precipitation kinetics, microstructures and mechanical properties.  As compared to binary Al-Sc, the ternary alloys exhibit: (i) the same incubation time, except for Er and Yb which accelerate microhardening; (ii) the same, or a reduced, peak microhardnesses; and (iii) the same over-aging behavior. All REs segregate to the core of Al3(Sc,RE) precipitates, as determined employing atom probe tomography.  The creep resistance of the Al-Sc-RE alloys is substantially improved, as the Al3(Sc,RE) precipitates exhibit an increase in the lattice parameter mismatch with the matrix, which results in strong interactions with matrix dislocations.  Among these REs, Er and Yb are particularly interesting given their relatively high solubility in Al and complete solubility in Al3Sc, and their significantly lower price as compared to Sc.

1843.prez_name: Processing Recycled Rare Earth Magnet Alloys
1843.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1843.prez_authors: John P de Neufville, David  Murphy, Randall  Ice
1843.prez_abstract: Eutectix, LLC resulted from the recent acquisition and restart of two rare earth magnet alloy manufacturing companies: Great Western Technology, Inc. and Molycorp Metals and Alloys, Inc.  This talk will review the technology of some specific processes of potential use in the recycling of scrapped rare earth magnet materials.  These processes include: 1.Decrepitation via hydriding at elevated temperatures with mechanical agitation; 2. Fluorination of mixed or pure RE oxides; 3. Calciothermic reduction of RE fluorides to produce rare earth metals; 4. Vacuum induction melting of REmagnet alloy compositions; and, 5. Rapid quenching of the molten magnet alloys to form strip-cast or melt spun powders for subsequent processing into sintered or polymer bonded magnets. There are additional or alternative technologies required to complete the entire recycling process. National security requirements may drive this process, involving extensive government investment and collaboration among the various potential technology providers and manufacturers.

1844.prez_name: Production Status and Forecast for the Availability of Rare Earth Materials
1844.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1844.prez_abstract: Rapid changes to the market for technology products has had a pronounced affect upon permanent magnet raw material supply, magnet production and device design.  This was evidenced in the “rare earth crisis” of 2011-12.  Further supply and usage challenges are anticipated.  Rare earth oxides, metals and alloys remain supplied from China at over 90% of the global total.   Rare earths are consumed in increasing amounts for non-magnet applications such as catalysis.  Cobalt, another critical element and required for samarium cobalt high temperature magnets and for improving NdFeB magnets, is increasingly consumed by the lithium-ion battery market.  Material supply chains will be reviewed along with supply and usage forecasts for several key elements.

1845.prez_name: Prospects for New Rare-earth Mines Outside of China: What Happened to the 400 Exploration Projects?
1845.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1845.prez_abstract: During and immediately following the boom in rare-earth prices in 2010-2011, the trade press reported that some 400 mineral occurrences were being evaluated for possible development into rare-earth mines. This paper reviews the progress these projects made in developing formal resource and reserve estimates and the movement from scoping to pre-feasibility and feasibility assessment. Following the fall in rare-earth prices after 2011, most of these these projects were abandoned or at a minimum were suspended. But a few are positioned to become mines should prices rise or process engineering improve such that costs are lowered. Although the boom in rare-earth prices led to little additional production outside of China between 2011 and 2017, the boom stimulated the development of knowledge about rare-earth resources and innovation in process engineering; this knowledge and innovation almost certainly will lead to more-diversified rare-earth production in the future.

1846.prez_name: Rare-Earth Permanent Magnets without Heavy Rare Earth Elements: Recent Developments and Applications
1846.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1846.prez_authors: Yutaka  Yoshida, Atsushi  Hattori, Minoru  Aizaki, Takahiko  Iriyama
1846.prez_abstract:
Since the “rare-earth crisis” in 2010, the permanent magnet industry has been working to reduce or eliminate the use of HREE (Heavy Rare Earth Elements) that are effective in improving the heat resistance of Nd-Fe-B magnets for applications such as traction motors in electric or hybrid electric vehicles. 
The central issue is how to increase the coercivity of these magnets without the enhancement of magnetocrystalline anisotropy that HREEs provide. This requires a multi-faceted approach to optimize the microstructures. Through the utilization of melt-spinning and hot deformation techniques, we were able to control the grain size, grain orientation, and grain boundary characteristics to achieve a high coercivity of 20 kOe without the use of HREEs. Combined with the optimization of rotor designs, these HREE-free Nd-Fe-B magnets are now adopted for the new generation of hybrid electric vehicles. PLP (press-less process) sintered Nd-Fe-B and Sm-Fe-N polymer bonded magnets will also be discussed.

1847.prez_name: Rare Earth Metals (REMs) Additions for Precipitation Strengthening High-performance Al and AlMg Alloys
1847.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1847.prez_abstract: Scandium is the most potent strengthening element in aluminum, on a per-atom basis, via precipitation strengthening by coherent L12 ordered Al3X (X=Sc, RE, …) precipitates, permitting the development of high performance high-strength Al alloys for use in aerospace and similar applications. Other alloying additions can affect precipitation kinetics and structure, opening up the opportunity to fine-tune the hardening response. Precipitation strengthening, however, is generally limited by the amount of alloying additions that can be dissolved for subsequent nano-scale precipitation. This presentation describes industrial manufacturing approaches employing rapid solidification for generating hyper-eutectic highly supersaturated Al-Mg-Sc base materials, namely powder metallurgical processing for profiles, thin sheet strip casting and laser-powderbed-fusion for additive manufacturing (3D-printing). The resulting supersaturation attainable by each particular solidification technique as well related subsequent precipitation processes are characterized by atom-probe tomography. Properties and application potentials of these unique materials will be disclosed and partially discussed.

1848.prez_name: Replacing Scandium by Heavy Rare-earth Metals in High-performance Aluminum Alloys
1848.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1848.prez_authors: Nhon Q. Vo, Davaadorj  Bayansan, David C Dunand, David N Seidman
1848.prez_abstract: Scandium-containing aluminum alloys have shown excellent high-temperature mechanical properties due to formation of Al3Sc L12-ordered nano-precipitates in the matrix, acting as strong barriers to dislocation motion. The high cost of scandium, however, has led researchers to attempt to replace partially scandium by other elements, such as transition elements (Zr, Ti, Hf) and heavy rare-earth elements (Er, Yb). In this research, we discuss the ability of Er and Yb, individually or together, to replace and reduce Sc in aluminum superalloys. As an example, we will demonstrate a new Al-Er-Yb-Sc-Zr alloy, which has: (i) excellent aging resistance at temperatures up to 400 ºC; (ii) better creep resistance at elevated temperatures than prior studied Sc-containing aluminum alloys; (iii) can be produced through traditional casting methods; and (iv) excellent electrical and thermal conductivities.

1849.prez_name: Supply Chain Requirements for New Ocean Resource
1849.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1849.prez_authors: John  Halkyard, Nhon  Vo, Troy  Tack, Jack  Lifton
1849.prez_abstract: A very large commercialization potential exists for alloys of aluminum incorporating additions of Scandium (Sc) and specific Rare Earth Element (REE) substitutes for Sc. For this large Al-Sc/REE alloy potential to be realized, such that end-use applications such as disc brake rotors and the alloys used for them can be manufactured and produced in North America, a complete supply chain for such alloys and applications must be established in North America. This paper will address the requirements to establish a complete supply chain to take advantage of a recently discovered new resource: REE enriched deep sea sediments. Available technologies for treating the ore, separating the elements, refining the elements to master alloys and forming the alloys and parts required by the end user will be discussed.

1850.prez_name: Synthetic Methods for Establishing a Reliable Thermochemical Databank
1850.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1850.prez_authors: Richard Eric Riman, Zhichao  Hu, Paul  Kim, Daniel  Kopp, Ali  Eslamimanesh, Gaurav  Das, Andrzej  Anderko, Radha  Shivaramaiah, Lili  Wu, Alexandra  Navrotsky
1850.prez_abstract: The Critical Materials Institute (CMI) focuses on identifying materials whose scarcity or price instability could endanger existing and future technologies from entering the marketplace. CMI’s current focus is primarily on materials that use rare-earth elements (REEs). CMI has a thrust in chemical thermodynamics to create a thermodynamic simulation engine that uses a solution and solid-state databank to assist CMI investigators to design experiments that enable process discovery and optimization more rapidly than through the use of Edisonian methods. Materials synthesis plays an important role in establishing reliable thermochemical data for REEs as well as model validation. Synthetic methods are used to simulate various minerals found in rare-earth-containing rocks and waste-products from industrial manufacturing. These materials are used for solubility and calorimetry studies that not only generate thermochemical data but also provide fundamental information about how the REE is incorporated into the rock and mineral.

1851.prez_name: The Aging Response of a Sc-free Al-0.045Er-0.08Hf-0.08Zr (at.%) Alloy
1851.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1851.prez_authors: Richard Andrew Michi, David C Dunand, David N Seidman
1851.prez_abstract: Aluminum alloys with micro-additions of Sc, Er, Zr, and Si are promising for high temperature applications up to 400°C. They achieve high strength and coarsening resistance through the formation of nanometric, coherent L1<SUB>2</SUB> (Al,Si)<SUB>3</SUB>(Sc,Er,Zr) precipitates with a (Sc + Er)-enriched core surrounded by a Zr-enriched shell. Due to the high cost of Sc, there has been significant research on Sc-free alloys with similar properties. This presentation discusses an Al-0.045Er-0.08Zr-0.08Hf alloy, with atom probe tomography revealing a high number density of (Al,Si)<SUB>3</SUB>(Er,Zr,Hf) precipitates. Er is found to play a critical role in nucleating precipitates in the absence of Sc. Although this alloy maintains its peak hardness for longer aging times compared to similar Al-Sc-Er-Zr-Si alloys, it suffers from sluggish precipitation kinetics. Hf is found to provide no noticeable improvement on the coarsening resistance of the alloy, while Si and Fe have a significant effect on the precipitation kinetics.

1852.prez_name: The Regulatory Framework for Rare Earth Mining and Oxide Separation in the United States
1852.symp_name: Rare Earth Metals, Compounds, and Alloys: Synthesis, Processing, Emerging Applications, Recent Advances, Future Challenges
1852.prez_abstract: The federal and state regulatory framework for rare earth elements in particular and “hardrock” minerals in general is complex.  There are regulations that govern mining activity on federal lands while others regulate mining more generally on private and state lands.  There are a host of federal and state land managing agencies that play a role in the regulatory process.  This presentation will examine the regulatory framework and environmental concerns associated with rare earth mining and oxide separation.  The regulatory framework is viewed by some as an impediment or an obstacle to mine development but viewed by others as a necessary requirement to allow for public participation and to assess the potential for adverse environmental impacts.  Many critics of the regulations would like to see a more efficient process.  One public policy question being debated in the U.S. Congress is:  Does this regulatory framework discourage mineral investment in the United States?
