2014.prez_name: A Facile Preparation of Methyltriethoxysilane Based Transparent Silica Xerogel Monoliths
2014.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2014.prez_authors: Xuan  Cheng, Ziwei  Niu, Xiaoyong  He, Bicheng  Tang, Liuying  Huang, Ying  Zhang
2014.prez_abstract: By simply controlling the molar ratios of methyltriethoxysilane (MTES) and water, n(H2O)/n(MTES), the highly transparent MTES based silica xerogel monoliths were prepared via ambient pressure drying without going through the conventional complex steps of surface modification and solvent exchange. It was found that the water contact angles increased linearly from 91º to 123º with the increases of n(H2O)/n(MTES) values from 8 to 13. On the other hand, the average transmittances in a range of visible light wavelength (300nm-800nm) lowered linearly with the larger n(H2O)/n(MTES) values. The silica xerogel monoliths exhibited the excellent integrity. The bulk density of 0.672 g/cm3 with the BET surface area of 618 cm2/g and the thermal conductivity as low as 0.048 W/(mK) could be achieved.

2015.prez_name: A Hybrid Porous Spherical Structure for Enhanced Energy Absorption
2015.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2015.prez_abstract: Energy absorption structures have been pursued to protect personnel and infrastructures over the last few decades. In this study, a novel hybrid porous spherical structure that integrates the internal porous and external shell structures together is presented and investigated. The internal porous core inherits merits of large deformation from conventional porous structures and the introduction of the external thin solid shell is to reach high strength and delay deformation further, thereby achieving high energy absorption efficiency in the structures. Theoretical models are developed to characterize elastic modulus and buckling behavior of FSS structures under a compressive loading, and are verified through extensive finite element analysis. Further, the energy absorption efficiency is proposed to optimize the specific energy absorption density and critical triggering force of activating energy absorption, and is correlated with deformation mechanism and geometric parameters of porous structures.

2016.prez_name: Ab Initio Study of CO2 Sorption in the Flexible Metal-organic Framework Material Ni2(CN)4(Bpene)
2016.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2016.prez_authors: Eric  Cockayne, Andres   Correa Hernandez, Lan  Li
2016.prez_abstract: Ni<SUB>2</SUB>(CN)<SUB>4</SUB>(Bpene), where BPene = 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)-ethylene, is a flexible metal organic framework material that has been noted for possible CO<SUB>2</SUB> sorption applications.  We use density functional theory calculations to study the equilibrium structures of Ni<SUB>2</SUB>(CN)<SUB>4</SUB>(Bpene)-(CO<SUB>2</SUB>)<SUB>n</SUB> as a function of CO<SUB>2</SUB> concentration.  The volume increases as CO<SUB>2</SUB> sorption increases.  The CO<SUB>2</SUB> arrangement changes from linear alignment inside well-defined "pockets" to configurations with various orientations as interaction between CO<SUB>2</SUB> molecules becomes important.  Changes in the most-favored arrangement of BPene orientations also occur as the CO<SUB>2</SUB> concentration increases.  The experimental observation of hysteresis in CO<SUB>2</SUB> sorption-desorption is discussed in light of these results.

2017.prez_name: Applications of Porous Composites in Heavy Metal Extraction from Contaminated Water
2017.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2017.prez_authors: Daniel  Sun, Li  Peng, Sandrine  Chuard, Emad  Oveisi, Wendy L Queen
2017.prez_abstract: Due to widespread use of fresh water in various industries there is increasing human exposure to heavy metals. Because of their high degree of toxicity, we have begun to explore the adsorption of heavy metals in metal-organic frameworks, which have quickly moved to the forefront of materials research due to unprecedented internal surface areas and the ability to adsorb significant amounts of guest species. The attraction to deploy MOFs in water purification technologies is due to their facile tunability allowing their internal surface to be decorated with high densities of strong adsorption sites for heavy metal cations and, as a result, more control over their removal capacities, selectivities, and ease of regeneration compared to other commercially available sorbents such as activated carbons, zeolites, and silicas. In this presentation we will show our most recent results of several MOF based adsorbents and highlight their performance with regard to heavy metal extraction.

2018.prez_name: CAD-integrated Modelling of Lattice Structures for Additive Manufacturing and Property Evaluation of Generated Specimens
2018.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2018.prez_authors: Richard  Kordass, Peter  Koch, Thomas  Toeppel, Hannes  Korn, Christine  Schöne, Bernhard  Mueller, Ralph  Stelzer
2018.prez_abstract:
Additive manufactured (AM) lattice structures provide the opportunity for lightweight designed components with customizable mechanical properties and the reduction of manufacturing costs. Unfortunately, the requirement-specific design of cellular structures remains complex and resulting mechanical properties depend on multiple parameters. Today, AM-parts with lattice structures are still mainly used for illustrative purposes.
In this context, a user-friendly tool is developed that combines all steps from part design to build file generation on a parametric level within a CAD environment. A time-efficient computation of the mechanical properties to be expected by the means of FEM is integrated as well as a parameter based slicing function.
For verification of the mechanical property predictions, a workflow, based on a draft German standard for tensile tests on lattice structures, is developed and performed on Ti-6Al-4V and X3NiCoMoTi18-9-5 specimens. Also, an automated continuous determination of Poisson’s ratio via computer vision techniques is included.

2019.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2019.prez_authors: Jeffrey  Culp, Lei  Hong, Robert  Thompson, Fan  Shi, Nicholas  Siefert, McMahan  Gray, David  Hopkinson
2019.prez_abstract: Liquid-based CO2 capture processes are preferred since they use a simpler and more efficient continuous flow reactor design; however, many solid sorbents markedly outperform liquid solvents in terms of CO2 capacity and diffusion kinetics. One solution is to combine the advantages of each of these classes of CO2 capture agents by suspending porous sorbents into an appropriate solvent to create a high CO2 capacity fluid phase which can be used in a continuous flow CO2 capture process.  This presentation will give an overview of our recent work with these hybrid fluidized sorbents along with a discussion on the advantages and challenges associated with using sorbent suspensions in both pre-combustion and post-combustion CO2 capture methods.

2020.prez_name: Connecting the In-operando Reduction Kinetics of Porous Nickel Oxide and Copper Oxide in Dilute H2 from the Molecular- To Micron-Scales for Clean Energy Generation
2020.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2020.prez_abstract: The kinetics of porous nickel and copper oxide reduction has applications that range from chemical looping combustion to solid oxide fuel cells. While previous studies reported the structural changes in materials independently of the microstructural evolution, it is now possible to simultaneously probe the microstructural and structural changes from the molecular- to micron-scales using multi-scale X-ray scattering (Ultra Small Angle/ Small Angle/ Wide Angle X-ray Scattering (USAXS/SAXS/WAXS)). By combining multi-scale X-ray scattering with X-ray Absorption Spectroscopy (XAS), it is now possible to connect the chemically-specific short-range changes with the structural and microstructural changes across longer spatial scales. This in-operando experimental methodology is applied to contrast the reduction kinetics of nickel and copper oxides in dilute H2 (~3%) at temperatures as high as 500C. The dynamic changes in the porosity and particle size of nickel and copper oxides as the materials are reduced are related to their corresponding chemical changes.

2021.prez_name: Creating High Surface Area SiOC Materials Using Different Additives
2021.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2021.prez_abstract: Porous silicon oxycarbide (SiOC) is an ultrahigh surface area material that can be stable up to high temperatures with great tailorability through composition and additive modifications. Bulk SiOCs were fabricated from a base polysiloxane (PSO) system by using different organic additives and pyrolysis atmospheres followed by hydrofluoric acid etching. The additives modify the microstructural evolution by influencing the SiO<SUB>2</SUB> nanodomain formation. The SiOC ceramics contain significantly less SiC and more SiO<SUB>2</SUB> with Ar+H<SUB>2</SUB>O atmosphere pyrolysis compared to pure Ar. Water vapor injection during pyrolysis also causes an increase in specific surface areas. The addition of 10 wt% tetraethyl orthosilicate (TEOS) with Ar+H<SUB>2</SUB>O pyrolysis produces a specific surface area of 1953.94 m<SUP>2</SUP>/g, compared to 880.09 m<SUP>2</SUP>/g for the base PSO pyrolyzed in Ar. The ability to drastically increase the specific surface area through the use of pyrolysis atmosphere and organic additives presents a promising processing route for highly porous SiOC ceramics.

2022.prez_name: Developing a New Low-cost Self-forming Dual-phase Membrane for Advanced Electrochemical CO2 Capture from Flue Gas
2022.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2022.prez_authors: Kevin  Huang, Peng  Zhang, Jingjing  Tong
2022.prez_abstract: Carbon capture and storage (CCS) is a critical technology to stabilize the atmospheric CO2 concentration and mitigate global warming and climate change. The current CCS technology is too expensive, cumbersome and energy intensive, making large-scale commercial use challenging. In this presentation, we report a new type of dual-phase mixed e- and CO32- conducting membrane for low-cost CO2 capture from flue gas. The membrane is consisted of a CO32--conducting molten carbonate phase and an e--conducting lithiated Ni-oxide interphase formed in situ between molten carbonate and a porous NiO skeleton. Given the performance level demonstrated, this low-cost and easy-to-fabricate membrane is superior over its conventional inorganic and organic counterparts, promising to be a very competitive technology for future advanced CO2 capture from flue gas.

2023.prez_name: Diesel Particulate Filter: Interaction between Lube Ash and Cordierite Substrate, which Leads to the DPF Premature Failure
2023.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2023.prez_authors: Kun  Yang, John Thomas Fox, Robert  Hunsicker
2023.prez_abstract: Diesel Particulate Filter (DPF) has been widely used on commercial vehicles around the world. And the DPF premature failures have been observed. The effects of Na, K, and Fe with porous cordierite DPF were investigated at elevated temperatures. Samples of unused cordierite substrate DPF were doped with sodium, potassium, and iron.  The doped samples were heated in a thermal gravimetric analyzer to 300, 500, 900, and 1100oC.  The resulting interactions were analyzed with scanning electron microscopy (SEM), x-ray diffraction, and wavelength dispersive x-ray microscopy (WDX).  The alkalis and iron induced corrosion and degradation to the cordierite substrate at lower temperatures, than un-doped cordierite.

2024.prez_name: Evaluation of Materials for Gas Blowing Device in Molten Steel
2024.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2024.prez_authors: Akifumi  Takeuchi, Tatsuya   Oouchi, Katsumi  Morikawa, Hatsuo  Taira
2024.prez_abstract: Gas blowing is often carried out as a refining process in steel making using a device called porous plug mainly to homogenize the components of the molten steel.  Penetration of the steel into the porous plug material during interval of the blowing with resulting in clogging of pores in the plug is factor determining the performance and life of the plug.  Thus, anti-penetration property of the materials for 3 types of the porous plugs with different microstructure made of alumina particles was evaluated using a testing fixture capable of vacuum suction of the molten steel through the specimen of the porous material.  Then, the properties of the plugs were discussed by correlating the results of characterization of the pore size distribution of the specimen using both mercury porosimeter and capillary flow porometer in conjunction with a fractal dimension analysis using the data of the mercury porosimeter.

2025.prez_name: Fabrication of Engineered Aerogel with Micro-Scale Interconnected Porosity for Volatile Halide Capture
2025.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2025.prez_authors: Bonan  Wang, Krista  Carlson, Brittany  Higgins, Alexander  Reifsnyder
2025.prez_abstract: Economically viable solutions to controlling radionuclide air emissions during Hanford waste processing are dependent upon the development of innovative sorbent technologies. A main concern is the capture and immobilization of iodine-129 present in various off-gas streams. Silver-functionalized silica aerogels for iodine removal have been shown to be an advantageous sorbent media, specifically due to the high loading capacity and effective retention of both elemental and organic iodine (methyl iodide). The main challenge hindering aerogel use in filtration applications is the isolated porosity of the structural framework, making them nearly impermeable to gases. While chemistry adjustments can be made to allow for slightly higher flux, a method was developed for generating micro-scale interconnected porosity, independent of chemical composition, that significantly enhanced gas permeability through the sample. Fabrication and characterization of the functionalized aerogels, as well as their relevance to I-129 capture, will be discussed.

2026.prez_name: Fabrication of Ni-based Metallic Scaffolds with Dual Level Porosity
2026.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2026.prez_authors: Arun  Bhattacharjee, Haozhi  Zhang, Ajith  Achuthankutty, Aditya  Patibandla, Ashley E. Paz y Puente
2026.prez_abstract: Metallic scaffolds are good candidates for a variety of structural and thermal applications due to their decreased density and increased surface area as compared to their bulk counterparts. However, many technologically important alloys are difficult to fabricate in such geometries using either traditional manufacturing or newer additive manufacturing techniques. One alternative approach is to decouple the scaffold fabrication and alloying steps. Here we use additive manufacturing to produce pure metal scaffolds as precursors and subsequently gas-phase alloy via pack cementation. An interesting feature of this approach is that, upon interdiffusion and homogenization, Kirkendall pores can develop internal to the scaffold struts. Typically, attempts are made to avoid the formation of Kirkendall porosity because it degrades the mechanical, thermal, and electrical properties of materials. In this case, however, the Kirkendall effect is actually harnessed to create scaffolds with dual level porosity. This concept is demonstrated for two different Ni-based systems.

2027.prez_name: Flexible Metal Organic Framework (MOF) {[Ni(dpbz)][Ni(CN)4]}n, dpbz=1,4-bis(4-pyridyl)benzene) with an Unusual Ni-N Bond
2027.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2027.prez_authors: Winnie  Wong-Ng, Jeffrey T Culp, Yu-Sheng  Chen, Jeffrey R. Deschamps, Anne  Marti, Izaak  Williamson, Lan  Li
2027.prez_abstract: To mitigate global warming as a major result of fossil fuel burning, effective sorbent materials are needed for carbon capture. Within the family of pillared layer metal organic frameworks (MOFs), the Ni-based Hofmann compounds [Ni’(L)Ni(CN)4]n (L=pillar ligand), have been shown to be especially diverse. To understand the CO2 sorption mechanism of these MOFs, and enable the design of efficient sorbent materials, detailed knowledge of the crystal structure is necessary. A selected flexible MOF, [Ni’(L)Ni(CN)4]n ((L= 1,4-Bis(4-pyridyl)benzene, or dpbz)) which shows a reversible structural transition between low porosity and high porosity phases during the sorption of CO2 has been synthesized and analyzed using synchrotron single crystal diffraction, powder X-ray diffraction, and adsorption/desorption isotherm measurements. The structure consists of an unusual 5-fold pseudo square-pyramid environment for Ni and a significantly long Ni-N distance of 2.369(4) Å. DFT calculations have been conducted to understand the charge distribution in this unusual Hoffmann compound.

2028.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2028.prez_abstract: Structural or functional gradients in natural and engineered systems are often used to control the directional transport of matter.  Gradients within MOFs would allow for selective and directional transport of specific analytes to specific regions of a MOF crystal.  A ligand exchange process has been implemented to systematically increase the pore dimensions within a class of 3-D mesoporous metal-organic frameworks (MOFs).  The mechanism of ligand exchange is investigated and revealed to proceed from the crystal periphery to the crystal core within single MOF crystals.  Upon halting the ligand exchange reaction at different time points, new single crystalline mesoporous MOFs bearing a porosity gradient have been realized, in which the pore dimensions gradually decrease when proceeding from the crystal periphery to the core.

2029.prez_name: Highly Compressible Carbon: Properties and Potential Applications
2029.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2029.prez_abstract:
A highly compressible carbon product was manufactured via continuous electro-thermal purification of calcined petroleum coke in a high temperature fluidized bed furnace. The material contains more than 30% of ultrafine, predominantly closed porosity in a highly resilient carbon matrix. 
Volumetric change in liquid was measured by subjecting the test sample to two pressurization and depressurization cycles between 100 psi and 10,000 psi with a high pressure, high precision syringe pump. In experiments the carbon particulates were found to shrink by about 20% when pressurized to 10,000 psi and rebound back to its original volume when pressure was released. The magnitude of volumetric change was independent of the fluid (water, mercury and diesel) used for testing. 
This paper demonstrates the unique properties of this special carbon product and explains details of the laboratory testing for a variety of potential applications.

2030.prez_name: Highly Porous Materials for the Sequestration of Gaseous Pollutants
2030.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2030.prez_authors: Pierre-Marie  Nigay, Ange  Nzihou, Claire  White, Winston  Soboyejo
2030.prez_abstract: Highly porous materials for the sequestration of gaseous pollutants were developed by the addition of organic additives in a clay ceramic. The structure was characterized using X-ray pair distribution function analysis, differential scanning calorimetry and scanning electron microscopy. It was found that the combustion of the organic additives resulted in a porosity formation of the clay ceramic during firing (in an air atmosphere). The morphology of the newly-formed pores also corresponded to that of the organic additives. In case of a 15 wt.% addition of organic additives, the clay ceramic had a porosity of 46 vol.% with 20 µm inter-connected pores. The resulting materials were shown to capture gaseous pollutants via circulation of contaminated gas through the porosity. In fact, the pollutants condensed as 2 µm beads in the newly-formed pores with a capture efficiency of 57%. The current results are discussed for potential applications in waste-to-energy plants.

2031.prez_name: Infiltration Studies in Porous Aluminum Formed via Space Holder Method
2031.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2031.prez_authors: Cindy  Waters, Daryll  Scott, Amy  Elliott
2031.prez_abstract:
Metal additive manufacturing (MAM) research must include rigorous studies of porosity of the parts. At the root of MAM are the powders and while powder metallurgy is an old process, it allows creation of parts in order to mimic binder jet processes and studies porosity.
Powder Metallurgy allows creation of specialized parts in house without the use of MAM machinery that do not have to be fully machined, retain the most prominent characteristics of MAM parts, and require less production hours. Using the space holder methods aluminum powder, salt particles (for porosity) and a chemical binding agent were combined. Infiltration included post leeched, sintered samples subjected to a bath of tin in intermediate time differentials. Porosity because of leeching is directly responsible for infiltrant diffusion. Post testing showed a low infiltration. Refinement is needed in the process and future experimentation is expected to lead higher characteristic volume in samples.

2032.prez_name: Lessons Learned from a Combined Experimental and Modeling Approach to Mixed Matrix Membranes for Post-combustion CO2 Capture
2032.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2032.prez_authors: David  Hopkinson, Surendar  Venna, Anne  Marti, Janice  Steckel, Samir  Budhathoki, Christopher  Wilmer
2032.prez_abstract: Mixed matrix membranes (MMMs) are an interesting gas separation technology because of their potential to beat the Robeson Upper Bound for polymeric membrane performance.  At the National Energy Technology Laboratory (NETL), MMMs are studied for the separation of CO2 from post-combustion flue gas.  However, while it is relatively simple to measure the gas permeability and selectivity of a polymeric material, it is quite difficult to measure those properties for a particle, prohibiting researchers from being able to intelligently match the properties of the matrix with the filler.  Using computational methods at NETL, we screened over 100,000 hypothetical metal organic frameworks (MOFs) for CO2/N2 permeability and selectivity based on the geometry of their pore cavities.  This was subsequently used to intelligently pair high performance polymer materials with MOFs to optimize the MMM performance, and to link the performance of the membranes with Department of Energy cost targets for post-combustion carbon capture.

2033.prez_name: Lower Dielectric Constant and Low Loss Insulating Films
2033.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2033.prez_abstract: Materials with a low dielectric constant are required as interlayer dielectrics for the on-chip interconnection of ultra-large-scale integration devices to provide high speed, low dynamic power dissipation and low cross-talk noise. The selection of chemical compounds with low polarizability and the introduction of porosity result in a reduced dielectric constant. Porous materials offer the opportunity to fabricate scaleable dielectric constant materials. We have been working on projects using porous silica materials as low-k dielectrics for electrical interconnections. Moreover, we induce low polarizability binder to hybrid with inorganic porous material to form thin film and the low loss (≦0.008), good adhesion and thermal stability (>250  oC) of thin dielectric films could coating on wafer.

2034.prez_name: Mechanical Performance of Graded Auxetic Polyurethane Foam Designs
2034.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2034.prez_authors: Yunusa A Balogun, Nathan  Durcholz, Shelby  Mullen
2034.prez_abstract: Auxetic foams are negative Poisson’s ratio materials with properties attributed to a defining re-entrant microstructure. Compared to their conventional foam counterparts, they exhibit higher viscous dissipation and inertial coupling properties, resulting in increased energy absorption capability, higher impact resistance and improved fracture toughness. These foams have useful applications in blast, shock and vibration mitigation, including the advanced combat helmet, shoe insoles, recoil pads, and vibration dampers among others. Density graded foams show a spatially varying yield surface, resulting in the maximization of physical/mechanical performance, and minimization of material size and weight.  In this study, the compressive stress-strain behavior of auxetic polyurethane foams is investigated experimentally at quasi-static strain rates. The compression profiles and energy absorbing performance of these interior impact protective materials, as derived from gradient auxetic foam structures will be presented and discussed.

2035.prez_name: Porosity and Strength Relationship in Carbonated Wollastonite (β - CaSiO3)
2035.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2035.prez_authors: Daniel  Kopp, Richard  Riman, Ryan  Anderson, Kevin  Blinn
2035.prez_abstract: A novel process was recently developed for low temperature solidification of ceramics called “gas-assisted reactive hydrothermal liquid phase densification (g-rHLPD) in which a liquid with dissolved gas infiltrates a porous solid and reacts with the matrix to create a densified monolithic structure. The final density of the product is determined by the initial green density, degree of reaction completion, and the ratio between the molar volumes of the original matrix and the formed product. In this presentation, we report a process in which gaseous CO<sub>2</sub> is infiltrated into a porous CaSiO<sub>3</sub> compact to form carbonated CaSiO<sub>3</sub> monoliths with high specific strength. This net-[size+shape] process can be performed at low temperatures (<100˚C). This presentation will provide an overview of g-rHLPD and describe the relationship between porosity, density, and strength in carbonated ceramics, as well as how the carbonation process can be exploited to fabricate composites with novel property sets.

2036.prez_name: Porosity Characterization of Solution-processed ITO Films by Neutron Reflectometry
2036.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2036.prez_authors: Ning  Xia, Valeria  Lauter, Rosario A. Gerhardt
2036.prez_abstract: Multi-layer indium tin oxide (ITO) films were deposited on quartz substrates by spin coating using a self-made sol-gel ITO solution. The surface morphology and properties of these ITO thin films were investigated with optical microscopy, SEM, AFM, UV-Vis spectroscopy, 4-probe dc measurements and neutron reflectometry (NR). The best ITO films had a good combination of optical transmittance (>85% in visible light region) and low sheet resistance (526 ohms/sq). The porosity of the ITO films were quantitatively analyzed by neutron reflectometry (NR). Fitting of the reflectivity data gave detailed microstructural information about the porosity and thickness of each of the layers present in the 1-5 layer ITO films. We found that the porosity decreased as the number of deposited ITO layers increased. NR is an excellent method for characterization of thin films as the scattering length density is representative of the material’s chemical composition as well as the bulk density.

2037.prez_name: Porous Framework Materials for Gas Separation: Mechanistic Investigation Using Neutron Scattering and Computational Modeling
2037.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2037.prez_abstract: Porous metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) and other related porous framework materials are promising candidates for gas separation. Rational design of new framework materials targeting for this application requires fundamental mechanistic understanding of the gas-framework interaction. In this talk, I will present our recent work on using neutron scattering to understand the gas adsorption in several new porous framework materials (UTSA-74, SIFSIX MOFs etc.). I will next discuss the gas adsorption energetics and interaction mechanisms in these materials, as revealed from detailed first-principles density-functional theory (DFT) calculations. The insights obtained from our studies provide important guidance for the development of new framework materials aiming for improved gas separation and capture properties.

2038.prez_name: Porous Materials for Carbon Dioxide Capture and Storage
2038.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2038.prez_authors: Izaak   Williamson, Winnie   Wong-Ng, Lan  Li
2038.prez_abstract: The adsorption of CO2 molecules onto nanoporous solids has potential for carbon capture and storage applications. A further understanding of the structure and sorption mechanism is still needed for advancing into large-scale use. First-principles density functional theory based calculations, with van der Waals interactions, were used to investigate the adsorption and diffusion of CO2 in nanoporous manganese dioxide OMS-2 (octahedral molecular sieve) and OMS-5. The charge, type, and mobility of cations in the material were found to affect the structure and CO2 sorption performance of OMS-2. Molecular orbital hybridization suggested that the higher-charge cations have a stronger interaction with the porous surface, and therefore worse CO2 uptake capacity. A comparison between CO2 uptakes in OMS-2 and OMS-5 will be also discussed in the presentation.

2039.prez_name: Porous Metals by Intraparticle Expansion: Opportunities for New Applications
2039.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2039.prez_authors: Laura  Guevara, Joseph  Wright, Erika  Zurita-Torres, Roger  Welsh, Samuel  Brennan, Mark  Atwater
2039.prez_abstract: Metallic foams may serve in a variety of structural and functional applications, but many processes for creating them are complex, result in low pore volume and/or are limited to large pore sizes. Many functional applications can benefit from high surface area which requires many small, interconnected pores. A recent development in solid state foaming allows for the simple creation of microscale to nanoscale pores within individual powder particles. This porosity exhibits a bicontinuous structure with greater than 90% of pores being connected to each other and the surface of the particles. The porosity is created by the reduction and expansion of entrained oxides, and the method has been employed to create a variety of porous alloys including copper, nickel and iron-based examples. The benefits of the process, the properties of these materials and functional applications will be discussed in context with other techniques for creating micro- and nanoscale porosity.

2040.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2040.prez_authors: Lawrence  Cook, Greg  Brewer, Winnie  Wong-Ng
2040.prez_abstract: Fully meso- and beta-substituted porphyrins include tetraphenyl porphyrin (C44H30N4) and octaethyl porphyrin (C36H46N4), respectively.  More complicated substituents and linkages lead to a large variety of structures, compositions, and properties.  Additionally, the nitrogen atoms of the macrocycle core may be deprotonated and bonded to any of more than 50 metals.  The variety of possible structures, compositions, and related properties makes synthetic porphyrins of interest for many materials applications, including:  artificial photosynthesis, solar cells, redox and catalysis reactions, molecular electronics, non-linear optics, displays, sensors, and gas storage.  In principle these functionalities can be achieved in semiconducting 2-D microporous arrays suitable for thin-film application.  Structural details such as type of substituents, covalent intermolecular linkages, metalation, and macrocycle planarity have a large effect on the π-π interactions and conjugations which determine the optical and electronic properties, and ideally can be tuned to achieve the desired results.

2041.prez_name: Pulsed Electrodeposition of High-activity Gas-diffusion Electrocatalysts
2041.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2041.prez_authors: Brian T Skinn, Rajeswaran  Radhakrishnan, Sujat  Sen, Timothy D Hall, Stephen T Snyder, Fikile R Brushett, E Jennings Taylor
2041.prez_abstract: This talk surveys recent work toward development of efficient, selective gas-diffusion electrode (GDE) electrocatalysts for conversion of gaseous reactants such as carbon dioxide and methane. Electrocatalysis embodies significant potential advantages, but a particular challenge of many electrochemical transformations is achieving rapid delivery of gaseous reactants to three-phase electrocatalytic active sites.  Efficient electrocatalytic conversion requires three key features: (1) facile transport in/out of gaseous reactants/products; (2) electrical continuity with the solid substrate; and (3) ionic continuity with the (typically liquid) electrolyte.  The GDE form factor itself facilitates rapid gas-phase transport, but traditional methods of catalyst application provide suboptimal electrical & ionic continuity.  Application of catalysts by electrodeposition alleviates both of these inefficiencies, as electrodeposition can only occur at sites also generally suitable for electrocatalysis. Preliminary results will be presented demonstrating the significant performance enhancements that can be realized with electrodeposited GDE catalysts, often at appreciably reduced loadings.

2042.prez_name: Sorbent Materials Applications in the Remote Sensing of CO2 and CH4
2042.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2042.prez_authors: Jeffrey  Culp, Ki-Joong  Kim, Jagannath  Devkota, Paul  Ohodnicki
2042.prez_abstract: The surface plasmon resonance (SPR) of metal and metal oxide nanoparticles is a commonly used phenomenon in sensing applications due to the sensitivity of the SPR frequency to the local environment of the nanoparticle. The sensing properties of SPR nanoparticles can be further enhanced when they are combined with organic and metal organic sorbent materials due to the inherent abilities of sorbents to concentrate and/or discriminate analyte gases at the sensor surface.  In addition, sorbents can also provide sensing mechanisms due to the changes in physical properties of the sorbent when guests are adsorbed.  This presentation will give an overview of several approaches under investigation in our laboratory for employing sorbents and sorbent-nanoparticle hybrid materials for CO2 and CH4 detection with an emphasis on distributed sensors amenable to remote interrogation.

2043.prez_name: Synthesis and Characterization of Aluminosilicate Network Structures with Controllable Porosity: Applications as Light-weight Mechanically Robust Thermal Insulators
2043.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2043.prez_authors: Pratish  Rao, Moe  Momayez, Krishna   Muralidharan, Keith   Runge, Douglas  Loy
2043.prez_abstract: Porous alumino-silicate structures represent an important class of materials for applications in catalysis and energy management. Towards this end, using silica and alumina precursors in conjunction with suitable blowing agents and surfactants, we demonstrate the ability to synthesize alumino-silicate materials with controllable micro and meso porosity with typical densities of 0.65 g/cm^3. Particular attention was paid to understanding the role of sonication time, hydration, precursor particle size and curing temperature on the resulting morphology of the final porous system, which was characterized using a combination of SEM, NMR, XRD and porosimetry. Equally importantly, the efficiency of the ensuing porous structures as thermal insulators and fire-retardants in building and mining facilities is also discussed.

2044.prez_name: Synthesis and Characterization of Biomass-derived Activated Carbon for Electrochemical Double Layer Capacitors
2044.symp_name: Synthesis, Characterization, Properties and Applications of Functional Porous Materials
2044.prez_abstract:
Carbonaceous materials of porous structures have potential applications in separation, adsorption and energy storage due to large ratio of surface area to volume and good conductivity. This work focuses on the synthesis of activated porous carbon materials (APCMs) from biomass and its application as electrode in electrochemical double layer capacitors. APCMs were formed via hydrothermal carbonization process at 220±2 ºC and activation at high temperature in nitrogen gas at 1 atm. The microstructure and adsorption behavior of the APCMs were characterized. Electrodes made from the APCMS were prepared for symmetric supercapacitors with 6 M KOH aqueous electrolyte. A specific gravimetric capacitance of ~210 F/g was achieved. The specific gravimetric capacitance decreases slowly with the increase of charging-discharging cycles and reaches ~186 F/g after one hundred cycles.
Acknowledgement: The authors are grateful for the financial support from the National Science of Foundation.

2125.prez_name: A new strategy to achieve high strength at elevated temperatures in aluminum alloys
2125.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2125.prez_authors: Nhon Q. Vo, Evander  Ramos, Davaadorj  Bayansan, Amirreza  Sanaty-Zadeh, David C Dunand, David N Seidman
2125.prez_abstract: Commercial aluminum alloys are not operational at temperatures beyond 250 ºC, where strengthening precipitates coarsen or dissolve. Many prior efforts have been performed to improve mechanical strength at elevated temperatures, including rapid solidification, to obtain a high volume fraction of thermally-stable strengthening precipitates. In this research, we discuss a new strategy to achieve a high mechanical strength at elevated temperatures in traditionally cast aluminum alloys. It is a synergistic effect between nanoscale coherent L12-ordered precipitates in the matrix and submicron-scale intermetallic precipitates, formed as primary or secondary phases. We will demonstrate its robustness by establishing this new strategy for a number of different aluminum alloy systems. Advantages of these new aluminum alloys are: (i) high mechanical strength at elevated temperatures; (ii) excellent aging and creep resistance at temperatures up to 400 ºC; and (iii) can be economically produced through traditional casting process.

2127.prez_name: Characteristic on nanostructured multicomponent coating layer using direct current sputtering
2127.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2127.prez_authors: Young Seok  Kim, Hae Jin  Park, Young Hoon  Lee, Ki Buem  Kim
2127.prez_abstract: In present study, the nanostructured coating layers with high hardness on WC substrate are investigated using high entropy alloy target made a powder metallurgy. Among the many surface coating methods, reactive magnetron sputtering is considered to be a proper process because of homogeneity of microstructure, improvement of productivity and simplicity of independent control for several critical deposition parameters. The N2 is applied to reactive gas to make nitride system with transition metals which is much harder than only alloy systems. The acceleration voltage from 100W to 300W is controlled by direct current power with various deposition times. The coating layers are systemically investigated by structural identification (XRD), evaluation of microstructure (FE-SEM, TEM) and mechanical properties (Nano-indenter).

2128.prez_name: Developments in ultra-low temperature mechanisms enabled by bulk metallic glass alloys
2128.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2128.prez_authors: , John Paul  Borgonia, Scott  Roberts, Douglas  Hofmann, Andrew  Kennett, Stephen  Hales, J. Drew Smith, Jason  Schuler, Bryan  McEnerney, Andrew  Shapiro
2128.prez_abstract: NASA’s planned Europa Clipper mission highlights a desire to explore such icy bodies and contributes to the possibility of a future landing to directly explore the surface of Europa, with technology applicable to Titan, Enceladus, and other icy worlds. To this end, investments to mature cryo-environment capable robotic technologies, which function reliably with a minimal allocation of limited system resources, and the underlying, enabling materials technologies, continue. Bulk metallic glass (BMG) alloys are one of the enabling materials technologies for cryo-capable gearboxes; gearboxes which do not require the mass and power consuming electric heaters currently used to enable state-of-the-art in cryogenic environments. In this presentation, the current status in alloy scale-up, processing, qualification, testing, specification development, and technology readiness will be discussed.

2129.prez_name: Effect of Interstitial Atoms on the Magnetic and Mechanical Properties of Equiatomic FeCoNiCrMn High-Entropy Alloys
2129.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2129.prez_authors: Suok-Min  Na, Alison B. Flatau, Nicholas J. Jones
2129.prez_abstract: High entropy alloys (HEAs) exhibit unique properties compared to conventional alloys, and have therefore received a lot of attention recently. One of the most promising HEAs is the equiatomic FeCoNiCrMn alloy with a single-phase face-centered cubic (FCC) structure stable even at high temperatures, exhibiting a high tensile strength and good ductility, but with relatively low yield strength. The addition of interstitial atoms such as boron and carbon in the FeCoNiCrMn HEAs, however, has not been systematically investigated for enhanced mechanical strengthening and magnetization changes; these small atoms may occupy the interstitial sites and/or form nanoprecipitates with paramagnetism and/or ferromagnetism. FeCoNiCrMn HEAs with small amounts of boron and carbon (up to 5 at.%) were fabricated using an arc-melting furnace. Thermomechanical processing (rolling and annealing) was employed to control microstructure refinement and texture evolution. Tensile tests of the as-rolled and recrystallized HEAs were performed and magnetic entropy changes were also measured.

2130.prez_name: Effect of Reinforcing Particles on Local Mechanical Property and Nanoscratch Induced Deformation Behavior in an Ultrafine Grained Precipitation Hardened Al Composite
2130.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2130.prez_authors: Adam E Kuehster, Blake  Fullenwider, Kaka  Ma
2130.prez_abstract: Addition of reinforcing particles not only strengthens Al composites but also alters precipitation kinetics in the matrix alloy. The mechanical response of the matrix region in composites cannot be assumed the same as the behavior of the unreinforced alloy due to the presence of the matrix/reinforcement interface and the plastic zones surrounding the reinforcement. Nanoindentation and nanoscratch were performed on an ultrafine grained Al composite consisting of Al-Zn-Mg-Cu alloy matrix and submicron B4C reinforcement to elucidate the effect of reinforcing phase on local mechanical properties and deformation behavior. Compared to conventional peak-aged Al-Zn-Mg-Cu alloy that exhibited nanoindentation hardness of ~2.4GPa, an average hardness of ~4.2GPa was achieved in the matrix alloy after the composite was aged at 80 °C for 2h. Age-hardening response in different regions was investigated through in-situ heating in the nanoindenter. An increase in the matrix hardness near the reinforcement was observed.

2131.prez_name: Effect of Sintering Temperature on the Corrosion Behavior of a Nanocrystalline Al-Ni alloy.
2131.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2131.prez_authors: Javier  Esquivel, Matthew  Wachowiak, Sean  O'Brien, Rajeev Kumar Gupta
2131.prez_abstract: Nanocrystalline Al alloys produced by high-energy ball milling have been reported to exhibit superior mechanical properties and corrosion resistance compared to commercial Al alloys. High-energy ball milling produces alloys in the powder form, which need to be consolidated for engineering applications. Consolidation is generally achieved by cold-pressing and subsequent sintering at elevated temperatures. However, exposure to elevated temperatures during sintering may cause grain growth and decomposition of supersaturated solid solution to more stable phases leading to deterioration of corrosion and mechanical properties. Therefore, understanding the influence of sintering temperature on the structure of the alloy and resulting corrosion and mechanical properties is of paramount interest. In this work, we present the mechanical and corrosion behavior of Al-Ni, Al-Mo and Al-V. Alloys were produced by high-energy ball milling followed by cold compaction under uniaxial pressure of 3 GPa. The compacted samples were sintered at temperatures ranging from 100 to 600 °C.

2132.prez_name: Effects of Elemental Interaction on Microstructure and Mechanical Property of Multicomponent TiZrHiNiCuM (M=Co, Fe) High Entropy Alloy System
2132.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2132.prez_authors: Hae Jin  Park, Young Seok  Kim, Ki Buem  Kim
2132.prez_abstract: In this study, alloys with composition of equi-atomic substituted TiZrHfNiCu, TiZrHfNiCuM(M=Co, Fe) high-entropy alloys (HEAs) were produced by suction casting method. The effects of addition elements on phase composition, microstructure and mechanical behaviors of the HEA were studied. The suction casted Ti20Zr20Hf20Ni20Cu20 HEA exhibits single C14 Laves phase (MgZn2-type) with fine homogeneous microstructure. When elements are added, morphologies are slightly modulated toward well-developed dendritic microstructure, phase constitutions are significantly changed from single laves phase to mixed multi-phases as well as mechanical properties are also altered with increased plasticity and high strength. It is believed that modulated mechanical properties are mainly ascribed to the change of phase constitution and crystalline structure, together with the microstructural characteristics. This clearly reveals that the selection and addition of supplementary elements based on the formation rule for HEAs play an important role on the evolution of phase, microstructural morphology and mechanical properties of Ti20Zr20Hf20Ni20Cu20 HEA.

2133.prez_name: Enhancement Of Fracture Toughness Utilizing The Material Inhomogeneity Effect
2133.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2133.prez_authors: Roland  Kasberger, Masoud  Sistaninia, Bruno  Buchmayr, Otmar  Kolednik
2133.prez_abstract: The improvement of fracture strength by insertion of thin, soft interlayers is a strategy observed in biological materials, such as deep-see sponges. The basic mechanism is a reduction of the crack driving force due to a spatial variation of yield strength and/or Young’s modulus. The practical application of this “material inhomogeneity effect” is demonstrated in this paper. Composites made of X210CrW12 tool steel as matrix material and approximately 100 µm thick interlayers made of deep-drawing steel DC04 were manufactured by hot-forging. Fracture mechanics experiments show significant improvements in fracture toughness, which are in good agreement with the results of finite element computations, where the material inhomogeneity effect is modelled using the configurational forces concept. Other toughening mechanisms, such as interface delamination, did not occur. The results of our paper demonstrate that the material inhomogeneity effect opens new prospects for the design of future fracture- and fatigue resistant materials and components.

2134.prez_name: Features of the microstructure of rapidly cooled alloys of the Al-Mg-Zr-X system
2134.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2134.prez_authors: Dmitrii  Budelovskii, Vadim  Lipin, Sergey  Petrovich, Sergey  Ganin
2134.prez_abstract:
The paper studied the effect of the fourth element on the microstructure of rapidly cooled alloys of Al-5Mg-1.2Zr (wt.%) system. This alloy additionally doped refractory metals Ti, Hf, W, Nb. The introduction of the fourth element in the system Al-Mg-Zr alloys and their subsequent rapid cooling effect on the composition, shape, size and distribution pattern formed by the crystallization of intermetallic inclusions. In the case of W and Hf additives in the matrix microstructure observed flake and evenly distributed intermetallic particles in a matrix about 200 nm in size. Addition of Nb and Ti microstructure is the same, but intermetallic particles are larger (up to 1500 nm).
In the case of Hf additions (0.5, 1, and 2 wt.%) its content in the matrix decreases flake section with increasing distance from the cooling surface. The volume scales are observed lamellar intermetallic Al20Zr6Hf ended with a mass fraction of 2.8%.

2135.prez_name: First-principles calculations of stacking fault energies in quinary high-entropy alloy systems
2135.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2135.prez_authors: Alexandra  Scheer, Joshua  Strother, Chelsey Zacherl Hargather
2135.prez_abstract: High Entropy Alloys (HEAs) are composed of equal or nearly equal quantities of five or more metals in a single solid solution phase.  Because of improved resistance in high-temperature and high-stress applications, HEAs have the potential to replace traditional engineering alloy systems in the future.  In the present work, first-principles calculations based on density functional theory are used to calculate a relative stacking fault energy (SFE) of several quinary HEA systems in order to better understand the slip and deformation behavior of HEA systems.  Special quasirandom structures are used to represent a random solution with a finite number of atoms, and calculations are performed within the generalized gradient approximation as implemented by Perdew, Burke, and Ernzerhof.  FCC systems are investigated first, where the SFE is calculated as a difference between the pristine (FCC) and faults (HCP) structure.  Computational results are compared to experimental data for well-studied HEA systems.

2136.prez_name: Fracture Characteristics of Discontinuously Reinforced Aluminum Composites
2136.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2136.prez_authors: Conrad  Park, Erica  Bindas, Corey  Meyer, Don  Hashiguchi, Kyung  Chung, John   Lewandowski, Matthew  Willard
2136.prez_abstract: Metal Matrix Composites (MMC) have the potential to replace conventional materials in designs requiring high specific strength and stiffness, such as in aerospace and automotive applications.  Ceramic reinforcement of a ductile metal results in improved stiffness and reduced density, which may be beneficial in lightweight applications of materials. Discontinuously Reinforced Aluminum (DRA) composites were produced by a Hot Isostatic Press (HIP) method from 2124A and 6061B series aluminum alloys reinforced by 20%, 25% and 40% vol. SiC particulates between 0.7µm and 3µm in diameter.  Mechanical properties were evaluated by uniaxial tension testing and supplemented by acoustic measurement of elastic constants via the pulse-echo method.  Fracture surfaces examined by Scanning Electron Microscopy (SEM) revealed microvoid coalescence (MVC) and other localized deformation mechanisms.  These mechanisms have been correlated to variations in reinforcement volume fraction and measured mechanical properties.

2137.prez_name: High Strength MgAl Alloys Produced By High Energy Ball Milling
2137.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2137.prez_authors: Mohammad Umar Farooq  Khan, Farhan  Mirza, Rogelio  De Las Casas Aranda, Rajeev  Kumar Gupta
2137.prez_abstract:
In present study, nanocrystalline Mg-xAl (x: 0, 5, 10, 20 wt%) alloys were produced using high-energy ball milling (HEBM) followed by compaction under uniaxial pressure of 3 GPa and subsequent sintering at temperatures between 100 and 425 °C. The hardness measurement were performed using Vicker’s microindenter. Significant increase in hardness was caused by HEBM and alloying with Al. Hardness of nanocrystalline Mg-80 HV, was significantly higher than that of commercial Mg alloys. This hardness decreased with increase in sintering temperature. In contrast, for Al containing Mg, hardness increased during sintering up to 400 °C. For example, hardness of the HEB milled Mg-20wt%Al increased from 180 HV to 229 HV due to sintering at 400 °C.  Scanning electron microscopy (SEM) and X-ray diffractometry (XRD) were used for characterization. Hardness, as a function of alloying content and sintering temperatures, will be discussed based on characterization results.  
Keywords:  Magnesium, high-energy ball milling, nanocrystalline

2138.prez_name: Improved mechanical properties of Al-Si3N4 metal matrix nanocomposites fabricated by microwave sintering followed by hot extrusion
2138.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2138.prez_authors: Abdul  Shakoor, Penchal Reddy  Matli, Fareeha  Ubaid, Ama  Mohamed, M  Gupta
2138.prez_abstract: Nano-sized Si3N4 (0, 0.5, 1.0 and 1.5)/Al composites were successfully fabricated using microwave sintering followed by hot extrusion. The influence of Si3N4 content on the structural, mechanical and thermal behaviour of Al-Si3N4 nanocomposites was systematically investigated. The results of XRD and SEM/EDS mapping images show a homogeneous distribution of hard Si3N4 nanoparticles in the soft Al matrix. The compressive and tensile strengths of Al composites increased with the increase of Si3N4 content while the ductility decreased. The thermal expansion coefficient of Al composite decreased with the progressive addition of hard Si3N4 nanoparticles. Overall, hot extruded Al-1.5vol.%Si3N4 nanocomposites exhibited the best combination of tensile, compressive, hardness, Young’s modulus and thermal properties of 191±4 MPa, 412±3 MPa, 16.3±0.8 GPa, 94±2 GPa and 19.3x10-6/K, respectively. The significant improvement in the strength properties of the nanocomposites is mainly due to the nano-sized Si3N4 strengthening and homogeneous distribution between the Si3N4 and Al matrix.

2139.prez_name: Large Strain Extrusion Machining Production of Strong Aluminum Alloy Electrical Conductors
2139.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2139.prez_authors: Mohammed  Issahaq, Xiaolong  Bai, Srinivasan  Chandrasekar, Kevin  Trumble
2139.prez_abstract: Large Strain Extrusion Machining (LSEM) is a single step, concentrated shear deformation technique that uses a constraining tool in a combined cutting and extrusion process to produce continuous strips from a bulk workpiece. By varying the deformation parameters, a wide range of resulting microstructures can be imparted in the strips, including severe plastic deformation (SPD) structures of high strength.  An initial study on the application of LSEM to commercial aluminum alloys used for electrical conductors is presented.  Microstructure and texture development in the LSEM strips is correlated with mechanical properties and electrical resistivity measurements.  Hardness (strength) values exceeding those of the limiting H19 temper of hard-drawn EC aluminum have been demonstrated, with minor increments in resistivity.

2140.prez_name: Mechanical Properties of Aluminum Silicon Carbide Particulate Metal Matrix Composites
2140.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2140.prez_authors: Erica  Bindas, Corey   Meyer, Conrad  Park, John  Lewandowski, Matthew  Willard, Don  Hashiguchi, Kyung  Chung
2140.prez_abstract: Metal Matrix Composites (MMCs) are in high demand for aerospace, automobile, and military uses due to their high specific strength and stiffness. For this project, samples with a 2124 or 6061 aluminum matrix and 20-40% Silicon Carbide reinforcement particles were manufactured through hot isostatic pressing (HIP) followed by heat treatment. Cylindrical samples were tested to failure in uniaxial tension while monitoring load and extension. Sample extension was measured either with a contact extensometer or a video non-contact extensometer. MATLAB and Microsoft Excel were used to construct stress vs. strain curves in order to determine the Young’s modulus, 0.2% offset yield strength, and ultimate tensile stress. Differences in properties were attributed to differences in SiC volume fraction.

2141.prez_name: Microstructural Analysis and High Temperature Creep Testing of Mo-9Si-8B-xAl-yGe Alloys
2141.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2141.prez_abstract:
Refractory metals and their alloys show great potential for high temperature applications, due to the high melting point and creep resistance. Spark plasma sintering technology as well as arc melting is used to prepare Mo-9Si-8B-xAl-yGe samples (in at.pct.). Fractions of Al and Ge are added in order to reduce the melting point and to increase the volume fraction of the intermetallic phases for creep strengthening. The specimens are homogenized by a subsequent heat treatment in a vacuum radiation furnace at 1850°C. This procedure is expected to generate an α-Mo interpenetrating network. The resulting microstructures are investigated using SEM, EDX and XRD analyses. A vacuum creep testing device for a reduced specimen volume (1 × 4 × 28 mm3) heated in a radiation furnace up to 1400°C is presented. Tensile creep tests at temperatures of 1250°C and 1400°C are performed to investigate the influence of different fabrication techniques on creep strength. Proceedings Inclusion? Definite: At-meeting proceedings

2142.prez_name: Microstructure and Mechanical Properties of AlCoCrNi High Entropy Alloy
2142.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2142.prez_abstract: In this study, the microstructure and mechanical properties of AlCoCrNi high entropy alloy. The alloy was prepared by arc melting method and analyzed using X-ray diffraction (XRD), Scanning electron microscopy, Field emission-scanning electron microscopy, Transmission electron microscope and Universal test machine, respectively. The XRD result shows body-centered cubic (BCC) crystal structure is obtained for the AlCoCrNi alloy. The microstructure of the alloy showed two phases such as dendrite and matrix. The ingots were examined as well after annealing at different maintenance times, and a compression test has been measured for as-cast and annealed samples at the room-temperature. Some of these ingots showed an increase in mechanical properties. The yield strength of alloys significantly increased after annealing between 1753 and 2925 MPa. The crystal structure, microstructure, mechanical properties and influence of heating of AlCoCrNi alloy system has been discussed in detail by high entropy concept.

2143.prez_name: Microstructure, Phase Equilibria and Properties of Chromium Containing Refractory-based Concentrated Complex Alloys
2143.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2143.prez_authors: Francisco Gil Coury, Kevin  Chaput, Todd  Butler, Christopher  Woodward, Paul  Mason, John W. Foltz, Connor  Rietema, Amy  Clarke, Michael J. Kaufman
2143.prez_abstract: Refractory-based Concentrated Complex Alloys (RCCAs) are an innovative class of materials that have been reported to exhibit increased specific strength and enhanced oxidation resistance at high temperatures compared to commercial refractory alloys. Chromium containing RCCAs are of particular interest, since chromium has the potential to substantially increase strength via solid solution hardening and is thought to improve oxidation resistance. However, the limited solubility of Cr in refractory element mixtures has been shown to promote intermetallic phases which can be beneficial or deleterious depending on their size and distribution in the microstructure. In this work, the microstructures of several Cr-containing RCCAs were investigated and resulting phase equilibria were compared to those predicted using thermodynamic-based modeling (CALPHAD). Preliminary mechanical response is presented and discussed relative to  existing strengthening models to evaluate their applicability to these complex alloy systems.

2144.prez_name: Ni3Al -based strips and foils for structural or functional applications
2144.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2144.prez_authors: Paweł  Jozwik, Zbigniew  Bojar, Tomasz  Durejko
2144.prez_abstract:
The structure and properties of Ni3Al-based intermetallic strips and foils (with thickness even below 100 µm) obtained by multifunctional plastic working and heat treatment has been reported in the paper. The material with specified properties adapted to specific functional or structural applications posses wide range of controlled usable parameters including e.g.: mechanical strength, yield point, deformability, stability of the structure - also in the corrosion conditions and a catalytic activity. The potential usefulness of these foils and strips were tested as: active elements in the systems for: “hydrogen production” by hydrocarbon decomposition, cleaning the air from toxic chemical substances (toxic industry materials and warfare agents), panels of high strength and stiffness (e.g. the structure of the honeycomb type), elements absorbing mechanical energy, elements of ballistic shields and high temperature resistant system.

Financial support from the Polish National Centre for Research and Development under grant No. 246201 is gratefully acknowledged.

2145.prez_name: Novel Castable High Strength Al-Mg-Zn Alloys
2145.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2145.prez_abstract: Novel Al-Mg-Zn castable alloys have been developed, with excellent fluidity, hot tearing resistance, and mechanical properties. Moreover, the alloys show more than 420 MPa yield strength after proper heat treatment. The strengthening mechanisms are the combination of solid solution hardening and precipitation hardening of a meta-stable T” precipitates. The T” phase is determined to have coherent L12 like crystal structure and it has disk-like shape with 5~50 nm in radius. The chemical composition of T” precipitate is also determined by Electron Energy Loss Spectrum (EELS) measurement. These results will be presented and discussed.

2146.prez_name: Oxidation Behavior of Laser Clad Ti-SiC-ZrB2 Cermet Coatings of Titanium Alloy
2146.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2146.prez_authors: Gabriel Ayokunle Farotade, Patricia Abimbola Popoola
2146.prez_abstract: An essential phenomenon that is constantly taken into consideration is the degree to which aircraft engines are subjected to ablation at ultra-high temperatures during service. In this present study, the oxidation mechanism and corresponding microstructural morphology of Ti-SiC-ZrB2 cermet coatings deposited on titanium alloy Ti-6Al-4V are investigated. The coatings were deposited via laser cladding technique at a laser power of 700 W and scan speeds of 0.8 and 1.2 m/min. Thermal gravimetric analyzer was utilized to examine the oxidation mechanism and evolved gases during the heating process, while the ablated samples were characterized. Analyses showed that the coatings experienced a significant transformation beyond the phase transformation temperature of titanium owing to the presence of heat resistant phases within the coatings.

2147.prez_name: Precipitation characteristics of gamma prime precipitate in Rene 65
2147.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2147.prez_authors: , Hanqing   Che, Benjamin  Turner, Andrew  Wessman, Stephen  Yue
2147.prez_abstract: Superalloys have been used for many years in the aerospace industry due to their excellent creep performance in high temperature and high stress environments.  The precipitation that contributes to creep resistance also increases the strength; however, this gives rise to thermomechanical processing issues.  Therefore, the ultimate goal of this work is to understand the precipitation characteristics in order to design heat treatments that make thermomechanical processing easier without compromising the final microstructure and properties. The main precipitate that was examined was the gamma prime phase (γ’) [Ni3 (Al,Ti)], which largely determines the mechanical properties of the alloy. The γ’ was found to form in three different sizes; primary, secondary and tertiary. The differences in the volume fraction and morphology of each precipitate type was noted and the relationship between heat treatment and precipitates will be discussed.

2148.prez_name: Structure and Properties of Heat-resistant Nickel Alloy Castings after Hot Isostatic Pressing
2148.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications

2149.prez_name: Thermal Cycling of Bulk Metallic Glass Gears for Enhanced Performance
2149.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2149.prez_authors: Scott N Roberts, Douglas C Hofmann, Peter  Dillon
2149.prez_abstract: It is well known the properties of a bulk metallic glass (BMG) depend heavily on its thermal history. For example, the faster an alloy is quenched, the higher its toughness. Secondary operations, such as rolling, shot peening, and long duration loading have shown modest increases in strength and ductility. More recently, thermal cycling, where parts are repeatedly cycled between cryogenic and room temperatures has been demonstrated cause significant rejuvenation, emulating a much higher speed quench. Additionally, the cycling does not cause a net shape change, can be performed on any geometry, and does not modify the surface of a part. This talk will discuss the changes in wear behavior of BMG gears after a series of rejuvenation treatments in a NASA-developed CuZr based alloy to be used in cold environments.

2150.prez_name: Ultrafine Grained Al Alloy Matrix Composites – A Review on the Effect of Microconstituents on Mechanical Performance
2150.symp_name: Ultra High Performance Metals, Metal Alloys, Intermetallics, and Metal Matrix Composites for Aerospace, Defense, and Automotive Applications
2150.prez_abstract: Particulate reinforced aluminum-based metal matrix composites (Al MMCs) continue to be of interest, partly due to their low density, but also because of their ability to provide tailored property combinations, such as high specific stiffness, specific strength and creep resistance. This talk provides a review on the progress that has been made in the field of Al MMCs during the past decade, paying particular attention to the influence of size and spatial distributions of the Al alloy matrix grains and the reinforcing particles on the mechanical performance of the composites. In addition, the state-of-the-art and the challenges facing Al MMCs are addressed, particularly on those involving ultrafine grained (UFG) heat treatable Al alloys as the matrix. Recent findings on a UFG Al composite consisting of Al-Zn-Mg-Cu alloy matrix and submicron B4C reinforcement will be discussed in terms of nano-mechanical properties and nanoscratch induced deformation behavior.
